text:
Paid 40 bucks for bathroom issues. 

I had heard really great things about this place and really wanted to try it for New Year's Eve. Got take out with my boyfriend. I found the price pretty expensive for two entrees with no rice or really any veggies but thought if it was great food it would be worth it. Got dry pot style and the eleven style. Fast forward to this morning and both my boyfriend and I are very very sick on our stomachs and having a lot of issues.

text: Great food, tried the tomatoe base, spicy base, and pork miso. Need try all 3 bases to get the full experience.  A5 wagyu was on point. Pork tenderloin and lamb were great with sauces even though they were lean cuts.  Cuts were thin, which is good.  Seafood platter was good to sample various types of seafood. Kiki was a great, attentive waitress!  Got water refills, fallen chopsticks replaced (at least 6 in our group of 3), and bowls replaced when needed. Price was on the higher end, but you get high quality raw ingredients. Would come again.

text:
A pretty good dim sum place, especially when Chinatown is so crowded it looks and feels like you're actually in China. 

The location is a little farther out of the way from all the other dim sum places and when the line is out the door for all the other ones we decided to try this one. And it was a good choice!

The prices are pretty good here and we got a decent amount of food to both be satisfied. We got the soup dumplings, stuffed eggplant, turnip cake, shrimp rice rolls, crystal shrimp dumplings, and scallion pancakes. They were all great and for the two of us, we were stuffed. 

Definitely coming back, less people with similar food quality.

text:
I really didn't think much coming here. I kept seeing it on food lists and was like fine.. if the noodles are freshly made I'll go try it. And I'm so glad I did. Walked through Chinatown to get here. The food here is great! We ordered the knife cut and hand pulled noodles. The knife cut noodles are the winner here. The texture was just perfect. The broth lots of body and flavor. Very generous with the meats and the price is very fair. I would recommend coming here to all noodle lovers. The brisket meat was fire in my house noodle bowl too.

Recommedation: House noodle soup with knife cut noodles

text:
THIS IS THE BEST HOTPOT I'VE HAD. The menu / conveyor belt were kinda confusing, but our server suggested we just order off the menu since we'd get more in the portion. I'm not sure what the point of having the conveyor belt is lol...

We arrived Sunday at noon (my only complaint is that I wish it opened earlier) and it was relatively empty. We ordered two individual pots: the original broth and the tomato ox tail broth. BOTH WERE EXTREMELY FLAVORFUL. I couldn't decide which one I liked better. We also ordered a noodle combo, a beef combo, and a veggie combo...and enoki mushrooms (as the veggie combo only comes with greens). Everything was displayed super aesthetically beautiful. My boyfriend eats for two and it was enough food for both of us (3 stomachs lol), with only some greens leftover. It was a bit pricey ($80 after tax and tip) but I think it was well worth it. I can't really tell the difference between wagyu beef and regular beef, both the broth was so flavorful I really didn't need to dip it in any sauce. The restaurant also provided their house sauce, which was something I'd never had (soy sauce with orange maybe?). I think they said that they hand pull their own noodles or create them with different roots (e.g., taro, green tea?). Another table got a seafood combo and it looked so beautiful. 

The servers were all super friendly and sweet. I thought it took a while for the food to come out, but they take such care and time to display it so beautifully so I guess that makes sense. Would definitely recommend giving it a try.

text: Just went here over the holiday break. The place was absolutely packed, but we were able to grab the last table in the house. We got an order of the pork dumplings (fried) and the chicken stir fried noodles. Everything was outrageously good. The flavor of the pork was incredible, the dumplings were amply sized and perfectly fried, and you get 8 to an order, so the value is fantastic. Our noodles in our stir fry were so fresh, you could see them stretch as you pulled them out of the pile. Service was quick, and those coming in after us only had to wait a short amount of time - seems turnover is relatively quick as well. We will be back!

text:
DSG is a no frills, cash only, reasonably priced restaurant with excellent food. The first time I went here was with a large group and luckily we were seated immediately. Walking past the kitchen to the back dining area it was fascinating to watch dumplings being made at the window. 

I've tried the pork soup dumplings and the crabmeat & pork soup dumplings and will go for the crabmeat in the future. The scallion pancakes are delicious and very fresh.  I love combining the dumpling sauce with the chili oil to dip my food in.  I've also had the diced chicken with chili pepper and it might have been the best we've had. I have a high tolerance to spice but I didnt think it was too hot.

The service here is questionable as orders were forgotten on both occasions I was here. I blame this on the fact that it's a cash only business with no computer system so there's bound to be issues. However, they were quick to bring the missed items out and the delicious food made up for it so I will definitely be back!

text:

Our table had the "Beautiful Tomato", "Tomato Oxtail", and "House Hellish" Entry Level broths. All were absolutely to die for. 

Definitely worth stopping in! Will be coming back. The tomato oxtail is a MUST.

text:
If you are looking for the best hot pot with reasonable price, this is the BEST place in town. They offer a all-you-can-eat hotpot lunch for only 16.99, which is a great bargain for the quality of food. 
Meanwhile, I also regularly order takeout from their kitchen. They offer a great selection of Chinese foods at relatively reasonable prices. Most of my orders are ready for pick up after 20 minutes, which is ideal for a quick bite for lunch.

text:
When my friend suggested Buddakan, I fully prepared to spend so much money because it sounds fancy af. 

But I was pleasantly surprised!

While you still feel v fancy eating there, most of the things are fairly priced. They suggest you split things family style too so if that's your thing it helps some.

My roommates and I split appetizers and dessert. For appetizers we got the Spicy Shrimp Bao Buns (which what is a bao bun I still don't know except DeLiCiOuS) and the General Tso Dumplings. So. Good. For dessert I think we got the chocolate tart and the maple blondie and it was the perfect way to end the meal. 

The service was great, the ambience was great, I definitely recommend trying this place out if you want to eat something a lil fancier than a Philly cheesesteak!

text:
I came here on a Saturday morning for an early lunch with my wife and sister. The place was quite spacious, with several tables with hotpot burners in the center.  We were promptly seated and the server was very attentive. The menu is all you can eat for $24 per person.  We were able to select as many items as we wanted from a large variety of meats, fish and vegetables. There were also options for noodles, or rice. For broths, we ordered half bone marrow and half spicy. We ordered spinach, skinny mushrooms, broccoli, potatoes, tomatoes, corn, water cresses, sliced beef, sliced pork, shrimp, fishballs and fish dumplings. We got vermicelli, udon noodles and rice. That was a lot of food, but we were hungry and ate all of it! 

The marrow broth needed a bit of salt, but there's an awesome condiment/sauce bar which has salt, so we added some and it was delicious. The spicy broth was good but really really spicy, especially if you drank the broth like soup. However, it was perfect if you were just heating food in the broth and taking it out of the broth. It gave the meat, veggies and noodles good flavor. We really enjoyed our meals. It was choatic and messy, the way hot pot should be. The mix of the flavors was very tasty. I am craving hot pot already. I will be back. Great meal for a great price.

text:
As someone who has eaten lots of hot pot, for the first time I was informed by my waiter that my friend and I had ordered more food than we can eat, questioned why we did not order meat and despite having sauce, refused to give me any. He soup itself, salty, watered watered down and not spicy. Needless to say, we finished all the food we had ordered and will not be coming back for overpriced vegetables. 
Little sheep soup season is available at any Asian grocery store. I recommend buying it there.

text:
Great, affordable place for soup dumplings. I've come here twice and it is always packed with tables ordering their signature soup dumplings, which if you haven't had them are tasty meat dumplings filled with a super concentrated, flavorful broth (hence the name). They come in sets of 8, which is a great deal especially compared to other places that usually give 6 per order. The dumplings are fresh, seasoned well, with an addicting soupy inside. They are definitely dim sum garden's specialty, so if you come here you have to try them.

The other options, unfortunately, are all pretty unimpressive. We've gotten bok choy, chicken with broccoli which tasted like generic fast food Chinese, and pan fried meat dumplings which were good but not especially memorable. I would definitely recommend coming here for soup dumplings, but know ahead of time what things to avoid so you only get their best offerings.

text:
Food: Super fresh and tasty noodles. You can't get any better in terms of noodles than here. Noodles are made fresh and Nan Zhou has many options. The dumplings and scallion pancakes were also very good. I would go for the hand drawn noodles but whatever you get you can expect a hearty bowl or plate of authentic Chinese noodles. There is a lot of variety as well from your classic Taiwanese beef noodle soup, to some spicy noodles, and even some shanghainese and other common Chinese noodle dishes.

Atmosphere: pretty standard Chinese resturant. Fast service and friendly staff, pretty clean as well.

Price: awesome price for how much noodles you get. Many people at our table had to bring food home and most dishes are less than $10. Get appetizers for the table to share!

Overall: If you are trying to find a quick restaurant to stop by in Philly, this place is definitely a very solid option.
name_x: Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House

text:

I split two appetizers with two friends (roti and wonton soup) then ordered the Cantonese Chow fun for an entree. It was delicious and flavorful. I loved the different seafood mixed into this dish, plus the egg combination with the flat noodles was luscious. 

I would recommend this place to anyone. The service was great, they brought the food quickly, and the prices were reasonable!

text:
We went to this place on Friday night on a whim in search of some good Chinese food. It was probably some of the best Chinese food we've had in all of the city for its price point! The service was phenomenal, as well. 

The restaurant itself has a very urban/eco vibe, and was very aesthetically pleasing. 

Like I mentioned before, the food was great for the price point. The service was was amazing with the employees holding the door as we entered and left, refilling drinks unprompted, being very courteous, and boxing up our leftover food. 

We will definitely be back soon!

text:
I wanted to update, really upgrade my initial rating because my beef with broccoli turned out to be a lot tastier than I noted, originally. Here's what happened, to the best of my recollection: on 4/28/18 my 2nd or 3rd serving I'm guessing the sauce oozed to base of the container, making the remaining dish a lot better!  (I've been knocking my head, unproductively, trying to recall whether that WAS my 2nd or 3rd portion.)

Another thing I neglected mentioning in my previous review the great deal the meal was. I didn't get a receipt, I don't think...but it was something like $10.50 for everything, which again was 2 egg roll, small won ton soup & that beef broccoli with fried rice!!!! Where can you get all this, for that price in am American restaurant???? I'd say NONE!

Finally, this would've been a 5 star carry-out had the won ton soup & shrimp egg roll been tastier & 
the oil, from the egg roll wrapper hadn't leaked so badly into my (take out) bag.

text:
Great restaurant for authentic dim sum for a very affordable price. I love coming here!

My favorite things to order here are the steamed soup dumplings and pan fried beef dumplings. 

This is a popular staple of Chinatown for a good reason. The restaurant makes the noodles and dumplings from scratch every day, so every dish is incredibly fresh and full of flavor.

The wait staff was very attentive even though it was a very busy dinner shift, and they answered all of our questions about what kind of food is most popular and most traditional.

text:
Absolutely one of my favorite places to go in Old City for both PRICE and FOOD. Every time I come here, whether it's with a small group or large group, they are so accommodating and everything is delicious. I came here again with a group of about 14 people without a reservation, and they managed to sit us at the VIP table on a Saturday night so we wouldn't have to wait too long. 

Apps: Dan dan noodles are hands down a MUST - so much flavor, easy to share. 

Entrees: My favorites are the double cooked pork and mapo tofu. Both have so much flavor. The double cooked pork is a bit like bacon, and has delicious spicy and scallion topped  sauce over it. The mapo tofu is soooo soft and just enough tofu to meat ratio. I also tried the green beans, the cumin style lamb, the kung pao chicken, a fish hotpot, and I would have to say that every single dish I had there was good. We ordered about 12-13 items, and it came out to about $15 pp including tip and tax! The portions were HUGE too. 

Best part: unlimited rice! (a tradition that seems to be dying out these days in Chinese restaurants) I went to a Han Dynasty location back in college when I was even MORE broke, and my brother and I split a mapo tofu and just ate it with all the rice we could, and still had leftover. Great bang for your buck.

text:
Went here for lunch with my family and was very pleased. While from the outside it may be hard to get a sense of what the focus of the restaurant is, they do great soup dumplings as well as Taiwanese rice dishes and other entrees.

Of course, we had to start with an order of their soup dumplings, which were fresh and super tasty, and the wrapping was just thick enough to not burst. The pan fried dumplings were also meaty and good. For our entrees we got a bunch of rice entrees dishes: Taiwanese popcorn chicken, garlic eggplant, shredded pork with bean curd and hot pepper, fish filet with bok choy. The popcorn chicken was crispy with that just right mix of savory and sweet. The pork, bean curd (tofu), and hot pepper was savory with a flavor that really soaked into the tofu, and the eggplant had a awesome, thick, garlicky savory sauce. The least interesting was the fish filet in a mild white sauce, which was good but the fish in chili sauce probably would've tasted better.

All in all, it's nice to have a place that does great soup dumplings as well as other Taiwanese dishes. Unlike some other places where the specialties might only be limited to soup dumplings or a couple other dishes, it's good to know that you try whatever you want here and it'll probably be good. Prices were very reasonable, I'm looking forward to coming back to try more rice platters!

text:
Finally on a third attempt, we were able to get a table. First couple times, I tried to get a reservation, they said they dont take same day reservations. Ok.... So we walk in and its a 40 min wait, so we decided on another restaurant and our visit was on a Sunday vs Fri/Sat.

It was a slow start as it took a while for the waiter to drop off our water and after he did that, he asked if we were ready to order (he inputs into a tablet vs a sheet a paper for a us to select). Luckily, i'm use to eating hotpot and was able to select items very quickly and my friend isnt picky about food. We weren't told we had to get our own sauces, but figured it out cause we were sitting right by the station.

First the broth pot arrives, we selected 3 style broth pot (kimchi, original, spicy - all was a bit bland, but did its job of cooking the food) and some small sides. Which was a combination of nuts, cold edamame, and seaweed salad (which was bad cause it had a sour taste to it, probably due to it sitting out and not being refrigerated - i spat out the bite i took). The food comes quickly and i start cooking. The beef was frozen, really frozen, to the point where it stuck to the plate (i know they're suppose to be, but it was to the point of beyond freezer burn and was chewy when done). The lamb was fine as well as the fish and veggies.

Overall, unless i want something quick and close by, i'll check out other hot pot places around. The price is a little lower than its competitors, but you can definitely tell by the quality.

text:
First of all, I think that I would give this place 3.5 stars, if I could. The service was fine, what you might expect at Chinese restaurants (you don't go to Chinese restaurants for their warm and friendly service typically). 
We ended up coming here because we were going to grab a small bite to eat for a light dinner. I wanted to get the pad thai from the Little Thai Market, but since we came closer to the closing of Reading Terminal Market, they were all out.
Suddenly, not being prepared for this sort of rejection we walk around the corner and see Shanghai Gourmet Chinese Restaurant. We were both craving Asian cuisine, so it looked like a possibility. While we were skimming over the menu, my husband saw that they had pad thai on the menu so we looked at some reviews and saw how it was not traditional at all. I just wanted some rice noodles with veggies and meat so I was not really reading the reviews too seriously. 
I decided to go for it, not heeding any warnings, and I got the pad thai and my husband got pork fried rice. To be honest, it really is far from pad thai and any variation of it.. The only thing that was similar between "normal" pad thai and the one here was that they both use rice noodles and meat (if you so choose). They used vegetables that I think they have on hand and that they frequently use in other dishes. These included: green bell peppers (maybe also red), carrots, and big chunks of onions. They did have bean sprouts though which is normal in pad thai as well as a sprinkling of peanut dust. Something I really did enjoy though was that there was both shrimp and chicken in the dish and it was a good amount too. Now, onto the actual flavor of the dish, as many have pointed out it doesn't really taste like pad thai at all. It wasn't very spicy but I could see how others may not be used to spice at all in pad thai especially if given the choice or option. The flavor was reminiscent of curry similar to Singapore mei fun. If they had substituted the rice noodles for the thin vermicelli noodles it would be a delicious variation of Singapore mei fun. Having said that, you can imagine that curry flavor and pad thai don't really belong together. I still thought it was delicious and enjoyed it, but I would not call it pad thai. Another down side was finding a hair in my food... It really doesn't bother me as much as some people, but if it had been someone else to find that hair I know that they probably wouldn't have let it go. 
I tried some of my husband's pork fried rice and I really liked the wok flavor of the rice. I thought it was delicious. Price-wise, Shanghai Gourmet is not too bad, but they don't accept card for anything under $8 so expect to use cash if it's less than that or spend more to get to the minimum.  
If you're looking for a place with an entirely "authentic" or "traditional" menu, I wouldn't go with super high expectations. If you wanted really legit Chinese food, I don't think you'd be at Reading anyway with Chinatown being so close. I still think you will be able to have a somewhat enjoyable meal, but if you're at Reading because of the hype of certain restaurants, I would probably stick to those places instead.

text:
Fantastic place for family-style Chinese seafood. They've got the tablecloth and napkin situation going on, yet doesn't feel like you need to go through the hassle of dressing up. The prices aren't cheap, nor are they too expensive for what you get. This is the place to go for exotic seafood items as well, and the entrance features tanks full of live seafood, a demonstration of how fresh things will end up on your plate.

Everything we've gotten has been mouthwatering good. Stir-fried lobster with ginger and clams stirfried with minced pork were particularly memorable.

text: My friends and I love some good hotpot, and if you do too, Chubby Cattle is the place to go! Upon entering the very fine, modern establishment, it was a bit crowded, but of course it being a Friday night in a restaurant with such delicious food, I'd expect it to be like this. After a very brief wait, we were seated by the very charismatic hostess. After ordering, our own pot of delicious and flavorful broth is brought out. There is one for each person at the table, allowing you to try different broths to your liking, rather than the whole table's. I suggest you order the Beef Combo, including delicious cuts of wagyu beef, for a very reasonable price. There is also a conveyer belt that has a variety of hotpot needs, just pick anything that pleases the eye! And if you're in the mood for a tasty drink to wash it down, I suggest you get the Coconut Drink, served from a fresh coconut. Another big plus of Chubby Cattle is the amiable and extremely helpful staff. The servers will make sure you are satisfied with everything on your table. Two of our food runners, Tithy and Soo, helped us understand how everything worked and made sure we knew exactly how long to cook everything for maximum flavor. Chubby Cattle is not just a "good hotpot restaurant", it is extraordinary and every gourmand should not only eat here, but experience it.

text: Just went for my birthday lastnight was disappointed because I made reservations for a group of friends to go celebrate and they wouldn't allow us to enjoy happy hour menu deals at our table and the bar had a 2 hour wait so that was embarrassing to have all my friends pay regular overpriced prices while people not even a foot away from us enjoying the happy hour deals. I had the kimchi rice that lacked flavor and was like eating burnt rice at the bottom of the pan how it was getting stuck in my teeth. The food wouldn't even come out all together so by the time u wait to eat it together it gets cold. The beef kabobs are so small and I guess everything is overpriced because of the location which makes me sad we were hoping to get buzzed but you break the bank on high the drinks are. All in all it's a cute place but I wont be returning. If u search outside the city you can find better tasting food and better deals.

text:
Little Sheep is amazing! I arrived at 5:30 pm on a Friday because that was the time Yelp said it opened. There were other customers already seated so I have a feeling that it opened at 5. Regardless, we were able to get a table right away. I did notice that it got busier around 6 so, but it never seemed like there was a long wait. 

We ordered the half house half spicy broth (the spicy broth is just the regular broth with chili oil and chilis). They charge you per person for the broth, but the waiters and waitresses comes around with additional broth pretty often. The menu prices are pretty decent. Our bill was $55 for two people, but we also ordered wayyy more than we should have. 

Little Sheep also recently started selling ice cream for $3 a cup. One cup is definitely enough for two people, especially after you've just stuffed your face with hot pot. The day I visited, they only had Taro and Black Sesame. I tried the Black Sesame and was very surprised by how much I liked it. One of the waiters swung by our table as we were leaving to ask how we liked it and told us that they will have more flavors in the future. 

What stood out to me the most about Little Sheep was how polite, attentive, and helpful the entire wait staff was. We didn't have a single waiter or waitress, but instead the entire staff attended to us throughout the night as they saw we needed assistance. The restaurant is also very clean and well run. I love that it is perfect for both small and large groups. I can't wait to come back!

text:
I debated 3 stars vs 4 stars for a couple of hours before I wrote my review. I went with 3 stars and here's why...

Wanton soup: For the ($2.75)price, you get a decent portion while dining in. The broth was very flavorful. It wasn't just full of salt and water. They had fresh cabbage or whatever that was in the soup. The wontons themselves were plump, fresh and firm. There wasn't any oil in this soup that I know of. I would like to say this might be one of my favorite wanton soups that I have ever tried. So 5/5 stars here.

Steamed dumplings: I asked her to bring out a couple of sauces to dip the dumplings in. I was assuming they wouldn't have much flavor without chili sauce added. I was wrong, they were actually pretty good without anything added to them. I thought the pork was seasoned well and they were generous with the amount they placed in each dumpling. The only issue was.. how much oil they coated these bad boys with. Holy hell, why must oil be added to everything? The piece of cabbage that the dumplings were resting on was covered in this slimy substance. 3/5 stars 

Spicy Szechuan chicken: okay, so this is where I struggled. I found the chicken to be very moist, it wasn't over cooked. The portion size was, eh, meh, nothing to write about. It's priced a little high for what you actually get. All of the veggies were fresh and cooked extremely well. Their mushrooms A+ 

Here's what ruined it.. the oil. I didn't realize how much oil was actually in this dish until I came home and ate a couple of bites. I wasn't able to eat it in the restaurant because my stomach started to hurt from the oil in the dumplings. 

Oh. My. Gosh. I'm physically in a lot of pain from eating this dish. I don't have a gallbladder, so oily foods do not sit well with me. As time goes on, it's actually getting worse. I find myself wanting to take another star off just because of the amount of pain I am in. 

Would I recommend this place? Eh, ya, I would. They have a nice ambience. Chestnut Hill isn't exactly the best place to go out to dinner, even though some people think it's the bees knees. So out of your other mediocre choices around here.. I would add it to your list.

text:
Decided to go there since it was close to my boyfriend. I was really skeptical since I do live in South Philly and work in the center city area where the sushi is really good. Overall, the sushi was good, i will say though that the cuts and amount of meat isnt uniform. You'll get a lot of salmon in one bite and little in the next. I would recommend the dynamite, spicy salmon, and spicy tuna. Save your time on the Out of Control.
We also got the walnut shrimp which I usually love, however something was off about this shrimp. I appreciated the portion size since it was great for the price, but the batter was way too thick and chalky! I found myself peeling part of the shell off just to get a normal bite. Also, the cream had way too much honey/condensed milk which made it overly sweet for my taste. Also, the broccoli was rubbery
Bonus points; our plates didn't match and the light next to us was shaking. The menus also had the old restaurant name on them
TLDR; Good food for the price, I'll probably order again, but if i had a better sushi option, i would go for that.

text: Keep reading everyone! Fun place good music, nice and friendly environment, food is great! Brandon was our waiter he was very dedicated and loves his job. Great guy I don't really have anything negative to say about him! And this is for the free ice cream that they ask you to write a review. Thank You! But $95 dollars later not including tip i expected wayyy and when I say wayyy it's WAYYY more food! still left the place hungry and kind of feeling ripped off ...shish-kabobs were great but it was the smallest kabob I have ever seen lmao and at 6,99$ EACH! I ate it in one bite literally hot pot comes with no side dishes  No liquor license so no alcohol at all. Their coconut drink was good but again just too expensive my girl picked this place and we both love food so for those prices we might as well of went to a nice steak house downtown, or some other 5 star restaurant and this place is defiantly not. The only things I really enjoyed there is the small Kabobs, ice cream, the coconut drink, and the service, kabobs were good so I don't know what the hell the chef is thinking serving portions like that. Sooo..yeah if you have money to blow and leave hungry but happy with your server at this time, this is the place for you!!!  Hopefully when they get that lounge running it will most likely be a lot better and more fun. One more thing-  don't tell your customers to write a yelp review for free ice cream  which was small as hell too! Would I go back maybe after they open a lounge! And drop their prices a bit.

text: I was in Philly for a convention with a group of friends, we passed Nine Ting while searching for Bubble Tea for me. We all decided it would be what we got for lunch the next day, since we all love Korean BBQ. We didn't have to wait for table, which was wonderful. Our waiter was friendly and got our food. He didn't completely put our order in correctly a few times (not getting us an order of this or that a few times.) we just asked for it again the next time he came. Overall the restaurant was very quiet, there were a few very loud crying children (it's a small place, so it carried to the other tables well.) But over all, good food, great price, and we left full and happy, great experience.

text:
First time trying WM Mulherin's for dinner after countless recommendations. The expectations were set very high and perhaps I'm being too critical, but I feel like there was just something missing.

We ordered the seafood mixto, the Hamachi crudo, sea scallops entree, and the half brick chicken. Seafood mixto was average, which I guess for being the lowest priced menu item was expected. The Hamachi crudo (as recommended by the server) was excellent and probably the best dish we ordered. The entrees were good portions and balanced in flavor, but nothing popped off the dish. Perhaps the wood burning stove crusted chicken had the most flavor. Next time want to try the pasta dishes.

5/5 for the cocktails. Will definitely be back for happy hour! Best drink was the Born Again on dessert menu, which had duck fat mixed in.

Also, seating was right next to the window and could feel the cold coming in. Be careful where you are seated, so be mindful when making reservations.

text:
I'm a big fan of hand-pulled and knife-shaved noodles, so Nan Zhou was the obvious choice when looking for a quick and cheap dinner spot on a cold and windy night after a day of travel and convention. I dragged along 5 friends on a Friday night and we were seated immediately, to our surprise.

We ordered several variations of noodles and appetizers, and one guest even opted to order fried rice. I can say for myself that the duck shaved noodles were delicious when I had them - the meat was not tough, the broth was not too salty, and the noodles were the perfect texture.

The lamb skewers were reminiscent of the dollar carts back in Flushing, NY- well spiced and aromatic. We also ordered some scallion pancakes, steamed dumplings, and fried dumplings. I have to say that the scallion pancakes were a bit smaller in portion than I'd have liked, but they were still good. The sauce for the steamed and fried dumplings were different, though I favored the fried dumplings themselves, the sauce for the steamed was much more interesting.

The service is very much what I have come to expect from any authentic Chinese restaurant- efficient. It is not polite, it is not friendly- but that is not something I hold against them. The menu, water, dishes, check were all brought out very quickly as soon as we requested. This to me is much better than spending 20 minutes flagging down a polite and likable waiter when all I want to do is pay and get out.

The food and prices here are great- so much that I strongly considered going back a second night in a row since a different group of friends were going. This is definitely a go-to the next time I'm in town.

text:
As a Vietnamese american who grew up in South Philadelphia, walking into this restaurant felt like a punch in the gut. The walls are plastered with caricatures of dumplings and bowls with slanted eyes. The food was overpriced. 

The restaurants website states that owners openly share that they know nothing about "authentic" Asian food - and that authentic Asian food is not their goal. Its a common attempt to defend the impact of their cultural appropriation with their intent - claiming innocence. This type of appropriation, intent aside, is violent. 

One suggestion would be for Bing Bing to provide a listing of restaurants around Philadelphia that do service authentic Asian food. This way Bing Bing would be in partnership with the Philadelphia Asian business/ community, rather than blatantly profiting from another culture's cuisine.

text: I will admit I was nervous coming here because of some of the bad reviews previously written, but I did have a good experience. We went for restaurant week; 4 courses for $35 a person so I can't speak of the price. Food was GOOD! Lots of people raves about the soup dumplings which I got but I liked my partners rock shrimp more. Service was very fast despite some previous reviews claiming it is slow. I gave 4 stars instead of 5 because the servers did some serious hovering and also took my chopsticks away and proceeded to give me 5 forks throughout the meal. I know I'm about as white as they come but I at least deserve the chance to fail on my own using the chopsticks before swallowing my pride and asking for a fork! But the food was very good and I will certainly go back.

text:
Pros: 

1. Excellent broth. We tried the tomato based soup, Tonkatsu miso, and spicy. The tomato and spicy ones we're very flavorful. 

2. Attentive staff. Brandon was very sweet and interactive if you enjoy the small talks. 

3. Meat and veggies are super fresh and the cuts are great. They offer Wagyu beef. It just melts in your mouth. 

4. Large variety of meat and vegetables to choose from. We got the meat combo, veggie combo, and noodle combo- heads up: these combos are pretty small so it feeds about two people if you're not trying to get full- this is a con I guess. 

Cons: 

1. Proportions we're smaller for the price tag so you do rack up the bill pretty quickly.

2. We tried the wagyu uni nigiri and wagyu beef tongue uni nigiri. They're $18 for two piece , which was good to try once.. haha but I would not order again. If you're choosing between these two, go with the beef tongue. It's soft and flavorful. 

Would we come back? Probably for the broth. 
Would we recommend it? Yes, I think it offers some unique options such as three flavored noodles, wagyu beef nigiri, and conveyor belt style hot pot. If money ain't a thing, check it out once... or twice if you love it.

text:
I have been here several time for Dim sum with family and with friends. It's a great options for Dim sum out side of Chinatown. This last visit, we ordered the tofu rolls with a pork and veggie filling, pork shao mai, shrimp shao mai, har gow, chicken feet, rice noodles filled with shrimp with soy sauce, pineapple buns, eggs tarts, sesame balls filled with mint bean, bbq pork buns, and chive filled dumplings as well !! 
Pro tip: try to get to this establishment early because it gets crowded pretty quick. The pineapple buns are filled with custard and are very delicious !! 
I would like to come back and try their dinner menu !

text:
So this review is just for dimsum.  We've been here twice and it gets better each time.  First the restaurant is huge and can accommodate a lot of people.  This is an area in Busleton that some consider to be the next up and coming new Chinatown.

On a Sat brunch time it was busy which was reassuring so that food would be fresh.  They have all the essentials shumai, hakgow and roast pork buns.  My favorites are the fried almond bun with roast pork buns.  They also have lots of flat noodles with shrimp or beef.  The congee is just ok not great.  The service is better than most other dimsum places.  Prices are reasonable.  There is also free parking in the lot.

The only knock is that this place is so cold that in winter you may need to keep your coats on.  We mentioned it to staff and they couldn't do much about it.  However food is good, nice selections and prompt service so we will definitely be back!

text:
When you walk into a chinese restaurant and it's full of only a bunch of young chinese people, it's a pretty good sign you can just look at their tables and go for the same dishes. And walking into Xun Yu Si Kao, from the moment the smells hit to seeing all the dishes come out, we knew we'd be in for a good dinner. Once you open up the menu you'll be pleasantly surprised by how all the dishes have pictures, and while the initial lay out of the menu may not be super intuitive, it is nice to just point at what looks good and ask your server for that. We opted for their signature fish pot, along with stir fry intestines and ma po tofu. The intestines were some of the best I've had; great texture and savory and spicy sauce made me crave more with each bite.

Shallow Fish pot is a little bit pricey but ultimately delicious; your starting fish are $40 but you add veggies and carbs to it so that it bathes in the sauce and gives you a savory, spicy, altogether tasty combo that you will want spooning over your rice for days. As a default, just go ahead and order the $5 veggie combo(with enoki, seaweed, and sliced potatoes), and then throw in whatever else makes you happy. We liked glass noodles, black fungus, but you can really customize as you wish. Everything is cooked nicely and the grill they serve it on keeps everything nice and warm throughout your dinner; the sauce is delicious enough that we packed it home afterwards just to throw in more vegetables and replicate the meal the next day. 

Overall, a bit pricier than most Chinatown establishments, but the quality is worth it, the place is clean, and they also do a surprisingly good job with the presentation of their dishes. If you can handle the spice, you'll be in for a good time if you stop by here to eat.

text:
I really like Jin Wei as a quick and cheap meal and have come here quite often. The price has steadily risen unfortunately and is now $5.50 but that's still extremely cheap for the amount of food that they give! I've attached a photo of my take out box and they include seaweed soup as well. As you can see it's quite a decent amount of food. It comes with a choice of rice, chow mein, or mei fun (rice noodle) and 4 (yes FOUR!) entrees and soup! I usually get the rice noodle, I think it's quite tasty and I find their rice to be a little too mushy (but to each their own!). The entrees I had here were clams, spicy chicken, pepper steak, and mushrooms in sauce. 
It is a small place with few tables so I recommend it as a take out place. Also everything is prepared already so I see a lot of comments about freshness. I personally have never had a problem with the food, even the seafood, maybe I'm less sensitive or just luck of the draw. But in my opinion they have huge variety and many authentic dishes. 
They ARE cash only so come prepared!

text:
This is what a hot pot experience should be! We picked the hotpot-only option (although the combo hot-pot and BBQ option looked tempting) which was $23.99 for all-you can eat. They brought us an endless variety of beef, lamb, chicken, pork, meatballs, fish balls, sausage and fresh vegetables and everything was of good quality. We helped ourselves to different combinations of sauces and condiments from the sauce station at the side of the room. There is a simple menu and we appreciated the frequent and attentive service. 

Sodas and other beverages come at an additional price.

We got a small dessert of free ice cream for checking in on Yelp and writing a review - although we wished a small dessert could be included routinely with the all-you-can-eat price. 

Altogether with tax & tip, our bill was ~$30/pp, very affordable for what we got. We plan to be back soon!

PS: Diners eat free on their birthday (with an additional paying guest)!

text:
I religiously go to the Han Dynasty by UPenn, and it is amazing. So I thought I'd try the one in Manayunk, after all, it's a bit closer. What a mistake. First, there is no sound deadening material in the restaurant. With only two tables having conversations at a moderate volume, it was unbearably loud -- something that would have been no issue at all with some sound deadening. 

The plates were cheap, as well as the Coca-Cola cups. Which is fine, on its own, but they are much nicer in the location I usually go to, and there's no discernible price difference on the menu.

I ordered exactly what I order at the Han Dynasty by UPenn, and I was rather disappointed. The main dishes -- the Scallion Style Chicken and the Garlic Sauce Chicken -- were not as good. Our appetizers -- the scallion pancakes and the dumplings in chili oil -- were half as good. Frankly, they were mediocre. All of this I would consider amazing at the other location. 

Finally, the service was entirely inattentive and much slower. 

Next time, I will drive the extra 10 minutes to and from to Philly (when there's no traffic).

text: Already came back to this establishment and left very happy and satisfied. My bf and I wanted to try something different since the menu is pretty big. Everything we ate tonight was delicious, but the food we ordered the first time was way better. Tonight we ordered the pork wonton in chili oil, steamed shrimp and vegetable dumplings, sautéed seafood noodles and diced chicken w/hot pepper. The pork wonton was good, but the chili oil wasn't what we expected. It had a nice kick to it and also a strong peanut taste. The sauce was good and I wish I could've saved some because it would've been good with noodles, rice or anything really. Strong peanut taste so if you're not about it maybe skip this dish. We both agreed that the shrimp and vegetable dumplings was the best thing we had tonight. It was so good!! Sautéed seafood noodles was nice because they were very generous with the assortment of seafood, BUT drunken noodles was 100% better. Seafood noodles were very wet drenched in sauce and was nothing mind blowing. The drunken noodles w/shrimp was out of this world and we also just prefer the wide noodles. Diced chicken was good, but also wasn't something we expected. It was a bit overpriced compared to everything else on their menu. $14 for the entree and 50% was all hot pepper flakes and 50% was small fried popcorn chicken. Tasty but we both dipped it in the dumpling sauce because it was fried and needed a tad bit more flavor. Everything was still delicious, but the food we ordered the first time was way better. Will definitely come back again to try more items. This place is byo so don't forget to bring some drinks!

text:
Although I'm sure they had something else in mind in naming this Chinese fast food establishment at the corner of Castor Avenue and Unruh Street in Northeast Philly, that " Boom" can signify the other side of explosive pleasurable cuisine, and be something quite the contrary. Unfortunately, that was where our experience cratered. 

We stopped in for late lunch around 3 when part of the menu shifted from lunch to dinner prices. As all ordering is done online even when sitting in the restaurant, it made for some confusion in both ordering and paying. To make matters worse, there were two menus - a paper menu on the tables and a very different online ordering menu, that were not well coordinated. 

So, while we wanted and thought we ordered beef soup with dumplings; what we got was just poorly crafted dumplings with thick skin and low flavor. Disappointing. Beyond that, the Vietnamese style spring rolls @$3.95 for twins, was mostly cabbage within. Double whammy!  Finally, the beef sandwich was basically a soft scallion pancake rolled up with "meat" inside and a squirt of hoisin sauce for sweetener. While the best of the bunch, it left alot to be desired. 

No doubt this Boom Buns is primarily a takeout joint, and customers are far away when they open the bag and see what they got (BOOM!) For those of us eating in house, the sound of deflated expectations created a rumbling crash in our stomachs (BOOM)! 

Maybe the Xao Long Bao is the way to go here, but we'll never know, because a return visit is just not in the cards. There is too much competition in this growing Asian neighborhood for anyone to give Boom Buns a second try. 

DOUBLE BOOM!!

text: After reading the reviews, I wanted to give this place a try. I had to order outside because the restaurant still doesn't have indoor dining even though Philadelphia had lifted their restrictions. They had a table blocking the entrance.  I ordered the 3 meat on rice. It surprised us that the 3rd meat was a fried egg. Typically, the 3 meats were customers' choice but I wasn't asked. Instead, I got soy sauce chicken, bbq pork and an egg. According to Hubs, a Cantonese friend said that this is an old trick to keep prices down. Should've asked what the 3 meats were. The rice had bone chips in it that's probably from the chicken. The chicken were chopped up pieces from the boniest part. It was tasty but this explains the bone chips. Also, the roast pork was very lean and sliced very thin. Probably saving the best meats for their regular customers. Will probably not return again. There are plenty of options in the area.

text:
The sort of market I wished I had closer to home.

It's indoors with lots of food options: hot cooked to order, pre-made, baked goods, juice places, bakery items, fresh made baked goods, confectioners, smoothies, etc, etc. Some of the small restaurants have seats (from a couple of bar stools up to 15-20 seats). There's also common food court seating, although it was mostly full when I was there.

It could be chaos, but it's actually laid out pretty well, with a number of entrances, and enough division between establishments that it doesn't feel like a street market.

I sampled from 4-5 places (that's all my stomach could take). ALL were decent, and honestly surprisingly well-priced for the city center of a major metropolis. If I lived or worked nearby, I'd be in here regularly.

There's also one or more places offering a butcher, fishmonger, florists, produce, and a variety of knicknacks and home goods. It's a complete market, and that's though I probably missed a quarter of what was on offer.

At this point (June 2021) the majority of the market was open but masks were required inside. A handful of empty or vacated spots implied places that didn't make it... but the vast majority of the place was not just operating, but bustling.

There's one sour spot-- closing time is 6pm (when I was there), which is awfully early for the dinner or commuter crowd. I don't know if that's normal here, or a covid effect.

All of that deliciousness is housed in a historic structure with easy access from the city and tourist destinations. Small local businesses, a variety of good eats, a sense of community. Check it out!

text:
Dim Sum Garden is a lovely, casual dim sum restaurant. The prices are good (so much bang for your buck here) and the food is better! There can be a wait outside the door during busy times (such as a Friday Evening), but other times you can walk right in! The dumplings are consistently delicious here. I love the spicy pork soup dumplings or the shrimp dumplings. The scallion pancakes are soft and crisp at the same time. Atmosphere is pretty casual, it would be the best place for a meal after a long morning at work or after work! 

Keep in mind this place is cash only, but there is an ATM near the front of the restaurant if you forgot!

text:
New Viet spot at Philadelphia Mills (Franklin Mills). I've been waitinggg for a Vietnamese restaurant to open near me so I was super excited to try.

However, for the price ($$) and the food was just okay. Not sure if they just opened and everything was new but food was OK. I ordered a variety of different entrees for my family. We had 5 different platters; some rice and some vermicelli. The grill pork/pork chop over rice: it was regular white rice and not broken rice, portion of rice was small, and the pork was dry. The beef and shrimp vermicelli: the beef was dry since it was the thin beef from pho and the shrimp was over cooked/dry. 

Since they just opened and it's nearby, I will give it another try. Most likely order something else and see if it's better. I ordered takeout and the food looked alright.. so I didn't take any photos of the food.

text: This was my first time trying this spot. I was kind of disappointed that their hot pot all had some sort of pork and our only option was just hot water so we just did bbq. The selection of meats was pretty decent, however there was no seafood. The sauce bar had a wide selection as well. The one thing that bothered me most was the employees just staring at you and your food. It wasn't like a check up thing either to see how everything is going, but really like just standing there and staring. At times it was multiple employees too and it was uncomfortable. Overall pretty good for the food and price

text:
Visited Fèi​chéng recently, wandered around Chinatown one evening and ate at David's.
The dry satay chow fun noodles and the garlic eggplant were quite credible examples of their type. Tasty, believable spices in both, and a trifle more than enough for dinner for the two of us.
The menu is classic. Huge selection of dishes, rather informed by south China Cantonese & Min cuisine but with many popular other dishes. 
Also reasonably priced.

text:
pho ha offers a solid bowl of pho for a reasonable price. a small #13 and an order of spring rolls to share is usually plenty to fill me up - i can never seem to finish the huge bowl of broth, but i always leave satisfied.
the interior is no-frills and can get muggy/steamy on wet days (i seem to always be there on a rainy day, maybe because those are the best kinds of days for pho), accommodating large groups is usually reasonable, and the staff get the job done, but don't expect any exceptional service.
it's not a place i usually think to go, but i've happily gone back again and again when friends want a pho fix. it's reliable, cheap, and filling which fits the bill for me!

text:
This is my favorite hand drawn noodle place in chinatown out of all the ones I've tried! I can't believe I didn't visit this place sooner. 
Their hand drawn noodle soup is delicious. I've gotten the tripe and brisket in the past both of which were very good. It is also quite a good amount and filling for the price. You can opt for either hand drawn or shaved noodles which I think is a nice touch and adjust the level of spiciness to light, medium, or hot. I love my spicy food Snd their hot is actually quite spicy with a lot of flavor. 
The service is top notch! Even though they are popular and not exactly a big space, I've never found myself waiting too long. Usually seated immediately and the food is fast as well. The servers check up often and are very attentive. 
I will have to try other things on their menu besides the noodle soup but honestly it's so good I usually go just for that

text:
One of the best places in Philly! So much to choose from, so much to see. I love the fact that you can buy a beer and walk around. 
Weekdays are obviously less crowded than weekends, but any day is a good day. Choose from an array of different cuisines (I recommend the burgers and tacos) or if head over to the bakery for some awesome sweet treats. 
I love the fact that there are fresh fruits and veggies at a VERY favorable price. Also, a sweet german lady sells some beautiful artwork of Philly landmarks. I got some beautiful coasters of the area. 
AMAZING PLACE! 10/10 recommend.

text: The last time I visited Reading Terminal Market was over 10 years ago, when I was in middle school. Even at such a young age, I knew this place was special. The thing I remember most from that time was an ice cream cone that was bigger than my head at the time, but you better believe I polished off that entire thing! Now, coming back as an adult, I was able to appreciate Reading Terminal Market in all of its full glory. Over the past few years, fancy, often overpriced food halls have become more popular, but Reading Terminal Market embraced that concept years ago, and is quite reasonably priced. There are upwards of 30 vendors offering everything from meals to dessert to groceries and various Amish delicacies. It is always extremely crowded on weekends and at lunchtime on weekdays, so if you can go during off-peak times, you will have the best experience! Keep in mind that this is not a fancy restaurant, and not necessarily the cleanest, most modern interior, but the food is great and the prices can't be beat!

text: First time eating at this location, though I have visited another little sheep restaurant before. The restaurant is clean, has good food quality, decent prices, unexpectedly good decor, and very good service!  Their lunch special is a nice deal, and I'm happy they have a sauce bar now, for those who are sad that they didn't before! I brought my homemade sauce not realizing they now have sauces, but it worked out cuz my sauce contained a bit of raw garlic paste, a key ingredient they didn't supply!!

text:
We had the lunch special: 2 entrees, soups, appetizers, rice and a milk tea for $22. Delicious and affordable. I had the sesame seitan. It was crispy and quite a large portion. Hubby had the eggplant & tofu. It was sweet and spicy, and the eggplant was very tender. The milk tea wasn't as horrendously sweet as most I've tried - you could actually taste the tea. 
The interior was gorgeous and the service was good. Overall, we were very happy and we'll definitely be back!

text: Best Hot Pot place!! Definitely the best restaurant in Chinatown, too. Service was amazing! Everyone was so kind, and helpful. Especially Zoey! Food all came out pretty fast, too. This place has such a beautiful aura and atmosphere. Definitely make sure to make your reservation and get your seat saved! There's not only hot pot but many other great dishes, prices are all worth it, for the quality of food this place serves. I've had many hot pot places and this place has the freshest food out of literally everywhere. They even have fresh coconut juice from an actual coconut, very exotic. I have yet to see a restaurant that creative. I personally recommend the bibimbap. You really won't be disappointed coming here to eat, because the food and service really is amazing.

text:
Yikes. This overly hyped restaurant is not worth your time, tastebuds or $$. From poor service to barely edible food, this establishment's attempts to put a spin on Asian cuisine is flawed in every possible way. 

We had a reservation at 9:15 pm on a Friday. I know, tragic. The entrance was crowded and 6 hostess' stood behind their stand taking directions from one. We came in at 9:10 pm & was told our table was ready and they'd seat us shortly. By 9:40, after standing around and getting bumped into by every other hostess we were finally seated. So much for reservations - sigh. 

Our server was kind but skeptical to even serve us food. Three Asian girls amongst a restaurant full of patrons who believed that this establishment's cuisine is SO delish. 

We tried the following: 

Tuna Tartare Spring Rolls ($16): 3 tiny deep fried spring rolls stuffed with a cold tuna tartare. This, although overly priced was the only edible shared plate we all could eat without downing wine or water to muddle the taste. 

Crispy Calamari Salad ($24): An over powering sweet miso dressing is tossed with tiny chopped up pieces of romaine lettuce & red cabbage & overly salted & super oily, deep fried calamari. I questioned every time I chomped on a lettuce if it was water or oil. Who knows. 

Dim Sum Sampler ($21): Honestly, it's just terrible dumplings in a dim sum container. Yikes. The pork dumpling I had was dowsed in soy sauce and over powered the meat so I can't say what it actually tasted like, but I know it was so salty I gulped down a whole glass of water. The "popular" edamame dumplings were mixed with all kinds of ricotta cheese and whatnot, making it unpleasantly fatty, mushy and gross. The shrimp dumpling had an odd cold center. 

Black Pepper Beef ($30): No one at the table could eat this bc it was so, overly salty even after downing two glasses of wine. I wouldn't want to know what this tasted like sober. We asked for medium and some of the meat was rare inside. To top it off, the only to make it partially edible was to cut off the sides of the meat that was SO overly drowned in some sort of play on Chinese take out Black Pepper Steak sauce, gone wrong. 

Shrimp Lo Mein ($23): Cellophane like noodles mixed with a, you guessed it, OVERLY salty sauce. This dish was destroyed before it had a chance to survive. I wish they had used the lo mein noodles bc it would have probably made the dish a bit less salty. 


We couldn't necessarily make comments to our server as for some reason, he was never around.. yikes. 

Think of Buddakan as Chinese take out gone wrong, placed in an over priced restaurant. I highly do not recommend. 

Thank you, next.

text: Food is good but nothing really stands out compared to an $ asian restaurant in south Philly. text:
I don't see how people cannot love this place. It's fantastic and probably one of the best restaurants in the city. Extremely underrated! Everything from the atmosphere, service and food are perfect. We had 5:30 reservations but didn't arrive until 6:15 due to traffic. The staff were friendly enough to hold our table.

Upon arrival we were sat immediately by the window in the bar area. The place is dimly lit and has a romantic vibe. It was perfect considering it was date night for my wife and I. We started with the seafood mixto. We didn't expect much but it was delicious! The octopus was by far our favorite. The rock shrimp was also a nice touch. It was a perfect light starter. The acidity was great with just a touch of spice. For entrees my wife went with the scallops and I opted for the pork cheeks. I'm not exaggerating when I say these were the best cooked scallops we've ever had. They were that good! Cooked to perfection! The butternut squash was fantastic and whipped into something so light and airy. The mushrooms were equally as good. The vinaigrette cut through the richness and it was simply perfect! The plate while beautiful was a bit odd, it was a massive sized plate but with just the right amount of food. Now, my pork cheeks were equally as good. They were melt in your mouth and the word tender doesn't justify. The sauce was perfect and the cabbage was delicious. The cohesion of the dish is something I couldn't even imagine. The love city drafts and the montepulciano were amazing and priced fairly. As for pricing I think everything was fair, especially for the quality of food here. 

I can't believe it took us so long to get to WMS. We will surely be back for brunch and to try the pizzas. The staff and service were excellent! Solid 5 stars!

text:
Thank you for making my dad's 50th birthday party a memorable one! 

We were originally going to plan my dad's surprise birthday party at Tango, but after messing up our reservation, Lair KTV became an option for us and I am glad that it did! 

Linda was kind enough to let us leave party decorations earlier than our reservation so we can set it up for later since it was a surprise party. 

We reserved the room good for 20 people, which was true to size. They were pretty strict with ID's upon entry, so make sure your guests are 21+ :) 

There were three huge screens and two mics available and it was perfect. The song selections were pretty nice and had a pretty big range. It seems almost up-to-date. It was very easy to navigate and look for songs. Everybody definitely sang their hearts out. 

Room service was great! Everytime we rang they came in at a timely manner to serve us.  Staff was so nice. I can't remember everyone's name but I believe David, Linda, and Sandy were a whole lot of help to us! 

The food was awesome! We ordered calamari, French fries, steamed shrimp dumplings, beef chow fun, and crispy chicken wings. They came pretty fast too. They also let us bring in our own cake and they were nice enough to store it for us until it was ready to serve. 

We also ordered cases of beer so I like that they have this option. 

Price was reasonable having the room available to us from 9:30PM to 1AM. Gratuity was included already, but we also tipped more because the staff was excellent. 

Thanks Lair KTV for an amazing time and experience!

text:
(2.5 stars) Pretty disappointing dinner experience. Maybe the full dim sum route is the way to go, but I went with full meal, the kung pao chicken, and it was underwhelming. It's not very much chicken, it's pretty oily, and most of the dish is spices or peppers that's supposed to make the plate spicy but fails to do so. They also don't have brown rice, so the dish had to be enjoyed with white rice, which does nothing for it. Not worth the the $14 price tag. 

The truffle edamame dumplings were cute, but at the end of the day, tasted pretty much like mashed potatoes. Not bad but didn't live up to the hype of their name. The dan dan noodles were also super oily, couldn't see myself having a lot of it. Probably wouldn't return unless for happy hour.

text:
Dimsum outings with friends in my opinion is one of the best things you can do. Ocean City did not disappoint with fresh food and service where the servers will actually bring you tea when the pot is open.   As a Chinese American, I truly appreciated the dimsum carts and the bustling noises of the crowd waiting to be served their favorite dimsum delicacy.  

We ordered it all.  Chicken feet, spare ribs with black beans sauce, Chinese broccoli, shumai, rice flour crepes with shrimp, clams, crispy shrimp, jelly fish, congee, buns, and so much more.  The only dish I would say wasn't up to par was the jelly fish. Just bland and no seasoning at all. I am used to jelly fish being served with some pickled daikon or some flavor.  Overpriced and not worth getting.  

If you want to come for a true dimsum experience, this is the place to come, but don't expect any frills.  This is a no frills dim sum restaurant.

text:
Fusiony Asian food with a mix of Thai(but with some other fusion things) and Szechuan primarily (actually two chefs here); quality is not amazing, but overall, have had some good meals, especially from the Szechuan side. Lunch specials are a very good deal with a decent mix of items. For best foods, I'll focus mostly on the dinner menu, as I have a solid portion of the menu. Service is fine, if not incredible, and prices are quite good. Haven't tried individual entrees enough to say what my favorite meats are with each style

Favorite Things:

Appetizers: Indian Pancake ($5), Mini Wonton in Chili Oil ($6), Peking Duck Crepe ($9), Blue Crab Fajita ($9), Ahi Tuna Dumpling ($11), Spicy Cucumber (cold-$6)

Soups: Tom Yum ($5)

Salad: Duck Salad ($9), Shrimp Mango ($9), Blue Crab Avocado ($10)

Noodles:  Pad Thai ($11V/$12C/$14B/$14S), Drunken Noodles ($11V/$12C/$14B/$14S), and Dan Dan Noodles ($7-appetizer size)

Asian Entrees (not Szechuan): Mango Style ($13T/$14C/$16S), Green Curry Style (favorite of Thai dishes here-$12V/$14C/$16B/$16S), Pan Seared Pepper Tuna ($23), and Chilean Seabass ($25)

Szechuan Entrees: Double Cook Style ($13P/$17F), Cumin Style (favorite of Szechuan entrees-$16B/$19L), Dry Pot Style ($13C/$16B/$17S/$17F/$19L), Dry Pepper Style ($13C/$16B/$17S/$17F)

text:
FYI: Put your name down on the iPad by the front door to be added to their waiting list! Also, the iPad above the table is just another menu, in case y'all are wondering.

PROS: You come for essentially 2 things: the novelty of the whole idea of "conveyor belt hot pot" and the wagyu beef. Literally that's it. Granted the beef is probably one of the better hot pot meat I've had in all my years of eating hot pot. It's pretty soft and melts in your mouth. Tastes better if you dip it into their house made yuzu sauce thing (which by the way was the star of the meal). The convenience of the whole thing is pretty great: you see an item you want on the belt and you take it. Our waiter was also an absolute gem. So nice and really attentive. The whole thing is definitely a fun thing to do maybe like...once.

CONS: Where do I even begin. For starters, they don't got a sauce bar. The waiter will come around with this big tray of sauces and you take from that. Then they take it away. So basically, you either leave that thing on your table and have it take up literally 75% of the space on your table or you let the waiter take it back and are sauceless halfway through your meal if you don't make enough. We also ordered some pork belly with our wagyu and that thing came in the most pathetic little slices. Like so small and so thin that you can't taste nothing after you put it in your pot. To be honest, I lost half of them in there. They also don't tell you what items are gonna be on the conveyor belt. When we went, we basically saw the same couple of items being offered on it (mainly fish balls and veggies with a few spams, tofus, and eggs). You can still order items from the menu but it'd be helpful to have some kind of like "conveyor belt" list of items or something to let you know what'll be on it so you can plan out what you order a la carte. Let me also just say that even when you order a la carte, the portion sizes vary from too much (they gave us a whole butt load of quail eggs) to LITERALLY NOTHING. Don't judge me but I actually counted how many strands of potato noodles we got cause it looked really empty in the bowl. THERE WAS ONLY LIKE 12 STRANDS! 12 STRANDS! EXCUSE ME???And lord have mercy...THE PRICE. IT AINT WORTH IT PEOPLE. It's really not. My husband and I ate less than what we usually eat at Little Sheep and had to pay MORE. Besides the wagyu beef, everything else didn't taste any different from another hot pot place in Chinatown so essentially, you're paying more to eat the same food but a lesser portion. Their stock was also...mildly flavored at best. Like dawg...if all you really have to offer me is one choice of good meat and a conveyor belt with like the same 8 items circulating around it, you better not be charging me those ridiculous prices.

text:
I don't know why there is a guy giving his food the finger in the main photo for this place. I'll have to go and get some of my own photos because this place is awesome. That guy doesn't know what he's talking about. This is one of the best hole in the wall Chinese food places that I have ever been to.

I ordered their food after moving. Boy, was I hungry! We ordered three orders of General Tsao's chicken. They each came with an egg roll and soup. The food was great! Also, it was reasonably priced and came very quickly - like 20 minutes!

My next time ordering from there I was having a bad day and was trying to cheer myself up. I ordered the same thing but I forgot to specify what kind of soup I wanted. When it arrived, I realized. I called to let them know and they told me I could just tell them this happened the next time I order and they will give me an extra soup. That's so nice! I never took them up on the offer but I appreciate that.

I love this place. Thanks for serving up great food at great prices.

text:
When you first get here, head for the line that starts inside the restaurant and trails along the wall down the ramp. Our starting spot in line was where the ramp ends and it was about a half hour wait (this was on a Thursday night at 7 pm). Even though this place is called Dim Sum garden, we didn't order any Cantonese styled dim sum and instead opted for their Shanghai dishes. You'll see from the items we ordered we went kind of overkill on the carbs... Don't know if it was because we were starving but every single item we ordered was amazing. Their prices are also very affordable; we paid about 20 bucks per person and had lots of leftovers. Highly recommend coming here! 

1. Shanghai steamed pork soup dumpling
4.5/5
Yes I agree that these were comparable to the soup dumplings at Din Tai Fung and each soup dumpling had lots of soup in them. There soup dumplings were also bigger than the typical size. 

2. Shanghai pan fried pork soup dumpling
5/5
This was one of the best versions of this I've had (second only to an amazing place in LA)--the pan fried skin is super crispy, the pork is tender, and lots of good soup. Best item we ordered, and when you look around the restaurant you'll see that literally every table has ordered a plate of these!

3. Pork with sauce noodle
5/5
This item was ordered on a whim (we literally only ordered it because there was a picture of it in the menu so we figured it had to be good) and luckily it was! Noodles were perfect texture and the brown sauce is slightly sweet. Solid version of the popular Shanghai dish.

4. Sliced pork with garlic sauce
4.5/5
Comes with a bowl of rice which made it easier to finish. The pork was very tender with a sweet and tangy glazed sauce. 

5. Scallion pancake
4/5
A little bit on the dry and oily side but these were the first item to come out so we nommed on them happily.

text:
This place was for sure 5 stars. So much so that I'm about to say a bunch of negative things that were out weighed by the food!

We got the booth in the very far right of the restaurant and I literally could not sit in the seat away from the door. There was no space between the wall where the seat was pressed against and the hot pot table. I had to switch seats with my girlfriend because I actually couldn't get in so I don't know how thats allowed to be a seat. Also, you are technically supposed be able to fit 4 in that booth. 

Also, instead of a big hot pot in the middle everyone gets a personal pot which I didn't like but that was just a stylistic thing. Finally the price adds up but I'd say it was worth it. 

The beef combo is for sure the move. It was like 25 bucks for 16 oz of really good cuts of beef. It tasted like nothing else I've ever had before. We got two broths, the tonkotsu which was the best hot pot broth i've ever had an the entry level hellish spicy broth. Entry level still had a good kick to it. Udon noodles were great, nice and chewy but the real star were the rice cakes. It was sort of like korean Ddukbokki but shaped differently. Shrimps were great, they were already cut so it wasn't super hard to eat them. 

I sort of rambled this review but it was amazing and definitely going back!

text:
Literally amazing. 

I was in town visiting friends and we planned to hit Happy Hour once I got to town. They both had been before and said that they were a good place to go. 

Happy Hour is at the bar only, so if you want to go, be sure to come early when they open (at like 4PM) so you won't be stuck waiting. We arrived around 4:15ish, and when we left at 5:15 there were a lot of people waiting to be seated. 

The most that you'll pay for a food item is $5. I wasn't really intrigued by any of the happy hour drinks that day, so I just got a glass of Chardonnay. 

To eat, I had the Crab Rangoons, Kimchee Fried Rice, and Chicken Bao Buns. All three were delicious, but my favorite of the three was the kimchee fried rice. You get a GREAT portion for the price, and I had some leftover for the next day. I did not get the chili sauce that came on the chicken Bao bun and opted for extra ranch instead. 

I think the only food item that my friends wouldn't recommend was the roasted broccoli. It simply seemed to be steamed and then tossed in the wok for a few minutes. Other than that, everything was great and I will definitely be back in the future!

text:
I'll start off by saying if you want pho, under no circumstances order that here. The broth is bland, the meat disappointing, and worst of all the noodles are chopped up into small pieces that takes all the joy out of eating them. Honestly the most disappointing bowl of pho I've ever had.

Still giving 3 stars because the Peking duck was really good. Flavorful, juicy, crispy and came with nice soft buns. However, the half duck is absolutely not worth $27 and I wouldn't order it again just based on value. 

The last thing we got was the pork belly rice bowl. Was the best item by far in terms of flavor and value! Came with an egg and bok Choy and we loved it, probably the only reason we'd order from here again.

text:
Philly Classic. The place that really made Stephen Starr the success he is; this was the first really higher end Stephen Starr restaurant, and when it was open, it was among the first on the East Coast with Asian style fusion (mid 1990s). The problem is just many more Asian restaurants exist in Philly for lower prices (not with the same style), so the impact is just not the same when entrees are commonly $30+ a plate, given the other options. It still seems pretty busy with the tourist crowd though. Desserts are really good, as are some of the foods (try spare ribs).

Bento lunch is also a pretty good deal ($15 or $20, depending on selection). But overall, this is a poor facsimile as to what it was in the past. Not really recommended.

These are items that I have liked in the past, but since the quality has come down, it's hard to say what I recommend anymore. 

Like most Stephen Starr restaurants (especially the older ones), it is quite noisy and difficult to have a conversation when crowded.

text:
I went here when my dad came to visit. The food was really good and it's all vegetarian so that's a plus! I really liked the Sesame Tofu and the spring roll. The miso soup was good and I don't really like miso soup so it must've been really good for someone who likes miso soup. The menu is really lengthy even for lunch and they seem to have something for everyone even people who may not particularly like Chinese food. Overall, I would recommend this place for lunch or dinner and I would really like to go back.

Update: I can't stop getting takeout here. The seitan on a stick and the sesame tofu are my favorite dishes by far. The prices are fair and the service is much better than a lot of other Chinese restaurants I've been to. They even offer brown rice which is wonderful because I don't eat white rice anymore. If I could give more than 5 stars I definitely would!

text:
Literally amazing. 

I was in town visiting friends and we planned to hit Happy Hour once I got to town. They both had been before and said that they were a good place to go. 

Happy Hour is at the bar only, so if you want to go, be sure to come early when they open (at like 4PM) so you won't be stuck waiting. We arrived around 4:15ish, and when we left at 5:15 there were a lot of people waiting to be seated. 

The most that you'll pay for a food item is $5. I wasn't really intrigued by any of the happy hour drinks that day, so I just got a glass of Chardonnay. 

To eat, I had the Crab Rangoons, Kimchee Fried Rice, and Chicken Bao Buns. All three were delicious, but my favorite of the three was the kimchee fried rice. You get a GREAT portion for the price, and I had some leftover for the next day. I did not get the chili sauce that came on the chicken Bao bun and opted for extra ranch instead. 

I think the only food item that my friends wouldn't recommend was the roasted broccoli. It simply seemed to be steamed and then tossed in the wok for a few minutes. Other than that, everything was great and I will definitely be back.

text:
My favorite karaoke place in philly! The reason I enjoy it so much is because you do not need to book a private room to have a good time. The dance floor is fun, lively, and the crowd is usually super cool who all just want to enjoy music and party. 

They do take requests for songs but I do believe you have to buy something at the bar first, which I found odd since how could they prove you haven't spent any money yet? But I digress. Drinks are moderately priced if I'm not mistaken. I usually come here after pregaming at home or drinking at another bar. 

Another good thing about this place is that they card. So be prepared to show ID. This is good because I've been to too many shady karaoke bars with drunk high schoolers running amuck.

text:
Nan Zhou has been part of my Philadelphia experience for many years now. I've been through many dietary changes and I always found something I am happy with. Overall, it's traditional, buzzing at almost all times, and quite delicious. One of my favorite spots to take out of town visitors.

Location: Heart of Chinatown on Race. Restaurant is always clean. Cash only, ATM in the lobby. They will seat you very close to other parties or at tables with others when it is busy. Just ask your neighbor for the condiment caddy and share the love. Recently upgraded their menu appearance, but no noticeable changes to the actual content of the menu. 

Food: Two varieties of noodles, hand drawn and shaved. Pho is huge and they do have a mushroom based broth for vegan/vegetarian folks--but you have to ask for it. I've heard people say the broth (mushroom or beef) is not flavorful, but I'm of the unpopular opinion that it's suppose to be this way (that's why they have chili oil, vinegar, soy sauce, etc on the table). Good variety of choices and scallion pancakes are some of my favorite in the city. Always pleasantly surprised at the low cost of eating here. BYOB if you please.
