text:
Better Than I thought but...

I've always had my go to staples in Chinatown, but was invited to Tai Lake by my parents for dinner so I happily went along. I know some Chinatown restaurants can be hit or miss so my expectations weren't that high.

I was pleasantly surprised at the food. Real and authentic (as it should be in Chinatown). We had a large party of 12 so we had a bunch of dishes family style to share. We had a little bit of everything - lobster, fish, fried rice, and the works. Everything was great (food 5/5).

Service was also top notch from a normal take your order, server your food, check on you standpoint..

However, we were on the second floor and there was without a doubt that the servers use the second floor bathroom for their smoke break (it's a small, personalized style bathroom with one toilet). It was one of the coldest days of the year so it was probably a combination of the weather and having to go all the way to the first floor. The bathroom reeked of cigarette smoke and, as anyone knows, smell and taste go hand in hand. It really made the food taste different. Unfortunate (service 2/5).

Ambiance is like any normal Chinatown restaurant (ambiance 3/5). 

Drinks were fairly priced with a limited selection (3/5).

text:
I was pretty disappointed in Chushang, especially since I like their concept. They offer typical Chinese dishes and your lunch combo type meals on their menu. I'd say that style of food is average here, given how many places in Chinatown have dumplings and scallion pancakes. 

I ordered their hot pot style dish, where you can pick out what you want on a piece of paper, mark it down and get a very large dish with everything ordered. It's supposed to be hot pot without the hot pot. The concept was slightly confusing, but essentially you have to pick enough ingredients to hit the minimum price for a hot pot or dry pot. I did the dry pot so it was $15. It wasn't hard to hit and the portion size is definitely meant to be shared (which I didn't realize and ordered all for myself lol). I got it a little bit spiced. 

My noodles and veggies came out soaked, literally soaked, in the hot pot spicy chili oil, and I was not really satisfied with it. It was way too much oil, too spicy and way over cooked. The concept is interesting but I ended up just wanting normal noodles cooked normally. I probably won't be doing this again, and if I do, I'd want to get the actual hot pot version, because the dry pot isn't really dry.

text:
After a visit to the Philadelphia Auto Show, we went to Bai Wei to satisfy our craving for noodle soup. The restaurant's interior is modern and spacious for a Chinatown venue. The waiter reminded us at the entrance immediately that they did not accept credit cards. Only cash and Venmo was accepted. I suppose they want to earn a little extra by not having to pay credit card costs, which is not a customer friendly way of doing business. If you want to earn more as restaurant, then you should improve your service, not cut costs by limiting the customer's options. Luckily we had enough cash with us. The waiter assigned us a table in the back. After a while, we noticed that other customers got water and tea on arrival, but we did not get anything. How can you treat customers differently like that? We are paying the same as everybody else, so we also want the same service as everyone else!
Anyway, the Taiwanese noodle soup has too many noodles and too few vegetables for my taste. Moreover, half of the meat was skin, which I find chewy and not particularly tasty. We enjoyed the scallion pancakes however.

text: This place has been on my list for a while since it opened. Finally made it here last week and was definitely worth the wait. Not a super big place, so understandable why wait times can be up to an hour or more. Decor is pretty generic except for the revolving conveyor belt in the center with all the extras you can add into your hot pot and the long conveyor in the center of the revolving one that shoots out stuff from the kitchen. Service staff is friendly, knowledgeable and helpful. We ordered a lot, the wagyu brisket, lamb, purple noodles, udon noodles, wagyu soup dumplings, squid, bok choy, mushrooms, mini sausages, fried rolled tofu. I got the tomato soup base and my friend got the spicy. Everything was delicious and not super super expensive, the only thing I thought that was okay and a little over priced was the wagyu soup dumplings. Would definitely eat again!

text:
Rating is more like a 3.5. Bougie interior with decent, but over-priced food. Service is top notch, and the dessert definitely saved the day.

FOOD: we ordered the dim sum sampler, black pepper beef, snow peas, and dan dan noodles. I personally think that fusion food should seek to elevate traditional food, instead of arbitrarily combining elements. Buddakan attempts it with varying success. The dan dan noodles, at a pricey $16, incorporated chickpeas and not much else. It tasted like ordinary dan dan with chickpeas. 2/5. The black pepper beef was very non traditional, with hunks of ribeye cooked medium rare- 3.5/5, it was quite salty. The snow peas were actually the star: bacon went super well in the dish, making it a great example of good, purposeful fusion. 4.5/5. Dim sum sampler was a mixed bag- the edamame dumplings were interesting, but the pork ones were super salty and objectively not great. 2.5/5. 

The dessert was fantastic: got a poached pear. I think this one was successful because the fusion wasn't really attempted, and therefore the flavors felt much more cohesive. Came with gold foil on top too :) 

SERVICE: excellent! Our waitress was kind and knowledgeable. One qualm is that she didn't tell us that the bottled water would be extra ($6 to be exact) - I suppose if it's an upscale place it's to be expected? There's also coat check, which is nice in cold Philly.

ATMOSPHERE: it is way too unnecessarily dark in here! My eyes felt like they were straining the whole time. Multiple people, including us, pulled out the phone flashlight just to read the menu. Especially frustrating when half the appeal of the food is the presentation.

text:
Pretty good restaurant overall that is a bit off the beaten path. I'd classify it as Chinese-American food (vaguely Cantonese, but is designed to appeal primarily to Americans) and as competitive in quality with similar types of restaurants in Chinatown such as Lee How Fook. Food is not hugely seasoned (although by Cantonese standards, it is rather spicy, so spicier dishes here are fine), but is prepared very elegantly, and has a very clean taste to it. Fairly quiet in general. Pricing is quite affordable. Lots of good food options. I do worry a bit about it becoming a relic similar to places such as Imperial Inn and some others that are more along this style. Consistency is very strong; I always know what quality I'm getting when I am  here,which is definitely a plus.

I usually will get one appetizer, some sort of veggie dish, and some sort of meat dish (or fried rice dish).

Options my family and I have liked are below (honestly most of the menu is good though):

Apps: Dumplings (Steamed or fried-$8), stuffed eggplant ($8)

Soup: Curry Beef Soup ($8 for two people), Wonton ($4), Chicken and Corn ($4)

Veggies: Mustard Greens ($10), Mixed Greens ($10), Tofu with Vegetables ($10, Snow Pea Leaves ($14)

Beef and Lamb: Lamb Chops ($19), Hunan Style Beef ($17)

Pork: Roast Pork ($15), Firecracker Pork ($16)

Poultry: General's ($15), Duck Special ($21), Chicken with Shitake Mushrooms ($15)

Seafood: Steamed Salmon ($16), Steamed Tilapia ($16), Fish of the Day

Fried Rice: Veggie ($8), Garlic ($7), Pork ($11)

Philly Classic, and I am a fan overall.

text:
Totally worthy of all the hype and definitely worth all of the 5 star ratings!! This place will sustain me all winter! Yum!! 

I've been to hotpot places before, but never have I seen this type of variety of food for cooking, a conveyor belt AND tasted this kind of flavor!! I've also never seen a pot for each person! This place is the coolest!! 

 I loved concocting my own sauce with a ponzu base they give you at the beginning of the meal. I added garlic, scallions, crushed peanuts, sesame oil and hot chili oil. This added to their vegan mushroom broth was complex and totally outrageous!! 

My fam also ordered the other vegan broth, which was a creamy tomato and hubs ordered the 'Hellfire' in entry spiciness, and even that was quite hard to handle. Watch the spice level, you could easily just add chili oil if you need more kick. Each broth came with some added veggies and seasoning. 

So this is the only hot pot place in the world with A5 quality wagyu beef. They take their meat VERY seriously here. Hubs enjoyed his thin sliced angus brisket and huge tiger shrimp thoroughly. There's some crazy stuff on the menu like duck flippers and beef throat, which admittedly freaked me out a bit. 

Fellow veg-heads, fear not however, there's a TON of options for us!! For instance, their beautiful mixed mushroom basket that blew my mind. Also there's more than 4 types of tofu and over a dozen noodles including green tea, sweet potato, purple yam aka ube. Needle, glass, wide potato...and so on.  

They only take reservations for parties of 6 or more and the wait on a Saturday night can be well over an hour. You can however just check in via iPad at the entrance and stroll Chinatown a bit until they text you! We somehow got super lucky during Lunar New Year festivities and wound up with only 3 parties ahead of us. 

Enjoy B1G1 conveyor belt dishes during Happy Hour 9:30-11:30pm M-F and one free conveyor belt item with Yelp check-in. 

*Be sure to check the belt as bok choy, tofu, some mushrooms and shrimp are on there and are $1 or so less expensive. 

Kids broth is half price. My 7 & 9 year old got a kick out of everything. Def bring the (bigger)kids!

I'm quite impressed with quality, the portion sizes, the powerful flavor, the over all cool vibes, the beautiful presentation, the vegan options, and the option to make your meal as health conscious as you choose! I'm now a huge fan, as is the entire fam! We will definitely be back soon! I want this at my house for everyday consumption!! Soooooo good!!

text:
No Philly food experience is complete without the Reading Terminal. Whether you're foraging ingredients to make a great meal or you're grabbing some eats, the Terminal will set you right. 
All of the meat stands are great particularly La Divisa. Great raw fish is available as well. The produce from Iovine's is fresh, varied and affordable. 
Termini brothers, Bassets Ice cream, Beiler's donuts and the apple dumpling from the Amish counter will all satisfy your sweet tooth. 
For savory eats I love the oysters and soups from Pearl's, the roast pork from Dinic's (as much a Philly sandwich as a cheese steak) Sang Kee's duck/ wonton noodle soup, Cajun food from Beck's, ribs and wings from Diener's. Really, you can't go wrong and there are a ton of options. Amazing place. A must see and feel if you're visiting.

text:
Sure it's not bad but no I do not feel that it is as good as everyone said it is. The gastronomy is nice but the taste is nothing special. I would easily be able to find the same or better taste in Chinatown. 
The service is very friendly and professional. I went on restaurant week so the price is acceptable. But if I were to go again, I do not think the price is worth it. The only dish that I like is the scallop. It was not chewy and I really like the buttery and lemony flavor to it. To be honest, the ice cream taste like McDonald's quality. It was advertised by many people as a truly delicious 'one of the kind' type of restaurant but I am personally disappointed in how the food tasted and the lack of uniqueness in flavor.

text:
Love this place, so far my favorite hand drawn noodle place in philly. The beef brisket hand drawn noodle soup is the best - honestly any of the beef noodle soups are good. ALSO get the snow pea tips if you want a vegetable!

Note: it is CASH ONLY but they have an atm in store

text:
While most people go out for a classy dinner on Valentine's Day, my wife and I often devolve into the following:

A) I make a reservation somewhere nice in Center City or adjacent.
B) Let's go somewhere closer to home?
C) Are you really sure you wanna go there?
D) What about this place (that at least one of us isn't into)
E) Takeout?

This always happens - we've spent our entire fall/winter going from our Birthdays to our wedding anniversary to the Holidays to the anniversary of our first date to...Valentine's day.  For us, it's the end of a long run of Holidays and is the least special.  So, inevitable and for like 8 years now, we get takeout.

Enter Xi'an Sizzling Woks, which was conveniently on our way home from some earlier day errands.  As a result, this is a takeout only review, but given Xi'an's proximity to college students, should be useful.

Xi'an is a slightly modern, fairly Americanized spin on traditional Szechuan cuisine in the US.  I've read on Phillymag that Xi'an features a lot of Shaanxi specialities, which "shares a border--and occasional outbursts of chili heat--with Szechuan its southern neighbor, but westward influences loom large in its cooking." (https://www.phillymag.com/articles/2013/10/25/philadelphia-restaurant-review-xian-sizzling-woks/#XMqZbRofStTM52l5.99).

While I found the heat slightly lacking, it still had a little more spice than maybe some are used to and I'm sure you could ask them to turn up the heat (I will next time).

Pros:

Service and the niceness of the staff were great.  They were ready when we got there some 20 minute after ordering.  Friendly and easy to get in and out

The restaurant itself was nice.  For a place the probably resides between the relative niceness of Han Dynasty and your local Chinese joint, Xi'an is a place that feels a step above fast casual and is a little cozy.  I believe we would eat here in the future.

Our food ranged from Average to great.  (See some cons below)

The Duck and Pork buns were leaders of the pack, which deliciously soft bao puns on some well-seasons and slightly sweet duck or pork.  Both were our favorites!  

My wife and I tried the Sauteed Spicy Chicken and Noodle and Pan Fried Spicy Pork for dinner.  The chicken was the star with enjoyable potatoes lumped in - it was well-seasons and a little bit of heat, but a saucy favorite when mixed with the noodles.  The Pork isn't something I'd re-do (with so many great options to try), but we liked it none-the-less.  It lacked the heat of it's compatriot, but was filling and enjoyable.

We still have plenty of leftovers (did we over-order?!), but no matter, chinese leftovers are our favs!

Cons:

The price is arguably slightly higher, but for a comparable Szechuan menu to Han Dynasty, I found the prices on point.  

Our Shanghai Bokchoy with Green Soy Bean was fine, if mostly a steamed mixture of the two - nothing special.  Our Won Ton soup was enjoyable but typical - it features a lighter wonton than less quality establishment that my wife gave a thumbs up.  The Dan Dan noodles were acceptable, if slightly less spicy and saucy than other places we've had.  

Conclusion:  If you're looking for a slightly different spin on typical Chinese-American takeout, you could do much worse than Xi'an Sizzling Woks.  With prices comparable to other less-quality Chinese joints in the area and food which far-outstrips them, Xi'an has typical Chinese-American fare (we spotted Sesame Chicken and boneless spare ribs on the menu, among others) and some more traditional fare which my wife and I have grown to enjoy since becoming more adventurous.  

And also the Buns - this side of a proper Center City and/or Chinatown place, you can't do much better!

text:
Really fresh and a step above the other hot pot restaurants in Chinatown. But it comes at a price. Spent three times as much as we do elsewhere so be ready for that. 

Also, be prepared for a wait. We arrived at 1:15 in the afternoon which we figured was a safe time.  Surprisingly we arrived to an hour and a half wait as we were informed. They do have a good notification system though so at least you can go elsewhere while you wait and they will contact you when they have your table. You have to check in at the door on their iPad though, so no luck calling ahead to skip the wait. 

Service was surprising. Not necessarily surprising good, but a little good and a little bad. Hostess was super nice. 

On the other hand, our actual server was rushed and hardly checked on us at all. Seemed like he wanted to be elsewhere. In 2 to 2.5 hours we spent there (yes that long) he stopped by three times in the first 10 minutes then not once again until we were trying to get a check at which point he returned with his winter coat on and a can of drink in hand. Our two glasses of water were not refilled once the whole time. 

The bussers and non-specific wait staff were all, however much nicer and very good , and since our server never checked in or did anything, so that's a really good thing...so we relied on them to refill our hot pot broth and bring orders (including the ones he forgot, lol). Luckily they did a good job of saving the experience. 

On to the food:

Wagyu nigiri was a treat. really nice meat and good rice.

the rainbow soup dumplings are really yummy too...liked the consumee and the wagyu filling was a nice departure from the traditional pork.

Oxtail tomato broth was the standout between that and the house original.  Although once mixed in my little soup bowl with a spoon of the ponzu and spices, the original woke up very nicely and satisfied.

Ponzu house dipping sauce and all the sauces are really good accompaniments 

No a5 wagyu today which i really wanted to eat so I'm a little disappointed there. The wagyu nigiri was a substitution for the a5 sashimi...it was good but hard to be excited when substituting for a dish i craved. More forgivable if it weren't for the fact that they advertise the a5 as one of the reasons to go there and also more forgivable if our server hadn't talked it up as what i needed to get before coming back to tell me i couldn't have it because they were now out.

Sous vide wagyu tongue was ok but not amazing.  Not worth it. 

House made noodles were very good. The trio on the combo plate were excellent in texture and flavor. 

Tiger shrimp were fresh and good quality. 

Squid rings were decent. 

Watercress was very fresh and tender.

Napa was ok...they could have been a little more selective though and removed the few leaves with black spots. 

Mushrooms were all very fresh and good quality. 

So...why three stars?

Overall a four to five star food experience but a bad server, missing a5 wagyu which they advertise as one of the reasons to go there, and overly high prices made it a three star dining experience instead.

Now that we know how to order here for an optimal experience at a better price, we'll know what and how to order in the future to ensure a four star meal.

Tip: order soup, beef, and special items from your server, maybe a couple specific items from the menu with that, and get the rest from the conveyor which will provide you small cheap plates to compliment.

text: Chubby Cattle may be my new favorite place in Chinatown Philly. Hot pot is one of my favorite meals and Chubby Cattle perfected the experience. We had the choice of each picking our own bases which we went with the beginner spicy. Even though it says beginner, it's anything but. You can pick your different meats, vegetables, noodles, and fish balls from the menu when you sit down. Once they bring everything to you, you then will have the choice to pick from the conveyor belt going around the restaurant. The prices are expensive but it is a treat for once in a while type of meal. Also the wait times can be very long so be prepared.

text: Sampan is definitely one of those places you may want to consider visiting when you're on a culinary adventure in Philly. The cool, dark and edgy ambience stands out compared to regular Asian fusion restaurants (it kinds of reminds you of Mission in NYC or Morimoto which are on the higher end category -- so Sampan definitely deserves a five-star for even making the comparison). We ordered pork buns, general tso soup dumpling, kimchi fried rice and Sichuan chicken stir fry. The pork buns come with a twist -- it's very crispy outside (which is quite unusual for the pork in buns, although it feel a bit dry) but they definitely get points on this because the middle part of the pork was very tender! The soup dumplings were really good too. My favorite was definitely the kimchi fried rice because it was diverse in flavor that it tasted like a mix of Thai, Indonesian, Chinese and Korean fried rice -- a very inclusive fried rice! The Sichuan chicken stir fry was also very good -- it gave lots of veggies (which amazing)! Don't trust the server when he/she says it's spicy -- it's not -- as long as you don't accidentally bite the chili. Dessert was also nicely and fancily-plate and rightly priced and portioned (not too big). Our server was also very attentive and they have a coat check which is convenient. They also accommodated our shellfish allergies need. I would certainly come back here if I crave for clean-tasting, affordable, great ambience Asian fusion in Philly

text: Recommend coming to this spot for all you can eat hotpot! I eat a good amount of food when it comes to hotpot...so all you can eat is worth it for me. There's other spots in Chinatown that have hotpot but it's not all you can eat and it's pricey. They give you a piece of paper and you just order the amount of food that you want. Giving three stars because the beef that they gave us at one point was not fresh but all the other times it was good. Customer service was great, they come by with boiling water to fill up your pot when it starts to run low. Place is very clean and has TVs has well. They also have a station where you can make your own sauce. Definitely recommend coming for all you can eat. It's the best in Chinatown in my opinion.

text: I love Reading Terminal, it's obviously a Philly classic and everyone needs to go at least once. (Just make sure you're able to handle tight spaces and crowds!) There is so much to look at and eat, you almost don't know where to start. I also think it's kind of charming how easy it is to get lost, it adds to the character, that's for sure! I definitely want the tradition to be preserved, but it would be great to strike a balance between the historic authenticity and more contemporary innovative food options. You're surrounded by animal products there, and I think it could be awesome to update some more for the growing plant-based population. I think there might be one vegan stand occasionally but that's all I've seen so far. You can find vegan options, but it's not as easy as it could be with a few alterations or new vendors. That said, there are terrific whole food options for good prices at Iovine's and OK Produce!

text:
I remember this location when it was King's Palace.  Ping Pong is just as good as King's Palace was, maybe even a tad better.

Although it was a bit jarring seeing the area which used to be the sushi bar boarded up.  

The quality of the food is top notch - better than many places in Chinatown!  And the price is just right, too.  

I had my usual soup, spring roll, and chicken and none of it was greasy.  The portions were perfect and had a nice presentation.

Comes highly recommended!!!

text: Brought a group of 23 high school students here for lunch one day and dinner the next. What an amazing place. There is literally something for everyone. Ethnic food galore and something for any food allergy. Tons of food and drink options and so many privately owned restaurants with specialty homemade food items.  During busier times, seating gets very limited and lines can get pretty long but it's worth the wait. Some of the prices are inflated but it's what you'd expect for a prime tourist attraction, staple of Philly history and so many (not all) homemade food items.  Perfect place to bring a large group or a solo meal. I will definately be back!!

text:
I came here with my friend on a Tuesday evening around 6pm and we were seated right away. There's quite a bit of seating, and the restaurant is clean and nicely decorated.

I ordered the Vegetarian General Tao's Chicken which had a bit of a kick to it and was delicious. I thought it was a little pricey, but the portion was large enough for me to take leftovers home. My friend had the Pork and Egg Congee with Mushrooms and really enjoyed it. 

Service was fast and the food was tasty. I would definitely return to Sang Kee!

text: I've been to Chima many times but this was by far the worst visit. My fiancé and I were there on Saturday at 5:00. The rodizio service was super slow & when they did come around we were told multiple times that they didn't have the steak at the temperature that we wanted. My fiancé asked for more mashed potatoes & those never got to our table. I feel like we barely got any food. I ordered the coconut lava cake, I was told 10 minutes. We waited well over 20 for it to come out. I don't understand why it took so long because when it finally got to me it wasn't hot....it was barely warm. For the price this definitely was NOT worth it. The service gets worse and worse every time I come back here and it's a shame because my fiancé and I used to love this place.

text:
Overall Value: Strong flavors, quality, and decent portion sizes (eh, probably could be bigger) make up for the slight upcharge over the hole-in-the-wall places that we typically prefer.  

The Food:  We ended up getting a feast.  We ordered the scallion pancake ($3.95) and beef tendons in chili oil ($9.95) for appetizers.  The scallion pancake was fairly standard and unremarkable.  The beef tendons in chili oil - my wife was quite proud of how far I've come in terms of openness to different food (I'm at "level 2 ordering") - were really good. 
 They are super thin with a little chew, and really soak up the chili oil to make for a fairly spicy dish (it was the spiciest dish we had, although it is not going to come close to the actual spice levels we had in China).  

For entrees, we ordered the dry pot style with pork entree ($15.95) and the crispy rice style with chicken entree ($14.95), as well as the bok choy with black mushrooms ($12.95).  The dry pot style was the star of the show - really bold flavors, and the pork was very tender.  We kept the spice level at 10, which really ended up being only a medium spice level.  But still excellent flavor, and the mini wok it is served in is great presentation (and keeps the dish warm).  The crispy rice style is always fun to eat because the rice has a nice chew to it, and can really soak up the sauce.  It was slightly too sweet for my liking, but the chicken was also very tender and the dish complemented the dry pot style pretty well.  The bok choy with black mushrooms is also a bit of a sweeter dish, but it was cooked well and the mushrooms were plump with great flavor.  We also ended up getting a free cumin style with tofu entree by accident, which ended up being a freebie (who am I to say no?).  The tofu was a bit too dry, but great strong cumin flavor on the dish (and I'm not complaining because we were not charged).  

Service: We had to wait 5 minutes for a table, which made no sense because there were a ton of tables open.  But once we got seated, our server was great.  He also was really nice to box up the leftovers for us (and even threw in some extra rice).  Overall very good service.

Space and pace: Huge interior with really tasteful decor.  It was mostly filled with students (no shock, given the location) but I think it is also a fine place to bring a date or family.  Definitely on the list of places for when my mother-in-law visits.

text: Went during happy hour on a weekday. Apparently, you can't use the yelp coupon with the happy hour deal. There was only 1 other table being served and it took forever for them to get us the beef. We told the waitress and she finally brought out the beef. It took about 30 minutes and we didn't even order much(1 order of soup, 2 orders of udon and 2 orders of beef). There was a short piece of hair on one of the meatballs when I went to put it in the soup. My hair is long so it definitely wasn't mine. I didn't wanna make it a big deal because I was tired and they were taking too long with our order. I would rather do all you can eat hotpot at shabu shabu because you get a lot more variety. The prices are pretty expensive here. Conveyer belt is a cool concept though but I've had it in Japan and it was a better experience over there.

text:
So this place has been in construction for the a while and opened late last year and finally decided to make a visit to try. My visit resonated all the other reviews. The ingredients were fresh, tasty and is definitely a higher grade above typical hot pot places. The environment is nice cause it doesn't leave you smelling like food like other places and the individual hot pots are nice. However, the prices do add up after making sure everyone was filled and we spent about $60/per person before tips. I didnt care for the fact that they charge you for a soup base even with higher menu prices. The waiter said the combo feeds about 2-3 people, which i dont think is accurate unless you order everyone one of the combos, which we did (and more). Highlights were the beef and seafood combo, which gave you nice quality items, but definitely not too filling. The homemade noodles are delicious also. The rainbow dumplings are definitely very lack luster as i dont think there were any real soup when biting into them, plus you have to put them in the hot pot to cook, which i expected like a regular soup dumpling. 

Overall, its a good place to try for the beef and fresher ingredients, but i'll probably go to another hot pot place in the future.

text:
Chubby Cattle was my first experience at a hot pot and I have to say it couldn't have been better. Wait time wasn't long at all for it being a Saturday night- half an hour which with the texting system they have worked out great as we were able to go into a few shops without fear of missing our table. 

The restaurant itself has great decor that feels really clean and new, and the delicious smell of the food when you walk in makes you want to stay to find out how good it tastes. I have to admit at first it was a little intimidating how wide a selection their menu is, especially having no prior experience at a hot pot, but our server, Zoey, couldn't have been more helpful. She explained everything, down to what items are most popular and how we'll actually cook the food. 

We all ordered the same soup base, the tomato oxtail soup, so I can't attest for the other bases but the oxtail was amazing and paired with everything we got perfectly. I highly recommend first timers trying it. 

Next was the meat which was what I looked forward to the most. We ordered cod, the A5 wagyu, chicken, and lamb. The presentation on everything was amazing and unique, with every plate looking tailored specifically to that food item. We also ordered the vegetable combo, pasta combo, and a side of mushrooms and bamboo shoots. Everything came out fresh and ready to cook. 

We didn't wait very long at all for our food and every item was explained in detail how long to prepare. I was amazed at the quality of the meat, and everything tasted amazing. The vegetables in particular were so good paired with the oxtail broth. 

I've never had such a good experience with a restaurant before, it was so cool to cook your own food and it's a meal I'll be craving again soon. Of course, the food is a bit more pricey than other places in the area, but the quality, atmosphere, and experience is worth it. If you've been meaning to try a hot pot place this is the one I'd recommend! I'll definitely be visiting again soon.

text:
Benefit for the Market: this is an annual event to benefit this wonderful Philadelphia tradition. Although pricey, the food is amazing (don't eat for like 3 days before) and the drinks plentiful. As this has progressed, they have gotten wiser to having more water and seltzer on hand - smart. So the evening; the libations: good with a superior assortment of beers, sad assortment of wind and even a coffee roaster....noice!

Music: jazz and cool not too loud
Dancing: till late and amazing
Food: wonderful

Bottom line: maybe not an every year thing but certainly worth a 'go'

text: If you love Chinese food and grew up eating it as a city kid like me then I think you will definitely find some things you like. I have had some hits and misses when it comes to this place but overall its good and you might find a favorite. The place is really clean which is definitely a plus for this area. The general tso's is really good not that cheap weird orange color you usually see and with big chunks of fresh chicken probably my favorite so far. I'm not  fan of the fried rice it taste really healthy if you know what I mean, they put peas and carrots in the fried rice and it doesn't have a lot of flavor to it like it just steamed and not fried which is unfortunate cuz good chinese always needs a good fried rice. Beef and broccoli was good the quality of meat looks and taste like actual beef, not that weird gelatinous meat from the corner store. The chicken wings are ok they use a thick coating which taste like some kind of batter is on it, its not bad just different. The lomein is really good sticky noodles with a good sauce on it although they put in a really small bowl for pint, not the large white containers like I'm use to. This place is worth the try because they use high quality ingredients and give great service, so although there things that could be better this place is clean, the food is cleaner and taste pretty good and the prices are very reasonable so that's a plus. So far this place has replaced my usual corner store chinese.

text:
Bai Wei is not my cup of tea. We stepped in the restaurant and before anything else was said, some teenager abruptly said to us "cash and Venmo only". We already knew that from the paper sign scotch taped to the front door.

Service was slow and seemed more interested in flirting with young female customers than serving food. When we sat down some guy came over to us and said "hello" unenthusiastically. He didn't say anything else. We said hi back and it was a little awkward until my girlfriend said we would like some water. 

We ordered dim sum and scallion pancakes that were recommended by the server. Dim sum is supposed to be ready to go when you order it but we waited like twenty minutes for it. They brought out what appeared to be Worcester sauce and ginger immediately but nothing else for a while. The food was just okay. The pancakes were pretty greasy and not very good. Dim sum was really hot but at least it wasn't bad. The menu was pretty expensive for what it was. Entrees priced around $16. If they were as good as everything else, definitely not worth the money.

It got pretty crowded and loud so we paid and left. I wouldn't go back here unless I was really really hungry and there was nothing else open.

text:
I could not write other review on open table due to me not making other reservation so I will write one on here . On Jan 9 2019 I had a big party of 10 people at Sampan for my boyfriends 30th birthday party . Here is the review I left on open table the next day : 

I had a reservation for 7:30pm, however, we weren't seated until 8:15/8:20pm. To me, it's unacceptable. The reservation was for 10 people, and we were sat in a booth which was barely giving us enough elbow room. Mind you, there was an empty table right next to us that was eventually offered to us to spread out- but at the end of our dining experience. The whole evening felt unorganized and lacked professionalism. I have dined here many times and have thoroughly enjoyed myself. Last night was quite the opposite: dishes were mixed up, orders weren't correct, and we were all squished. I don't typically write reviews, but I was celebrating something special, and my evening felt quite the opposite.

So after this was done a manger called my phone left a voicemail stating they saw my review on open table and they would love to speak to me about what had happened . I called the same day and stop to a gentleman explained everything to him . His exact words I am so sorry this happened you and your boyfriend can come in any day just please make a reservation and we will give you a complimentary dinner . So I do not live close to Sampan but my boyfriend loves it when we are in the city so I decided to call yesterday to see if I could set something up for the weekend . I called one at 2:45 spoke to a woman Amanda she transferred me to the restaurant and they keep me on hold for about 5 min and explained to me that management was on a team meeting before the restaurant open and they would call me back, no one called back . I called again at about 4:20 and same female picked up Amanda and she told me they would call me back because they are busy due to serving but I called at 2:45 so that this wouldn't  happened they had a whole hour to call me back and also I explained to them that I just wanted to make sure I was staying around the city because remember I don't live around here , she seemed like she could careless . Not one person called me back yesterday ! I am very very disappointed !!!! I wasn't trying to get a free meal I was inquiring about something that was spoken have and that they told me was promised to me . Very bad professionalism and also customer service ! 

Sad because I really loved this placed but probably would never eat here ever again due to them just neglecting to call back a value customer .

text: Tried LaTao this week for my friend's birthday. I just want to say off the bad, I am not a Chinese food connoisseur. I walked into the dining section and was impressed with the look and ambiance. It was not busy at all, only one table taken. I decided against trying the Hotpot, due to the price, $23.95 per person and went for an entree instead. I ordered sesame chicken. The portion was good, but was only given a small bowl of rice. I ordered brown rice and when I started to eat it, realized parts of it were crunchy. The sesame chicken had good flavor, but was not crunchy, which is how I prefer it. In my opinion, was not worth $13. I was wishing I was somewhere else where I could get a platter and drink for $6 lunch special. I will not be back, because the prices are high and I was not impressed, but I cannot speak on the quality of the hotpot.

second crab and pork soup dumplings , no juice! No soup too paper thin upon picking them up they

text:
When you first walk into this restaurant, the greeters n waiters were so friendly and right away we got a seat. The whole concept of conveyor belt with food on it is fun and we just watch the food go around and around. But on there is mostly veggies. The soup base was good with strong beef broth. N if u come during happy hrs, they just left the stuff on there without adding new stuff til the happy hr ends. Between me n my friend, we order enough food that we had decent amount of leftover to bring home. But the price still came out to be $45 a person with tips. I would say it is quite pricy for hotpot. 

Food wise, the beef is pretty good but have a lot of fat. I love the lamb shank. Broth is strong n smooth. The beef screwer is so small n tiny n sad n expensive!!!!! Oh, n super salty too. Price wise is pretty expensive too. I won't say that I have to come back but the experience was quit different.

text:
You can really never go wrong with Reading Terminal.  A particularly favorable option if you have a group of people with different palettes - there's something for everyone! My most recent try was Becks Cajun kitchen, which was pretty good (a little overpriced) - but other favorites include Keven Parker's Soul Food Cafe and Beilers Doughnuts. I'm not sure of what healthy/vegetarian/vegan food options are available - there seems to be a lot of fast/gluttonous food. To me, produce is overpriced too, but a convenient offering of fresh fruits & veggies for those living in the city. 

It can be overwhelming, especially if you're a bit indecisive and on an empty stomach. For that reason, if possible, I would avoid peak lunch hours because of the heavy crowds. 

It seems like they're constantly under construction here. The building is historic, but it's nice to see some updating  taking place where necessary and improvement of the facilities (bathrooms, ect...) Park at the garage across the street next to Panera and get your ticket validated!

text:
It's really rather unfortunate that I found this place on my first trip to Philadelphia. I don't want to explore any other restaurant. This place is perfect! The decor is very urban Asian and very clean. The kitchen looks like a walk up food shack. Maybe I'm describing that wrong. It looks cute anyway. I came at 6 PM on a Monday evening and it was not busy at all. As soon as I sat down I was brought a pot of hot tea. I don't usually drink tea, but I loved it today! It was a perfect contrast to the chilly evening.
I started with the Roti Telur. I'm an amateur bodybuilder, but I thought the portion size was actually large enough for myself and another person, and I am telling you that I NEVER say that. It was such a good value. I got the basil chicken for my meal and once again it was large enough for 2 people. I thought the price suited it well. There was more than enough meat to satisfy my diet which can make eating out tricky for me sometimes. It's so easy to make healthy choices at restaurants like this. Roti Telur? It's basically little healthy breadsticks, but like, made of egg and onion.

text:
Han Dynasty is the sorta old reliable of accessible Sichuan Chinese fare in Philadelphia.  It's frequently delicious, mildly adventurous and easy for groups big and small.  I've returned several times to both this and the Old City location.

The Good:

Delicious Sichuan food with the right amount of spice for anyone (you pick on a scale of 1-10).  The Dan Dan noodles are a personal favorite (any every one else agrees), the Bok Choi is a great add on and I have yet to dislike any entree.

The service is pretty standard.  As I like to say, if you didn't notice it was bad, then it was good.  Also, the food comes somewhere between an ideal pace and fast.  

The Old City location is a bit more enjoyable ambiance than the U City one.  Things are dim, but the decorations and furnishings are nice.  It's slightly less accommodating to large groups, but YMMV.  

I think the prices are pretty reasonable.  Entrees range from 15-20 dollars but are meant for more than one person.  It's hard to say if it's a good deal, but the food is still excellent.

The Bad:

One issue I find is that it's hard to push the issue on spiciness.  I've grown to really enjoy some heat and it's hard to get servers to really let the chef kick it up a notch.  

The other issue is that I often don't feel super great the next day after eating.  Maybe that's the spices or my amateur palate or the several cocktails I had.  

Conclusion:  I return because it's reliable and delicious.  I will continue to return.  Just keep a bottle of pepto in your cabinet.

text:
I was so thrilled to see this place open up in Chinatown - I absolutely love hot pot, it's one of my favorite eating styles and comfort foods to get during cold winter days.  The conveyor belt aspect really intrigued me.  I love being able to get a variety of ingredients, but often times with hot pot you can only order maybe up to 3-4 ingredients plus your meat option because they tend to be generous portions and you get full.  At Chubby Cattle, not only do they have wagyu beef options which is unique, but the conveyor belt portions are so much smaller.  This might be a weird thing to say about a restaurant, but smaller portions means more room for more things.  The plates that the ingredients are rotating on are color coded to indicate their price (which is shown on the side of your table) and they're all pretty cheap.  You can rack up a TON of plates and still not run up a huge tab.
The wait staff is really friendly and super helpful - I had no idea what I was doing with ordering and the conveyor belt and they all were there to answer questions promptly and thoroughly.
I got the oxtail tomato broth and my partner got the tonkotsu miso.  I absolutely adored my broth - I think it might be my favorite non-spicy broth option, it was so incredibly savory and the tomato flavor also rounded it out nicely.
The interior is pretty spacious, and this would be a great option for taking guests who have never done hot pot too (especially again because everything is portioned smaller, if you don't like a hot pot ingredient, you can get rid of it fast!).  You do low key have to know though what is what - they are price labelled, but not labelled with what they are (though most are easy to figure out). You can also still order off the menu if you don't see anything you want coming down the belt.
I wish they had a more extensive sauce bar, like LaTao hot pot (my #1 spot) but their sauce options aren't too bad! 
Also, I would recommend just sticking to the hot pot - we decided to splurge a little and get wagyu foie gras nigiri and it was good but not amazing and probably not worth its price - learn from my mistake.

text:
Mapo tofu noodles at Dim Sum Garden, Philadelphia.

The tofu was incredibly tender and the seasoning was phenomenal. Also, the house made noodles were cooked perfectly and definitely had a pleasantly unique bite that added dimension to the dish. They serve a large-sized portion for the price, so that's always nice. 

Cons: Line was long (took over 20 minutes standing on line since they do not have a waitlist and do not take reservations), and it was crowded. 

Despite that, I definitely plan to return soon!

text:
Fantastic experience!! 

I am NOT a spice person and this place is known for its spicy cuisine. I had help from our great waiter to pick items that weren't too spicy and I was golden so know that if you don't do spicy you can still go here! And you should!!! They give their items a rating from 1-10 for spiciness, 10 being the most spicy. I would suggest if you can't handle spice definitely stick to anything less than a 3! 

Highly suggest getting a reservation if you can. This place is always packed and always a wait. We had a reservation for three people and were seated immediately. 

Served family style but can get individual meals- but everything is large portions and greatly priced. Great bang for your buck. All of the food comes out when it's ready so you just kind of wait and anticipate things to come out whenever it's ready. 

Amazing experience. Definitely go! And whatever you get, make sure one of the items is the pork buns!

text:
Hand drawn noodles were perfect-great texture! We had the soup with shrimp and with beef tendon. The house was definitely not skimpy with either of the proteins. Lots of shrimp and tendon in the broth. I think the tendon may have gone through a pressure cooker, there was really no bite to it. The broth could have used a little more something, but we were happy after adding some hot oil. 

They have supplies of soup spoons, chopsticks and napkins available at each table, along with hot oil, sriracha and other condiments. Unlike Spice C around the corner though, they don't have pickled veggies on the table. I actually didn't mind that, as the ones served here tasted fresher than the ones that sit out on the tables at Spice C. 

The interior is clean, bright and spacious, with generous aisle space. 

Service was fast and efficient, the usual for Chinatown and the prices are very reasonable.

I won't be a stranger when I have a taste for delicious hand drawn noodles.

text: All hail happy hour! Lol They have a happy hour everyday from 4-7pm. Food and drink prices range from $3-$10. I feel like you can't beat that! The ambiance and decor is very nice. If you had a long day of work and need cheap food and drinks, Sampan is the place for you!

text: I came here with a friend on a weekday around 4pm and the restaurant was not busy at all. We were the only table dining so it was overall pretty quiet. We ordered the Singapore noodles, the salt and pepper pork chop with black bean sauce, and bitter melon with spare ribs. The Singapore noodles were pretty bland and even an addition of siracha did not help. The salt and pepper pork chop was good, but not worth the price you pay. They were pretty thin and it only came with 2 pork chops. As for the bitter melon dish, it was good and there was a lot of spare ribs. Overall, the food was average and I was not impressed.

text:
Offering Szechuan Chinese dishes in Center City Philadelphia, Jane G's fills a niche of authentic Chinese food in a highly convenient location. While it's difficult to compete with the cheap and delicious Chinese restaurants just a couple streets down in Chinatown, Jane G's is a classy Chinese establishment in Philadelphia and offers an average dining experience at a moderate price. The interior is pretty as well, with plenty of space and tables in an ornate set-up, so definitely great for formal occasions or just the quick dinner take-out as well.

From my visits, I have found the food to be just average, notwithstanding the huge assortment of similar restaurants nearby in Chinatown. From the Dan Dan noodles to its Peking duck dishes, the food is alright, but I left wanting more in both portion sizes and taste. The Dan Dan noodles were decently tasty, but just a little bit on the salty side, and can't beat the noodles at the aptly named Dan Dan Noodles restaurant just a couple blocks away in Center City. Most of the main dishes are just lacking in taste and aroma, not packing the punch that I was looking for from a Szechuan restaurant, but I do like the Chili Oil Wontons... definitely my favorite dish and appetizer whenever I come here.

The interior is quite intricate and visually appealing, with the perfect lighting combination at dinner--not too dark nor too light, perfect for the special occasion or even a formal business meeting--and suits the crowd at the towering buildings of the financial district of Philly. Its location is a bit out of the way, about halfway between 30th Street Station and Suburban Station, unless of course you work in one of the JFK blvd buildings, in which case its location is perfect. For the moderate prices and just average food, I wouldn't recommend Jane G's to the foodies of Philadelphia, but it's a great meeting-place otherwise if you care more for the ambiance.

text: Decent Chinese food and pretty wide selection. I'm glad they have beef noodle soup, but I was disappointed at the texture and consistency of the noodles. They were overcooked and too soggy. The beef was fantastic and so was the broth, but the noodles are supposed to be much chewier and less mushy. Prices are decent, but they only take a maximum of 3 credit cards per table! The food came out pretty quickly and the wait was not bad at all. There is, however, only one bathroom so it is pretty much always occupied. Overall, okay place for quick Chinese food, but this place lacks authenticity and quality.

text: Unpleasant experience! 领位员不太友善，态度snooty，全称英文（找个会中文的不是更好吗），不让把外面的食物带进去，我的奶茶早已经喝完了还非要让我把奶茶杯交出来扔掉才让我进去！我真的不理解。酱料给得太少，菜量也很少，没吃出比别家的牛肉好到哪里去，很不值得！和牛拌饭很咸，说实话还不如吉野家好吃。不愉快的体验！The flavor is OK. I love their tomato beef flavor pot. BUT the waiters, especially the girl at the front desk 领位员, is kinda snooty and don't treat clients in a nice attitude. Besides, they only provide limited amount of sauce contained in their small bowls that would be taken away after you scoop the sauce out. The quantity of the dish is also too little. And the price is more expensive than other hotpot places in Philly, the food and service don't worth the price! I will never come here again.

text:
I really really really like this place! 

Atmosphere and service: the inside is very nice with a semi chic vibe. It wasn't too loud either. I can't wait until it's warm enough for them to open the doors to let the sun and breeze in!! Our waitress was a young, friendly girl who explained everything on the menu and was just very nice. Other staff would also check on us- we were there for a while lol. The prices were pretty low too! 

Food: literally so good! We had the Brussels sprouts, wasabi shrimp, pancakes and chicken and broccoli and it was all delicious! I just want to order everything because I just know it will be good. Be aware, there are spice levels that they allow you to choose from. If you can't take the heat stick to a 1! 

Drinks: the drinks are ok nothing special, the house wine did give me a headache so I will be avoiding that. 

I can't wait to go back!

text: I got delivery and I was surprised by how hot the food was. General Taos, Shrimp lo mein, Scallion pancakes, and chili wontons. All of them were steaming hot as if they were just being served to me from the kitchen so I was super impressed, The portion sizes are also adequate for the price you pay. I definitely wished they allowed you to choose what kind of rice they gave you as well as included chop sticks in their delivery bag. Over all if I'm in the neighborhood again I would definitely order!

text:
Needless to say, this place is absolutely the best dim sum place in the whole Chinatown!
The most important thing is you get what you see so there's no messing around with confusion!
The foods are always fresh since they do sell a lot of them during the day!
The wait time are usually tolerable(within 45mins)!unless there are event going on( like Chinese New Year parade) 
Crystal shrimp dumplings are the best in town as well!
My go to place for dim sum in the area!The foods are also very affordable with great quality! Great for groups
P.s.  If you are looking for an Americanized dimsum place you should go somewhere else. Not all the best but authenticity guaranteed!

text:
One of my favorites restaurants in the city.  I've eaten here twice now.  The first time we didn't have reservations so we found a spot at the bar and ate.  The bar tender was knowledgeable regarding the food and the selection of Sake.  Their house sake is reasonably priced and quite good. 

All of the dumplings are wonderful but my favorite are the edamame dumplings.  The cauliflower appetizer is also something I recommend trying.  

The deserts were excellent as well.  Tell them it's your birthday and it'll come with a sparkler.  The ambiance was wonderful.

Last, we ate there on a colder windy day.  It was quite drafty and even with the external door cover the wind was apparent.  But none of that was enough to detract from the excellent experience.

text:
Their food is pretty good... We ordered duck, a stir fry and some other dishes. No one in our party seemed to complain about anything, and I personally thought they had some good flavors going on in each dish, but it is a little below par compared to restaurants around the Chinatown area.

The thing I am concerned about however is the overall price. Their food is moderately pricey, since the food prices are the same if not more expensive than the other local restaurants. But, my true concern was that they charge tax. Other restaurants around the area don't do this at all (at least according to my observations). They also don't have a lot of variety since they were missing some dishes that we really would have liked. 

Service is quick and prompt (even threw in an extra fried dough stick) and the overall experience was not bad. Would I come here again? Probably not, unless my favorite restaurants close up shop in the near future.

text:
A small shop full of authentic Asian breakfast and lunch goodies! I tried their buns, Chinese 'tamales', sweet tofu, savory tofu, and fried dough - all for under $15!

My favorite was the Chinese tamales wrapped in bamboo leaves, there are multiple flavors so you can find one that suits your taste. Their tofu was soft and silky, clearly homemade. Everything truly reminded me of how it would taste in Asia.

Highly recommended for an authentic experience for an affordable price!

text:
Iam beyond upset. My favorite sushi restaurant for the last 7 years.  
Had dinner here for my birthday the last 5 years. In a year: monthly dinners with girlfriends, my parents' anniversary, my sister's bachelorette dinner. 
Today for my birthday, 14 adults & 6 kids. Made a reservation last week & confirmed Friday. I asked if I can bring pizza & fries for kids. Over the phone they said ok, even put me on hold to speak with the manager. 

When we arrived today, lady behind the desk (same person I spoke over the phone twice) was beyond rude. 
She said: too much food, we are taking a table for kids that other costumers could use. We were there 1pm, we were the only one in the restaurant. We left 2:15pm, there were 2 other couples in the restaurant. 

My guests felt not welcomed & not comfortable. 
I spent $270  in a little over an hour. 
Iam going to miss always great food & amazing waitresses!

text: Discovered a great Chinese food truck near Penn! It's in the alleyway right behind pottruck the gym and I was actually quite surprised at how good this was! I ordered sesame chicken and it was $5.50. The price isn't too bad and the chicken was very meaty and didn't have too much coating on it. Some places don't give that much chicken but this food truck gave a lot of chicken and the balance was good with the steamed broccoli. There wasn't much of a line so I waited for only about 10 minutes to get my food. Very delicious Chinese food and highly recommend !

text:
Wow! Night and day. My first review has been overshadowed and I feel chubby cattle is due for and deserving of a re-appraisal.

Went back for lunch today and was immediately seated. Nice surprise and a bit different than the hour and a half wait last time.

Very attentive servers who kept checking back and charming were so much better than our waiter the first time as well. 

A5 wagyu sashimi with good wasabi and soy was available this time and very nice. 

The tomato oxtail broth is fantastic. As before the Yuzu and toppings on point. 

I have to say, although expensive, this is so much better than other hot pot establishments that I've had that it's worth it if you can afford it.

Usually the broth is just a cooking medium at other places. Here, after finishing my meats and vegetables I find myself drinking the broth as well because it's so good. Even before departing, one last sip of the broth...yum...So nice how all of the meats and vegetables permeate the broth after cooking and topped off with that delicious sauce I could just drink the stuff all day.

Damn you chubby cattle, you have ruined cheap hard pot for me! I'm going to find it difficult to enjoy the affordable all-you-can-eat hot pot i used to crave. 

Well done.

text:
I've been here many times in the past 7 years and came again for lunch with my family on Friday. It's pretty empty during lunch, which is probably why they didn't take a reservation. 

Atmosphere: Venue is beautiful, but people kind off dress however they see best. Business casual is fine, but jeans and a t-shirt is also more than fine. Go with small parties or big, they will accommodate you. Make a reservation for dinner, especially if your party is on the larger side. 

Food:  Delicious as always. For 6 people we ordered, scallion pancakes, 2 orders of Dan Dan noodles, cumin-style tofu, and garlic sauce - style tofu. We also ordered a side of the dan-dan noodle sauce on the side with chili oil on the side. Everything was delicious and comes out made to order (when it's ready, they send it out). 

Drinks: I've had the Empress drink before, and it was really good! Otherwise I just get water with lemon.

Service: Great service, quick, efficient, WELL PRICED!

Pro tip: portions are huge, so maybe start with fewer things and order more as you need.

Pro tip #2: adjust spice levels to what you want! You can also just ask for the chili oil and do it yourself as needed.

Pro tip #3: make a dinner reservation

text:
Like most dim sum spots, Tom's first had me at dumplings! But as the spot that moved into the original Dim Sum Garden location has become a more regular destination I've grown fond of it for dim sum staples at a reasonable price, tons of spice, and other such perks.

In addition to being one of the top dim sum spots in Chinatown, Tom's also makes for the perfect last minute BYOB spot that requires minimal planning. For just a minimal corking fee your table of 2-4 can sit down to a couple bottles, and enjoy all the dumplings, steamed buns, noodles, and more.

Some of my favorites and must haves include:

Steamed Crab Meat Pork Soup Dumplings - can't decide between having bits of pork or king crab ooze out of your supple & warm soup dumplings? Go with both for maximum flavor!

Crystal Shrimp Dumplings - the perfect combo of tender cooked shrimp and just a little bit of a spicy cook.

HK Style Shumai - Amazing bits of sausage wrapped in dumpling skin. What's not to like?

Scallion Pancake - a simple dim sum classic done right!

Roast Pork Buns - bao style buns with perfectly cooked pork sandwiched inside.

8 Delicacies Hot Sauce Noodle - If your looking for a perfect dish of spiciness, this one is at its peak.

Like most perfect Dim Sum destinations, Tom's is perfect with a group. So bring friends and enjoy. Just save a table for me!

text:
We started with drinks, cheesesteak bao buns, pork soup dumplings, and the crunchy lamb rolls. Everything was great. They carry a rotating Tired Hands beer. This time it was Alien Church. 

They have a $7 cocktail during happy hour. I think it's off-the-menu and special for each day. The rest of them are around the average price for the city. 

The cheesesteak bao buns are the best "cheesesteak" I've ever had in Philadelphia. The cheese and meat are mixed together, and there's a small hint of long hots in there, but it's not hot. They are $3.50 each during happy hour (reg. 2 for $9).

The pork soup dumplings were great. You get 4 for $7. Our waitress even explained how they are best eaten (with a bite out of the top to let the broth cool, then eating the rest). The crunchy lamb rolls were great. The chimichurri complemented the rolls, and all the flavors were balanced except for the cumin.

The duck wonton noodle soup was great, but there was something off about the egg noodles. They tasted store-bought and felt out of place with the quality of the other ingredients. The chicken dumplings, duck broth, and duck meat were all great.

text:
I have introduced many friends here of all different cultural backgrounds, and EVERY single person loves this place.

They give you complementary snacks while waiting for food to arrive if dining in (pickled vegetables and Chinese style salted peanuts). 

The food came out pretty fast and also freshly made, which is very surprising.

Dishes to try:
-Chong Qing spicy chicken ( a bit pricey than usual but with it). Side note: pretty large portion dining in but take out they seem to give a little less :(
-scallion pancakes
-cumin lamb or beef
-best hot and sour soup in philly Chinatown
-Dry hotpot 

Service is great and attentive. When ordering takeout it is pretty fast!

My traditional Chinese parents approve of this place and so does a diverse culture of friends I have introduced here!

Must try!

text:
Dump-N-Roll is a food truck that gets its name from what it serves: dumplings and spring rolls. It's a roaming food truck that doesn't have a specific location, but participates in a lot of weekly food truck events in and outside the city. This month, you can find them in LOVE Park every Wednesday during the Lunch in LOVE program.

Now I'm no expert on dumplings or spring rolls, but I've never had a bad experience with either. They have a lot of different options on their menu to choose from, all of which include a description to let you know what you're getting. I wasn't sure what to get at first but when I saw their Sample Platter, which includes serving options for one or two people, I figured this would be a good place to start. At $14.00, it might seem a little pricey to some, but the amount of food you're served more than makes up for it. I placed my order and was served after about five minutes or so.

When sat down to eat and opened the box, I couldn't believe how much food there was! I mean I knew it was a sampler, but I never expected this much! I got six dumplings in total: three of the Infamous "Piggy" and three of the Veggies in Heaven. The Infamous "Piggy" contains pork and chives (hence the name), and the Veggies in Heaven is a combination of seasonal veggies, glass noodles, and exotic mushrooms. In addition to the dumplings, I got the original spring roll and a side of truffle fries. The dumplings were perfect. Soft enough that they melt in your mouth, but just crispy enough on the outside. The truffle fries were some of the best I've ever had, and appear to be a favorite among guests. You're also given access to as much soy sauce as you want, which is a great addition to the dumplings and spring rolls.

Dump-N-Roll has a few other dumplings and spring rolls on their menu in addition to the ones I got with my order. There's the Chick-A-Palooza, which consists of chicken, veggies, and spices, and a specialty dumpling called the Holy Phuc Wonton. The description for the Holy Phuc Wonton reads "award-winning tempura turkey bacon cheese burger wonton". I haven't tried it yet, but that sounds awesome right off the bat. They also have a spring roll called the Ooey-Gooey Mac, which is a spring roll stuffed with mac and cheese.

Like I said earlier, Dump-N-Roll can be found in LOVE Park every Wednesday of this month from 11:00am to 3:00pm. Next Month, they'll be spending their Wednesdays at the Porch at 30th Street Station. They participate in a lot of other food truck events in the area and even offer catering services for private events. The best way to keep track of their whereabouts is through their website, which has a listing of all the events they'll be participating in over the next few months.

If you're a fan of dumplings, spring rolls, or both, Dump-N-Roll is a food truck that you definitely need to check out. If it's your first time, I highly recommend the sampler to get a full taste of what they're all about and to try their one-of-a-kind truffle fries.

text:
I was surprised by the number of lower ratings for this place honestly. Good food, nice clean interior, and some unique dishes that I haven't seen at other chinese restaurants in the city. 

Menu is HUGE and a bit daunting with all of the rather unique ingredients (Intestines, fungus, feet, pig ears, etc etc). Nice pictures with everything that was relatively accurate to what we got. As others have said the smashed eggplant with preserved egg was excellent and very different. Also had the griddle cooked short ribs which were nice and spicy and cooked very well. We also got some on the hose edamame, pickled veggies, and green tea ice cream which was a nice touch. Service was good and one of the waiters very nicely explained to us how to mash the eggplant and egg ourselves to our desired flavor. 

Honestly, menu was almost TOO big and a bit confusing as to how it was organized which can make it hard for people not familiar with the cuisine to order. Had the cold chili chicken too which was very meh. 2/3 ain't bad though right? 

Will definitely be recommending this place to my more adventurous friends and will try to come back with someone that can guide me through the menu a bit more. Overall a good experience at a very decent price.

text:
I only give reviews for places that are really good or really bad.
This place is really good. My third or fourth time eating hear in the last couple years and I am impressed. Each time I had the drunken noodles.
Drunken noodles are a wide, flat rice noodle, similar to a lasagna noodle mixed with peppers, onions, and green beans in a very tasty sauce with chicken, beef, or shrimp. I get the chicken and it is excellent. I also had the won ton soup. You have a choice of chicken or pork. I had the pork. A generous serving and very tasty. Prices are very reasonable for a downtown restaurant. I will be back during my next visit to Philly.

text:
A very cute space, modern take on most Chinese / Sichuan joints. We came on a Sunday night around prime dinner time and we got seated right away. This place does fill up quick and has only one table for a larger party I believe. 

Prices were reasonable, especially compared to the places that serve the same type of food in NYC. We had dan dan noodles, tripe in chili oil, wontons in chili oil, and the sweet and sour ribeye pot. Portions were decent and filled four people up, although we didn't come starving, that might have changed things. Their chili oil definitely has a kick, and spice level was definitely high, but super flavorful. Get a bowl of rice with the tripe, it can be a meal instead of an appetizer. Really liked the glass noodles in the ribeye pot although I thought it wasn't enough. This dish also came on a plate and not a pot.. I saw pots with other dishes on other table, not sure if it's supposed to actually be in a pot or not. But this was probably the least spicy of the dishes we got that night, dan dan noodles coming next, the tripe was probably the spiciest because it was drenched in the chili oil.

text:
We had just returned from a trip to Singapore, and I was hoping to get close to the delicious Malaysian food we had on the trip. Penang didn't disappoint, and was, in fact, quite true to the style of Malaysian food we had on the trip. 

The chicken satay is absolutely perfect. Made is fatty chicken thighs, the skewers bore the signature sweetness from the dry rub that one expects from a good satay. The dipping sauce was just the right consistency and had the right amount of heat too. Highly recommend. 

For our main courses, we had the Chow Kueh Teow and the Nasi Lemak. The chow kueh teow tasted just like the version we had at the hawker stalls in Singapore, and I enjoyed the beef that was included in the nasi lemak. I'm looking forward to coming back to try more of the food. 

Another bright spot of the meal is that the food is very inexpensive. For the three dishes I mentioned, our tab was less than $30. Great value for the price. 

If I have minor critique it's that the service was a bit slow and a bit brusque. I don't mind, since I didn't have anywhere to be and I just wanted food (could take of leave the smile). But just something to consider if you are in a rush or only want to interact with someone with a perma-grin. 

Overall good experience and will definitely come back.

text:
This review is for the location in Ceasars Palace, Atlantic City. 

3 stars overall. Buddhakan is truly a beautiful restaurant, with excellent service, and some awesome dim sum. 

We ordered the sashimi, lamb dumplings, and calamari salad, Shrimp Lo Mein, and the Kung Pao Lobster. The sashimi and dumplings where definately show stoppers. The calamari was cooked perfectly, but the rest of the salad lacked something else to be desired, and was way too large. 

As for our entrees, the lo mein was passable, and the Lobster missed the mark for me.

For a 40$ value, it is a nice amount of lobster, but the sauce was very overwhelming. My favorite part of the dish was the fried claw meat (served without sauce) I ate the rest of it for lunch today and I felt like I was eating chicken nuggets drenched in sauce. The dish needs some work.

text:
Lovely place with nice decorations. The wait staffs were polite and friendly. I ordered the Hazelnut with mayonnaise shrimp, crabmeat and the spicy soup dumplings. The hazelnut mayonnaise shrimp was only a few shrimps about 7 shrimps in a typical honey glaze. It was very normal which cost me 18ish dollars. Very pricey for a normal tasting shrimp dish. 

The soup dumplings flavor was good especially the spicy ones. However the dumpling skin was not very good. It was doughy, not smooth, and easily to break. A few dumplings broke in tray that they came out of. 

If I ever have to come back here by forced, I will order the Spicy soup dumpling or some other dish to have my second thought. Other than that, I'm not coming back here.

text:
Four stars just for overall value.  Stopped in for a quick lunch, and for $8, I had a perfectly Americanized combo of sweet and sour chicken, white rice and a fried vegetable egg roll.  I liked that they did not pour the sauce over everything, so I could dip each chicken piece individually.  They had chunked up onions (whew, I could pick them off easily) and green peppers alongside the main dish. Service was fast, but expect minimal communication. Not a whole lot of love and laughter in this place - they want you in and out.

Conveniently located just steps away from the 9th / 10th and Locust PATCO stop.

The only downside to the experience was that on a chilly day, every time someone opened the door, the freezing cold air wafted in. A little curtain does nothing to protect the diners from the temperatures. Most of us who had to sit near the door wore our coats. Lesson learned - sit away from the front door if it's cold!

text:
Alright, alright, Reading, you got me. I'm upgrading you to a fifth star. Fortunately, my last two visits over the weekend resulted in a much smoother shopping and exploring experience than my last visit. It probably didn't help that the last time I visited it was over a holiday weekend. 

This round I made a bee-line to Miller's Twist to snag the world's best pretzel and from there I toured from vendor to vendor to soak in the fudge, fresh juices, deli meats, doughnuts, you name it. What incredibly tasty and buzzing lineup! I also really appreciated the dedicated produce section that offers a farmers market vibe and reasonable produce prices for locals. This market is great to find something for all types of food interests and allergies but not so much to find a spot to eat and enjoy your purchases. Seating is a hot commodity. Fun note: they do have great free wifi.

text:
Sampan is definitely a place to visit with a friend or two to catch up. Everything about the place is lovely but I would not recommend it for a big group. Firstly, they would not sit us until our entire group was there, which is understandable but also somewhat annoying when we had a reservation and we had to wait for 9 people to all arrive before we could be seated (2 of them ended up stuck in really bad Broad Street traffic). I really recommend making a reservation as it will get busy very quickly on popular days (Thurs-Sat). 

The interior is your typical modern asian-fusion style place with low lighting and loud environment from the mixture of almost clubby music and tables packed together. The decorations were very modern and interesting but nothing really wow-ing, which is understandable since we are there for the food, not the decorations. Waiters seem to be good at their jobs and pretty attentive while the hostesses seem very dismissive and anxious about how they are going to seat all the reservations they accepted. 

I had the Sampan version of the moscow mule and it was very good along with most of the other drinks I tried from friends. As for the food, we ended up doing the chefs selection which is $45 a head and it was all delicious. We got to chose about 8 different dishes and they brought them very quickly, almost too quickly as we barely had time to breath in-between bites. All of the selections we made were wonderful and I don't think they brought us out any food that we didn't scarf down. That being said, the bill was very expensive and we were not sure how if we didnt do the chefs selection and ordering just a few tapas would go for filling up 9 people. Everything we got from our selection included: Chicken Bao Bun (pretty good, kinda tasted like Chik-fil-a), Pork Potsticker (a crunchy and light potsticker), Korean BBQ Beef (one of the best in our opinion, very tender and flavorful), Crispy Rock Shrimp (pretty much your average battered rock shrimp), Szechuan Chicken Stir-fry (wish we could have ordered two of these because it was so delicious, we ate it all in about 2 minutes), Seafood Stir Fry (pretty good but wish it included more seafood, it was mainly scallops and shrimp), Kim Chee Fried Rice (your better-than-average fried rice), and finally the Shrimp Pad Thai (pretty average but its hard to deviate from a standard pad thai). 

All-in-all the food was delicious and the environment was cool and I would love to go back with one or two friends but would not come back with a large group as the price climbs quickly (even if you don't do the chefs selection) and the space is somewhat cramped and loud to really talk to everyone from your group.

text:
We were a party of 11 and we had to eat off of the price fixed menu.  There is also a separate menu for beverages.  Many in our party did not understand the beverage menu.  Apparently if you are drinking alcoholic beverages, you have 3 pricing options and it is all you can drink, I think.  However, it also states non-alcoholic beverages, so we assumed it was $30 for all you can drink iced-tea.  What was probably the most disappointing was that people drinking alcohol didn't know they had to ask for refills and didn't know that it was all you can drink, so many in our group ended up paying $30 for one beer.  And then if you are just drinking iced tea and coffee, there is no fee at all.  Before you go, you probably want to vet this out a little more and make sure all in your party understand how the beverages work.

We had menu #1.  I couldn't tell you what we ate because it all came out in waves and we didn't have a menu in front of us, we only had the confusing beverage menu.  Again, people in our party were confused about courses, so some people were eating a lot at first not realizing there was more food coming.  It didn't appear we received enough of each dish for 11 people.  We had steamed dumplings and we didn't know there were two trays stacked (it's so dark in there), so they got cold before we realized there were more in there.

Everything I had was very good.  Everything was warm enough (could have been warmer), everything was well seasoned and very flavorful.

Dessert seemed skimpy.  The hit were the home made donuts but, again, not enough for everyone at the table.  I'm not sure if we were allowed to ask for more.

Service was excellent, our table was ready when we arrived, but we could not sit down until our entire party arrived as we were all coming from different hotels.  We paid a $400 deposit, so I think it was clear we were good for the table and should have been allowed to be seated.

Bathrooms were clean and enough to accommodate the crowded place.

I would probably go back and order off the regular menu on a less busy night.
