text:
I must start off by saying that a few friends and I were drawn to come here purely because of the hype. We had heard countless students in University City hype this place up and tell us how great the Dan Dan Noodles and other menu items were.

We had made a reservation ahead of time, and we came in at the time of it and were seated promptly. Once we had placed our orders of 'Chicken Dumplings' and 'Dan Dan Noodles,' we waited to receive our food. Upon trying the 'Dan Dan Noodles ,' me and my 2 other friends were grossed out by the flavor. With a description of having peanut sauce, this seemed like something we were interested in. However, the noodles tasted more like straight peanut oil, and they left a very sticky residue on the tongue. 

Although it was kind of awkward, we were able to have our waited take them back, and take our new orders for us. Upon waiting for our new orders of 'Garlic Sauce Style' chicken, we were served our dumplings, which were mediocre at best. They tasted kind of like packaged ones that I buy at the grocery store.

A manager of some sort came up to us to ask about what we didn't like about the 'Dan Dan Noodles,' which I appreciated but also felt bad about.

Once our main dishes of 'Garlic Sauce Style' chicken came out, they were SO salty. I just felt like I was eating thin strips of chicken with so much salt and garlic. 

Although I came in with high expectations, I'm so sad to say that none of the food even lived up to average quality. I do feel bad saying this, because I know many fans of the restaurant. The customer service was also decent. 

Sorry, but due to the prices and quality of the food, I definitely wouldn't come again. From a huge fan of all types of Asian food, I was left nothing but disappointment.

text:
As my first hot experience (but with people who are very experienced), I was impressed with the quality of the food and taste. The restaurant has a fun, modern aura with the Japanese style conveyer belt running through the middle, brick/wood panel walls, and small booths with individual hot-pot stoves for each person. 

I got the House Hellish Spicy Broth at the Entry Spicy level, enough spice to get your attention but not too hot that you don't enjoy the meal (for those with a low spice tolerance beware, even at the lowest level it has a kick).

As a table we split the Beef combo (comes with wagyu brisket, angus prime rib eye, and Australian Short Rib) which is a great value and very good mix, along with Udon Noodle (nothing special), Glass Noodles (they were great but suggest holding it while you cook or you'll lose them in the pot), Sweet Corn (highly recommend, we ended up getting another order), and baby bok choi (solid). 

While the food was great, Chubby Cattle could improve on their service. Our waitress was friendly and had good recommendations at the beginning of the meal, she forgot our order of Fish Balls that we asked about 3 times, and had to end up cancelling because it never came by the end of the meal! We also had to ask for water refills and sauce refills, and they were a bit slow clearing the table once we had finished a dish. Overall would recommend, 4/5.

text:
I came to Tom's Dim Sum because I was craving soup dumplings, and my go-to soup dumpling restaurant had too long of a wait, so I needed to try somewhere new. A friend recommended Tom's, so I walked around the corner and there I was. 

Luckily, there was no wait, and we were seated quickly. Unfortunately I didn't know it was BYOB, so I had to eat Dim Sum empty handed.. or empty livered! But, I will come back with booze next time now that I know. 

The waitress was super fast, but no frills. She took our order immediately, and the food came very fast. But, she didn't help us get drinks, so it took some time for waters and soda. 

The soup dumplings were the entire reason we came, and they were pretty good. Not as good as my favorite place, but these were a very good backup plan. I wish there was an option for shrimp, without meat.  the Duck noodle soup was not our favorite, a lot of bones to pick around, but the noodles were perfectly cooked and really good. The broth was a bit salty. The roast pork bao buns were good, and the Shanghai shumai was good too. 

Overall, a good place for quick, easy, no frills Dim Sum. Not my favorite place, but good enough to come back for tasty soup dumplings, for a good price, and quick service. Also, good to save money with BYOB.

text:
I stumbled upon this place bc I was craving skewers and TT skewers was closed on mondays, the disappointment was beyond imagination.

Service: terrible, I only brought enough cash to pay for what I planned to order and bc my bill and a small piece missing the lady started screaming at me incoherently. Not wanting accept my bill

Place: kind of hard to find, not too much room to sit

Food: wow I did not know it was possible to screw up making all types of meats. I ordered beef, chicken, squid, tofu puff, and bacon with enoki mushrooms. Each one was more disappointing than the other. All the spices were on the outside and not inside and almost coughed out cumin powder if I inhaled wrongly. The worst offender is the beef. Good lord, I didn't think I ordered beef jerky. It was hard to bit into and had zero flavor. The only flavor is cumin covering the taste of burnt crap. It tasted how my cat turds smells. I was disgusted and couldn't finish it. Chicken was the most tolerable one and tasted something resembling chicken and not cat turd or over burnt/unrecognizable meat. Squid had all the spices concentrated in a pocket and tasted like...well squid. Tofu puff just tasted one frozen puffs thawed out with cumin. Last but not least, I did not think it was possible to screw up  bacon........if you want to taste how someone can make bacon taste disgusting, then you must try this place. 

Price: definitely a lot cheaper, but you get what you pay for. Shitty service and shitty food. 


Overall, this place is disgusting. Not worth stopping by and if you're craving skewers on a day TT Skewers is closed, don't stop by here. TT is def the best bc those ppl know how to make them the way how these skewers are made in China. I should know, I grew up eating these

text: I came here with a large group of people on a Monday night, but the place was still packed. Luckily we had made reservations! The place is very noisy so it was hard to hear every speak in my party. The waiter was very patient with my large party. He was also kind enough to bring me a separate vegeterian menu since I do not eat meat. We ordered a plethora of dishes, my favorite being the vegetarian pad thai and the brussel sprouts. The style of the restaurant is small portions or tapas, so we ordered about 10 dishes for 6 people who I thought was sufficient. The place is also well priced! At the end we told them it was 2 of the party member's birthday so we received these small ice creams with candles in them! Beware, you do have to pay for the ice creams, they do not come free just because it's someone's birthday! Would def come back here!

text:
An absolute disgrace of an eating establishment... I will never go anywhere near this horrible place again. I dined in with two of my close friends while we were exploring the city. We arrived with more than 30 minutes before their closing time and a general idea of what we were planning to order so we could speed the dining process up allowing them to close sooner. We did not order appetizers and did not even ask for any changes to our entrees, which again only sped up the dining process.

Immediately after walking in, we were not made to feel welcomed at all and the staff made all three us feel extremely awkward about being there. They gave us a very "uneasy" feeling because we were hoping to dine in with what they thought was close to closing. I recall having to repeat that we wanted to eat in more than once. After ordering our food, the food was absolutely MEDIOCRE AT BEST... Rather bland and boring. The noodles I got in my stir fry felt much closer to a pasta than a more traditional Asian noodle. Absolutely overpriced on top of the mediocre quality. However the worst hasn't even happened... Someone came over to our, presumably the restaurant manager and asked us to please pay for the food. I said sure and continued eating assuming she meant "pay when you are finished". NOT EVEN A MINUTE LATER she came back and said "can you please pay now?"... All three of us were in the middle of eating but I figured it's not a huge deal, and my one friend and I handed her our debit cards to pay for the meal... "Cash only". She said there is an ATM right outside the door. So I said sure and continued eating figuring there was absolutely no way she wanted us to stand up and get money at that very moment. I was VERY wrong. Now for a third time she asked for us to pay... NOW. We stood up and walked to the ATM that was turned off. It appeared to be an older unit and needed to boot up. You better believe this thing took it's time to turn on... At least 5 minutes and the staff made us stand there for the entire 5 minutes. Finally, the restaurant manager came over and told us we could pay in card... Meaning!: THIS ENTIRE GOD DAMN TIME THEY COULD HAVE TAKEN OUR DEBIT CARDS FROM THE START! In the midst of all this, the waitress took our unfinished meals. Now to top the whole "wonderful" experience off, I was handed my receipt to sign. I didn't even CONSIDER for ONE GOD DAMN SECOND to tip the staff after such an awful experience. I signed the receipt and handed it back to the lady and the other 2-3 staff around her watching. They looked at it confused and handed it back to me. I couldn't BELIEVE this was actually happening, so I kindly wrote the exact total in the "total" section of the receipt, left the tip section blank, and handed it back. These people actually had the audacity to GIVE ME DIRTY LOOKS!

I would no sooner wish even my worst enemy to eat at a such a disgraceful restaurant and I wouldn't eat there if it was the last god damn place on Earth! Do yourself a favor never even think about giving these people the time of day so hopefully they can shut down and no one will ever have to have this type of "dining" experience again.

text:
One of my fun place to eat in Philadelphia. When our ACP day meeting was over , I decided to take a stroll through Chinatown. My aim was to explore this part of the city. There were so many restaurants on both sides of the the 10th Street. Being a relatively new one, I just wanted to try this restaurant. It was relatively empty. I was greeted cordially and seated without a delay. The waitress Simin ( if I remember her name correctly) was very friendly and helpful. She went over the menu and explained the process of using hot pots with different ingredients. There were 4 places on the table to setup hot pots. You choose the broth first. Then you choose different ingredients to cook in the broth. The cooking time is different with different ingredients. You create your own dipping sauce based on your taste. I had trouble taking the long noodles out of the cooking pot. Of course, Simin helped me to get those out from the pot and transferred to the bowl. I tried scallops, fish balls, beef and noodles. It was really fun to cook and I enjoyed the meal. 
If you like to have fun while making your meal, this is the right place for you.
The price is $$$ , but worth the fun. 
HAVE FUN.

text:
I lived in Malaysia for short time in the past. I am familiar with Malaysian cuisine. While walking through Chinatown, I found this one. Very simple looking but packed with customers inside. Initially I was hesitant to go inside , but I did at the end. It was a good decision and realized it  after I started testing their food. I went there several occasions afterwards. The waiting time was relatively short but the service was relatively slow due to lot of hungry customers. It was noisy. It has a large menu to choose from. They have Chinese and Malaysian food. So, you will not be disappointed. I tried Nasi Lemak and it was good and fill you up easily. 
2nd day , I tried vegetarian steamed potstickers. It was average. 
But the steamed sea bass with ginger and soya sauce was delicious but little pricey. 
Overall, I had a satisfying experience with my orders and definitely plan to come back in future.

text: This was one of the best dining experiences I've had in a good long while.  The food was truly fantastic. I had a porcini cavatelli that I've been thinking about ever since. The wine selection was great, the menu had a nice mix of the classics - margherita pizza and pasta with Italian sausage ragout - and more signature dishes like lamb polpetini and duck and pear pizza. The prices were relatively high (approx $12 - 19 per plate, small portion sizes aside from the pizza with at least two plates needed per person for a full meal), but if that's not an issue for you or your looking for a place to celebrate a special occasion like we were, this is a great spot. The food comes out as it's prepared, which you'll be made aware of upon seating, but that only added to the excitement of the meal for us. Romantic atmosphere, fresh pasta and great wine. I can't wait to go back. PS. The rice pudding brulee dessert is... yum. Enjoy!

text:
This is rapidly becoming my favorite go to spot for eggy-waffles in all of Chinatown, partly because they sell it for just $2.50 and there's only one waffle machine, making the wait seem a little bit more magical and slows down your daily grind. CASH ONLY

Must get: eggy waffles, takoyaki (takes 15 min)
Meh: curry fish balls, pork/veggie buns (beware of the rice paper)
Missed: noodles

When you arrive, it's clear that this little store has something for everything, and it's all within $2-4. My favorite of course, is the eggy-waffles that is made right in front of you with the store's secret batter. The magic of the waffle is not just the fact it's made fresh, but it forces you to take the time and wait patiently as the batter sizzles and forms into hot little balls of magic that's sweet on the tongue, but not overwhelming. It's an amazing snack to devour solo or share with friends. The first time I had it, it was perfection, the second time felt a little less cooked.

Yummy Yummy's next best item is the takoyaki, and I highly recommend eating it while it's still piping hot and inhaling as you eat. I like how the bonito flakes dance around and I was glad that the balls weren't too oversaturated with the mayo-sauce.

Unfortunately, I was not a big fan of the pork buns, despite it's $0.90 price, as there was just not enough filling. The curry fish balls were good and juicy, but a little on the pricier side for just 4.

At the end of the day, the eggy waffle stole the show and I highly recommend visiting this little shop.

text:
My cousin told me about this place, and I decided to give it a try with my friend, since we both work only about a block or so from this restaurant. 

It was super easy to find. The only thing I'd say is the signage was a little hard to see (their awning is super high up with smaller font) Perhaps having a sign on the sidewalk AND/OR signage on the windows/door would make it easier to find? 

We were seated immediately by a man (who I believe to be the manager?) He was very nice. We even got a nice end spot with a booth/table set up. Our waitress seemed a little "over it", she took our order, but was not very friendly. I was pleased to hear that soup was automatically included with the Lunch, especially because it was such a good price! 

The soup came out almost immediately which I was very satisfied with. The wonton soup tasted okay, not much noodles/chicken, but for the price, it was fine. 

The chicken was pretty good, but lots of fried bits and not enough chicken. I do love how there was a lot of sauce to pour over the chicken on the side, and came with pineapple in the sauce which I love!!

Overall, this place is fine, not my favorite Chinese place, but the fact we were seated very quickly, and the food came out fast, I was content!

text:
Came here with a reservation for a large table (6+) on a weekday at 7pm and were seated very quickly.  The servers came and explained everything to us and brought over our drinks and sauces.

You can tailor the sauce to your liking since they have many add-ons for the sauce. We ordered all the combos: meat, seafood, veggie, mushroom, noodle, and meatball. Plus additional noodle and tofu sides. All of the food was delicious and fresh. The different noodles were definitely worth getting, especially because they make a good amount of their noodles in house!

The portions were a little small for the price so if you're hungry then I would suggest going to an AYCE place to not break the bank, but I had a great experience and would return again for a quality hot pot meal.

text: We were in town and craving some Asian food-stumbled upon this place not far from our conference. It looked nice from the outside. First up, they only accept cash or venmo (which was very weird). The owner/manager is kind of rude (no people skills whatsoever). They charge for soda refills and it's by the can. Ok now that that's outta the way let's get to the food - we ordered appetizers and entrees - both were brought out at the same time even tho we put in for the apps way before the entree. The spring rolls were stale - as though they microwaved it from the night before. There is no flexibility on the menu (for instance, I wanted a different side other than rice - nope, no can do, the manager is really strict... and also the only Side they have is rice). I had the spicy beef and I couldn't even eat 1/4 of it cause it just wasn't tasting good. I ended up having to nibble on the nasty spring roll since it was better than my entree. Oh and the waiter came and took the spring roll away before I finished it without even asking - like wth. I wish I could give this place a negative star because it really did suck. I'm assuming the manager is just trying to cut cost but it's not working. Save your money and go somewhere else.

text:
When we first moved to Philadelphia, Reading Terminal Market was one of our first stops in the city. It is now a place we regularly visit when in the city. 

You can find anything from around the world here at Reading Terminal Market. From Indian cuisine to seafood, from fresh flowers to homemade accessories. 

It is fairly priced but it's all dependent on the place you decide to eat from. It is always packed and busy with all kinds of people. Definitely a must when visiting Philadelphia!

text: I moved to the area after living in center city for 3 years. I quickly realized there's slim pickings for sushi, and especially if you want delivery. Someone recommended lucky star and we tried it. Honestly for the prices I was certain it wouldnt be good, but I was pleasantly surprised. We've consistently ordered from here for takeout sushi and it has always been really good and pretty creative if you like the rolls, which I do. The Chinese food is also tasty and they give you a really decent portion of food. Usually my fiancé and I can split a combo dinner (chicken, rice, soup), egg rolls, and a couple sushi rolls and we find it to be perfect. If you live in the area and need a solid delivery option, this beats out the other (very few and not as good) options nearby.

text:
I don't know what those 5 star rating yelpers we're eating but the one review that said this place has a variety of skewers was dead wrong. 

The menu here isn't that large, the food needs to be labeled spicy if made spicy. The prices are a bit high and the portions were minimal. 

We ordered the escargot, fried soft shell crabs and the clam with rice noodles.

The noodles were ok, couldn't taste anything other Han the spicy burning my tongue.

The escargot, oh man that was hit or miss depending on the escargot you picked up, some were bitter others were just weird tasting. They need to work on seasoning. 

The soft shell crabs a bit dry. I could season this way better at home.

Overall, I did not like the food here. Nothing was seasoned properly, everything was overpowered by spicy. The only thing my table liked was the white rice...

text: So happy to find a dim sum place in Philadelphia with gluten free dumpling options. Everything that Nom Wah can make gluten free is clearly marked on their menu, so when you're filling out your order slip, just write "GF" next to items you select. My boyfriend and I split several things--shrimp rice rolls, tofu skin rolls, fried shrimp and bacon rolls, soup dumplings (not gluten free), and vegetable rice vermicelli. Everything was really good, and I especially loved the tofu skin rolls--it was the first time that I've had anything resembling a spring roll since getting celiac, and wow, I've missed them. The fried shrimp and bacon rolls were good but more of an American appetizer than dim sum, and something I'd skip next time around. Prices are a bit high so things can get expensive quickly--I'd recommend starting small and then ordering more in increments if you decide you're still hungry. In terms of space, the restaurant is super cute, but gets incredibly crowded as the night goes on... definitely make a reservation. Last Friday, they only had one waitress working the entire first floor, i.e. taking orders, hostessing, running drinks, and bartending. She was SO sweet, but also spread very thin, so we walked up to the bar to place our order, get drinks, pay, etc. Nom Wah could certainly benefit from some more staff. Overall, really good experience, and I'm looking forward to returning during happy hour sometime!

text:
This place is more of a 3.5, probably closer to what the average review is. The beef noodle soup is pretty good, it will warm you up on a cold rainy day and remind you of when your parents grounded you and the only good part of the day was eating beef noodle soup. The sushi is also decent- they have lunch specials for that as well.

While it may be a little pricey, overall the food is fine and the seating is readily available so you can easily go with a big party.

text:
Shanghai/Taiwanese fusion. 

The 2 things to order are the braised pork rice which is only 6.50, and the beef noodle soup which was around 8-9. For the price, that value cannot be beaten. They were very filling portions that were incredibly tasty, albeit maybe a little salty. 

The chicken dishes were kind of dissapointing and I would not order those again. The garlic eggplant was amazing though- tasted just like what I would eat at home. 

The service was pretty quick and we got in and got out in an hour. Overall a great shop with lots of seating that you can get a reasonably priced meal.

text: Thank you! I relocated to Philly from NY and while Im not going put alot, I do order in. (I used Door Dash and they were great) I tried delivery from other places that ended up in the trash. I love the name of place and they were my last hope of finding old school Cantonese food. The food was delivered hot and on time. It is a little pricey but the good news is that you can eat this for a few days and its still great. Chicken Corn Soup is perfect, dumplings are fantastic. Please remember if you are ordering in to ask for your sauce or you wont get it. Its not the restaurants fault, the online ordering via door dash makes you spell it out. Its a must try!

text:
Probably the best tasting and most authentic Chinese food in the Philly area. I had the fish, chicken, and crispy shrimp dishes he recommended, I honestly don't remember the names since he was talking in Chinese and I speak at a first-grade level, but hey it was good practice. 

The food itself was very well made and used all the right spices- tasted like something my parents would make. On the flip side, it was pretty pricey averaging about 20ish dollars per main dish. Go with your family or for a special occasion.

There is free parking in the back which is so clutch. Also, the service is fantastic and they are very prompt with your orders. There is plenty of seating, so no problems their either. 

I also had some cheese foam tea which was delicious- they use either like chrysanthemum or rose or some essence of a flower which adds a delightful flavor accent. It was a bit sweet though, so I recommend getting maybe 50 or 30 percent sugar. 

Overall a great upscale Chinese restaurant perfect for date night or special occasions.

text:
Spent a fun time here for my friend's bachelorette party. She enjoyed herself and we all had a good time. The rooms were nice and fit 8 of us comfortably. There is also conveniently a bathroom is the room for the group. Also the food and drinks were decent and everything was served in a timely fashion. 
My qualms we're mainly with the system. It super hard to choose songs. It's not intuitive which is necessary for a room full of people who are drinking. Also it a bit expensive. We took advantage of spending the price of the room on food and drinks but it was an expensive evening.
Overall it's a fun experience but I'd prefer an easier way to have fun.

text:
The restaurant is small, but cozy. It is often pretty full.

When I go, I always order the beef noodles. Those are some of the best noodles I have ever had. The noodles are hand drawn and cooked to perfection, and the beef is tender and delicious. The serving size is pretty big, so the price is very reasonable.

Service will not be the super friendly type found in traditional American restaurants, but they will get you your food and whatever you need quickly and efficiently.

I highly suggest this declines restaurant!!

text: Thought this place was very interesting from the looks of it when we looked it up. Our wait for a table of 3 took about 40 minutes, hence, I would definitely recommend reserving a table ahead of time. The restaurant is split off into two sections, tables that have each personal grills and then tables that have a center stove for family-style hot pot. We were more interested in the grills, but the wait was too long so we took what was available to give it a shot even though it was the "more expensive option." Our server was nice, but lacked attention to our table compared to the one next to us. He explained everything thoroughly, and considering it was all new to my friends and I, we got a basic general understanding of what was what. We proceeded to order the Spicy Soup and the Oxtail Soup for our Hotpot and added various amenities from the menu including Meatballs, Octopus, and one of the beef. A problem we had was that we ordered an order of dumplings as an appetizer, but they didn't have it in stock at the time. I'm not sure if there was a misunderstanding between the server and me, but we got an order of this well designed beef that came with a good presentation with vapor. What we got was apparently "Beef Tongue." We thought it was the dumplings that we ordered, didn't realize until we got the receipt, and ate it anyways. To our surprise, tasted pretty good, but was shocked to the price of it that it was $20 for 3 Rose shaped slices of beef tongue. Our server was able to get us 30% off for the misunderstanding which was good b/c the dumplings we wanted was probably around $12. The restaurant does offer Free Ice Cream at the end of your course per person in exchange for a review. Overall, it was an experience to try something new, but make sure to know what you're ordering and know what you're eating and keep in mind the prices load up.

text:
My family and I came upon this place by accident (I think we were trying to go to another noodle place but ended up here?) and I'm so glad we had lunch here instead. The noodle dishes and soups here are reasonably priced and generously portioned.

We ordered 4 to share (we always do #familystyle): the house special noodle soup w/hand-pulled noodles, braised sliced beef noodle soup with shaved noodles, stir-fried seafood hand-pulled noodles, and peanut sauce dry noodles. (The waiters helpfully brought smaller bowls for us so that we could eat from all the dishes.) 

The noodle soups both tasted great; the braised beef soup contained shaved noodles that had a good texture, though I felt like they could have been a bit more generous with the portion of meat. In contrast, the amount of seafood in the stir-fry noodle dish - which was savory with the perfect touch of sweet - was pretty big. The peanut sauce dry noodle is only a little over $4, but it tasted great as well and the portion size was surprisingly large.

Our family of 4 were quite full by the time we finished all the food. If I'm ever in the area again, I would love to visit this restaurant again. But BRING CASH - it's cash only, and we were lucky that we happened to have enough on hand.
name_x: Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House

text:
Honestly a little bit overrated. The food is pretty decent, except for Sang Kee which has incredible duck dishes and char siu as well. Most things are a little bit overpriced, but I guess you are paying for the experience. If you want the foodie walkthrough, here's the must hits:

Beiler's has good donuts, but lines are long. 
Bassetts has good ice cream with lots of creamy flavors. 
Dutch eating place for apple dumplings. 
DiNics for a pork sandwich (personally not a fan but others like it). 
Kamal's Middle Eastern for a mint lemonade or some other fun and unique drink. 
Sang Kee for a duck fried rice. 
Mueller for a fresh soft pretzel. 

Other people have things they like also, but these are the ones I commonly hear about- I've tried them all and they're all solid. 

Pro tip: if you are driving, you can park in the garage next door for the hotel and then get your ticket validated for free 2 hour parking by a vendor if you spend 10 dollars at their stand.

text:
I was just in Philly visiting for the weekend and we had a phenomenal group dinner here! The restaurant is super trendy with cool mood lighting, and felt like it could have turned into a club at any point. We went all out and did the 7-course tasting menu, where you get to pick 1-2 items from each category (somehow, we were all able to come to a consensus as a table on what items to get). This was very reasonably priced at $45/person and a good way to try a lot of dishes. Note: if you have any vegetarians in the group, they can do a vegetarian tasting menu for that person or let them opt out and just order a la carte, which I thought was very accommodating. 

Now for the dishes! Here's what we enjoyed from most to least:
- Amazing: waygu beef (absolutely melts in your mouth), crispy rock shrimp (super crispy with just the right amount of sauce), XO scallops (seared perfectly), crispy brussel sprouts (couldn't stop eating) 
- Great: peking duck (with yummy scallion buns, but you have to eat it quickly or else the duck gets a bit tough), seafood dumpling (nice chili sauce), edamame dumpling (very unique and can definitely taste the truffle, but paled in comparison to the ones I had at Buddakan the night before)
- Average: shrimp pad thai (a little too much sauce, nothing mindblowing), roasted broccoli (a bit plain)

They finish off the meal with 2 types of soft serve ice cream cones, which were orange creamiscle and chocolate cherry our night (I think it rotates). Definitely recommend the tasting menu for your first time here as it was a really fun group experience (dishes just keep coming out) and you get to try a lot. If I were to come back, I would then get some of the best stand-out dishes as mentioned above.

text: I have been to this restaurant before but I went today and had an awful experience.  We arrived by 1215 pm for lunch and had to order quickly because of limited time.  The restaurant was relatively empty. We received our drinks and appetizers on time but waited, as others who arrived after us not only ordered food but received their food.  As of 1259pm ( when i left the restaurant - we had not received our food.  The waiter was no help as he failed to enter our order in the the system until 1244.  When we asked for the manager, the waiter was not helpful in getting him to us and we finally had to summon a server support person ( busboy)to get the manager.  We we complained about the service and demanded our food be provided to us for take away ( since our lunch time window had expired ). We also asked the manager the we be provided the food without cost .  The manager initially said no but that he would have the waiter pay for the food and therefore waive the cost to us.  While the result was the same, a person patronizes a restaurant not a waiter and would have liked the establishment to make it right and not involve the customer in the inner workings of their product delivery.  Unlikely that i will go back to a restaurant that i have been to a number of times.

text:
We have been here several times in the last couple of weeks. We are a couple that love Asian food, I actually lived in China for about 4 months. Been to most of the Chinatown restaurants here in Philly, and was blown away by how good this place is. Super authentic, the family are originally from Fujian Province in China, and they really know how to cook. The son and his father work for 6 months on perfecting recipes and combining different cooking styles from the different China provinces. This, they have done before they opened the restaurant. And the quality of the food really reflects it! All vegetarian food, done in the most delicious and special way. Extremely aesthetic and beautiful restaurant, amazing service, and there are so many different options. would strongly recommend getting some of the appetizers such as the seaweed patties,  fried tofu with cashews, the ginger taro and others. From the main dishes, you really can't go wrong, but I would recommend at least one of the clay pots, in addition to one or two Chef specialities. they also have an excellent lunch menu as well.

 It is also very affordable, and overall in my opinion one of the best and most affordable Chinese restaurants in the Northeast of the United States.

text:
Incredible experience all around, and probably some of the best dim sum I've ever had!!

The carts moved around at a surprisingly impressive pace, food was fresh and flavorful and piping hot, and it was obvious this place was popular by how many people were waiting. We loved our experience and loved everything we got! Their porridge/congee is exceptional, bean curd wraps the best I've ever had, and everything was fresh and had generous portions.

Prices are also AMAZING -- my boyfriend and I ate so many plates and paid $15 each after tip. My eyes almost fell out of my head when I saw how cheap the meal was!! We will be regulars and I can't wait to come back!

text:
Good, not great food. It was definitely delicious food but there wasn't anything unique or especially tasty that would justify the exorbitant prices for me, besides a special event like a birthday. I'm glad I tried it but I don't think I'll rotate back to it soon when there are so many other places to try. 

That being said, I loved the decor. A waterfall feature greets you as soon as you walk in. The iconic buddha statue is visible no matter where you are in the restaurant and that plus the music, candles, and atmosphere really transports you outside of Philadelphia. 

Ordered the dim sum sampler and char grilled aged beef. The Szechuan fries that came with the beef were delicious. The edamame dumplings were great but tasted similar to other places. For dessert I wasn't too impressed with the bento box or sorbet, but I may come back to try the dip sum doughnuts as that is their most popular.

text:
It may be confusing at first but if you ask them what to do then they will help you out. This spot is not as busy as other hot spot place around Chinatown so if you want to skip the long line during weekend dinner hours, i would recommend to try out this place. 

I got the half n half broth (original n spicy) and the original broth was very well-seasoned and the food, which were cooked in the original broth tasted much better than the the one in the spicy broth. The spicy broth is just the normal broth with hot oil and it's a big greasy so i didn't really like it. 

The toppings' prices are reasonable  and the meat toppings come in good portion. Mushroom and vegetables are also pretty fresh. 

Waiter were attentive and friendly. 

We came in a group of 4 and we left full and happy with the bill around $65 ( not including tip)

text: Excellent home cooking at very affordable prices! Best Chinese home style spicy cooking in Philly! The dry pot stir fry is outstanding, and the Ma La soup is superb. Service is good, the waiters are attentive and will bring you whatever you need. And the dining room is cozy, bright, with Chinese karaoke classics going in the background. A+ hao chi!

text:
Was in Philly for a concert and stumbled across this gem. The small restaurant can seat maybe 25. The menu is expansive and has some traditional and American-Chinese staples. The service was good, food came out quick. Portions were a good size. 

My only complaint about this place was the price and limited dinner options for 2. There wasn't a cost effective way for us to get more than one item each. they had a 2 person dinner combo but the pre-fix wasn't really what we wanted. Had they given a few options for the items on that dinner we would have been able to try more for a reasonable price. 

I look forward to going back to try more the next time I'm in Philly.

text:
I eat Chinese home cooked food on the daily, so while I enjoyed my dishes at sampan, I was not hugely impressed for the price. Everything tasted good, but I wish portions had been larger. I came in a group of four and we ordered

+ lobster chow fun (this was nicely flavored, warm and hot. Just wish there had been more noodles -- got mostly veggies with every forkful and it was a small serving)

+ hamachi ceviche (not that high on my list of ceviches. It was a bit watery and did not have too much fish) 

+ general Tsos soup dumplings (the flavor is great, but the dumpling wrapper is very very delicate, so many of us had our dumpling burst in the process of picking it up)

+ wagyu beef skewer (my favorite dish of the night! Beef is tender and the slightly sweet jam-like sauce gives a nice acidity)

+ beef short rib lettuce cup (you diy your cups. This was good, not amazing. Beef is mashed to almost a paste-like consistency)

+ Peking duck fried rice (duck could have used more flavor but good overall for sharing)

I also ordered the Ming mule cocktail, which I thought was reasonably good, except I couldn't taste the lychee. I think I'd come back for happy hour (or more likely go to double knot, which I've really enjoyed in the past) but probably not for the regular menu. Service was also really fast paced - we were in and out in an hour (something to keep in mind if you want to linger).

text: What a fun place and a must-go for anyone coming through Philly! I had a conference near the convention center and my hotel was around there so I was luckily able to get to Reading Market every day very easily! Would definitely recommend- but very crowded over the weekday lunch hour- I could barely walk through the aisles. I had gone back on Thursday and Friday around 4 pm and this was a much better time for me to go and wander the stalls and have a look at everything without feeling rushed. There is definitely something for everyone here- vegan, Chinese, thai, your typical Philly Cheesesteak, great desserts and wonderful cookies and baked goods!  Everything was pretty affordable as well.

text:
Sober review: delicious food, good prices. The rolls were amazing and I highly suggest using eel- sauce over soy sauce. If you've never had it, it's thicker and amazing and good on everything, but especially on rolls. Their lo mein is really good. And their food did not make me sick unlike most Chinese restaurants in Philly. They do a good hybrid of Chinese and Japanese. I got full quickly However it lasted for a few hours So I say that makes a good review right there. I had a hard time picking from the menu so I just kind of randomly picked a bunch of things That sounded good and then ordered. It was like Christmas when I got it and I was not disappointed.

Drunk review: it's still freaking delicious! Even cold, that lo mein is amazing. Sure, it's nothing spectacular, but many hours later it's not spoiled like so many places! It's actually going to make many meals. Still got full quickly but that's okay. That's a plus when you're drinking. Plus now I feel like I could drink more. I'm not going to because it's 2:00 a.m. and I have to be a responsible human tomorrow, But at least I will be a responsible human with more delicious food to devour tomorrow.

I will definitely order again and I am glad I found a restaurant that will give me beef lo mein and some rolls and good miso soup all in one.

text:
I  got takeout and spent over $90 worth of food here and only a quarter of it was edible. The only thing good here is the sushi as the sushi is pretty fresh.  All of the cooked foods were all overcooked, burnt and had no flavor. The food here is very overpriced for what you get. You can get better food elsewhere for less.

Avocado tempura app  - Too mushy and had no flavor. Could not eat it.  I love avocado I salads and sushi, but fried it tastes completely different.

Grilled scallops app - 3 scallops, all overcooked, and two of them had a little sand in them.  Disgusting.

Shrimp tempura dinner - 4 small pieces of shrimp and 4 pieces of sweet potato.  The tempura was not crunchy and it was soggy.  The portion was small and not worth it.

Filet mignon teriyaki dinner - I asked for medium and my steak was burnt on the outside and overcooked in the middle. (see photo).  I can't believe I paid $22 for this and can barely eat it.  Small portion as well.

Smoked salmon sushi - fresh 

California roll - tasted good to me and fresh. Who can screw that up?

I would NOT recommend this place whatsoever, unless you're coming here just for the sushi.

text:
Oh this place, why did you have to disappoint me? Having the original Nom Wah in Chinatown nyc and eating dim sum all my life and in Philly, the dim sum I had was as dreary as the lighting in the place. Never been to a Dim sum where it was dark, usually expect bright lights lots of people running around yelling and fresh hot food. I got slow service, byob wine bottles everywhere, oily and lackluster food that was brought out at 4 different times. Really? I don't want to eat my meat last. They brought out in order of 15 minutes for the scallion pancakes, another 10 for the OG, another 10 for the shrimp shu Mai and chicken fest, and another 10 for pork ribs. What the heck? If you folks have eaten Dim sum you pair and eat things together not just eat a whole tray of meat by itself. 

Also regarding the food, it was totally not made fresh to order that's a complete lie. My chicken feet, the feet was cold and skin soggy. That usually means it was made and reheat again probably like a day or more ago. I would like to see how you get cold chicken feet, never had that at a dim sum before. Maybe nobody orders chicken feet here?
Also, the scallion pancakes were soo oily, how do you make it so bad? It's not hard just get fresh dough, scallions, roll it up and press down then pan fry on both sides until brown and crispy. This was like thrown into the frier for like 10 mins until the oil seeps in. Same concept with chicken wings to not have oily skin. 

The shumai the skin was falling off couldn't pick it up, means it was old. The only saving grace was the tea and the OG. The OG was crispy and egg roll omelette and veggies pretty good combo. I feel like everything would've been good and my review much better if it was cooked well, on time, service better and priced better but unfortunately for me not coming back a byob dim sum isn't my thing. Or at least I'll just go to Chinatown or Dim Sum House.

text:
I had dined in once at Mustard Greens and it was good. Fast-forward to today ordering $55 + $3 tip take out and it was TERRIBLE. I ordered Chicken Tai chin, Beef Hunan, Spare ribs, and mustard greens. I asked for the beef and chicken to be extra spicy and they had no spice. The Beef was poor, nothing special, but the chicken was awful. It was not as advertised and swimming in vinegar/sugar water. The ribs were tough and very old and the mustard greens were very bland. When I called MG to tell them that the food was terrible, they told me that they were sorry but too bad; they would not take it back or do anything to rectify the situation. 

I understand a restaurant making a bad dish, or four, but to not stand behind your product is unacceptable. Old, tough ribs are a crime. I wish I had gone to Han Dynasty instead; it would have cost the same but it would've been delicious and spicy!

text:
Great for anytime but especially a late night snack, great taste and fantastic value.

This is it.  if you are in the mood for hotpot you can not go wrong with this place.  I came by myself and ordered the fatty brisket and shrimp with bokchoy and oyster mushrooms and udon noodles.  I also ordered the grilled scallops as an appetizer but more on that later.  My total bill was about $50 and I had so much left overs, this is definitely a place that  someone can eat for $20-30/person easily.  In addition you can get your own soup base for just a few bucks so you can easily have the same number of protein as I did but have another type of broth for a few bucks more.

The broth I chose was the tomato based one and it was very good, a little hint of sour like lemon grass and a little bit of spice, perfect to compliment the beef and shrimp.  When you are served your dinner you are also given a variety of condiments and sauces you can customize your broth further.  I definitely would suggest also the oyster mushrooms as it soaks up the soup and gives you that texture that brings the broth in even closer contact with your taste buds.  

My only nit pick was that the grilled scallops were a little bit bland when compared to the hot pot so I'd recommend not getting that and instead getting another serving of meat or other seafood for your hotpot.  Overall, this is one of my new favorites in Chinatown.  PS they have ipads at the table so I "borrowed" the charger for my phone:-) A++++++

text:
I like the concept but maybe I'm just not a fan a hot pots. They won't let your table order hot pot unless everyone orders a hot pot, by the way. I just wanted the high-end and very expensive wagyu steak - we went with a sushi version of this and absolutely loved it ... although $18 for 2 pieces isn't exactly what I'd call a bargain. A steal maybe! But not exactly wallet friendly. 

The hot pot was more reasonably priced ... but if you're an impatient eater like me, expect to get your mouth scorched - you need to blow on the soup or figure out how to lower the temperature with the buttons under the table. There is a hot pot for each seat and they are close enough to the edges that you can eat right out of them - although I would not recommend that. The cups they give you are very tiny too- would be smart to ask for a bowl so you don't have to constantly fill up - and so it can cool a little more over time. 
I went with the mushroom broth - it was just okay. 

PS. This place is tiny. We put our names in on the electronic keyboard on the wall (make sure to do this when you enter- no one really tells you to do this unless you ask or figure it out) and it it took close to 2 hours for us to get a seat.

text: I searched "Taiwanese restaurant" and one of the results happened to be Shang Hai 1 in Chinatown.  We have been in several restaurants in China town but haven't been in this one so we decided to try it out.  We went during lunch time. The place has decent amount of people but it was not packed (about 60% full). The waiter was attentive and quickly let us choose between complimentary hot tea or iced water; the tea was standard green tea and was nice and hot.  There were a lot of good stuff from the menu (dim sum, hot soups, cold appetizers, and Szechuan style entrees). We opted for spicy beef noodle soup and spicy fish filet over rice. Both of them were nicely priced at $8+.  I was expecting a small amount for the lunch. But was pleasantly surprised with a generous amount. We love both our meals and vowed to come back again to try the other options.

text:
Kim's offers Americanized Chinese food at cheap prices, good for students or others living on a budget.

The unadorned white truck, parked right across Walnut street from Huntsman Hall, and right next to the Penn Recreation Center, is a bit sketchy from the outside. But the lady inside is sweet, and the business is legit.

Speaking of sweet, so is the food. Expect overly sweet, saucy, fried, Americanized Chinese food here (e.g., orange chicken or broccoli and beef). Think Panda-Express-type quality. I wasn't a huge fan, but your taste preferences may vary.

Of course, the best part is that meals here are just around $6, which is pretty nice if you're trying to manage a budget. Though keep in mind they only take cash, so make sure you have some on hand.

Overall, not my favorite Chinese food, but the price is right. Walk on over during lunchtime, if you'd like to try for yourself.

text:
Again, I wish Yelp let you do half stars because I would give it a 3.5 over a 3 if possible. The experience was good, the food was good and the bill was inexpensive for how much food we got. 

THE GOOD:
The dim sum portion of the menu here is where you should stay. The pork soup dumplings, shrimp dumplings, chicken on a stick, moon cake, scallion pancake were all great. Surprisingly, the dried string beans were also very good. The service was good, not the most attentive but the servers definitely got the job done and were polite and helpful. As mentioned, the prices are super reasonable so you're able to get a lot of bang for your buck.

THE BAD:
The General Tso's chicken was well below average , to be honest it reminded me of frozen Trader Joe's brand. I would definitely not get again. The beef ho fun was just fine, I have definitely had better at other restaurants in Philadelphia. Spare ribs were fried and super crispy (which is usually a positive) but they were dry and the flavor was not very robust They tasted old to be honest. 

Overall - I would definitely come back for specifically Dim Sum but would stay in that arena.

text:
Uggh this place sucks.  My daughter's daycare is less than a mile away from this and I've stopped by Woosa Bubble Tea before and this place is right next door so I decided to try it for lunch.  The two staff workers working at the desk to process your order and payment are super slow, can't speak English, and one of the employees decided to chat with her friend while people are lined up to order. She was noticeably oblivious about the growing line while she keeps chatting and gossiping with her friend.  I can tell people were getting antsy and she was just laughing in the counter with no care in the world.  The other guy stepped in to take the order since his co-worker decided to chat instead of work,  was nice- but can't speak English very well.  They have wide range of Chinese food in their menu, but I decided to order a safe dish since I'm not sure- Kung Pao chicken. It's also good to mention that they don't have a cheaper lunch menu so you have to pay full price even during lunch time.  

My dish arrived and I was severely underwhelmed.  The dish was too wet, had too much bell peppers and peanuts and not enough chicken.    

Also, be warned that they don't serve any beverages besides lukewarm water, and few sodas in can.  No- they don't even have any tea- warm or cold. 

With the lack of parking, lackluster food, awful customer service- I definitely won't be back

text:
A bit pricey, but the quality of meat here (particularly the wagyu, which is heavily featured on the menu) is top-notch, so I felt like I got my money's worth in the end

A few items our group really enjoyed:
-wagyu brisket
-signature hand-cut wagyu beef
-beef brisket wrapped enoki
-kurobata pork belly
-fish tofu (it is realllllly good here)
-hand-made fish balls
-aburi wagyu foie gras nigiri: one of the non-hotpot items, but absolutely scrumptious with the fat of the wagyu and foie gras!

A few tips:
-the meat is thin, and since you're paying so much for it, I would cook the meat shabushabu style rather than letting it sit in the broth to avoid it being overcooked
- the broth is delicious by itself, even before absorbing the flavors of the ingredients you throw in. Feel free to drink from the beginning!

text:
I travel to Philadelphia for work often and stay right in the downtown core. Being pretty busy and tired, Reading Terminal Market is a great spot for any meal or snack during the day. Super convenient, quick, full of variety and options and is reasonably priced. 

There is a fresh juice stand and they make me ginger and lemon shots for $1.50. Love it. 

The thing I love most about Reading Terminal Market is that my 73 year old father used to eat here with my grandfather when he was a kid. Makes me feel like the entire market is family.

text:
Not sure how many bad things I can say about this place.

We had a private room. It was VERY hot in the room even with the air conditioner on full blast. We ordered "bottle service" they brought in a regular size bottle of liquor with plastic cups, 2 plastic pitchers of soda, and some limes. All that for the ridiculous $150 price tag. Complete and total ripoff. Everything was completely over priced, and only one of our mics was fully working.

Also the bathroom door in the room didn't lock, the fan inside the room was filthy and didn't work. 

With all the money this place is stealing from its customers, it surely needs to upgrade. Or at least provide true bottle service. That was terrible.

text:
Where do I begin? This was my first stop in Philadelphia, fresh off the plane and having just had the chance to drop off luggage at my friend's house. All we knew was that we were hungry and also wanted to take in some sights. So we walked down the street and headed straight for the market. And this place was PACKED! I was not prepared for the onslaught of sights and sounds and choices. I had researched some things to try - such as the pretzels, donuts, and pork sandwich - but that barely scratched the surface of what this market has to offer. I mean, c'mon, chocolate noses! 

The first day, we tried the pork sandwich with broccoli rabe and sweet pepper and it was quite tasty. Also loved the pretzel. The donuts were unique although not my favorite, but there are definitely so many to choose from you are bound to find something you enjoy - we tried the key lime, oreo creme, and sugar. 

The next day we needed a quick breakfast and had to stop by for famous scrapple and the hot apple dumpling. When it came down to a choice of adding heavy or whipped cream, I decided to be daring and go with some heavy cream and I have never been happier with my decision! That hot apple dumpling was one of my favorite things. And scrapple was unique. I ended up adding some syrup and enjoyed it. Definitely not something I get back home!

This place is a must for both tourists and locals. Good food, good prices.

text:

Seems like regular price for dinner was 13.99 
I gave them a call to ask price for dinner that night 
The woman on the phone said it was 15.99 since it's holiday. I dont know why mother's day is holiday but anyway.. when we got there, price was actually 16.99 and 
The place was packed. So many food tray were empty or filled with non popular or cold food. 
We got the check around 74.95 ( including 2 seniors and 2adults)+ tips. Which was not worth a price at all!

text:
So I recently came for dinner, in what's been a really long time, because I haven't been happy with their price changes, menu changes, and always their lack of customer service, especially their management, front desk, and that one guy that cooks everywhere, recently at the sushi bar the last year or 2. 

Overall, the food was pretty decent. Except for United Buffet's Poke Bowl, they were far better than United.

Few Disappointments...

They charge the same price for dinner as they've always had...
YET....
No Crab Legs, No Roasted Duck...
No Lobster Claws which they had offered once they stopped serving Crab Legs a while back...
This time around, not much Sushi Nigiri if any. It was 95% Sushi Rolls.

Service is decent as usual, better than most Chinese buffets, not by much, but better.

text:
We came here for a friend's birthday. The hotpot broth was good, but the lack of options on the conveyor belt was very disappointing.

We arrived around 8PM on a Tuesday and we ordered a few things from the menu. In general, the meat was overpriced and we got little to no meat in quantity. We even ordered the mushroom basket, but it didn't quite hit the mark. The conveyor belt had a special (BOGO) but they didn't put any product on it, so we kept seeing the same items over and over (literally the same plates). So in the end, we didn't really even pick things from the conveyor belt. They took away our sauce tray at one point as well, informing us that they needed it at another table. It wasn't a big deal... but it was kind of awkward. Why not just have enough sauce trays for all the tables?

"High end" doesn't meet "great experience". There are other hotpot places I would venture to before going back to this one.

text:
I like the concept but maybe I'm just not a fan a hot pots. They won't let your table order hot pot unless everyone orders a hot pot, by the way. I just wanted the high-end and very expensive wagyu steak - we went with a sushi version of this and absolutely loved it ... although $18 for 2 pieces isn't exactly what I'd call a bargain.

The hot pot was more reasonably priced ... but if you're an impatient eater like me, expect to get your mouth scorched - you need to blow on the soup or figure out how to lower the temperature with the buttons under the table. There is a hot pot for each seat and they are close enough to the edges that you can eat right out of them - although I would not recommend that. The cups they give you are very tiny too- would be smart to ask for a bowl so you don't have to constantly fill up - and so it can cool a little more over time. 

went with the mushroom broth - it was just okay. PS. This place is tiny. We put our names in on the electronic keyboard on the wall (make sure to do this when you enter- no one really tells you to do this unless you ask or figure it out) and it it took close to 2 hours for us to get a seat.

text: UNPROFESSIONAL, ILLEGAL, WAITERS/OWNERS BULLY CUSTOMERS INTO LEAVING MORE TIP, NOT EDIBLE. CHECK CURRENT REVIEWS AND REVIEWS THAT ARE NOT RECOMMENDED AT BOTTOM OF PAGE. Came here last night for my grandmothers birthday dinner. She heard that you get a free meal if it's your birthday so she insisted we come here even though my siblings and I had no interest (we know it's not good having been here when they first opened, and from word of mouth we know it hasn't gotten any better). The kind of customers this place attracts are usually people who are looking "all-you-can-eat" because it's the only place in Chinatown that offers this. But if you're looking for quality, spend more and go to Hippot Shabu Shabu at 10th and Arch. I arrived a few minutes late, right after my family members had placed their orders. The waiter informed me that they had ordered enough but I still wanted to add some more vegetarian options. As soon as I asked if I could add more, the waiter told/yelled at me no and I should wait until we finish what we ordered first before ordering more. I quickly shot back, "so I can't eat??" he continued to go back and forth with me until he finally gave in and said "k, fine, go ahead", he stormed off and a waitress took my order. The food comes out, the broth is bland, the ramen noodles looked and tasted like plastic/cardboard, the fried tofu was not tofu at all just a fried empty hole. Nothing was good. We barely finished what we ordered and did not order any more because it was not edible. The check comes, my grandmother gives them her ID to confirm her birthday. My grandmother also insists on treating us. She pays cash. Gets her change and leaves the rest as tip. The waiters and waitresses stand in the corner and laugh and giggle the entire time you are eating but I guess they also watch to see how much tip you are leaving because when got up to leave, the waitress comes over and tells us we did not leave enough and bully us into leaving more.... yes you read that right. She demanded we leave her more money. After going back and forth with her a little and then feeling bad that this place puts their employees in a position that they have to ask for more money, we decide to give her a fee more dollars. This is sad and disgusting!! It's unprofessional and SUPER uncomfortable. If anything, do not support a place that does this!!! The waitress also continued to argue with me (her argument seemed very rehearsed) and hovered over my grandmother who was scrambling for change to give her! I had to tell the waitress to stop arguing with me because we are giving her more money! What is the point of continuing if you see us giving you more than you deserve?? And for god's sake, you know it's her birthday and Mother's Day was just the day before!! Unbelievable and seriously despicable. There are so many better places to eat in Chinatown PLEASE AVOID THIS PLACE AT ALL COSTS. My family owns businesses in the area and I will be telling all of our family, friends, employees, and clients to go elsewhere. Bad service, rude staff, food not edible, force you to leave more money. Don't say I didn't warn you.

text:
1st time here. Picked up a low-key Mother's Day buffet for dinner.  

I agree with others: not oily, tasted fresh. Will order again. Well, some things. 

Shrimp egg foo young & mu shu pork were outstanding. 

The family liked the shrimp egg rolls & dumplings. I gave up my eggroll because they loved it so much so I didn't get to try. I did try one dumpling, I personally didn't care for it. 

We had pork fried rice... It was fine. The Singapore noodles were lacking. But my wife put it in the pan and added seasonings, and then it was amazing. So we honestly don't mind getting Singapore noodles again just to throw it in the pan and fix it up a little. It's like they gave us a great head start, LOL.

The only downfall was the orange chicken. I've got that with the kids in mind. They use the rind or the zest of the orange. It is so bitter and terrible. I appreciate the fresh zest, but that was a fail. And we literally are dreading having to eat this chicken, but I'm not wasting it because it was around $9. We're eating this bitter chicken! When I edit duck sauce it was so bad. Next time we will definitely try sesame.

Overall, I think it's very well priced & quality. It's really difficult to find good Chinese food takeout. Solid pic.

text:
I hadn't been to Han's Dynasty in quite some time! I remember it being way to spicy for my taste at the time, but since then my spice tolerance has grown so much thanks to all the cool foodies I know who forced me to embrace the spice lol

I took the family here for Mother's Day because I knew everyone in that area of University city would be out of town, so the restaurant wouldn't be overly crowded or marking up the price that day.

We were told all the food is served family style so 3-4 dishes should feed 7-8 ppl which was pretty accurate. The host said rice comes out unlimited, but the only tedious thing was having to constantly ask for it instead of them bringing it out as we finished or just bring out one super huge bowl. We are professional rice eaters in my family, and I don't think Han Dynasty was prepared for that. 

We ordered the Scallion pancakes,Dan Dan Noodle,  Pepper Chicken , on Black Bean Style Fish, and one Garlic Tofu dish. All were solid, but the  Black Bean style fish was by far the best. The flavor was so sweet and spicy all at once and the fish was super moist. The cold Dan Dan noodles packed ALOT of spice and flavor as well. I wish I could take that sauce on the noodles home and pour it on everything...except cereal of course.

Anyway, the food was a home run here and the price point was way lower than we all expected. I can't wait to eat here again!

text:
I'll keep it simple:  This is quite possibly the best Chinese food I've ever had.  Affordable, sizable portions, seasoned and cooked perfectly, and a menu that has some special items I haven't seen at other places.

I ordered the tofu and broccoli entree with rice, a vegetable spring roll, and an order of Chinese donuts.  Most places don't have broccoli AND tofu, you get one or the other, so that was already a plus.  The tofu was crispy on the outside and the broccoli was cooked but still somewhat crunchy.  The sauce reminded me of the Chinese food I used to get back in New York...but was somehow better.  

The spring roll was not greasy and the veggies inside weren't the same chewy stringy things I usually get.  The donuts were pretty incredible, especially because you get TEN of them for $3.49.  They weren't overly sweet or greasy - just a perfect end to a great meal.  

I'm nervous that I live near this gem - but nervous in the best way!  ;)

text: So I have been to this restaurant multiple times and never really had a problem, food is always decent but slightly salty at times. However, today when I went for lunch we ordered our food and I asked for some of their spicy cucumber sauce on the side. After some time the waiter/bartender came back and said they need to charge me for the sauce. He said it'll be $1.00, which I was fine with. When we asked for our bill I saw they had charged me for an additional dish, Dan Dan noodles, and I asked and he was like that was for your sauce. Excuse me? If you were going to charge me $8.95 for a side of sauce than I would have ordered the actual appetizer for $6.95!!! I don't think that was right and feel really cheated! In the grand scheme of things it is only a few bucks but it's more about the principle and the fact that it wasn't fully related to me the actual price. I will have got think twice before I ever come back here again!

text:
Chushang Spicy is right in the middle of Chinatown, making it a great place get some spicy food

FOOD: The way this place works is you choose either stir fry or a soup base. It's cool because you can choose exactly what you want to go in each and then your level of spice. It's entirely up to you what you want your meal to be and it is priced accordingly. One warning: even mild spicy is really spicy. 

SERVICE: I can't speak highly of the service. I felt like there were a lot of waiters, but we were still lacking in service. When it was time to get the check, we had to ask 2 different people to get our check. Not a dealbreaker, but it was a little annoying.

AMBIANCE: Honestly, it's very open a pretty cool place for large groups of people. It's still overall quiet and it's very clean on the inside.

Chushang Spicy relies on your own choices to make a great meal. Overall, it's a nice place to go with some friends or even share a couple dishes

text:
2.5 stars for food, 1 star for service. The service is among the worst I have ever received - very cold, slow, inattentive. Also, the seating is way too tight... you will be seated shoulder to shoulder with other parties while there are empty tables throughout.
Food:
CRISPY ROCK SHRIMP - tasty, good portion size, small shrimp size, lacking in crispiness
HONEY GLAZED CHAR SIU PORK - extremely fatty version of the classic char siu pork you can get in Chinatown for a fraction of the price - unnaturally chewy - do not recommend
LOBSTER CHOW FUN - tasty, large portion, light flavor, minimal lobster
CRISPY BRUSSEL SPROUT - this dish is absolutely offensive... the fish sauce was SO FOUL - extremely potent and extra sour - I know this is not normal as fish sauce is a normal part of my ethnic cuisine
I would not recommend this restaurant... go to any other Asian restaurant in Philly, for decent prices, quality Asian food, and better service!

text:
Im giving it a 3.5-4
The service really isn't the greatest but if you know what you're going for, you're good to go. 
Im from out of state but i was definitely craving some amazing soup dumplings and this place is the spot. So, the spicy pork dumplings are soooooo amazing. We also ordered the pork and crab dumplings which were also good. The broth wasn't as good as the spicy pork. 
We also ordered General Tso, extra spicy and there was literally no spice to it. 
Honey glazed walnut shrimp was good, it taste what it sounds like plus a little tang. 
I'd definitely go back just for the dumplings. Very good price for not only size of the dumplings but increments as well. 
Also, it's a cash only restaurant.

text:
Been coming here since I was a kid whenever I craved authentic hand drawn noodles. There's just something about the texture of hand drawn noodles that's unlike any other noodles out there - chewy, very al dente, but perfectly so. The knife cut noodles are also pretty great, though I've always favored hand drawn. I'd definitely recommend coming here if you're in the mood for chewy noodles.

I also recommend this place for their other authentic dishes such as their list of appetizers. If you're adventurous enough, their sliced jellyfish, pickled summer cucumbers, and marinated pork intestines are at the top of my list. 

The atmosphere is a little loud and cramped when there are a lot of customers, but otherwise, it's not a bad place for a sit down dinner. There's also the added convenience of take out. For their sizable portions and competitive dish prices, it's worth the wait.

text:
Would love to give this place a better review but honestly you're paying for the ambience and not the food.  The interior is very nicely designed, as you walk in there's an indoor wall waterfall, the lighting is very dark and intimate, the place is loud and crowded, there's a huge buddha statue that is pretty cool and nice to look at.  We sat at the long table in front of the statue, it has lights under that table, which looks nice but they forgot or opted not to put lights overhead therefore you can barely see your menu or your food.  We had a reservation but it still took about 20minutes to seat us. 
As for the food:  we got various things, the tastiest were the Curried Cauliflower and the Edamame Dumplings.  The edamame dumpling was part of the Dim Sum Sampler platter (for $21), every other dim sum was average tasting at best and I was still hungry after finishing it.  The wasabi mash potatoes and chinese eggplant were edible but basic.  My friend got the grilled lamb chops, and vegetable rice, both are a bit  overpriced, and completely forgetable, I can't even remember if I liked it or not as I'm writing this.

text:
Came here for the first time last night for dinner and was pretty pleased. 

The place itself is pretty cute and got good ambience. There is a bar area to sit at, few tables on the first floor, and more tables on the second. It is a relatively small space so around peak hours on weekends a reservation might be needed. 

The food was delicious! Between me and a friend, we ordered the Dan dan noodles, Szechuan fried rice, and cumin dish with white rice. I got cumin pork but it comes in chicken, beef, and lamb as well. The dan dan noodles tasted great although they were a little mushy, but they were spicy and it's hard for me to find a place that puts enough spice into their food. I wasn't too big a fan of the fried rice, didn't seem like anything special. The cumin dish was really yummy and spicy as well! Pork was cooked perfectly. Portion sizes were decent, this was more than enough for two people and a second meal to boot. Did not try their drinks but they have an extensive drink menu and a bar (as well as happy hour) so they may be good? 

Service was quick and the servers were very attentive and helpful. Water glasses were always full and food came in a timely fashion. 

One thing I will say is it's not exactly cheap for a Chinese place considering that chinatown is a thing. It's not terribly expensive. I know some people would rather go elsewhere. But personally I think it was worth the price and would probably go again if given the chance!

text:
I have wanted to try this restaurant for years and with my friend making a reservation for her bachelorette party the time had finally come! We were able to set up a family style meal for eight with a set price before we went with drinks a la carte.

The food was amazing. I loved everything that came out. We had brocollini and beets for our first courses. It was then on to pasta and pizza which was top notch. Next was steak and fish which weren't my favorite but were well cooked but a bit under seasoned. Lastly was dessert my favorite of which was the panna cotta like cheesecake.

My concern and why I chose to write a yelp review was that the server did something very sketchy and something I haven't seen before as a former waitress myself or in other restaurants. At the beginning of the meal I ordered a wine and where my red flag went up is when I had 1/4 of a glass left and he refilled 1. Without asking if I'd like more and 2. It wasn't a fresh full glass of wine so I only got a 3/4 pour. This was very strange to me but I thought maybe the other girls had gotten a bottle and he forgot which wine I got.

At the end of the night it turns out he was doing this to every lady at the table who had gotten wine. Our bill came back with 9 wines between two ladies which was very high. We complained to the server with him being rude about it. The manager ended up taking a wine or two off so while appreciated I just want the server to be trained as well. It was a very sketchy practice and while I don't personally blame the restaurant I would most likely not go back knowing this server was doing this. 

I have the servers name if management is interested but won't post it publicly here.

text:
Wanted to try Ocean City for a while after I saw a line leading out the door last year. It's located in the outskirts of Chinatown (away from the crowds). This place seems like a more traditional dim sum joint (carts and all!). As such, I'm not sure if this place has soup dumplings (if that is what you are looking for). It's a relatively big place and didn't feel crowded, which was nice for conversations! 

The food was as expected for your average dim sum place and the price didn't seem bad (probably spent less than $12 per person). My faves were probably the pan fried chive dumplings and the fried taro balls. The dumplings were crispy on the outside with a pretty generous amount of filling. Although it was quite oil-y. The fried taro had an soft, savory taro filling with a crunchy outer shell. I was probably most disappointed with the baked pork buns (which I had high expectations for). While I liked the taste of the sweet bun in contrast with the pork, the bun, itself, was dry. When you bite into it, it was hollow with a tiny portion of bbq pork. There are bakeries in Chinatown that sell baked pork buns that were more satisfying than this one.

Overall, I felt that this place is worth trying. I would probably give Ocean City 3.5 stars. Dim sum on a weekend is such a nostalgic memory. Being able to see the carts rolling by was truly a treat that I feel many places have retired. I, personally, would take friends and family here if they wanted the traditional dim sum experience. There are many "dim sum" places in Chinatown, but I don't think they all serve the traditional dim sum dishes. I think this place ticks that checkbox. The service was good. I felt that the carts made their way around the restaurant quite frequently. One lady in the dumpling cart was even kind enough to pick out a fresher looking set of dumplings (rather than giving us dried up ones).

text:
A top spot for family style, whether you have three people or 20 people. I've been here plenty of times now, and have yet to be disappointed by their dishes (and their unlimited white rice). Only thing I would have to knock is that the servers should come around more often to refill waters and rice.
For this quality, price (especially during lunch special), and portion size, this place is one of my staples when in a group.

My recommendations: dry pepper chicken/fish, mapo tofu, dan dan noodles, double cooked pork, string beans w/ minced pork.

text: A little pricey for what you receive, but if you need some dumplings, noodles, and veggies, it's worth a night out with a group. They keep a high-turnover, so it's not as relaxed coming in a small group, as it seems like they're always waiting for a large group to come in (they usually don't take reservations). The shrimp dumplings were small but satisfying, and I loved the brisket ho fun! The noodles are so satisfying and the sauce was a nice balance of salty and sweet. The steamed bok choy tied everything together. Here, you can find something to your liking. The cash-only was a little annoying to deal with, as they accept forms of online payment, but the ATM fee was only $1.75 so it wasn't the worst. Will be coming back soon to try something new!

text: This was our first stop in Philly after a long day of driving and it was definitely the perfect end to our day. We ordered the beef brisket noodles and roast duck noodles which were both amazing! The noodles were fresh and delicious, the broth was well made, and the meat was cooked perfectly. The service was quick -- after ordering, the food came out almost instantaneously. The price is also very reasonable especially since the portion sizes were pretty large! They do only take cash though. We also didn't drive here, but it seems like parking here would be pretty tough. Definitely would love to try some more items on their menu next time we are in Philly!

text:
Chu Shang is located right next to the iconic Friendship Arch in Philly's Chinatown.

It's a great restaurant, although it might not fit everyone's palate given the food might be a little too spicy for many people's tastes, myself included. 

I'd recommend getting the pick your own ingredient Ma La Soup, which is basically akin to getting hot pot although it's already made for you and given to you in a separate bowl.

Pros:
* It's super super super economical, meaning value for money and purchasing power are super high.
* The serving portions are simply freakishly humongous. I've never had bigger serving portions at literally any damn restaurant in my life.
* There's a great assortment of things that you can get in your bowl, be it meat, veggies, noodles, what not.

Cons:
* It could be super spicy. It's a Sichuanese restaurant, meaning their scale of spiciness is completely different from what a normal person would expect. FYI, mild doesn't mean mild in conventional terms; it'd be more of a "less spicier" one. Get the No Spicy option if you can't handle spice, you'll thank me later.

The biggest surprise is their Taiwan braised pork combo with rice/egg, it was quite tasty and portion size was huge. The price on each of those dishes are truly affordable with good taste. 
Another pro SH has is To use credit card, can't believe how many restaurants here only accept cash.
