text:
Went with some friends for a pre-Christmas get together. We've been to NaBrasa in Horsham (see my review) so we were curious to try Chima. 

The place has complimentary valet parking which is nice for downtown Philadelphia. We didn't have to worry about find a space and constantly running out to pay the meter. 

For those who've tried Brazilian steakhouses, Chima is pretty much like any restaurant in that style. The servers come around with the meats and you can choose if you want them to stop at your table or not with the little coaster like thing. 

The little cheese popover breads were soo good. I had to stop myself from eating too much of them so I could have room for the meats. All the meats were very juicy and flavorful. The only thing is we had to ask the manager a couple of times to have a certain kind of meat brought over to the table. Otherwise, the same kinds were being offered and we wanted to try a variety. 

There's a pretty big buffet of salads, fruits, and cheese that comes with the meal. The price here per person is pretty steep but this is Philadelphia and the restaurant is very nice and the food is delicious.

text: YOU HAVE TO GO HERE!!!!! Find a parking spot in one of the many lots in China town and walk, no RUN here because I am telling you, you will NOT regret it. They only accept cash, venom, or cash app but honestly once you have the food you will not care! Where to start! You have to make a reservation if you do not want to wait because it seems like everyone knows how good their food is, but trust me, its totally worth the wait! We have gone here 3 times in the same week because we (my fiancé and I) could not stop thinking about how amazing the food was. And also I was 5-6 months pregnant so that also was a factor ;) We start with the soup, and it was truly the best I have ever had. You can tell that it is fresh and they make the dumplings there because they do not taste like your typical around the corner ingredients. Next up we did the fried dumplings and again, WOW! They were soooo good we ordered a second round. For dinner we had the Truffle beef fried rice and when I tell you I dream about this rice and my mouth waters, I am not joking. I can honestly say that this is the best fried rice I have ever had. We have also tried a few of the sides, but we just kept going back to the rice. The first time there was after the auto show and my fiancé ordered the sweet and sour chicken which was also really good. You could tell they batter the chicken there and it is not frozen which is really important. The prices are NOT that bad, I am not sure what other reviewers are talking about. Other places in china town have cheaper menus because you can taste that they use frozen food. Bai Wei does not and it shows! We were so happy and delighted with everything we ordered I can not wait to go back again soon! You HAVE to go! And don't forget about their desserts. I can promise you wont have room left, but make sure you get one to go! And if you're as hooked to the candies you get after your meal like I was, they are guava and you can get an entire bag of them across the street for less than $2! This is totally my favorite restaurant in China Town! Hands down!

text:
Somehow I have been walking by this place for years and didn't come in for hotpot till now! I was pleasantly surprised when I first came at how clean the place was and well-ventilated. The prices are also reasonable, I liked the service, and I was happy with the quality of the food! I came with a group of four and we didn't want to do unlimited/buffet so we ended up saving some money by ordering individual ingredients. We opted to share a pot as a group that was half pork bone broth & half spicy broth rather than each have our individual pots.

Some of my fave ingredients from here: spam, frozen tofu, pumpkin, beef balls, fried shrimp balls, taro, sweet potato...all stuff that soaks up the flavor of the broth well. :)

I love the huge selection of dipping sauces! Here's what I put in mine and was really pleased with: garlic oil (this was a first for me!), sesame oil, peanut butter sauce (hadn't put this in my usual sauces either), hoisin sauce, soy sauce, sesame oil, sesame paste, cilantro, chili sauce. Really I'm writing this here so I don't forget myself haha.

text:
Took my girlfriend here for her birthday back in March. From the moment we walked in to the moment we left we were surrounded by great staff. Everyone from the host to our waitress. Even the general manager came over to our table to make sure we were satisfied. Also, the food was amazing! The steak was our favorite. We almost went back the next day just for the steak Haha. 

We were a bit overdressed compared to everyone else there but no big deal. Other than that we just wished there were more sides to choose from and drinks seemed a bit over priced. 

Looking forward to visiting again in June for my birthday.

text:
This bowl is huge and huge. I actually like this place since u can custom your own pot bowl at reasonable price. I had ear fungi, tofu, noddles, double meats, Mushroom, there is no veggie on here since I don't normally eat it. Mainly some dry mushroom, double meats, sausage with glass noodles. It ends up to be around $14, if you add more, it will cost more. U can choose ur own spiciness.

It is very interesting how I randomly just checked stuffs I would like to eat and they turn out to taste pretty good, I guess it is the broth is very flavorful in general. They also have dry pot or with broth. 

I came here 3 times total already, I had a lot of fun each time eating with friends since it was a challenge what you order and how much you can eat, but they were quite manageable. Price isn't bad at all for customized bowl you get 

Definitely will come back again when visiting Philly in the future

text:
Okay so surprisingly the food was good especially compared to the other Chinese stores in the upper northeast where I'm from  

The chicken wings tasted good and I can tell the oil used was fresh 

The shrimp fried rice w/Broccoli and egg added had a good flavor too 

I did notice my wings had a yellowish hue to them (seems to be a trend in the northeast I don't know why nor do I find it appealing)  

The egg foo young gravy was rather thin (however that actually made it being poured over the rice better because the rice soaked it up quickly ) 

I did order 5 wings I got 4 (I think she misheard me 5 &(fried ) sounds similar enough 
All my request where met and the lady at the front seemed eager to make sure I was satisfied. 

If I had one complaint I'd say it was kinda pricey I paid about 15$ and some change. 

The homemade pink lemonade was 2$ 
The wings and shrimp fried rice platter where about 7$ 
I'm guessing the egg and broccoli plus tax cost 5$ 
Not really sure how it totaled up 

I do think it's worth the trip and honestly the money I have left overs and like I said the lady at the counter made sure she got my order right and that means a lot to me 

I would like to know what that yellow tent is though

The spicy pork soup dumplings deserve 5/5, but the score is brought down due to the general atmosphere, cleanliness, and the shao mai.

text:
Penang is a very popular Malaysian restaurant in Chinatown offering delicious food and large portions at reasonable prices.

Easy to miss from the outside, the restaurant is actually quite nice and very large on the inside. Stylish decor and a spacious dining area make for an enjoyable ambiance. The restaurant can probably seat a few hundred, but even then, it gets busy in the evening - so if you're coming with a big group, you should definitely make a reservation. It also gets quite loud due to all the people, so just keep that in mind, if you'd rather dine somewhere more peaceful.

The menu here is huge and honestly gave me a bit of decision paralysis. They offer Malaysian soups, rice dishes, noodle dishes, stir fries, and more. The descriptions are vague, making it difficult to know exactly what you'll get, so sometimes you just need to order something and hope for the best. In fact, I'm pretty sure the dish I received was different from what I ordered (the staff are a bit difficult to communicate with), but I didn't really know what my dish was supposed to look like in the first place, so I just went with it. As a solution, I recommend family-style sharing as a way to try multiple dishes (and also hedge your risk in case there's one item that isn't quite what you expected!). If you're looking for safe bets on the menu, I'd recommend the Nasi Lemak (delicious and lots of variety within the one dish) and the Hainanese chicken (simple but tasty).

Overall, Penang is a fun - albeit sometimes a bit stressful - adventure into Malaysian cuisine. If you're down for tasty food at a good price-value with a dash of YOLO on the side, then bring some friends and visit Penang!

text: A planned evening with family led us to this classic Chinatown establishment. After a hefty walk we had worked up an appetite and were parched as well. Ting Wong is BYOB so we were able to mull over their extensive menu while rewarding ourselves for taking the shoelace express with a couple cold ones. The service was perfect and we did not feel rushed in making our decisions with the food subsequently arriving quickly after placing our order. We began with the curry beef stew - tender beef in a golden curry sauce with onion petals laid over a bed of white rice. A nice spice but not overwhelming to those who do not enjoy spicy. Next were some egg rolls - solid classic Chinese restaurant style. Dumplings followed the egg rolls with same sentiment, solid but nothing to make or break the review. The wonton soup on the other hand was a different take than I was familiar with, eight shrimp dumplings in a bowl of broth with bok choy. Hearty enough for a cold evening but light enough to enjoy in the warmer months as well. The final app we ordered was the roast duck. This was a no brainer. Ting Wong has a butcher up front slicing and dicing tender, juicy duck almost as if to say "I dare you not to order this". While I'm not a duck connoisseur I've had it at much more expensive restaurants and it did not compare. Succulent, fatty, flavorful. The star of the night making for two appearances on the table. The soy chicken was next on the chopping block and like the duck it was ordered twice. Rich flavorful chicken with a pillow of white rice underneath. The final dish was roast pork pan fried noodles. Crispy noodles on the outside with soft sauce-soaked noodles beneath a generous portion of roast pork and broccoli in a sweet sauce. With a feast like this you'd expect a bill only Daddy Warbucks could splurge on - not the case. Ting Wong's very reasonable prices and bountiful choices make for a great go-to for anyone looking for a meal in Chinatown.

text: I went into this place because I wanted to try xiao long bao (aka "soup dumplings") so much since it is a food from my bucket list. Once I arrived, it has a nice Asian American vibe across the interior of the restaurant. The staff are generally really nice and are able to be fluent in both english and chinese, which is great for me as a foreigner. I had the three main types of soup dumplings, they were all so good and we actually easy to eat. My favorite out of the three was the Wu Xi soup dumplings. Although the prices and tips can be a little expensive, I would definitely go here again for the soup dumplings and much more.

This restaurant has a mom and pop feel to it. The menu has pictures and prices are reasonable. Most dishes are 6-13$. The service wasn't that great as they never refilled our water unless we flagged them down. The other inconvenience is they brought out all of our food at different times. So some people had to start eating while everyone else waited for their food. The portions are a good size and the food is delicious I would just like if there was better service.

text:
Time for an update!  In the few years since I initially posted this review, Lucky Star is still one of my go-to sushi places in the area.  The fish is fresh, the food overall is always good, and I think it offers a great value.

Coming here for dinner over the weekend, my boyfriend and I were greeted with friendly service and were seated right away.  We were given waters and crispy wonton strips with two sauces for dipping: a sweet duck sauce and a spicy mustard. I like dunking the wonton strip in both dips for a spicy-sweet combo.

I ordered the Maki Combo which comes with your choice of three rolls under $6, plus miso soup and the house salad.  The miso soup was good (average miso flavor), and the salad was nice as well.  I really liked the dressing which was not overly acidic as I find some ginger dressings.  I do wish the salad had romaine rather than iceberg lettuce, but that's pretty standard.

The rolls I selected were:
-Salmon Avocado: Your basic salmon avo roll with good amounts of each.  This is a basic roll but it's one I always enjoy.
-Crunch Spicy Tuna:  This is one of my favorite spicy spicy tuna rolls of any restaurant.  I think theirs just has great flavor!
-Mango Shrimp: A little sweet for me, kind of like dessert sushi.  I probably won't get this one again, but that's just personal preference.  I will say the mango was perfectly ripe!

My boyfriend got the Orange Chicken entree with brown rice (you can also order white rice instead).  I don't usually like orange chicken as I find it too cloying or with a weirdly-textured sauce, but I really enjoyed this one!  I kept stealing bites.  The chicken was cooked nicely and had a lovely light crunch.  Happy to have tried this dish here.

Although Lucky Star is situated in a vaguely unwelcoming strip mall of sorts, don't let the appearance throw you off.  Inside is tasty food, good service, and a meal that won't break the bank.  I'll be back again!

text:
Customer Service: 5 stars: came in around 1150pm was seated immediately. The older gentleman was very friendly and engaging.

Food: 2 stars: the food was more salty than what im used to. Like salty to the point i had to pop a blood pressure pill and water pill, im so not joking. The hot and sour soup was gelatinous **gags** i could only take so much of that. Ive had hot and sour soup many places but not quite like this. I think they use more constarch than broth to strech the soup out. Very cheap move **tsk tsk** the food was ok but not all that. It was better than Chinese food in the south but to northern standards it wasnt all that compared to what ive eaten in nyc or boston. Overall its decent if you need late night eats but..... in the morning you will be blowing out! Lol drink lots of water eating this food. The steamed dumplings were decent. 

Cleanliness: 4 stars: a dated Chinese restaurant but overall clean. 

Price point: 4 stars: the prices are fair. 

Overall: it was decent but i probably wouldn't come back. I wouldn't recommend it unless its super late, you dont want to spend  a lot of money, and you want a short walk to dine from your hotel.

text:
If you want delicious and authenticity in Chinese cuisine, you've hit a goldmine! Unlike many popular fusion places around the city, this hole in the wall stay true to its roots. Everything is fresh, tastes delicious and priced low in comparison to the rising costs of dining out. Their portion size is more than decent for what you're paying for. 

The service is a hit or miss. I've experienced decent service here and occasionally abrupt service but I'm also understanding of cultural and language barriers. The waitstaff are much older so be patience with them. 

This is probably not the place to be if you want fine dining or cater-to-me service. As a true foodie, I'm just there for the food lol.

text:
Finally a good and cheap Chinese food chain in Philly!

I highly recommend the wonton soup, peanut sauce noodles, and dumplings. All 3 are very authentic. The Wonton soup has the thinnest skin you'll find in Philly, for only $2.50! The peanut sauce noodles are also only $2.50 and taste very good with the vinegar, however, it would've been even better if it was black instead of white/rice vinegar. The dumplings are very fresh and they only cost $5. I would skip the meat soup as it was literally just a bowl of meat in the wonton soup.

Only reason this place gets 4 stars is the fact that they only use plastic plates/bowls/utensils and cash only.

text:
I write this review with the preface that I have eaten at Dim Sum Garden before on a busier Friday night, so I was already a fan of the cuisine.  

It was a rainy Thursday night and I was traveling from Washington, DC to Philly.  After a tiring drive the popular spot was in sight, so I parked my car outside the restaurant.  A few taps of my phone directed me to the restaurant's website that said 
Hours : 10:30am - 10:30pm, 7 days a week 
The bright neon OPEN sign illuminated in front of my eager eyes, bringing me hope that I could still enjoy the different dumplings and delectable dishes.  At 10:22 pm I proceeded to walk in.  

Immediately I was stopped by a server (name tag said Ivan) cleaning the table who told me the kitchen was closed.  People were still eating at a few tables.  I explained I had been traveling far and pointed out the sign said OPEN.  Ivan responded that the kitchen had closed at 10pm.
I brought up the second point of the website's hours, but was ignored by the waiter who continued cleaning.

Then approached the dim corleone, the manager of mao pao - Sally, the daughter of the dim sum empire.  I had seen her picture on the website and was relieved she would break from her phone conversation to talk with me.  
Delivering to her my desire to dine at the Dim Sum from the duress of my drive, she responded that the kitchen closed at 10:20pm.  As I went to respond about the website hours, Sally turned away from me and went back to her phone conversation.

Now here's where it became frustrating - two different closing times, two different stories.  But even more hurtful was the lack of care from an owner who just went back to business, without any offer to apologize or invite me to return.

I'm not going to center on the service expectations for a bustling place like Dim Sum Garden.  Not expecting white table clothes or friendly conversations with the waiters.  You're in, you're out, you eat, you pay - the food is why you go.
But this interaction with Sally is an example of a powerhouse restaurant that understands the plateau they've achieved and can honestly turn people away without any regards for standards, and that's a dang shame.  The hours are the hours.  If a sign says OPEN turn it off, or lock the door, or how about just honor the hours?  If Sally had stopped to hear my story, apologize and just say come back tomorrow, I would have been way happier than just given the cold shoulder.  Indeed, a little bit of listening and building a long term relationship with any customer is a core value, no matter how big you get.

It's like that scene at the end of the movie Casino where Robert De Niro says "Back in those days people knew your name, what you drank.  But in the end, they messed it all up."  

Alas, I did not bite on the bao this evening.  I guess you dim sum and you lose some.

And since the waiter and Sally were so creative at offering their explanations of why they closed, I thought to contribute my creativity with a poem of my experience.  

I been done starvin' for the Dim Sum Garden
Kitchen's closed?  I beg your pardon?
The sign outside it gave no warnin'
The waiter's eyes they stayed ignorin'
Stomach growl, I wanted bao
But Sally said no way not now
I left still starvin' for the Dim Sum Garden
This whole experience was slim fun darlin


---
UPDATE : Sally from Dim Sum Garden read my concerns and was gracious enough to contact me.  She explained the kitchen serves dine in guests before 10:00pm, and takeout service continues for about 20 minutes prior to close at 10:30pm.  She clarified and invited me to return.  Just acknowledging guest concerns like this one even for a misunderstanding of hours is the way to go.  Take a Bao, Sally.  Many thanks!

text: Delicious, authentic, affordable! The crabmeat and pork soup dumplings are to die for. Although I wish it was served with some of that pink vinegar and ginger that usually comes with soup dumplings I used to get in NYC. The best thing on the menu is the beef scallion pancake/roll. Don't skip out on that! The cucumber is marinated with numbing chili pepper which was a surprising twist but it's very good and cooling on the palate while eating soup dumplings. The Taiwanese pan fried dumplings didn't blow me away but it was still delicious overall. Don't miss out on this spot when you're in Philadelphia!

text: Food isn't particularly 'fine' dining but it's solid tasting and a fun environment for a bar vibe. Dark-lit with purple lighting, loud atmosphere for a place to take friends, the food tastes like good-tasting bar food -- definitely fusion Asian food, nothing terribly authentic nor misappropriated, although they do use wooden, disposable chopsticks in a restaurant advertising itself as Asian.. A little pricey given the quality but it's still tasty, I would never oppose to returning.

text: I have been to many markets and this place takes first place. They have a farmers market and many places to eat different cuisine's. Prices were pretty fair. One thing that was surprising is the market closing at 6 PM. All of the staff encountered were incredibly friendly. With that being said, this is a very busy place! The space is tight and it could be overwhelming to make decisions of where to eat and the close proximity of vendors... Pretty typical of markets in large cities. I would not bring children here because of the limited space. They offer breakfast, lunch and dinner. Very fair competitive prices between vendors and generally kept quite clean. I'm going back again and again. Thank you!

text: Vegetarian Chinese restaurant with lots of vegan options. Made reservations via yelp. Superb service, we were immediately given water and tea and overview of the menu. Get the scallion pancakes. Deep fried, crispy and chewy, it's almost as good as my mom's (which is extremely hard to beat). Comes with 8 pieces and a great price. The boiled dumplings were ok but our main entrees the sesame seitan and eggplant tofu more than made up for it. Huge portions and both dishes were excellent. The seitan was perfect, lots of flavor and balance well with the broccoli. The eggplant tofu had good texture, spice and cooked to perfection. We had plenty of leftovers to take home and even given fortune cookies and sliced oranges for dessert. Reminiscent of our childhood days of going to Chinese restaurants with our parents, this was a great experience. But without the cruelty of animal products, this is a wonderful meal to have!

text:
I've never heard of conveyor belt hot pot so I decided to give Chubby Cattle a try!! It was definitely a good idea :)

To explain how it works, you pretty much have a couple of options such as seaweed knots, crabsticks, tofu, etc on the conveyor belt, and depending on the color of the plate, you'll be charged for a certain price. I highly recommend picking out of the conveyor belt if you have less people, because that'll guarantee finishing the meal. I only went with my boyfriend so the conveyor belt idea was really good. We got a couple of plates of food and then ordered more important things such as vegetables and meat on the menu. I highly recommend getting the $25 meat combo, it's such a steal. We also got the Wagyu Uni and Foie Gras Uni sushi ($18 for 2) for both and I definitely recommend the Wagyu over the Foie Gras. 

Overall, service was really great as well. Only thing I would say there aren't a lot of options on the conveyor belt and menu in general, and when I put myself on the waitlist, the waitress gave up on me after 5 minutes even though on the app it says I was #10 in line, which is why I was far away shopping. If you're in the area, I do recommend trying out Chubby Cattle!

text:
If you care more about the quality of what's on your plate than how pretty the dining room is, Penang is the place to go. 

If you aren't familiar with Malaysian food, it might help you to look at their menu on line before you go because when you get there and get seated, you'll be reading at least 6 pages of dishes and trying to decide what's what, what's good and what's not too weird to your Western tastebuds and sensibilities. Chicken feet with Chinese mushroom casserole anyone?!

This place is always busy when I go but they're quick to get you seated and give you tea. I like to sit by the kitchen and watch one of the guys make the hand pulled noodles (fascinating af!) and see what's coming up to be served. The kitchen looks clean and it always smells good in this place. 

Once you place your order, service is fast. No one has ever been rude to me and if I have a question about the food, the servers are always helpful  and often funny. 3 of my all time favorites are the shrimp puffs, which are big fried puffs of minced shrimp and bacon that are put in batter and quickly deep fried then served with a mayo-ish dipping sauce. You don't expect the bacon and these are so devilishly good, not at all heavy or greasy, I always consider making a second order but good sense invariably prevails. I like the spring rolls but in reality, they are nothing special nor will they rock your culinary reality. They are stuffed with vegetables, on the bland side but their crispness and non-greasiness appeal. I just have a 'thing' for spring rolls. Hey, I never said I was perfect.

People ooh and ahh about the roti cani but this one is under my radar. It's a hunk of pita-ish bread (they call it a 'pancake') that gets dipped into a curried chicken and potato gravy. Big yawn to this one. I've had it here and at Rangoon and it's basically boring, carby comfort type food. So order it if you need comfort but don't fill up on it to the detriment of trying other things. 

The beef or chicken skewers are okay but again, nothing extraordinary. The dish I'd really recommend is the beef rendang with white rice. Let me say first off that I am not wild about Penang's white rice. It's a bit on the mushy side but once you start throwing food on top of it, that becomes less bothersome. Anyway, rendang. It's tender chunks of beef cooked in coconut milk and flavored with cinnamon, star anise, cloves, cardamom and lemongrass. It's cooked low and slow, the meat is meltingly tender and the gravy/curry is a powerhouse of mellow flavor. Not sweet. No vegetables in it, just the fall apart beef in that marvelous, rich curry gravy. 

I always get an order of vegetables, too. My go to is the Chinese broccoli (gai lan) with garlic. Simple, garlicy, fresh. The bitterness of the leafy parts contrasts nicely with the natural sweetness of the garlic. The gai lan stalks are quick cooked and crisp-tender. It's not drowning in sauce. It's a bright, tasty adjunct to some of the heavier curries. 

Portions are very generous, prices are reasonable for the quality and quantity and you can go from very basic fare-like the skewers-to fish head soup and pork intestines so there will be something on the menu to please and offend everyone. 

Penang deserves your dining dollars.

text: Came here with my family on a Saturday afternoon. We were too late for dim sum but we were able to try their noodle and rice dishes. We got the wonton noodle soup, beef chow fun, seafood fried noodles and roast pork and duck on rice. Our favorite was definitely the roast pork and duck on rice. It might be a little too salty on it's own but with the rice, it was amazing. The roast pork had a good balance of fat so that it wasn't too dry and the duck was succulent. Our second favorite was the beef chow fun. It was drier than ones I've had before but also had great flavor and the meat was tender. The seafood fried noodles weren't bad but they got soggy very quickly, I felt there was a bit too much sauce. And the wonton noodles were just ok, the noodles lacked the bite typical wonton noodles should have. Their portion sizes are also appropriate for the price and for family style. Service was good, they were attentive and patient when we were deciding what to order. Would definitely recommend this place and come again, especially to try the dim sum.

text:
This is the first Asian bakery I've been to and it's still my favorite.  Everything is baked fresh daily. I typically go for the sweet pastries even though I've had the savory.  My favorite will always be the coconut cream bun. The bun is so soft and the cream is a a beautiful, buttery and fluffy filling that's perfectly sweet.  They use this filling is some of their other pastries. My fiance usually goes for the taro bun which has this excellent sugary layer on the outside of the bun that I wish covered the whole thing.  

KC is cash only which falls in line with most places in Chinatown.  Everything is so reasonably priced here I usually never have to take money out.  Even pocket change could cover the cost of one pastry.

text:
Hovering between a 3 and 4 star rating for this place because certain stuff here is a great deal, while other things not so much. If you come for the lunch specials during the week, you'll find a good price and good flavors. I really enjoyed the pad thai, but the curry and kenshin chicken were just alright. The bubble tea had an odd floral taste to it, but the sushi is pretty big and made fresh to order, plus the miso soup was perfect. The lo mein was not made with homemade noodles (more of a spaghetti noodle, I didn't really enjoy that) but the crab rangoon is awesome and so fresh.

You have to see what you like and what you don't, but this place has a pretty good sampling from different asian cuisines, and for that, I'll give it a 3.5.

text:
I don't really write reviews on Yelp much, so it means a lot when I have such a bad experience that I feel compelled to write something. My wife and I were walking past and saw from the window what looked to be a pretty lively restaurant with nice and clean decor, so we decided to go in. We got the Beijing zhajiang noodles, Shanghai bok choy, and stir-fried noodles with crab. 

Food - the flavor was pretty good so I was debating giving two stars instead of one. However it mainly tasted so good because it felt like they loaded it with a lot of MSG. I ended up deciding to not give a star because the noodles with crab were an absolute travesty. The crab is not removed from the shell and is embedded within the noodles. When you break open the shell you have to struggle to find a small piece of meat. They even for some reason thought it would be a good idea to leave a completely empty body of the crab on top of the noodles? On top of this, my wife bit into what she thought were noodles and ended up giving her tooth a nice hard surprise from a tiny crab shell. Later while I was eating the noodles I also felt a tiny crab shell piece stab me in my mouth. These are tiny pieces of crab shell that are impossible to see inside the noodles and are definitely going to break someone's tooth at some point. The Shanghai bok choy was acceptable, it was delicious in fact, but again tasted quite heavily of MSG. The Beijing zhajiang noodles were also authentic, but the quantity was very small so it felt like a poor value.

Service - the servers were not particularly friendly. They brought food to the wrong tables at least a couple times (including our noodles with crab) while we were there, as if they weren't very experienced with remembering who ordered what. The cooks didn't seem to be very fast because we had to wait about 15 minutes to get our whole meal (which is not very long but when you're in Chinatown it feels much longer than the norm here). Right when we got our food they immediately gave us the check and circled the tip calculations, I guess implying that we needed to tip at least 15%? This really didn't leave a great impression or atmosphere for eating. 

Finally, oddly this place doesn't have any real silverware and you're eating off paper plates and plastic bowls. I would love that if you're a cheap place providing quick food, but when I'm at a sit down place paying tip I'm usually expecting to eat off something better than a paper plate with a plastic fork. It's like this place didn't get everything ready before they opened up (I'm guessing they just newly opened?). I would give them the benefit of the doubt for being new but this was just a horrendous experience for me so I don't think I will be going back. Definitely the worst restaurant experience I can remember in at least the past few years.

text: My Weekend devours walked with me to @asianpalacerestaurant ; located on the NW corner of 20th st and Oregon Ave. this is a very huge establishment hosting catering events such as weddings, graduation parties, and etc; while also hosting a full restaurant that's fully furnished and decorated with lovely flowers  and vines. The lighting it perfect for all dates and pictures. The server was very young and very nice and well educated about the two menus that were being served. She was very helpful throughout the night and continuously checked up on the status of the dinner . They had both a Asian menu and a full seafood  menu. Their drink menu is very diverse with over 10 cocktails and over 11 imported beers. All of the food was ordered from the seafood menu by which the front of the menu had its simple yet really affordable appetizers. On the back of the menu is where it got good . On the back of the menu what is the amount of steamed seafood you can order along with all of their signature sauces. They also serve three different combos of Seafood boil's. First order was the fried calamari that was served with spicy duck sauce, which was really good and tasty. However, the fried calamari didn't really hold any competition with the salt and pepper fried shrimp  that was ordered next. The salt and pepper shrimp were full size prawns  with the heads still attached on them. They were fried to perfection yet being fried with the shell still on them. Yet, That didn't matter nor did it stop me from devouring the whole prawn ‍. Next was steamed shrimp in they're very spicy Cajun sauce; and the Steamed Dungeness crab legs  served in their signature medium hot Cajun sauce. Both were very juicy and FULL of flavor. The bid and gloves served no justice AT ALL ‍. If you find yourself in the south Philadelphia area and wanting seafood that's not expensive and a really kool date/celebration spot! text:
I love hotpot so I really wanted to try this place before leaving Philadelphia. It's not all you can eat though so beware. It's a la carte and charges per dish on the conveyor belt, so may end up being a bit pricey. The soup broth is super delicious though and the beef combo which comes with fatty brisket/wagyu is really good and a nice deal. I didn't like the calamari (squid) that we ordered and seafood in general seemed lacking. But other than that it was great. Other items off the conveyor belt we nice and service was fine. They kind of forgot to refill our water a lot, but not a huge deal.

Overall tasty and filling meal, I'd honestly come back for the super yummy broth and beef. The check-in deal is pretty nice too!

text: If you're smart, you will avoid this restaurant at all costs. We tried this place for their happy hour and ordered a meat dish. We could not even chew through it and had to send it back. We were told it was the end of the filet, which are usually tougher, and cheaper to buy. Our building then offered coupons for the restaurant, buy one/get one, and decided to return to try the full dinner experience. We arrived and the restaurant was nearly empty, which is not a good sign in our eyes at prime dinner time. We were served gummy dinner rolls and sent to the salad bar. A disappointment, not much to make a salad with, and quite a few pre-made salads that looked like that had sat out all day. When we tried the meats that came around (which were few and far between and the same came around a lot), they were very hard to chew through again or full of fat and gristle and we could not eat it. The only thing that was edible was the lamb and salmon, and the salmon was extremely dry. We were forced to pay 18% tip on our receipt, it is added onto your bill, so even if you receive terrible service, you will have to pay that. I think this is the first restaurant we have had this happen. Upon returning home, I became violently ill, and I believe I ended up with food poisoning. If you want the full rodizio experience with excellent service and food, try Fogo de Chao on 13th and Chestnut. They are consistently excellent in food and service and never disappoint.

text:
This place is SUPER unique. If you're looking for a spot to go with a big group of friends, look no further. Chuan Kee has something for everyone and everything on the menu is easy to share.

Went here with a friend on a weekday evening and were seated quickly. Our server explained the menu, how to order, and pointed out her favorites and popular items. I really appreciate when servers do this, especially when dining at a unique place - I'm sometimes shy to ask questions!

We ordered a few BBQ skewers, a hot pot, soft shell crabs, and fried rice. Portion sizes were on point with what I expected for the prices (skewers range from $1.50-5... but with the $5 ones we ordered, you get 3 skewers)! Everything was really tasty and an overall great value. The soft shell crabs and pineapple fried rice are a MUST. The hot pot really stood out and was super fun to eat. If you don't fill up too much, the mochi green tea ice cream is also really yummy.

We really enjoyed our experience here and plan to come back with more friends so we can try even more of the menu!!

text: You see a Chinese restaurant in this neighborhood maybe every 4 blocks-- but as far as post-bar food goes, this place is pretty great! The hours go well with late night munchies, and the menu has something for everyone, with some consistent quality. Don't let the bulletproof glass and cutouts in the window fool you! You can watch them cook the food in the back. Cash only! They cook fast, and you can pop into The Barn next door and grab a drink or play pool while you wait! This was my first experience with the Philly phenomenon Yat Mein, and I fell in love! The general tso's was a good texture and flavor, and the egg rolls pretty large and satisfying. Pretty great prices and portions!

text:
We had a really bad experience here! There was lots of confusion about our reservation. Multiple orders were messed up. Half of our drinks took almost 30 minutes to come out, and our food took more than an hour. Several tables who were seated long after we arrived received their food before us. We eventually left without eating because it was taking so long. 

Even if the service had been good, I have concerns about the menu. There is no draft beer, and instead they have bottled beer that is very overpriced. I'm not interested in paying $6 for a 12 oz bottle when I can get 16 oz of the same beer on tap for the same price at another restaurant. Additionally, their food is very expensive. I regularly eat the same dishes for half the price a few blocks away in Chinatown. Maybe the quality is better, but I'm skeptical.

text: This was our first visit to Sampan, a modern Asian Fusion restaurant, and we can't wait to come back. In short, excellent food and excellent service, but generally pricey given portion sizes. We have 5pm reservations for a Sat evening and arrived about 15 minutes early but was promptly seated regardless. The menu is printed on small paper, so between that and the dimly lit dining room, my old eyes had a little bit of difficulty reading the menu. Everything here is basically small plates and our waiter recommended getting 5-6 things for the two of us. We actually wound up going with the "7-course" menu, which was $45 per person. We were warned that food will come out as it's ready and won't come out in any particular order. What we didn't expect was our first item to arrive about 3 minutes after we placed or order! And it generally didn't slow down from that point forward. We basically got through the 7-courses plus dessert in a little over 30 minutes! We never felt rushed per se and we usually had a few minutes in between courses. After the first four courses, I was getting worried that I might walk out hungry, but happily I can say that was not the case. I was full, but not stuffed. Everything we had was simply amazing. We had the Shrimp Egg Rolls, Crab Wonton Taco, Szechuan Chicken Satay, Cheesesteak Bao Buns, Soy Glazed Chilean Sea Bass, Kim Chee Fried Rice, Filet Migon, and Ice Cream for dessert. Honestly, all of it was excellent but if we had to pick a least favorite, it would have been the satay. Our favorite though was the Sea Bass. So many other things on the menu that we want to try so we look forward to returning one day!

text:
Whenever I want great-tasting Asian food, I go to Han Dynasty in University City, Philly. But today, my wife & I were at Target - City Ave., and the Han Dynasty in Manayunk (5 mins away) was closer than University City. However, we regret purchasing food from this location. We should've just driven the additional miles to the University City location. :/

We usually get Dan Dan noodles, which are normally thick, and come in a delicious broth. However, the Dan Dan noodles from the Main Street location were thin, like spaghetti, and the flavor was nonexistent, as if the cook was rushing & ran out of seasoning. In closing, even if the Main Street location gave us a 50% discount on all future orders FOR LIFE, I would STILL go to the University City location and pay full price.

text: I've never eaten in the restaurant and can only speak for delivery. They are consistently good, fast, and really well priced. The spring roles are really tasty and never soggy or cold by the time we receive them (a problem I often have with other delivery restaurants). Ordered from them at least 10 times over the past year and a half and never had an issue with an order, and never waited more than 20-30 minutes. Wouldn't call it a life changing food experience or anything, but always a pleasant, dependably good, and drama free delivery experience, which is sadly a rare thing to find these days!

text:
Since I'm familiar with the choices of restaurants in Chinatown, I already knew what to expect from Jade Harbor. I chose this spot awhile back because the other restaurants I know are too crowded or close early (the ones that serve similar dishes). Jade harbor closes around 2-3. Meh, that's the only convenient thing I guess. 

A lot of Chinese restaurants have tacky interior...but the inside of this place is SEVERELY outdated, everything is janky and the workers eye you like hawks. I never really feel comfortable here. We had a few weird occurrences, but I shall not get into detail about that lol...just be warned if you are a person of color, AND It's actually ironic because I'm mixed with Asian. Let's just say we got accused of not tipping, and someone ran out after us. After that incident (which happened a year ago) we haven't gone back till this last weekend, just more cautious this time. The prices have significantly gone up. We got three dishes and the total came up to $70, which INCLUDES a tip they added. For all that we could have just went out to eat at a nicer restaurant and felt more comfortable!!! This WILL definitely be the last time we come to this establishment. 

So you wonder why we decided to go back?
Well, besides all the shenanigans...the food is actually pretty good. It's the only comforting thing about this place, and the reason why I am rating Jade Harbor with two stars. David's across the street sells the same dishes, but this place is less crowded. We always get the same dishes. Honey walnut shrimp, dry beef chow fun, and seafood fried rice. 

Such a shame. I guess my search for Chinese "banquet hall" food continues...

text:
As a lover of spicy szechuan food, I was super excited to try Han Dynasty and was not disappointed! Looks like this place is pricey from glancing at the menu, but keep in mind that everything is family style portions. 

Ordered the Dan Dan noodles at everyone's recommendation along with the dry chicken hot pot. The noodles were a flavor explosion, but not exactly my favorite mainly because I felt the peanut was a little overwhelming. I would definitely order the chicken dry hot pot again and again! A great combination of spicy, sweet, and sour. The only complaint was that it was a touch oily.

Would like to come back and try some more dishes, overall a good choice for a "higher end" Chinese/szechuan food experience.

text:
This is a true staple of Chinatown and this area wouldn't be the same without Ocean Harbor and its Dim Sum.  What better way to spend your weekend then to frantically search for your breakfast like a meerkat.  

Typically I've gone on the weekends around 11.  As you walk in there will typically be lines of people waiting with a numbered ticket waiting for a table.  The assortment of items is diverse, you'll always get your staples.  But what sets it apart is typically the good price and value for your meal, for a party of three I've typically left full for roughly $30.

text:
Been trying to get around to trying this place for a while and finally did. The ambiance is nice inside, think dimly lit and very wood heavy interior. Almost like a whiskey bar feel I think. Went in a group of 6 - make sure to have a reservation for a group otherwise on the weekends seems like they're pretty packed throughout the night.

We ordered some cocktails and ciders, specifically the tuxedo drink on special, the hilltop pop, and the once upon a thyme in Mexico. Cocktails to me were a bit average compared to other cocktail bars but I guess good for a restaurant bar. Service was also good. Our waitress was very cute and knowledgeable about all the dishes and drink items.

Thoughts on the food we had:
-veal tartare: I really liked this dish for the larger chunks of veal. My boyfriend however was expecting more of a ground/minced tartare
-duck agnolotti: SO GOOD. My favorite dish of the night. Basically like little mini raviolis stuffed with duck in a leek sauce reduction.
-bucatini: standard red sauce pasta dish I think. Noodles were too cooked and not al dente enough
-margherita pizza: also standard. Their pizzas seem to be neopolitan style
-speck and egg pizza: loved this! The caramelized onions enhanced the flavors I think
-hanger steak: well cooked steak. Perfectly medium rare but I think it was too salty. Looked like they sprinkled kosher on top of the steak and potatoes before serving the dish, could have done with less salt or no salt added. The shishito peppers helped cut the saltiness of the steak. The potatoes were a bit too well done for my taste. Couldn't feel a difference between the fried exterior and the interior of the potato slices
(Our friends also had the trout and the scallops. Heard the scallops were very good)

Overall, good food and drinks. Nice ambiance. But I think a bit overpriced for what it is. I would go back for the duck agnolotti and the speck and egg pizza for sure and will probably have to try some other dishes.

text: Chima was really good. The restaurant is clean and well-lit. The restaurant is a Brazilian style steakhouse, if you did not already realize. It's essentially all-you-can-eat, with a salad bar included. I actually chose to have the salad bar option, which includes either salmon or chicken. I still had a lot of options to eat. Everything was delicious, except the soup I had. The soup was a weird flavor and it was not warm. But otherwise, everything was really good. I think with the prices, dessert should have been included in the price of the dinner. But overall, it was a nice dinner and we all enjoyed the food and dining experience.

text:
Located in the heart of Chinatown on the intersection of Race and 10th, you just can't miss it.  Just seeing it from the window I'll be drawn to pick up either duck or roast pork to go.  It's not as if they roast their pork any better than any of the million other places that are located in Chinatown but it's all about location, location, location.  The prices are reasonable and comparative.  

If you want a more diverse and expansive menu you'd probably head down the street to Sang Kee.  You come here if you want a simple, inexpensive, high quality lunch of wonton noodle soup.

text:
I've been to several other hot pot places in Chinatown, and Chubby Cattle is by far the best by several margins and standard deviations. The ingredients they use are fresh, and the presentation of the raw ingredients are beautiful. The ox tail tomato soup base tastes like home and extremely flavorful. This place also has a conveyor belt, so if you see something you like, you can grab it. The price is very reasonable for the quality of food they serve. One negative criticism is that sometimes the air conditioner feels like it's on blast and can be extremely cold even when the weather is hot outside, so if you're wearing tanks and shorts, it can feel freezing. 

I would highly recommend Chubby Cattle above the other hot pot restaurants, even if you're not particularly fond of hot pot.

text: After a tough day on the job I walked aimlessly with a goal to enjoy some victory grub in Chinatown. Although I got lost initially, I knew I could not give up on the mission. I continued my journey not sure of what I needed but knowing it would call out to me. Seeing a rave review on a door from THE Craig Laban made it evident that was my place, and my place ending up being Siu Kee Duck House. While there looked to be a few delectable items the 1/2 duck was what I walked away with ( anything else would be like going to Burger King and ordering chicken ). Juicy and tender were the adjectives I've used to describe previous duck and they'll be the same I'll use today - juicy and tender. The succulent fat was rich and a nice compliment to the enjoyably gamey treat. Quick service and a reasonable to go price ($11 for the 1/2) made this a nice impromptu lunch surprise.

text:
Sampan Happy Hour is as good as it gets in Philly. Drink options are normal - wine, simple vodka drink (typically), and a beer on special. Food is exceptional. 

Recommendations include: Pork Potstickers, Chicken & Pork Bao Buns (really any bao buns), Brussel sprouts!!! (We have ordered multiple orders multiple times), and kimchee fried rice. 

Service is pretty consistent - nothing special, but effective and quick. Portions are small, but for the prices, it's worth trying everything!

text:
Bing Bing Dim Sum is a sister restaurant to Cheu Noodle. I went to Cheu Noodle about a year ago and wasn't super impressed, so I was hesitant to go in. My experience with Bing Bing Dim Sum was much better. I'll have to go to Cheu Noodle again to re-evaluate but until then, I'll review Bing Bing Dim Sum.

Despite it being Saturday afternoon, we were seated right away. The food came out very quickly and steaming out each time. For every dish, at least one or two servers came to see how we were doing. The customer service was great and the food was delicious.

What we ordered: 

Pork Soup Dumplings (4): miso soup dumplings.

4 dumplings were served quickly in a steamer. They were very juicy and quite flavorful. I liked them with a little sauce from the caterpillar bread.

Turnip Cake: matzo, fried egg, maple soy, bonito

Probably the best dish that we ordered. I'm wasn't sure if I had a turnip cake before, but I'll definitely be ordering them in the future. The turnip is mixed with matzah and drizzled with a maple soy glaze. It's topped with bonito and an egg. The over-easy egg makes the entire dish come together.

Cheesesteak Bao (2): Cooper sharp, long hots, wit.

How can you come to South Philly and not order a cheesesteak? This perfect twist on an American classic. The bao was stuffed with shredded meat, cheese, and peppers. The sweetness of the dough really hit the spot for complimenting the savory filling.


Caterpillar Bread: BBQ pork, caramelized honey, sesame

This was a close 2nd for the best dish we had. The BBQ pork and honey really went well with each other. Each bite with sweet and savory and a little bit of heaven. I would strongly suggest ordering this dish if you go to Bing Bing.

Overall, our experience here was really pleasant. The food was delicious and reasonably priced. The service was exceptional and I'm over here drooling over our dim sum selections while I type this blog up. If you're in the Passyunk area and don't want to spend a ton of money (there's a lot of pricey restaurants in this area), head on over to Bing Bing Dim Sum.

This is my go to Chinese delivery spot. They have the fastest delivery times in the city and their prices are more than reasonable.

I highly recommend it crispy cheese wontons as an appetizer. I go to dishes her the steamed tofu with steamed vegetables or the steam shrimp with steamed vegetables.  Both dishes are around $10 and can easily be made into two meals.

I am also a fan of the Hot and sour soup. Small has $1.95 and an absolute steal a side dish.

text: What a GREEDY, UNPROFESSIONAL place this is!!!  My sister held a graduation party here for her son on Father's Day, two tables.  Now, this is our first time at this restaurant since we usually go to the same place when there is a celebration.  Food was good and the decor was nice.  BUT, we can't deal with the HORRIBLE service that was given to us that night.  We regret choosing to spend $1000 on this place!  As expensive as this place was ALREADY, it should have included at least a bottle of soda, but NO!  the Manager shook her head at us and charged $20 for CORKAGE FEE bc she saw us buy soda from outside.  Apparently, the fee came with glass and ice.   Well, there was NO ice provided, and to top it all off, they decided to tack on 20% tip without even telling us beforehand or ask for our damn permission!  What kind of restaurant does this?!  I was thinking about doing my daughters Baptism dinner here for 5 tables, but I WILL NEVER step foot in your restaurant ever again.  Your greediness cost you thousands in return.  Good job guys, you should know better than this.

text:
Came here for Happy Hour on a Friday night and sat at the bar. Prices during happy hour are great and the food was delicious! We tried a bunch of things: Korean BBQ beef, edamame dumplings, Kobe sliders, pork and chicken bao buns, brussel sprouts, and the fried rice. All of it was delicious but my favorites were the beef and pork bao buns.

Service was a little slow but the place was packed and it was a Fri night so that was understandable. I would definitely come back for HH and would recommend to anyone looking for yummy asian fusion at a great pricepoint!

text:
One of the best places in Philly to get dumplings, especially in the University City area. Dum Sum House has a large menu with many noodle and soup dishes, but of course, they are known for the dumplings. The service is always exceptionally quick and it's a great place for a date night or out with 10 of your friends. They also offer a free pool table, so that adds to the fun, albeit the pool cues there tend to be below par so don't expect to play a competitive game. 

It would definitely be worth your time if you're looking for a quick bite to eat or trying all the dumplings you can. The menu items are both delicious and fairly priced!

Cheers!

text:
I love the concept of this place! It's a huge market with tons of vendors, both restaurant type vendors and produce and meat vendors. 

We went on a Sunday when we were traveling for work and a lot of vendors were still there but there were definitely some places that we closed. We also tried to go the last time we were in the area, but it was Labor Day and the market was closed. 

We tried to get small amounts of food from several vendors and almost all of it was really good. 

As an added bonus, they validate parking for the garage across the street. You just take your ticket to one of the vendors you purchase something from and they'll validate it for you. It doesn't cover the entire cost, but it's significantly cheaper. 

If I lived in the area, I would definitely frequent this place.

text:
A consistent Asian option with a variety of choices for if you're craving something hot or cold! 

Recs:
- Noodle soup - you can choose hand drawn or shaven noodles (skip on the added price spicy sauce, just use the chili oil on the table!)
- 3 rolls for $14 deal - choose from a number of roll options (including spider roll which has soft shell crab if you're looking to maximize on the deal) 
- Lunch special - their bento box is filling and I typically like ordering salmon teriyaki (bc I need healthy omega-3's in college)
- Bubble tea isn't bad but I'd skip on it since there are better options in the area

text:
I've been here twice - once for dinner and then another time for late night desserts/drinks. I've tried many times to get a seat at their happy hour but have not met success so I would definitely recommend getting there early since I believe you have to sit at the bar.

(+) lobster chow fun - I'm a huge fan of the thick rice noodles so I was very excited for this! The lobster was tender and there was a good amount and the flavor/texture of the noodles was really yummy. The addition of jicama made the dish unique.
(neutral) edamame dumplings - while they were soft and the broth was tasty, I've had edamame dumplings done better at other spots and for a cheaper price
(neutral) mapo tofu - a twist on the typical mapo tofu appetizer, they had crisps on the top of diced tofu pieces - definitely didn't taste bad but tasted veryyyyy different from the traditional mapo tofu so I'm not sure if I would order it again
(+) icecream sushi - a really fun dish to order with friends and has a great chocolate sauce!

text:
I've been hearing so much about this honey walnut shrimp at Panda Express and last Friday was the perfect oppurtunity for me to try and see if its all it cracked up to be.

Well the dish was delicious. Since seafood is my thing and shrimp is the best in the seafood game. I knew that I prolly would like it being as tho I rarely met a shrimp I didn't like.

My honey walnut shrimp had a nice crispy coating on the outside that was sweet but not too sweet. The glazed walnuts was the perfect consistency, it definitely added great flavor to the shrimp. Overall I think the honey walnut shrimp would pair well with rice or a side salad.

Great service, the line moved really fast even during lunch hour. My dish was pretty pricey. I paid about 14.00 for my side only but for the quality of the flavor. Its worth it plus they offer other items that are pretty reasonable like orange chicken and beef and broccoli. This was definitely a treat and a splurge for me.

Definitely would return anytime I want to get my honey walnut shrimp fix on!

text:
WOW!! First of all, this is probably the BEST value in Philly. Two of us ate, had a couple of beers, and even had leftovers for about $40, including tip! The crabmeat and pork soup dumplings are absolutely perfect and I would have been happy having those and nothing else! But the chives and pork potstickers and seafood noodles were also crazy good!

With an ATM at the entrance, I don't see why their cash-only policy is a big deal for customers. Although, in today's day and age, I would encourage the owner to raise their prices to offset credit card fees and make things more convenient for all. The prices would still be incredibly low.

I've already recommended this place to a few people on this trip and will remember it next time I'm in Philadelphia!

text:
*"Sham WOW" voice*
NOM WAH!

I love Nom Wah, and it's proven to be a consistently good spot for dim sum, drinks, and more. I love it for many reasons: It's clean, they're quick, they're friendly, they have a full bar, they have a great menu, it's an awesome value, and THEY TAKE RESERVATIONS! 

Amazing. What more could you want?

My favorites are the soup dumplings, the spicy wontons, and the shrimp rice rolls. You can't beat the price for the amount of food you get here. Dim Sum done right. Grab a $5 beer or one of their incredible looking Green Tea Martinis, and you're sure to have a great night.

text:
It has a couple of good things going for it, but I did not enjoy dining here. 

Ordered the beef combo, veggie combo, pork belly and some noodles with the original and tonkotsu miso soup. 

The beef and pork came out significantly earlier than everything else, about fifteen minutes and talking to the waiter before the vegetables came, and then asking again before the noodles came. Not sure if this was done on purpose so we would order more meat dishes, but it really makes a worse hot pot experience to burn through the meat before being able to eat it with anything else. It also made it difficult to take advantage of the conveyor belt offerings since we couldn't really assess how much food we ordered. 

The conveyor belt is a neat gimmick. The hot pot broth was also pretty good. Their house sauce is not bad. 

The quality of meat is high, and it tasted maybe better, but the hot pot experience is fine with just regular beef so I can't say it was worth it 

The high cost here and presence of AYCE hot pot options at other places nearby makes me not recommend this place.

text:
I hadn't been to Wm Mulherin's since they were new. I couldn't remember why I hadn't returned because I remember the food being good. I saw a late reservation slot open last weekend and decided to give it a go. 

Well, once the first dish arrived, I remembered why. The bass tartare was $18 and only about a tablespoon of chopped fish. While it was good, it wasn't amazing and worth the price tag. Other restaurants give you way more for that price. The cheese ravioli with favas had nice texture, but again, very small and pricey. It also was a little too salty due to all the cheese both outside and inside. 

The pizza isn't cheap, but is standard dinner prices for the city. The asparagus and ferns white pizza was excellent with lots of greens and flavor. It was perfectly seasoned with a nice wood oven crust and not too salty. I would order this again. 

Our bill was around $90 before tip, and my husband was still hungry. Service was also terrible for this price point. When I asked questions about the menu, "Can you tell me about the bass tartare?" I got generic answers, "It's bass tartare. Chopped up bass." Yeah, I know what that is, but when I'm paying $18 for an appetizer, I want a description. Is there a sauce? An oil? Seasoning? Portion size? The worst was when we finished our food, I asked for a dessert menu. It was 11:02 PM. She said the kitchen was closed. Okay, fine but what kind of place doesn't do last call/order? Even dive bars give you a heads up when the kitchen is closing. The service was incredibly disappointing, especially at this price point. 

Drinks were on point though. My mezcal green pepper cocktail was well crafted and a good pour. My husband loved his whiskey based cocktail. I recommend going for drinks and pizza if you aren't looking to spend a lot of cash. I think I would have been much happier if I'd done so.

Dim Sum Baô, saté Chicken (tremendous and delicious portion), and Mabu tofu Lô Mein for around $25.   Great parties of friends, couples, and singles fill up the place waiting for the fare.  Beer is not on tap.   BYO wine.   Bring cash only! Happy Dim Sum day!

text: This Malaysian restaurant is awesome! Roti canai, roti canai, roti canai! If I could come here again, that's probably what I would order: three roti canais lol. It is probably the best one I've ever had in my life! Couldn't stop eating it. I think their curry game is super strong- very flavorful and not overpowering, and the homemade bread was not too thick and perfectly soft yet crispy. I was only in Phily for one weekend (first time), and we came here twice cuz it was so nommy! I also really liked the Hainan chicken rice and nasi lemak. Our group also ordered the Indian eggy version of roti canai, rendang (not bad but not my thing), noodles (which tasted really good at first but then after a while it was okay), prawn mee (I didn't like this one). Another plus is that it's so affordable! I think our total came out to about $10pp excluding tax and tip. No wait on both visits too.

text:
Visited this place while on a business trip to Philly. Walked in and the environment was neat and inviting. We had a party of 7 and we were seated on a round table that allowed us to have great conversation and enjoy our dining experience together.

We elected to do the full dining experience which consisted of the carved meats as well as the salad bar. The salad bar was full of choices all fresh and presented elegantly. They provide you with some appetizers to help you get started. Cheese bread and fried bananas. Delicious. 

The waiters come by offering you different cuts of meats. They place the rack on the table, carve a portion, and you use your tong to place on your plate. They came around frequently and we were able to try out a variety of meat flavors, baked pineapple, chicken, and salmon.

Hint: If you don't get the cuts you want or the particular meat item listed as a choice, just ask your waiter and they will put your request in. Dessert is an additional charge, just be aware.

Fair is fair come check this location out. The waiters  were friendly and attentive and the food was delicious. Hopefully it will meet your expectations for the price tag.

text:
This place is one of the better dim sum places i had and the prices are super reasonable. If you go with a lot of people, you can eat a lot and still end up only paying 10-15 dollars (unless you're me than... you'll pay a lot more).

The wait in this place gets nuts if you come on a Sunday which is when i like to come with friends. It is mayhem and you need to fight your way to the lady with the ticket to get you seated. 

Once you are seated; the carts start rolling. They have all the basics from shumai to chicken feet. The one thing (and yes... you need to be persistent) you must get is pineapple pork buns. Holy moly... sweet fried bun on the outside while the inside has a moist, savory pork. It took me at least 4 visits to the place and constant haggling to get it. 

If you are a fan of dim sum, this place is a great spot to go to

text:
Came on a Tuesday evening at 7:30 PM, lots of business but sufficient seating, so we didn't have to wait. Food took a while to come out, but it tasted good overall.

Roti canai - we ordered it, but they forgot to bring it out, so we had to ask for it at the end of our meal; roti itself was good (crispy, wafery, and thin), sauce too spicy and oily for our taste

Satay beef - some chunks of meat were tougher than others, some were pretty tender; flavorful by itself, so I personally didn't really need the peanut sauce

Bah kut teh (chinese herb soup) - broth too sweet and darker than I've typically seen the dish; meat was relatively tender and had many different types of pork

Green nasi lemak - cannot really taste the coconut in the coconut rice?; just average

Busy, so it was hard to get a waiter/waitress's attention for the bill. Would come again bc prices were very reasonable, and portion sizes were large.

Came to Sampan for Happy Hour and was definitely satisfied. We ordered four dishes to share (for 2) & the three had already been enough to fill us up! Especially for such an affordable price (HH), would definitely come again for dinner! 

Seems pretty busy in the evenings, so you might have to wait, but it's definitely a place you should try! 

Also, there's a graffiti bar hidden at the back of the restaurant; great for after-dinner shenanigans!!

text:
As you walk in, you notice this place is clean and modern. It's perfect for a night out with friends or a date night that doesn't require dressing up. The wait time can be a little long, especially if it's during dinner time, but the time can be easily spent taking a walk around Chinatown. This place can be a little pricey, but it's worth it if split it between a couple friends and get a couple things to fill you up such as the veggie platter or some noodles.

Once seated, we were told to choose a broth and went with the original which was rich and flavorful. The broth was really decadent and pairs well with the beef combo that we got. The beef combo is good for first timers because it lets you try a little bit of everything for a set price and also lets you know which cuts of meat you like. I might just have a basic tongue, but I don't really taste a difference between these cuts and normal beef belly that you can get at regular hot pot places. 

Overall, I'd go again only if I'm with a larger group or on special occasions. The food was good, but it's not somewhere worth going on a regular basis.

text:
You can't go wrong with the dim-sum selection at Sang Kee. We ordered the shrimp dumplings, shumai, 1000 year egg and pork congee, braised beef wonton noodle soup, and the string beans in garlic sauce. The shumai and shrimp dumplings were pretty standard, I would recommend ordering one of each to share. The 1000 year egg and pork congee was surprisingly delicious. The portion size is also generous. The texture of the congee is similar to porridge or Korean juk (). The pork was dry and bland but it complemented the egg really well. My personal favorite was the braised beef noodle soup. The soup was flavorful and the noodles were just the right texture between soft and crunchy. The wontons also made the entree very filling. The string beans were also good but since they were slathered with garlic sauce, it was a pretty heavy dish. The string beans felt more like an entree themselves rather than a side dish. 
The entrees were delicious and reasonably priced and the staff was very attentive as well. The only negative part of our experience was the cleanliness of the restaurant. The sauce containers and tables were messy and at one point a fly actually flew into our noodle soup. I would've looked past this if we were seated outside, but since we were indoors we were pretty surprised.

text:
Visited Sampan for dinner Saturday night and I am still thinking about the pork bao buns. This is a must try if looking for pan-Asian food in center city, and their happy hour is fantastic if you are sitting in the bar area. It's also small plates/tapas style, which is my preferred serving method because I can never make up my mind. Weekend nights are typically crowded and I recommend making a reservation before visiting. The restaurant has a loungey feel with a buzzing atmosphere. The service is always very speedy and we were impressed with our last server's knowledge of the cocktail menu! 

We started off with some drinks (shocking) and had asked the server if any of the cocktails were spicy because we are huge spice people. She recommended the Kantoi Road, which was made with tequila and charred chili peppers - wow this drink was fantastic and my new fav! If you are a fan of spicy margs this drink is for you. The friend I was with ordered an Emperors Garden, which had aloe and cucumber in it, and was very refreshing. 

I don't have any pictures of the food we ordered because I was hangry (phones don't always eat first).
We started off with the pork bao buns, Korean bbq beef satay, and the Brussels sprouts. As I previously mentioned, I am still thinking about the bao buns because they were THAT good. The bbq beef was flavorful and the Brussels sprouts were cooked perfectly + I loved the chili sauce they were in. Next we ordered cheesesteak bao, Szechuan chicken stir-fry, and kimchee fried rice. I'd recommend the pork bao buns over the cheesesteak ones. My other favorite item of the night was the kimchee fried rice - it was yummy and you get a nice size portion for the price. We are repeat diners at Sampan and can't wait to be back to try more dishes!

Highly recommend!!

Everyone I've encountered has been really kind, and I always get a goodnight by the time I leave. The selection of foods are good, and the broth is standard. text:
Ah, Penang...

I have been coming here for years, mainly for the roti canai. It is a no frills  establishment in Chinatown that has been around forever. The decor is very industrial and functional. It gets busy and loud so keep that in mind if choosing this restaurant for your occasion. The staff's friendliness is hit or miss but they all hustle and work hard. Easy to do individual dishes or family style.

Every meal I get here starts with the roti canai. Flaky yet moist layered bread with a chicken and potato dipping sauce. The perfect combo of cinnamon and savory spices. We followed this with the mango chicken. This is always a favorite as the tart sauce complements the sweetness of the mango. We tried a new dish for us, the Beef Rendang. A good flavor profile with cinnamon and clove yet still somehow savory. This dish did disappoint as the texture was as if it had been sitting for some time or came out of the freezer. The veggie garnish on the side was also stale and dry. The downside of this place is that they don't give you rice with the meals. It is $1.50 extra....not breaking the bank or anything but at a cost to them of pennies, I feel like it should be part of the meal.

Overall 3.5, rounding it up to 4 for nostalgia for me.

text:
Why do I always find these amazing restaurants in faraway cities? 

Fantastic meal here. I wouldn't shut up about how much I loved the menu and the food. Sorry Mom and Dad (although they really liked it too).

MENU: Spectacular. So many great vegan options. Tons of dim sum and all sorts of awesome appetizer and entrée dishes. They also had all kinds of smoothies and juices and teas. 

FOOD: So good! I tried (all vegan): hot and sour soup, BBQ pork, fried scallops, vegetable dumplings, shrimp dumplings, meat dumplings, spring roll, and string beans. Everything was absolutely delicious (excellent flavor and texture). 

PRICES: Very affordable. Dim sum is a great way to try multiple dishes without spending a lot. They also have lunch specials. 

SERVICE: Very friendly and efficient.

SPACE: Nothing fancy but cozy and easy on the eyes. 

I loved this restaurant so much and would recommend it wholeheartedly!

text:
Found my new sushi spot in the neighborhood! 

I had a glass of plum wine, the rainbow roll, a spicy salmon roll, and a tekka maki roll. My bill came to $35 with the happy hour discount (not that bad for sushi, in my opinion). I didn't have any of the issues other customers seemed to have. When I went in, the restaurant was clean and bright. Wait staff were also really attentive. Super cute date spot!

I will definitely be back-- Especially for happy hour: 5-7!

text:
I'm not sure why I didn't find this hotpot place in Philly sooner...I truly believe that of all the AYCE hotpot options in the city, the majority of which are in Chinatown (this one is not), LaTao has the best bang for your buck by far.

Lets compare to the competitors in Chinatown:

Price: $24 dinner, $18 lunch, the price is pretty much the same as Nine Ting, Hippot, etc.
Quality: Much, much higher than the other AYCE places; the fatty brisket is to die for but I also really like the spicy beef and huge assortment of other options. The flounder. Don't be sleeping on the flounder. The fish at this location is just so tender and flaky. Not sure what they put in the fish but my friends and I absolutely loved it.
Assortment: I think this is really what makes this place the best bang for your buck. There's literally four pages full of different items to pick from including everything from fish, to many many different types and cuts of meat, to fish balls, tofu, veggies, etc. literally probably 3-4x the amount of different menu items compared to the other AYCE spots and yet much higher quality. 

Seriously, I am an avid hot pot fanatic and I think I've definitely found the place where I will frequent the most in the city. It does suck that it's removed from Chinatown but seriously worth swinging by UCity just for this.

text: Food was decent and service awesome but the chili cukes and Dan dans were next level spicy. I didn't specify a level but they were way spicier than Han dynasty or chili schezuan, however the hot and sour soup was next level best I've had in a while. I wish they didn't make their Dan dan's with regular old spaghetti, I wish they used a fresh soft egg noodle. But using dried Italian style Americanized pasta definitely helps them cut costs. Still paying $8 for a bowl of regular old pasta w chili oil garlic ginger and a few pieces of bok Choy seems like a rip. Spring rolls were decent. crab Rangoon was fried a little too hard and thus tough, almost too crispy and dry. Would reorder hot and sour soup though, best in the neighborhood!

text: We arrived at Nine Ting around 9:30 on a Saturday night after a day of fasting in preparation for the moment we had been waiting for - all you can eat KBBQ. The menu is all you can eat only with a choice of BBQ, hot pot, or both each with a different price. We started off the night with a mix of vegetables and various meats as the selection is extensive. The food promptly arrived and we were in business on the grill. The meat while tasty was not pre thawed which added to some cooking time. While there was a large selection to choose from, nothing blew us away to the point we wanted to double order. The price was reasonable for two and we made the most of our options trying most of everything offered, however due to the large selection the quality of cuts of meat were understandably not as high as most restaurants one finds themselves in. The ability to cook your own food at your own table was a fun and unique way to spend and evening and made for an overall fun date.

text:
I checked this place out for the first time today, and I wasn't a fan given how little meat they gave. Definitely not as much as shown in the pictures on this Yelp page (and all my three friends also agreed that there was almost no meat and that I got gypped). My friend's order had an okay amount if meat and we basically got the same thing (mine was actually a dollar more expensive), so the portions are just not consistent and just not great overall. It is only take out, so I didn't even see the portion until I had left their establishment. They also don't offer any pan-fried noodle option as a base, so you have to eat it with rice.

I heard this place is comparable to Mkee but it really isn't in terms of price or quantity or taste. I had hoped to enjoy it more but definitely not planning on spending $8 here again.
