text:
Square on Square is a nook, Chinese food restaurant located just off of Rittenhouse Square. This restaurant is surrounded by expensive Rittenhouse eateries and seems to serve as the local Chinese food spot for residents looking for something different. With that said, I should have trusted the reviews on here before placing that over my craving and ordering to-go.

We ordered the Beef with Chinese Vegetables and the Home Style Jumbo Shrimp & Scallops. Between the two of the dishes the best part were the shrimp, but that was just about it. The shrimp were huge and very flavorful. However, the flavoring of the sauces of both dishes were very bland and barely appetizing. The scallops were practically flavorless and the beef was just okay. While I can see that Square on Square serves to occupy the Chinese food market in Rittenhouse Square, it does a very poor job with its delivery.

If you are really craving Chinese food or any other Asian cuisines for a cheaper price, I recommend going to Chinatown where you know that the food will not disappoint.

text:
Perfection. Ever since visiting Chengdu, I've always tried to find those kind of dishes back in the USA. I've found decent places but DJ Kitchen knocks it out of the park! 

Chonqing dry pepper chicken: ma la flavor that has proven elusive at all the other places I order. This dish made the meal.

Xiaolongbao: perfect soup dumplings. Reminded me of some of the spots in HK. 

Egg drop soup: I get this whenever I order Chinese carry out. Solid, standard version of it.

It is indeed pricey but portions were generous, so you could easily split an entree. You also pay for the quality of the dishes, which were outstanding here.

text:
The Reading Terminal Market is a great place to just eat and eat and eat some more and then shop for food and more food. Sadly they now close at 6 PM so get there before 4 really. They start to close down shops around that time. You can also go on the weekend but get there early. The place gets super crowded.

They have all types of food. If you want the best ice cream go to Bassets. I think you can still have them ship you pints, so think about that. It is really great ice cream. Also note that nothing here is inexpensive. It is all pricey. 

The best donuts in town are at Beiler's. If you love donuts it is a must stop for you. For Breakfast try the Dutch Eating Place. Everything there is great and made to order fresh. You will love it. You also have to stop in some time to have a pork dipped sandwich at Dinic's. 

You will love this place. Have a great time.

text:
Asian-fusion restaurant in a modern setting with great service. The descriptions of the plates are a little off, but it is delicious. We had the rock shrimp bao, monkfish, and dungeness crab sticky rice.

The shrimp bao are delicious. The shrimp are crispy, fried, and served in buns. Technically they are not bao, but delicious nonetheless. The monkfish is described as "fried medallions" but it was more like "delicious chunks of heaven." It was firm and flaky like cod, but it melted in your mouth. The crab sticky rice is good, but it reminds me of a typical fried rice type of dish.

Overall good on everything, but alot more expensive than a traditional asian restaurant. Adding "fusion" to the name really drives up the price.

text:
Well?

Well I grew up in the area here and I remember the old owners of this place and it was great and was disappointed when they closed down. Well we figured we would check this out for lunch today and well the portions were a good size and fairly priced, but my wife's lemon chicken was not impressive at all and a great disappointment. 

My wife's lemon chicken didn't taste like lemon chicken and the sauce that it was in honestly looked like egg drop soup texture and it honestly didn't have much flavor at all. The chicken really didn't taste or look much like chicken.

My sesame chicken was good and I ended up splitting my order with my wife. 

The service was fast and the worker had a great attitude for sure, but I think next time we will go elsewhere.

text:
I have been going to this place since it opened. The prices have rised significantly yet the noodles have decreased in quality. Recently, I have had horrible experiences due to the service. The servers here are extremely rude and rushy. 

When I was hungry and ordered a lot, they were polite. They gave us bowls, scissors and plates without asking. When I ordered two entrees without an appetizer (2 people) the server gave me a weird look and ignored me for the rest of the meal. The male server that works here full time is especially rude. When I tried to get his attention twice, he ignored me and walked away. 

I got take out twice and he rounded up the price every time. When I walked out, the soup spilled and the bag broke. Every time I visit, I feel like all he does is seat people and let everyone else do the work. I understand its busy but he rushes way too much.

I would have never came back if my family didnt like the food.

text:
I'd recommend 100% 

The servers and staff are very friendly every time I go they are attentive and informative and give out great recommendations. Ask away and they are helpful and will make sure your dining experience is satisfactory.

I've only tried their hotpot so far and my go-to flavor is the tomato oxtail. They bring around the seasonings so you can add and adjust to your taste.  I love the conveyor belt idea (the past 2 times I've been there they ran out of some additions on the conveyor belt and didn't have the tomato oxtail I wanted which was a bummer but I managed to substitute with other things). 

For the price, I think it's worth it. 

Grab your friends for hotpot time and expect to spend some time there. It's a lot of fun, it's delicious, and you won't be waiting too long to eat since the food cooks within seconds or less than 5 minutes!

text:
The food is good. If you like Mongolian hot pot, it's a must try. I would like to give them a 5-star rating, but there was a couple of things that made the experience a little uncomfortable or offsetting. 

First the booths are very small. There's not much wiggle room. They even acknowledge as much by building in these table extenders to allow for some more table space. There's really no great way to put everything on the table at the same time when you're in a party of four. 

The sauce tray isn't as accessible. I've been to other hot pot places where there is a sauce bar. You can go there whenever you want to refill your sauce cup. At Chubby Cattle, you have to ask the server to get it for you. It adds a layer of inconvenience, but that's all. 

There's also some sort of member club that gives you 20% off conveyor items, but that offer was currently suspended. Also almost everything Wagyu was not available (except the brisket and later I found the dumplings on the conveyor belt). 

Lastly, the conveyor belt has lots of items for you to throw in the hot pot. A little offsetting for me is that some of the items were sitting a shallow pool of water. I value that everything is thoroughly washed, but maybe it needs to be drained better. 

Overall, it was a great experience. I really enjoyed my tomato oxbone broth and could consume it by itself. I've really just scratched the service of the full experience here. It was a little pricey as my individual bill came out to $27 even with a Yelp check-in giving me a free conveyor belt item.

text:
This is one of my favorite places to eat in Philly HANDSDOWN. As a student, LaTao HotPot is very close to my campus which makes eating there very easy. It where I like to go for big celebrations.

To begin LaTao has amazing broths (the tomato is my favorite). They are Buffett Style with great quality food. Unlike other buffet hotpots, their food is of a high standard for the cost. Personally I love the Angus Beef and fish balls with Roe. They have a large menu which I recommend become familiar with because the all the options are quite appetizing and can be overwhelming in a good way.

The staff is also helpful and brings out food quickly. You need to try their food to understand how good it is.

TIP: bring cash with you because there is a 10% discount for people who pay in cash. Also on your birthday, you get a hotpot if you are in a group of 4 or more (but make sure you double check this).

text:
Square on Square is located in a beautiful area in Center City. I usually am in the area on weekends to study at a Cafe or to take the bus back to my Univeristy.

After my friend and I had been studying, he was craving Chinese food. We decided to order from Square on Square because it was close to the coffee shop where we were at. Normally, I go to Chinatown for Chinese food. But since we were far from Chinatown we gave this place a try.

We ended up ordering the Jumbo Shrimp and Scallop. The flavor of the Shrimp was ok but the scallop was like eating a mixture between a dish sponge and potato. The other dish we ordered was Beef was veggies which was fine but definitely not rememberable. For the price we payed and the quality, I would not recommend this place although the location is superb. 

I would love to see Square on Square improve it's menu because it has a lot of potential to do well in Philly, but for now 2 Stars because the food waas not up to standard.

text:
Food is good for the area, probably one of the better chinese food places in the immediate area. Prices are in the decent range. Portion sizes are generous. They do run a lunch special if you're ever in the area. 

My usual order is the general tso chicken. I'm not a fan of the fried rice so I opt for the plain white rice. A large order runs under $10. 

Tips: 
Cash only, they do have an ATM inside. 
They deliver.  
Parking lot out front 
Sometimes the wait can be long so try calling ahead.

text: It's pretty pricey for hot pot but I was so full by the end and the quality was so good that I didn't even care when the check came. All the vegetables were crisp and fresh. Wagyu was so good and soft. And the soup was very flavourful. It was well worth the $35.

text:
Always seemed to pass this restaurant whenever getting off the train and decided to try it for once. I ordered the House Special Noodle Soup and Dumplings in Chili Oil. 

My impression: not really impressed. I expected some flavorful Chinese food, however the dishes I ate fell short. My noodle soup was bland; no amount of soy sauce and chili oil could remedy it. There were also so many ingredients in it, some I couldn't even distinguish. That's worrisome to me. I couldn't tell if I was eating chicken, beef, or something entirely different. The dumpling were heavy and had a sour(?) aftertaste. At least the spice level was good. 

Maybe I didn't order the right dish, but nevertheless I'm disappointed and think the food is not really worth the prices either.

text:
4.7/5

So many awesome stores, and great atmosphere/vibe! I love walking around here and checking out all of the different stalls, from different types of honey to different jams to spices (check out The Head Nut) and cooked food. I always end by doing groceries in the back, which are surprisingly decently priced -- and they offer a student discount!

Reading Terminal also has a lot of really cool special events throughout the year to keep a look out for. For example, there was an Ice Cream day recently where many of the stalls served some form of Ice Cream. My favorite was the Filipino food festival. Do be warned that lines tend to be long during these special events, and it gets quite crowded!

text:
Very good Cantonese house on Race Street near 9th, with front of the house glassed in roasting kitchen and regular food preparation room in back for the rest of the menu. Our server advised that the chef was Fuzhounese. Regardless of his beginnings, he knew his way around a South Chinese chopchop. 

The dining room was small, even by Ctown standards. Maybe 7 tables altogether. The food list was extensive, and we settled on Hong Kong Wonton Vegetable Soup (very good), Salt & Pepper Spare Ribs (excellent) and Beef Chow Fun (excellent). All dishes were substantial and we had plenty more than the two of us could handle, and a large amount to take home. On top of that, before leaving we picked up a pound of sliced roast pork because it looked so good hanging in the window. It was delicious and we worked through it for the next week. It was lean with thin layer of fat under the crispy brown dermis. 

Lau Kee reminded of Ting Wong, a worthy place for a solid meal across the traditional food groups of Cantonese cuisine, with a comfort level that was inviting to regular visits for families or octogenarians on a date. Prices quite reasonable, too.

text: Terrific food. Line was all the way to the door when we arrived on a Saturday night at 8:30, and we still had a table for 5 in less than 20 minutes. And fed our whole family a ton of great food for $125, tip and drinks included. Unbelievable value. It's loud and with the language barrier there was a bit of confusion in getting our order right.....pretty sure we got an extra plate of something we didn't order and we definitely had to wait awhile for things we did order that were probably forgotten on the first try. But minor quibble on an overall amazing experience. Word to the wise: the soup dumplings are indeed to die for, but the soup inside is piping hot. Wait a bit after served before biting in or you'll get scalded like I did!

text:
I came here for CCD SIPS with a group of friends and it was by far our best SIPS experience yet (and we've been around). 

Because we were mostly drinking, we can't really comment on the food, but the cocktails were delicious and colorful--and there was a HUGE variety for CCD SIPS--more than any other business, and the staff were so friendly and patient, explaining to us all the appetizer portions.

We got dumplings and wontons in chili oil--which were fairly standard--Indian pancakes with a curry dipping sauce which was excellent, and wings which were on the smaller side but delicious and priced reasonably. 

This isn't high snobiety food, but it was a big variety of excellent drinking food, affordably priced, in a cool restaurant with very pleasant service. Definitely would recommend for SIPS if you're young and on a budget.

text:
This place was slightly underwhelming for me.  Although none of the food was outright bad, I would not return considering the price tag.  The best dishes of the night were the toro egg roll (which I ordered on top of the tasting menu). 

The pan seared sea bass was cooked nicely (tender, moist), but there wasn't much flavor (not much flavor in sauce/ sides for the fish to absorb). Everything else was just mediocre. I think Buddakan is overrated to be honest, and there are better places to spend $80-$100 on a meal.

text:
Service lack a heartbeat , very slow for not a busy Sunday night dinner service. Server came to our table 3 times  , came to take order ,  back to serve our food and  last to collect the check . Our server must have been allergic to our table , only explanation. 

Food - The wagyu beef is so tender ! Other items for hotpot on the menu was your typical fare , veggies , noodles and fish balls . The  conveyor belt dishes was a absolute joke , saw the sorry looking California sushi roll and same 3 , 4 hotpot items come around too many times . It looks like plastic food replica  . The oxtail broth was the saver, excellent flavor. 

Overall - night club beer price $7 ,without the line , food is good but a bit pricey . No value here beside the gimmicky conveyor belt , wait to you see it. Good place for a solo dine , impress your date here but, impress your spouse  at the hotpot place around the corner . Not great for family Hotpot . Chinatown is getting crowded for hotpot places and this place stand out , but not on top .

text:
Bomb dim sum spot located right in the heart of U Penn. You'll find plenty of Chinese decor and traditional furniture here. I came here with some friends and we were seated really quickly. We ordered pork soup dumplings, crab & pork soup dumplings, extra spicy soup dumplings, pan fried soup dumplings, edamame dumings, beef scallion pancake, pork & shrimp siu mai, shrimp cheung fun har gow and chicken feet. We ordered around 2 rounds of each dish it was plenty for our party of 8. The siu mai we had were huge and they stuff it with plenty of meat. The beef scallion pancake is a must order. Very little grease and plenty of meat as well. Highly recommend ordering the spicy soup dumplings first as they do pack some heat. Then go to the regular soup dumplings and to the fried stuff. Dim sum here was on point. Definitely high quality ingredients and strong flavor. 

My friends really enjoyed our food and service here. This location is kept clean and the staff is really friendly. Street parking is really easy to find. Some may feel that price wise this spot is a little high. But, I'd rather pay more for 0 wait time, better quality dim sum and spacious seating. We'll definitely be back to try their other dim sum dishes

text:
Chima is the place to go for a group of former coworkers that I used to work with, we actually prefer Chima over Fogo de Chao due to its more spacious atmosphere and comparable salad bar.  

Recently we came to take advantage of the summer special, however, we were really confused how it would work.  I would probably ding them if it weren't for how gracious the wait and host staff handled everything.  But I'll call out their marketing department on this, the summer special is for $35 on a certain day and there in the "FINE" print states that you have to tell them that you're doing the special which you WON'T be offered all the various meats.  To me, this whole thing is a crock.  When we realized we weren't getting the special price, we worked it out with the staff, were more than happy to pay it cause the food was amazing, just wasn't too crazy about how the promotion was set up.  I'm more than happy to pay the full price cause the assortment is amazing, I just don't like the marketing ploy, and would advise against it, it's the only thing stopping me from giving them 5 stars.  Other than that the service and food is great.

text:
3.5 stars
There's something very homey about eating at a family-run Chinatown restaurant that turns out simple yet tasty plates of authentic Szechuan food. The "small eats" or appetizer-style dishes shared family-style are my favorite part of this mouth-numbing cuisine! We started with the Chengdu-style cold bean noodles, and the soft, slippery noodles were a great conduit for the slightly spicy chili sauce. The dan dan noodles with minced pork were a bit of a miss--the wheat noodles seemed a bit overcooked, and the sauce was rather flavorless. Similarly, the mapo tofu with ground meat was surprisingly bland and the sauce was way too soupy. The smashed cucumbers in vinegar/soy garlic sauce were tasty and refreshing, but the highlight dish here (also the owner's favorite dish) was the beef, tripe, and tendon in chili oil (fuqi feipian). The thin, cold slices of brisket and offal were tossed with a delicious chili sauce and had a great lean texture! Nice!

Overall, all the dishes here had very clean flavors and were surprisingly mild for something branded as Szechuan cuisine (I barely got any of the characteristic numbing spice). However, this also meant that nothing was overly salty, and the great value food and friendly service made this an authentic, homey experience!

text:
Dim Sum Garden is one of two extremely popular, non-cart-style Dim Sum spots in Philadelphia's Chinatown.  It's cheap, it's delicious, it's fast.  The ambiance is lacking and the service can be a little more "efficient," but it makes for a great lunch.  It's also cash only!

Pros:

The soup dumpings are delicious - vegetable, pork, crab, spicy - you name it and they're quite good!  Additionally, the Shao Mai was a delightful little surprise I had never ordered here before.  

It's fairly inexpensive, with an order of 6-8 soup dumpings ranging from 6-8 dollars.  

Service was typical for a packed house, but the group seemed to communicate well and delivered the food fast!

Cons:

The place is busy and often hard to get a table for a larger group at all and certainly during the busy times.  That's probably more to their credit than a true "con."  

The ambiance is certainly far from fancy or even "nice."  Plastic tables, foggy water glasses, and a kitchen in front of you as you walk by (close enough that you could reach out and steal a bun if you wanted!).  The cleanliness looks suspect, but it's hard to question the freshness at which the food is prepared!

I found the Pork buns to be overly doughy and lacking a filling pork and the hot and sour soup was a bit too viscous for my liking, but was sufficient spicy and filling!

Conclusion:  

Cheap, delicious and made-to-order Dim Sum makes Dim Sum Garden a quick go-to for a fun lunch.  Cash only, makes it a little bit of a pain, but it's worth the extra effort for the price and deliciousness!

text:
Been here quite a few times, not sure where to start!

Wagyu nigiris are must get: seared/not seared/uni/no uni are all bomb.com of cut right. Had it for one dinner & it was SOOOO GOOD. Literally ordered like 6 orders(12 pieces) total between 2 girls. Melts in your mouth. We went back the next day but during lunch & it wasn't the same.. cut was thicker, making it chewy so we sent it back. Politely asked for thinner cuts. Forgot our servers name during lunch but he was awesome! Ivan maybe? not sure. Sooyoung is cool too! Kept us entertained during dinner. 5 stars for service, always!

We always get beef combo cause it comes with 3 different kinds of beef. Good quality, me likey. Also IG worthy cause of the presentation haha

Tried duck flippers for the first time in my life. It's crunchy. Kinda in between pig ear, tendon & tripe lol. I wouldn't order it again but at least i can say I've tried it!

I love that they bring the whole shabang of condiments for you to mix it in your ponzu(citrus soy sauce). Huge star for having chopped Thai chilies. It's the main ingredient in all of my sauces!

Tomato oxtail broth is my personal favorite, extremely flavorful. Anything oxtail really, i love it all lol. If you're lucky, you'll actually get an oxtail in the soup. I like to suck the marrow out of it. Y U M !

I've sat at the 4 seater booths next to the conveyor belt every visit. BE CAREFUL getting in & out of those; my girl hit her leg pretty hard on the edge. You can order veggies from the menu or just grab it from the belt. Items on belt are in a smaller portion. Prices are listed below the belt.

My bf & I love AYCE, but CC isn't. It's on the pricier side when you have to order everything a la carte. so I only visit on special occasions, like when friends are in town. I usually bring them here for dinner. 10/10 would recommend!

text: This restaurant is one of my personal favorites to go to for dinner in Chinatown. It is reasonably priced, the service is quick, the food is gooood, and the wait to get a table is usually not too long. Most dishes are $10 or less and the portions are large. Some of my favorite dishes are the scallion pancakes and the duck noodle soup. I've tried other dishes such as the coconut chicken curry dumplings which weren't the best. However, this place is known for their noodles so I understand why their noodle soups are some of their better dishes.

text:
This place is a letdown, but an acceptable one since they have a much superior rival a block away. I lived in China from '09-'14 and the kind of skewered meat (and other options, but really it's all about that lamb) was a constant source of snacking joy, with nights at outdoor night markets often revolving around them and endless Tsingtaos. I include that to say I love Chinese skewers.

This place looks good from the outside - it's small, a little dingy looking maybe but in an appealing way. I pass by it all the time and it always seems like people are enjoying themselves over beers, conversation, and skewers. 

Well I went in once last year by myself and found that it was ok, but nothing that blew me away. The portions of meat on the skewers wasn't amazing by greedy American standards, but neither are they always in China. The difference here is that they're at American prices, which makes me want a bit more. But even with that in mind, I went there with a visiting friend from the old China days and wound up passing because of how unfriendly and unaccomodating the employee was to us. We went in, greeted her in Mandarin (we're both capable speakers) and asked if they sold beer. When she said no, we asked if we could bring some in since people always seem to be living it up in there when I walk by. She grumpily laid down a hard rule that each of us could bring one. We went out to check out TT Skewer on 9th Street. The kicker was that later on that night, we walked by again thinking they might still be open...and the door was unlocked and full of Chinese folks whooping it up over, you guessed it, skewers and drinks. They then told us they were closed and shooed us out.

So we get an unfriendly place that serves not-nearly-the-best of their product in a one-block radius. Skip.

text: Good Ameri-Chinese food! I enjoyed the Chicken Chow Mein and bestie ordered shrimp egg foo young. The latter was good, but i preferred the Chicken Chow Mein- it was all white meat and the vegetables were thick cut and very flavorful . Prices aren't bad and delivery fee is low. I would order the chow mein again but I don't think I'm an egg foo young fan though I think it was well prepared. There was a mixup with my order - though I ordered the Shrimp Chow Mein, I received Chicken Chow Mein. But just a simple phone call to the restaurant triggered a reimbursement of the difference. The manager asked me how I wanted it handled and was very polite and customer oriented. I appreciated that very much! So in spite of receiving the incorrect order I still enjoyed it very much and wasn't annoyed in the least :)

text:
It's been a while since I last came here and I forgot how good this place is! Not mind-blowing, but a very solid Shanghainese restaurant. The soup dumplings are flavorful and have a relatively thin skin. I personally think they're better than the ones at Dim Sum Garden. I also got the pan fried soup dumplings (sheng jian bao) and they were decent. The beef scallion pancakes are also yummy, though oily. Finally, we ordered the braised pork belly (hong shao rou), a Shanghainese classic and childhood favorite of mine. Understandably, it took longer to come out than our other dishes, so be aware that it takes a while to cook. I compare every pork belly to what my mom makes, and this one is (almost) just as good! Great flavor on the sauce and the pork belly is tender, though it could have been even just a little more so. Pro tip, mix the extra sauce with your rice. Don't let any of that deliciousness go to waste! 

Service here is surprisingly good for a Chinese restaurant. We were able to get both hot tea and cold water. It's actually lemon water and comes in a mason jar, a nice touch. However, none of our drinks were refilled throughout the course of the meal. The prices on our dishes were also very fair. Overall, not a restaurant you'd go to impress, but I'd definitely come back again and again.

text:
Cash Only. There is an ATM inside restaurant (but its best to just bring cash so you don't have to pay a fee). 

Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House is located in Chinatown, next door to Dim Sum Garden and 2 doors down from The Halal Guys. 

My husband and I came here a few minutes before 8 pm on a Friday night and were seated immediately. But we were lucky to get a table because it didn't look like there were any other tables left. 

Anyways, we were given menus and then ended up ordering:

Taro Smoothie, $3.25 prior to tax- My husband ordered this. This drink was on the sweet side and would ask if the sweetness level can be adjusted. Also this drink was powdery at times and would not recommend getting drinks here. 

Bok Choy With Fresh Garlic, $8.95 prior to tax- Tasty bok choy that is large enough to share with 4 people. Great garlic flavor but was oily. We did not finish this and had leftovers. 

Noodle With Peanut Sauce, $4.25 prior to tax- I opted for this dish since I prefer dry style noodles over noodles in a soup. I decided to get my noodles hand drawn (or hand pulled). But you can also choose knife cut, which makes for an even chewier texture. I liked the sauce that was used in this dish. Although this dish appears to be small, it was a perfect size for one person. 

Beef Tendon Noodle Soup, $8.50 prior to tax- My husband ordered this, as a recommendation from our friend who has dined here a few years before. He opted for the hand drawn style noodles too and thought it was a good texture for him. The tendons were tender and the soup was flavorful. A great portion for one but really could be shared with another person. 
------------------------
(Total= $26.95 after tax, prior to tip)

Service was fine for the most part. We had our water glasses refilled during our meal and we had dirty dishes removed. Employees did also check up on us more than once during our dining experience. 

Overall, the food was delicious, the price was pretty reasonable and I would come back here again if I was visiting Philadelphia again.

Please note that the restrooms are in the back, pass the register and down the long hallway. It was clean and adequately stocked with the essentials. 

Also the servers here do speak English so you shouldn't have a problem with making an order and eating here.
name_x: Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House

text:
Lunch special on point.  I had the Gen Tso Chicken.  Yes I know, pretty generic but since I had to get in and out it was quick and easy and tasted great.  

Lunch specials runs about $8.00 with your choice of steamed jasmine rice or brown rice, and wonton or Tom Yum vegetable soup.  

They have three themes with many more options beneath the those themes to choose from: Asian, Szechuan and Vegetable lunch plates. 

You can check their menu out here. 

http://www.spice28.com/menu-spice-28-asian-fusion-restaurant-1228-chestnut-st-philadelphia

text:
Ocean Harbor is a solid place to have dim sum at in Chinatown. 
The food is good and I would personally recommend the chicken feet (it's very good I swear!) and the shrimp dumplings and rolls. While you will get the fresher food on the weekends, I would expect a wait for weekend dim sum especially if you happen to come after 11:30 am when it generally seems to be busier. 
I'm pretty used to the dim sum style service but if you've never been to a dim sum place expect to have to be more proactive about asking for dishes especially on busier days when the servers pushing the carts are busy. Service here is meh... it can be extremely slow on busier days and some servers can be a bit rude sometimes. The food somewhat makes up for the service though and I would recommend Ocean Harbor for families or groups who are looking to eat dim sum for a cheaper price for pretty authentic food.

text:
While the atmosphere was lively, we were disappointed with the food. We made a reservation to celebrate a big birthday and wedding anniversary so we were expecting Buddakan to live up to its reputation of high end Asian fusion dining. 
The drinks were good and the tuna tartar spring rolls were delightful, but the rest of the meal fell short of excellent. 
The curried cauliflower tasted too much of mayonnaise, the soup dumplings and pepper beef were too salty, the noodles in the beef chow fun was a touch undercooked and the spicy eggplant was delicious but a dish I can find at any Chinese restaurant for half the price. 
The beef fillet and the shrimp were the best parts of the meal.
Overall, we are glad we ate at Buddakan but we will likely not return.

text:
Food [5/5] - My friend and I got the tasting menu, and we didn't regret it one bit. It was about 8 courses covering a gamut of Asian food offerings, and every course delivered. We also each ended up getting a fishbowl to ourselves; they don't have a ton of alcohol, but they're a blast to drink. The watermelon-flavored rum one was the best.

Service [4/5] - Our waitress was sweet and came to our table outside at fairly regular intervals.

Ambiance [5/5] - We sat at the outdoor tables, which are literally on the Philly street. I absolutely love sitting on city streets because you never know what's going to happen. In this case, a boppin street band marched right down the street next to us.

Value [5/5] - For the tasting menu and the fishbowls, it came out to a little over $100/person if I recall correctly. Solid deal for the amount and quality of the food we got.

So if you're looking for a hotpot experience for a good price, then this place is your best bet. Will def come back!

text: I have been going to Danny Wok off and on since 1993 when their wings cost about $.40/per wing. They are $1+ per wing now. This Thursday turned from not having my lunch day to my Treat Thursday! This was a normal setup for this kind of store, but nothing inviting about it. The sketchy people that hang outside begging for money when you come in and out of the store made me uncomfortable. However, when I am in the area, I make sure to get there wings. They weren't crowded like in times past. I was in and out the restaurant in less than 5 minutes. The young guy behind the counter was professional when he greeted and asked me if can help me, took my order and money. He even said thank you. In the past, it was a hit or miss on whether they would say thank you. They are so consistent with having those hot wings ready to pick up. They are crispy and not over cooked. Yes, the taste is equally yumful.

text: I go there with my family at least every month. This is the best hot pot place that we've tried and we've tried places in NY, NJ and PA. My daughter is a vegetarian and this is her favorite place to eat. The service can sometimes be a little slow but the servers and very nice in general and very polite.  Parking is pretty easy, so much easier than Chinatown.

text:
I so wanted to love this place. Heard plenty of good things, but it just didn't do it for me. Came in on a Friday around dinner time. We were seated quickly with a reservation at a table by the bar. I ordered a bourbon cocktail, which was pretty tasty but extremely small that it almost felt awkward picking up the glass.

We ordered the seafood mixto, cacio e pepe, and speck & egg pizza. Figured an appetizer, pasta, and main would've been sufficient. We were wrong. While everything tasted good, portions were tiny for the price point. After we ordered, bread came out, portioned by slice based on how many people were at the table... I know some places do this, but it was almost ironic as it set the stage for what was to come for the rest of our meal.

The seafood mixto was served in something smaller than a dip bowl. Again, taste was on point, but portion was just way too small. Next, the pizza, which was the highlight of the meal. If you're hungry, definitely order a pizza as it's reasonably sized and easy to share. Finally, the pasta, which despite my best efforts to eat slowly, was finished in 2 minutes. We asked for another menu but didn't get one until 15 minutes later. By that time, we decided to keep our money and eat something at home.

Overall, food was good, I just can't get behind places that charge high prices for tiny plates... if you want to be a fine dining spot, that's fine, but I like my Italian food big and heated up as leftovers for days.

text:
My friend and I eat here regularly either before or after a movie at the Riverview just a block away. The food is always impressive and near-empty bins are replaced regularly. It's very easy to overeat here because the food is just so darn good! Be careful how much you put on your plate, though; they will charge you a little extra if you waste food.

Prices are half price during lunchtime hours, so it's well worth the mid day meal! Check it out, you won't be disappointed!

text:
Came here with 3 friends for dinner on a Saturday, so it was decently busy but we were able to get seated right away. FYI this place is cash only but they have an ATM if needed.

We ordered salt and pepper squid as an appetizer (it was good but not amazing) and then ordered our respective rice noodle soups. First the noodles come out with the various side dishes that go into the soup, and then the soup comes out in a hot stone bowl. You can either have your server add and mix everything for you, or do it yourself. Service was also pretty good. They refilled my water when needed.

I got fish with sour cabbage rice noodle soup. For the price, the portion was pretty generous and there was a lot of fish. According to the menu it's pretty spicy but I didn't think it was that spicy at all. Even so I thought it was pretty good. My friend got the spicy szechuan soup and there was a lot of beef!! If you want to eat a lot of meat and like spicy food you should get that.

I'd come back to try the other soup bases.

text:
Nom Wah is a dim sum extravaganza with amazing quality and a nice ambiance.

The restaurant is a bit smaller than your typical dim sum palace. There are just a handful of tables on the main floor, with a few more in the basement. But it's a nice place if you want a more intimate experience. Plus, the decor is fun and the staff are friendly.

The food itself is why you come, though, and I can happily say that the food here does not disappoint. We enjoyed a feast of shumai, har gow, sticky rice, lotus leaf rice, bao, bok choy, spare ribs, soup dumplings, rice noodle rolls, turnip cakes, scallion pancakes, and more. Everything was amazing, and writing it down right now made me crave it all again! They don't have carts here - you need to order off the menu - which is a bit of a bummer, but it means all the food is fresh and delicious.

Prices are a bit higher versus other dim sum places in the area, but if you come with a big group, it's still a good deal - around $15-$20 per person. On the whole, a fantastic dim sum eatery which I'll definitely visit again!

text:
Tasty Szechuan dishes and excellent service at very reasonable prices in Center City. The space is small and the upper level has more seating. The decor is modern which I appreciate as it doesn't give off a typical Taiwanese/Chinese restaurant "feels". 

My two friends and I ordered several different small plates and entrees to share. My favorites were the pork belly with garlic chili oil, the pickled Szechuan shrimp and the snow pea leaves. I like how they didn't overcook the snow pea where it becomes soggy and drench in oil. The shrimp was cooked perfectly with the right amount of flavors. The pork belly was melt in your mouth spicy good. That dish might have been my star on the table. 

Unfortunately, I wasn't a fan of their version of dan dan noodles. It had an unusual peanut taste, which I'm not used to when it comes to dan dan noodles. Also, it was lacking in flavor. The spicy cucumbers were refreshing. The spicy wontons had spiciness and flavor. I'm just used to the wonton skins being thinner in texture with this dish. 

Overall, very delicious meal. We ate to our bellies and hearts content with a good amount of leftovers, and the total bill was just $82.56. Now that's value! I can't wait to come back when I'm in Philly!

text:
The roast pork wonton noodles are my go to at Ting Wong. The food here is pretty fresh and you get a considerably large portion of food. The prices here are fairly low in comparison to a lot of other restaurants I've been too. 

The service is okay. Your food comes you very quickly, but sometimes the service can be abrupt and the waiters can be irresponsive especially during rush hours when they're trying to shuffle people in and out. 

If you want a simple, authentic bowl of noodles in Chinatown, come to Ting Wong. They have great food and you really get your money's worth here.

text: I literally called before driving 20 min to this place to find out if they allowed ppl to take crab legs and crawfish home, the women told me "yes, seafood is $7.99 lb to go". I get there, there's barely any food out so I had to ask. The first waiter told me the crabs were $10.99 lb.  & I told her no, I called & asked. She says something to the other waiter, and then that waiter tells me $12.99. I explained the same thing to this waiter, and she just said "sorry & walked away." The same restaurant and different prices depending on who you talk too. I guess it depends on how much that particular waiter is trying to make on the side (probably because I was getting it to go & they wouldn't get a tip). Why would I pay $12.99 a pound when I could literally pay $13.99 to for all I can eat?

text:
Consumer beware: trickery and Fat, fat, fat! 

We ordered their famous beef noodle soup since we've heard great things. Much to our surprise and disappointment, 90% of the beef in the beef noodle soup was just sliced fat! When we complained, the wait staff tried to justify that the particular soup we ordered only uses the special kind of "fat beef", while they pointed to another dish and claimed "this is the one with real beef". They continued to say that the recipe we ordered can only be prepared with fat. WHAT? There's a dish that they only use fat?? Since we complained that the title of the dish said "beef noodle soup" and not "fatty beef noodle soup", they agreed to bring out some real beef. I suspect this is a common trick they pull on customers to cut costs. Terrible business practice, disgusting quality, even worse excuses. We will not be coming back here.
name_x: Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House

text: I went there with a coworker on a Tuesday night. It's crowded and we're seated in about 15-20 mins. The service was prompt. The atmosphere reminded me of any  gastropubs. It's hippy, dimmed light, loud music, and loud talking voices everywhere. These are all not bad. The reasons that I gave 3 stars are: (1) foods are expensive and not up to the quality I expected. I ordered a shrimp pad Thai and an appetizer of Mapo tofu. The sauce for both dishes tasted the same except a little spicier for the mapo tofu. (2) Foods are served in small portion. Be ready to order more than one dish if you want to have a full meal. Foods are served in tapa plate. Interestingly, sides are bigger portion than a "full plate" meal and they are cheaper too. It's a busy night and it took us a bit to get the order and the bill though we're not in hurry so I was okay with it. The server messed up my order thinking that I wanted both dishes when I asked him about the portion of the foods but luckily they took it back without charging me for the cost. I might failed to order the best dish on the menu. Given that there are so many other restaurants in town, I'd probably not going to return to the same place given my experience.

text: Location, location, location. If Dan Dan was located in Chinatown, it would get lost in the crowd, but because it's on 16th and Walnut/Sansom, it has an advantage of being the only Sichuan food in the area. Location is about all it has going for it though. I mean, the food is fine, but I certainly would not go out of my way to visit this place. The dan dan noodles were fine, the dumplings in chili oil were fine, the fish and string beans were fine. The Ma Po tofu was definitely below average. It had no taste other than spiciness, and I'm not sure if that's a real taste. Nothing really stood out, and it was kind of pricey for what it is. Then again, real estate in that part of town can't be cheap, so I'm sure that's baked into the prices. I'm more partial to Han Dynasty, but this place is ok if you're craving Sichuan cuisine in Center City and you don't mind being in a cramped restaurant.

text:
Overall Value: A very solid Sichuan restaurant, just a bit on the pricier side for the setting and amount of food.  Love these flavors, which I was first introduced to overseas, and coming here let's me get a much-needed fix.  This is probably 3.5 stars, weighing the food and price, but I rounded up.  

The Food: We got the Beef Brisket Noodle Soup ($8.96, A9 on the menu), Chilled Fungus (such a literal translation - it is wooden ear mushrooms.  $7.96, E7 on the menu), and Beef Drypot ($14.96, F1 on the menu).  
The brisket noodle soup was hearty with a rich broth flavor.  This would be perfect on a cold day (it was, unfortunately, the middle of summer). .  Not a TON of meat so manage your expectations, but it was one of the relatively cheaper options, so I can't complain too much.  
The wooden ear mushroom is always fun to eat because of the chewy texture.  This was no different, and it comes loaded with a vinegar/soysauce/garlic sauce and chilled, so it was very refreshing with strong flavor.  Again a little pricey at $8 for just mushrooms, but the mushrooms were big and fresh.
The Beef drypot gave us our much-needed meat fix, and with really good portion (and it should at $15).  In addition to the beef, there are also peanuts and scallion in the dish, and just loaded with dry spices.  I was definitely feeling the heat from the dish, which was perfect, and it's served with white rice to help balance out the flavors.  
Overall, I would return to try some of the rest of their very expansive menu.  

Space and Pace: Relatively small interior, but there was plenty of seating around dinner time.  Modern-ish vibe in a very casual setting, not too much different than a fast casual spot.  Probably a good spot for lunch, and a very casual meal with a small group of friends.  If you want a date spot, Han Dynasty is a better option.  

Service: A bit aloof, but overall they were fine.

text: Legit spicy beef noodle!! Having lived in China for more than half a year, I can attest that their 紅燒牛肉麵 is very authentic, it was better than any 蘭州拉麵 Lanzhou Lamian chain I've tried during my stay in China. 蘭州拉麵 chains were literally everywhere where I lived, Lanzhou lamian aka hand-pulled noodle is one of the most popular dishes across China. They were mostly owned by Chinese-Muslims, which is why the meat used for the noodle soup is either beef or lamb. I loved the 刀削麵 daoxiaomian (knife-sliced noodle) they used, I prefer this type of wide flat noodles than 細麵(thin noodle) because of the starchy and bouncy texture. The broth had a great flavor, its spiciness was just right and the exotic flavor of cilantro complimented the soup perfectly. My Korean and Jamaican friends who have never tried this noodle soup before all fell in love with this dish. The price was also great, super affordable and the service was quick too. 好吃又便宜！

text:
Call it 3.4 Stars - Dim Sum House is a slightly trendy, slightly college-begat-chain feeling dim sum spot that can hit the spot at a price that's fueled by Sally Mae (RIP).  The entrees were enjoyable, but the dim sum was nothing special.  I'd probably return for another shot at that Philosopher's chicken though!

We visited here as quick stop after my sister's brief graduation ceremony and I wanted to take the family out for a little nearby flavor.  We weren't disappointed, but I find it hard to go back with so many other delicious options nearby and in Chinatown. 

Pros:

The atmosphere is warm, inviting and clean.  While it was (of the smallest) inconvenient to walk upstairs to the restaurant, we were warmly greeted, quickly sat and appropriately waited on.  

Service was very fast and attentive.  Our food came in what felt like maybe 5 minutes (or less).  Almost disconcertingly fast.  I'm not sure how it was cooked that fast (or maybe it wasn't...hmm).  

I had the Philosopher's chicken, a warm, gooey, chipped chicken with a slightly spicy sauce.  It was enjoyable on the bed of white rice and I'd like to have again.  

My family tried other staples including chicken and broccoli and orange chicken.  They found them delicious.

Cons:

Again, the food came out very fast...but weirdly fast.  It's disappoiting that things are basically sitting ready to be sauced and plated that fast.  

We also snagged a few dim sum appetizers.  They were fine but uninspired.  Soup Dumpings were bland and even a spot of chili sauce or garlic sauce didn't save them.  

Prices were fairly high - even 14-16 dollars for a chicken and rice entree seems steep to me.  

Conclusion:  It's hard to nail down Dim Sum House as anything but another sorta mediocre Asian spot.  They've got a few stars on their menu and it's open late, which is great for the local crowds (I'd probably stay away at my advanced age), but the food is uninspired and generally average, especially it's name-sake dim sum.  However, do give the Philosopher's chicken a try if you'd like a little more heat than usual.

text:
It was my first time coming here. The servers and hosts were kind of awkward but it was nothing offensive or unbearable. 

When we ordered, we (a table of four) shared two orders of the classic DanDan Noodles, the Beef Noodle Soup, a Mini Rice Bowl with Meat Sauce, and Wontons. The food arrived pretty quick and I can definitely say the portions are huge. Price wise, you can expect to pay something similar in Chinatown, but the portions are definitely as big, if not bigger than other noodle places. It was like each bowl of noodles had 1.5-2 heavy handfuls of noodles and I was shocked by also appreciated of it. The portions, in general, were good if not generous. 

Flavor wise, it was good. I dont think we were blown out of the water when it came to flavor. The DanDan Noodles were a huge portion which a good amount of sauce, but the sauce had a weird after taste to me. I'm not sure what it was, but It was kind of bitter or medicinal?-- maybe some sort of fermented ingredient or msg? But honestly? The perfectly cooked, almost al dente, noodles and the other flavors of the sauce kept me going at it. We ended up having to split a lot of the noodles because the portions were so huge. The rice seemed like your standard meat sauce over rice dish, but it was super fragrant and my friend said it was "quite filling." The beef noodle soup broth was super savory and satisfying- and they didn't slump on it at all. Huge portion as well. The wontons on the other hand were kind of ehhh. Like they didn't have flavor or seasoning that was crazy or great-- it just tasted like meat and dumpling skins. 

Otherwise, Id still give this place a 4/5. It's definitely like perfect or great, but I would not be opposed to going again if it's on the way to somewhere or if others want to go. 

TL;DR- portions are quite generous. Flavors range from okay to good. Service is kind of awkward, but would go and try again!

text:
This review is for takeout only, as I have only ordered on Caviar. It's important to note their food is superior to all Chinese food I've had in Philadelphia. Specifically, the wonton soup is delicious; and I've had their chicken dishes, veggie dishes, pepper steak, and lo mein. I've been impressed with everything.

However, their prices are a little outrageous sometimes- the string bean dish is $12. It doesn't have any protein, and that feels steep. I know we are paying for quality, but I think a veggie side shouldn't be more than ten dollars max.

Also, the last time we ordered, the pepper steak was completely different and not good at all. It was way too saucy. This was only the one time, so we weren't sure what happened.

Overall I will keep eating here, but I know I will be spending upwards of $60 for two people. Maybe I will visit in-person to see if the quality control is a bit better.

text: My girlfriend, her friend and I went yesterday, Friday, for the first time. We arrived a little before 4pm to make sure we got seats at the bar for their happy hour. We ordered edamame dumplings, pork dumplings, chicken and steak skewers, banh mi, pork bao buns, Kobe beef sliders, kimchi fried rice, and pine it broccoli. We expected the size of the dishes to be small considering the low prices ranging from $4-$5 depending on the order. We had a plethora of food while enjoying decent house wine and Yards Philly Pale Ale that we're $5 a glass. The bartenders were delightful and the food came out quickly. I would recommend showing up a bit before 4pm if you don't want to wait because the place filled up quickly, and rightly so. The food was excellent, environment was superb and the service was impeccable. What a great place for any occasion with happy hour deals offered Monday - Friday.

text:
The hours of this place are awesome, open till 1 am. We landed late into Philadelphia and I was craving soup dumplings, luckily we were able to find this place on yelp.

We got there at 10 pm and it was still very busy, lots of people were ordering dinner. The restaurant is on the second floor in the university area. 

We ordered the 2 orders of the pork soup dumplings, the pickled garlic cucumber, the crystal shrimp dumpling and the veggie fried rice. 

The picked garlic cucumber was one of the highlights, I'd come back just for this. It was flavored really well and added a fresh, cool aspect to the meal. 

The two things that I thought were just okay were the crystal shrimp dumplings and the veggie fried rice. Both were cooked well but lacked flavor. Adding the vinegar chili oil helped bring some flavor to the dish but not sure I would order those again.

The soup dumplings were great. Came out hot and were filled with flavor. They were actually larger than most xiao long bao's I've had in the past so great value too. I'd definitely come back for the soup dumplings.

text:
My go-to restaurant for the past 3 years. I come here for a lot of different occasions and really there is no bad time for Dan Dan. I've done take out a few times as well and had no issues. The dishes are pricey so this may be a treat yo self kinda meal once, rather than a weekly event. A few dishes I've enjoyed over the years:

1) Veggie Dan Dan noodles - a classic must try. 

2) Cumin Tofu - LOVEEEE. Chewy fried tofu - It grows on you. I usually don't like spicy but 4/5 spice level is very easy to enjoy in this dish. This isn't the fact for some other dishes!!

3) Tofu with long peppers - good!
4) Scallion pancakes - yum, get it. 
5) Mapo tofu - the sauce is bomb.

text:
Parents beware: burn risk! 

Possibly one of the worst dining experiences we've had in Philly. 

Menu recommends that only kids 6 and up cook their own food in the hot pot.  The pot seems far enough away and deep enough that burns are unlikely. I helped my 9 year old with most of the cooking but she grabbed the ladle at one point and by accident dropped it into the soup. Boiling liquid went flying and she now has a second degree (partial thickness) burn on her flank (my wife and I are both pediatricians). 

She was in severe pain and very frightened. Staff hurried over with ice and were very apologetic. 

Of course it was our responsibility as parents as well but this is not appropriate at all for young kids. They really should restrict the age further. They make it seem like kids do this all the time and it's not a problem. 

Manager took off 50% of bill which was probably not enough in my opinion. 

Food we got to eat was good but added up to $100 before too quickly. Not a great value. 

We went on Labor Day Monday. Checked in on Yelp but when we got there and we were first in love, was still 15-20 minute wait for lunch. 

Grossly understaffed on a very busy day. Poor staff was literally running to keep up. The place felt tense and hurried. They did their best but everything came out slow and not together. 

We're not coming back.

text:
My review is based on 5 factors only in this hotpot place.
Broth, the base lets me know this is a regular hour restaurant and they make the soup not much earlier than customers step into this place which makes it less flavorful.
Sauce bar, it's pretty regular. They can clean it more often if waiters are not busy playing with phones or staring for gratuities.
Food quality, it depends on what you pick. Beef and pork could be good most of the days. They could be more generous with portion due to limited time and price per head. Seafood is something you roll your dice with. My shrimp is not big size at all like they describe on menu. Dumplings are bad and frozen for long time, do not try dumplings.
Service, we were satisfied with our waiter. But only our waiter, not anybody else since nobody willing to help him to take care his table.
Space, it's not the most ideal space to have hotpot since it's spacing is tight and they can only put trays of food on the table, not on a tray by table. The vent system is worst here. We got the steam comes back down to our pot and bodies when there's no good ventilation. Time to check with department of health.

text:
This place is delicious! I came here on a Monday afternoon with my friend, and it was not too busy! We were able to get a table the moment we walked in. 

The restaurant itself is very spacious and the decoration was cute. It definitely has a good friendly vibe to it. It is also not too loud and perfect for friends to catch up. I ended up chatting with my friend here for 2+ hours!

This place is known for their dry and soup spicy pots. My friend and I both got the soup one. You could pick your own protein, vegetable, base, etc. you could add as much stuff as you want in your bowl! You could also adjust how spicy it is. I personally got mild mild because I have a baby's tongue. It was iust perfect. 

The serving size was huge for a really fair price. This meal ended up turning into 3 meals, but I only paid 18 ish dollars for it! It was also really good. Would definitely come back here again!

text:
So, I have never been to another Brazilian steakhouse for comparison's sake but IMO this place was a-ok. I suspect it'll give you the meat sweats just as well as any other similar spot in the city. That being said, it's a good spot for a group. The tables are large and the food keeps on coming until you're ready for it to stop. 

We started at happy hour. Drinks were 1/2 priced which is a good deal but be warned, the second it's done the prices are no joke. The drinks are delicious but also VERY spend-y, even for the city.  

The salad bar was not what I expected. I would probably refer to it as a bar of salads rather than a traditional salad bar. Depending on your interests there may or may not be salads that appeal to you.  At the end of the day, you're not there for the salads so maybe it doesn't matter. There was a good quinoa salad that I liked and they had tomato, mozzarella and basil so I could make my own caprese. I did love that there were rice and beans on the bar as well as a creamy vegetable soup that was quite good.

There was meat... a lot of it. They come and slice it off for you and have a variety of done-ness available each time they came around. Some were better seasoned than others. I particularly liked the garlic seasoned and the picanha. The others were ok but nothing spectacular. That being said, there was a lot of whatever you liked. The variety of sauces on the salad bar were great and, necessary for some of the less interesting/flavorful cuts.  

This is a fun thing to do for a group dinner or special occasion but I can't see myself becoming a regular. Too many great options in the city.

text:
A perfect lunch special for a hole in a wall restaurant. A gem on Spring Garden that has me excited to go back. The reasonable prices and diverse menu make this a must visit for another asian craving.

I went with a work colleague at the SDOP and he has been a frequent customer. I was feeling the onset of a cold so I opted for something spicy . The Double Cook with Chicken is what I chose and it's spicy and fresh taste are the reason for this review. My colleague had the Curry Sauce that I will try next time.

Additionally I had the wonton soup and was glad this, or a salad, were some of the options for the lunch special. Both were good tasting and I recommend this restaurant when you are nearby.

text: This was my second time trying Shan Chaun. The first time I dined in, this past time I opted for take out. The spicy tuna was not good. The tuna did not taste fresh or look fresh, like other places I have tried. I had the Alaska roll, that was okay, but only a small piece is salmon. The third roll I tried was the Shrimp tempura, which was tasty. I also tried the Kano salad, it was deconstructed, not mixed together like I typically see. The food was less than average, and unfortunately, I will be looking for another sushi place to try. They were close to me, with okay prices, but the food quality is not up to my standards for sushi. I definitely had a better experience when I dined in.

text: As a previous review mentioned, this place is what you think it is- easy, fast delivery for chinese food with no-frills and no hassle. Food came within 20 minutes for lunchtime and the spring rolls were hot, the rice was steamed well and the noodles were good. Beef lo mein was my favorite in my order, just needed a little more soy sauce, beef was pretty good quality, and it was an average price for a pint of lo mein. The only problem I had was I ordered two types of chicken- general tso and orange chicken, both lunch specials. The chicken itself was pretty well cooked and the sauce was sweet, but they tasted exactly the same. No difference in flavor, quality of chicken, or orange to be found anywhere. While I agree that some things can be overlooked when ordering from a neighborhood joint, having two separate dishes cooked the same exact way? Not really a good way to get consistent new customers. Not necessarily a sign of gentrification, more a byproduct of people wanting what they paid for.

text:
This is a great example of Hong Kong (HK) food,the style is very authentic ASK FOR SWEET & SOUR SOUP/USE THE RED HK-STYLE vinegar on the top of the soup along with the light gray-black HK pepper (No that's NOT the salt), stir & ENJOY and the duck and the pork hanging in the window is to die for! Better than Peking duck in Beijing (NO JOKE). 

You can try the authentic bamboo shoots and pork, and noodle soup with duck (or, swine) is the perfect hangover cure! Prices are very reasonable service is blistering fast and you'll be the only foreigner/NON Hongkongese person in HERE---& they speak primarily Cantonese FYI NOT Madarin....TOP TIP: REQUEST they use LESS SALT/Less GREASE prior to ordering, Chinese American restaurants try to kill our food w/ salt & fat which is completely different in HK where the primarily OMIT the aforementioned & let the food & flavors stand on their own!

"Please use LESS salt & fat for my order PLEASE, thank you!" THEN you'll see why this fast, simple, homestyle HK fast food duck restaurant gets 5 STARS !!! DISCLAIMER the duck fat & salt is the BOMBdotCOM!

text:
Hello yes I know I'm black lol, walking into this establishment all eyes were on me and my 7yo sdaughter... not a cruel evil feel just an awkward "are you sure you're in the right place" look.. after 10 long seconds an older woman asked did I need "help" i wasn't sure if this was strike 1 or 2 at this point. I asked for a menu and to be seated and she just pointed... (that was definitely a strike) the restaurant screamed Chinese store and that's exactly the prices I was looking for. 

I ordered chicken lomein for my daughter,(we both shared it... it was good the noodles seemed to literally soak up all the seasonings perfectly, at first glance you'd think they are dry)

the fried pancake thing everyone else seemed to have(I thought it would be like a scallion pancake... not at all, that was awful) 

a duck soup (which I thought was a pho but they use a different type of noodle still good)

 and pork dumplings(juiciest dumplings I've ever had, fried just right) 

They only took cash so I went across the street to the gift shop... nothing was wrong with the bill it added up just right with 8% tax and I gave them a $5 tip... 

The second time I returned it was a lunch break I remembered it was cash only and only had their magnificent dumplings again can't beat it st $10! Still those awkward looks though.. this time the customer service was much better from the older woman.

text:
"Good things come to those who wait" (so they say). Bai Wei has been saved in my collections for a while now & I'm glad to say I finally made my way here (though it wasn't planned)!

Arrived shortly before closing and although you can tell they were preparing for that, the waiter was super nice and took his time attending to my guest & I. 

We ordered the Shrimp & Vegetables dumplings along with two separate orders of fried rice. Even though I am not a beef fried rice fan, I decided to try their Beef Fried Rice with Black Truffle. TBH! The idea of truffle in fried rice did not sound all that appealing, but since the waiter recommended it I decided to go with his suggestion. Thank God! Because, WOW! I have never had anything like it. If you ever get a chance to visit Ba Wei, I would highly suggest trying this dish out. 
The dumplings were also pretty good. 

Fairly priced, located in Chinatown and the decor is super chic and modern. Would definitely recommend (However, bring cash because they were not taking cards at the time.)

text:
China Gourmet is a very pleasant surprise if you, like me, love a traditional dim sum Chinese brunch every once and a while. 

Situated on St. Vincent Street in Northeast Philly between Brous Avenue and Roosevelt Boulevard in Mayfair, it is a large house in a developing Asian neighborhood that puts out trolley carts loaded with small dish treats both savory and sweet, at reasonable prices and with the expected hussle and flow that this dining style uniquely delivers. Admittedly, the aggressive nature of the cart ladies hawking their delicacies takes some getting used to. You have to be able to say "no" when you feel overwhelmed by the surrounding din. But, know that slowing down the onslaught is proper, and multiple opportunities will present themselves. Just take what you want in the moment and let the trolley women return when you are ready for more. 

The most important thing at China Gourmet is that they know from dim sum. There are dozens of choices and most of them are good to great. Shrimp and pork shumai, shrimp hargow, beef rice rolls w vinegar, fried stuffed buns, various dumplings, fish filled chili peppers, egg tarts and many others are well prepared and served hot or cold as appropriate. My bowl of congee was also decent with plenty of ground pork and fresh cut scallion on top. There is plenty more, but you get the picture. 

What's even better is the availability of FREE PARKING right in front of the restaurant, and the large Asian supermarket and Vietnamese kitchen right next door. The money saved is like getting a 25% discount off your check! Hard to beat! 

Now that we've experienced the fun and convenience of a strong dim sum morning with grocery shopping for dessert, Chinatown has lost some of its cultural luster for us (not completely). 

Gotta love it!

text:
So, this will have to be a pass for me next time. I'm a huge hot pot fan and had my share of hot pots around Philly. This was probably rated the lowest. Service was great, which upsets me giving them only 2 stars, but the food was just not there.

Came strictly for hotpot with my kids. Prices are similar to other AYCE places, but not everything was included that would have been included at other places.

Broth - the tom yum broth just wasn't there. It was missing spice and the sour taste that a tom yum should have. I had to grab some spice and sauces from the sauce bar to try to give it more flavor. The oxtail broth was decent and filled with more oxtail than others, but again, lacked flavor and was an upcharge. It might have been because the server came by rather early and drowned down the broth with their standard water. My broth wasn't even halfway gone and they came by with the kettle and started pouring.

Choices of meats/hotpot items - there was plenty of choices available, but they had a good amount of stuff that was upcharged. I really wanted tofu skin rolls, but that was additional. For the cuts - the meats were SO THICK! Typical hotpots would dip the beef, swoosh swoosh a tad, take it out, and YUM. I had to leave my beef in here for quite some time as it was like bacon. And bc the meat was very thick, it was hard to chew as well. Shrimp - pass on this! It's not the full sized shrimp that was pictured. It's the type of shrimp I would find in a seafood salad at the grocery store.

text:
Tom's is a disappointing "dim sum" restaurant with just mediocre dim sum quality and more generic Chinese food than actual dim sum.

We've come here multiple times for group events. In general, the dumplings have been good, but the rest was lackluster. The shumai is nontraditional, the har gow and the scallion pancakes are so-so, the bao are too bready, and many quintessential dim sum dishes are just missing. Instead, their menu has a lot of so-so generic Chinese dishes, such as chicken stir-fries, noodle dishes, pork skewers, and other random things. These tasted ok, but they definitely didn't fit the dim sum theme.

Service was generally friendly and fast, and the prices were ok (around $15 per person). The venue is also decently nice, though it can get loud when it's full. Also, since it's under a covered stretch of the road, it's not as bright inside.

Overall, there are significantly better dim sum restaurants in the area, so if that's what you crave, try somewhere else.

text:
If you're dreading the traffic towards Center City and Chinatown. Then this is great place in the NE for quick no fret Dim Sum. I'm only speaking for the Dim-Sum only as I've yet to try their other items. 

Huge Restaurant. Never knew that it was this large inside. 

Parking is available. 

Many selections and offerings. It was a pleasant surprise that their Shu-Meis were actually made in-house. Something that we should appreciate. 

Price point is great as it seemed to be a little cheaper than Jade Harbor on Bustleton Ave. watering service was on point and very attentive. Will definitely be back.

text: I can't believe I'd gone so long without coming here! The food is incredible, with great prices, and a clean atmosphere with attentive staff - what more could you ask for? I love braised beef noodle soup, so I knew I had to order it here - flavorful and perfectly seasoned with just the right amount of spiciness! The portion size was generous with plenty of meat, perfect for leftovers. We also ordered the Szechuan cold noodles, which I would also recommend. For an appetizer we got the scallion pancakes, which were very crispy and thin. I will definitely be back!

text: I have been in this place numerous times as their cuisine is very nostalgic. I have enjoyed everything in their menu. Price is affordable and serving size is moderate. The place can get crowded during dinner time and there might be a wait approximately 15 minutes. I have brought my uncle and aunt here from California and they have enjoyed it as well. Growing up with Chinese traditions and food, this is the closest thing I had while living in Philadelphia. I definitely recommend this place and would come back. They have a branch in reading terminal Market that I frequently visit especially for the duck. Don't forget the hoisin sauce with the duck.

text: The Chubby Cattle was a really cool and different experience for my Wife and I. It is located in Chinatown in Center city Philadelphia so you will have to find a parking garage or Uber in. The establishment is primarily a hot pot restaurant but they do offer sushi along with other oriental cuisine. The restaurant is very well maintained and beautifully decorated. The staff is more than helpful if you have never done hot pot before and very friendly and professional. The food is a bit pricey but very fresh and tasty. It is a very cool experience where you order your meat, veggies and starch and cook it yourself in a hot pot at your table that contains a broth of your choice. We were more than happy with the experience except for one thing and that is we got the check about half way through our meal. We felt a bit rushed because of that. I would definitely recommend giving them a shot if you have never done hot pot before it is a nice experience. I may be back at some point but it would have to be at a time that  I had a few extra bucks because it is an expensive dine out.

text:
This is the one of the only two places I would get hot pot in Philly. The other place is About Hotpot and I go for their spicy soup base. Chubby Cattle, on the other hand, is a very different style and more specialized in their top-quality beef, and very smooth and rich bone soup base (non-spicy). The lines are crazy during weekends, but you can join their Yelp waitlist and you get a free dish of meat if you wait for more than a certain amount of time (maybe around 15 minutes). The dishes are just the regular ones you'll be able to get in a typical hot pot restaurant, with normal prices. 
There are three complaints though:
1.  I'm definitely not a fan of their spicy soup base, and it's no way near the traditional Szechuan soup base you're able to get in Chinese supermarket
2. They don't have pre-mixed Ma Jiang (sesame sauce) that is used as a dipping sauce in North. When I ask for Fu Ru (bean curd paste), I was told that they don't have any, so I couldn't even make my own dipping sauce.  
3. Although the restaurant seems clean, there are some flies in the room and we had to pay very close attention to make sure that they don't land on our uncooked food.

text: If you are looking for the traditional dimsum from Hong Kong, this is the place to go! They have branches both in New York and here in Philly! I have been to this place countless times  mostly with friends to have them a taste of the nostalgic dimsum. The traditional way was serving it in mobile carts but the food nevertheless still has the authentic quality. The siao long bao somehow isn't done to perfection. The rest of the dimsum are great. Order the siomai and the bean curd dishes. You will never go wrong. They have vegetarian options as well. If you are looking for something spicy, they also offer. Not much waiting time and plenty of tables and chairs to sit. Restrooms are clean. The noodles with dumplings are also delicious. Clearly this is one of my favorite places to eat! Prices are very affordable. There is also adequate parking nearby. Definitely recommended!

text:
Love the novelty of an all you can eat Brazilian steakhouse.  The buffet is chalked full of good high end items where some theorize they try to get you to fill up in that as opposed to eat the more expensive meats.  Regardless the salmon at the buffet and carpaccio are a real treat.  They have other veg options there along with an accompaniment of sauces to pair with the meats.

The meats themselves are top notch.  Personally I prefer the Rib eye and lamb chops.  In my eyes the filet doesn't hold weight to the these especially with regards to quality and taste.  

I will say the mixed drinks are pricy coming in at $14 a pop for a capharina that you can suck down in less than 3 minutes.  Opt for the beer and wines better buy.  The happy hour helps out with drink prices are some become buy one get one or half off.

text:
I've walked by this shop innumerous times, each time thinking this place is perpetually closed with the dark-lit windows and the seemingly un-openable doors. However, if you muster the courage and pull hard enough, turns out the door is just really heavy. 

Oh yeah, CASH only.

I've lived in Northern China throughout my childhood and I have developed a fondness for skewers, particularly lamb skewers. What attracted me to Solo was the fact they not only carried the traditional cumin-laced lamb skewers, but also chicken hearts and gizzards, some of my favorite childhood snacks. While the place was completely empty with barely any place to sit down, Solo Skewer is meant for a quick drop and go kinda place. Ironically, since all of the meat are cooked at the spot, be prepared to wait 5-10 minutes for the meat to cook and eat. My favorites is still the gizzards. I think the chicken hearts were a bit undercooked and the lamb a bit too fatty.

Overall, this was a great blast of the past and I do recommend it, especially if you haven't had any comparable experiences.

Food: 4 stars
Service: 3 stars
Price: 3 stars
Ambiance: 2 stars

text: I am not going to lie, my friend and I drove from DC to try these hyped dumplings. I have to say it was worth it. They are delicious. We came at lunch on a weekday and it wasn't busy. By the time we left, the line along the wall had started to form for people to be seated. We had the pork and crab soup dumplings, shrimp dumplings, and pork pan fried dumplings. They were all delicious. The pan fried dumplings might have been the best I have had. The only negative thing is that they don't give you the small containers for your sauces, so it was very difficult to have soy sauce on the small plate they provide- especially if you wanted vinegar, also. The soup dumplings were so rich and warm, I will definitely be thinking about them until I return. The service was quick and food came out pretty fast. It is cash only. The prices are really cheap! This is a really good spot in Chinatown- and worth the hype!

text:
I work near to Spice 28 and it's become a pretty regular lunch spot for me. Their lunch deal is great, you get a large entree with a soup for under $10. 

I was conflicted on what rating to give Spice, because I literally only like two items there. I've tried a bunch of different stuff on their menu over the past year and I generally am not too into their offerings. There's so much great Chinese food in Philly that this place just doesn't cut it for most dishes. The food tends to be super greasy and just low effort overall. 

BUT, that take does not apply to their Dry Pepper Chicken and their Three Pepper Chicken (which is just Dry Pepper Chicken with some chopped up peppers mixed in). These dishes consist of a huge portion of white rice with ultra spicy fried chicken. It's absolutely horrible for you, but it tastes SO good. The chicken is well cooked and that spice mixture is fantastic, I can taste it as I type this, I wish I could mix garlic and peppers as perfectly as they do in these dishes. 

For the soup, I usually get miso. It's pretty good, it honestly used to be really bad, but out of nowhere they upped their soup game. Their version is simple, with only some tofu chunks and seaweed floating in the broth. 

I've never eaten in the restaurant, so I can only speak to the pickup experience. I order online via their website and my food is ready in 15-20 mins. The place is really busy at lunch time, so I think that's pretty good timing. 

As for the rating, I had to go with three stars. I almost went with four stars because I love those two dishes so much, but everything else I've had just wasn't that great. But, if you're in need of a quick, filling, and affordable meal, Spice 28 is a really good option.
