text: Was craving some Asian food while staying in Philly for work. Saw good things about this place online and on yelp, and because I'm a huge fan of Dan Dan noodles I had to come here and try it. I have to say I was a bit underwhelmed - the flavor was decent but the noodles were a bit too thick for my liking and I wish it was a bit spicier. Just not quite as good as the Dan Dan noodles I've had back home in the LA area. I do have to say the portion was pretty good for a decent price (~$8). It'll work if you're craving schezuan food and don't have other options. But I probably won't come back.

text:
What a disappointment. This used to be me and my friends favorite Chinese restaurant, but now it has become one of the worst. We don't know if the chef or owner has changed, but the food is just so bad.

We ordered pork belly in sweet garlic soy, and that turned out to be some pathetic looking thin slices of unevenly cut pork in a bowl of chili oil. The dish tasted like it just got out of the freezer. But this used to be one of our favorite dish at Dan Dan.

We also ordered wonton in chili oil. The wonton tasted soggy and was again, in a bowl of chili oil. It was so spicy we couldn't even finish it. (Waitress was yawning when she was taking the order and didn't bother to ask what level of spice we wanted).

Anyways. Will not come back here. Jane G or a couple of Chinese restaurants in Chinatown (E Mei or Bai Wei) have really stepped up their game while maintaining good price. Dan Dan shame on you.

text:
I mainly went here for the (double) margarita pizza which was delicious (but Beddia has better). I also got the Cacio e pepe and sausage ragu. They were all small plates which I was unaware of because the menu doesn't specify that the pasta and pizza options are shareable between 2 people. The cacio e pepe had way too much black pepper. The pizzas are also only 12".

If the menu portions were full entrees for one person, than I would've rated this 4 stars but unfortunately, the prices were too high. 

I also like places that give free bread in the beginning and this place did but they only gave 2 small pieces - who does that?!

This is the only place I could find my hometown taste which is closest to where I live, yes, 3.5 hours driving without traffic. Whenever I come to PA, or pass PA, I would always stop by here. 

The price on the menu was good(if she didn't added some "additional charge" on your bill). The food was very tasty and it's transitional Fuzhou style food. 

This time I ordered several dish and was told the total was $26, I gave her $30 and told her to keep the charge. I never thought the bill was wrong until later I added up all the amount together when I was driving. 

I know I would still come back whenever I go to or pass PA. But I will definitely ask for bill or calculate it before I pay. 

Oh, do not expect any customer service. The lady has some attitudes, really impatient and get annoyed at whatever you ask her.

text:
Restaurant week review: I couldn't help but compare Chima to its competitor that's down the street. Price was $35 for a limited selection of meats and no dessert.. They offered the full churassco plus dessert for $50 but that personally is too pricey for me to spend on one meal. I felt like I was discriminated for choosing the limited meat selection! Every time a server came up with meat, he'd turn around seeing that I didn't have the full selection. I swear every server had a meat for the regular churrasco and none for me. There weren't that many meat servers as compared to its competitor. I was waiting long periods in between my meats and I was unhappy. The only meat I really got was the top sirloin, everything else, I had to personally ask my waiter to order for me. Not to mention, the meats that I did receive were all so salty. Was so underwhelmed and disappointing. I regret choosing Chima over Fogo! My dad felt embarrassed becuz he was made to feel like he couldnt afford the full churassco and was left waiting for meat constantly and everyone else was getting consistently served. But my servers Gabby and Hamilton were great; I just didn't find worth in the food and the dining experience. Constantly waiting and watching others get meats left and right. 

I think everyone received a $20 coupon for next time use but I don't think we will be coming back.

text:
I'm beyond thrilled to see Pei Wei come to the Fashion District Philadelphia!

Anyone who follows me knows that Pei Wei is my favorite chain restaurant, and may know that I frequently hit the suburbs to get my fix. A few of those have closed up, but now we have a brand new location right in the heart of Philadelphia's East Market resurgence!

This may not be a typical Pei Wei restaurant, being a smaller location in a shopping food court, but it does include a number of menu highlights - including its most popular appetizers, entrees, noodle & rice bowls, sushi, and drinks. You will have a small wait for the food, but it's never frozen and always freshly made upon your order.

There are few seats in this primary space, but there is plenty of seating just a step away within the mall corridor.

The easy way to access Pei Wei is to enter the Pennsylvania Convention Center entrance on 12th & Market, go down the escalators on the right-hand side, and the Food Court will be straight through the doors (which is also where Jefferson Station is, for Market-Frankford Line).

Unfortunately Pei Wei does not serve its delicious crab wontons or its spectacular Mandarin green tea here, nor do they seem to be a part of the Pei Wei Rewards program (you don't get credit for your meal). Although, many restaurants have similar practices to limit menu & rewards when it comes to their mall or airport locations.

But, what you do get here is Pei Wei's delicious & fresh food at reasonable prices, in the heart of Philadelphia and within steps of your home or office!

text:
Pretty good food with reasonable prices! We used this place as and opportunity to try some dishes we had never seen before (see: jellyfish picture) and were pretty satisfied. The servers were really nice. They get really busy, so you might have to wait a little but if you want something like water, but for the most part, I couldn't complain too much.

The food was pretty good -- not necessarily anything worth screaming over, but I definitely don't regret it. If you do go though, the chicken is WHERE IT'S AT! Get it over rice, and it was my favorite part. 

The jellyfish was okay in our opinion in case you were wondering, but obviously we can't tell you how it is with respect to other jellyfish dishes

text: We went to Chubby Cattle on a Saturday night at about 615 and were able to get a great seat considering when we left it was a complete zoo and people were lined up outside. The table was comfortable for two and the atmosphere and the vibe were really nice. The service was very good. We ordered the Kobe beef platter as well as a mixed array of beef platter and had a few of the dumplings (yuk) and mushrooms that came around on the conveyor belt next to the table. I ordered one beer and the price of dinner was $92 plus a $20 tip for a total of $112. Considering Chinatown the type of food etc. I thought it was overpriced. I I am glad I went but doubt I will be running back anytime soon.

text:
3 for the food, 5 for the service, 4 for the overall ambience, 3 for the pricing

Setting: Sunday lunchtime around 1pm with 1 other guest, we were seated promptly with Chinese music playing in the background and fun decor inside

Ambience: The wait staff are incredibly efficient and attentive

Food:
Xiao Long Bao Soup Dumplings - have a weirdly acidic aftertaste, definitely could do better at other locations such as Dim Sum Garden, would NOT recommend

Crispy Salted Chicken / Popcorn Chicken (Taiwanese) - pretty good crispy texture, large pieces of chicken with a standard serving size and price, comes with a slightly tangy mayo sauce - partially would recommend

Taiwanese fried rice noodle - also pretty standard quality food, comes with a large serving, has egg, some meat, not overly salted

Tips/Takeaways:
-Would recommend return every 5-7 months, would recommend the Taiwanese fried rice noodle
-Would recommend against the Xiao Long Bao here.
-Good overall ambience and service, nice music in background, clean, quick service

text: Dinner devours are came from Sang Kee Peking Duck House! Upon entering the restaurant who agreed it in a very nice manner and Sho to our table. While sitting at the table I've noticed that this restaurant has a very nice decor. However, since it was a little warm that day and temperature, they had the air conditioning on frostbite. We ordered a simple comfort food  dinner just to warm up. We ordered the spicy Tom Yum seafood soup for two . This soup included very large scallops, large pieces of tilapia fish, nice size pieces of squid, and very large shrimp. It also came with onions and assorted vegetables such as mushrooms carrots. The broth was very flavorful and not too spicy. This dish came with udon noodles, but I preferred it with a side of rice. This was a very affordable dish ranging in at $13.95. If you ever want a nice bowl of comfort Tom Yum soup please check out the same king Peking duck house in china town. #philadelphia #chinatown #philly #soup #tomyumsoup #carrots #vegetables #mushrooms #food #foodphotography #foodie #foods

text:
Restaurant Week Review! 

Overall Value: Wow, such high hopes based on the other reviews - I really don't get it.  Watered-down tasting "Modern Asian" food (whatever that means) at a price that just isn't worth it (not even at restaurant week prices).  Just go to Han Dynasty or any number of places in Chinatown and get the good stuff.  

The Food:  This was $35/person restaurant week prix fixe menu. For the most part, it was aggressively bland and underwhelming.  I know the quality usually takes a bit of a dip during restaurant week, but wow I cannot imagine ever paying full price for this stuff. 
Tuna Pizza: The bread on this was way too thick and flavorless, totally masking the flavor of any tuna.  Could have used a spicy mayo or something to inject some flavor.
Chicken & Ginger Dumplings: Also pretty bland, even with the dipping sauce.  They were fine, just not as good as run-of-the mill Chinatown spots. 
Pan Seared Bass: This one really disappointing, because the reviews were all so positive.  The fish and every component on the plate were just so bland, like they were afraid of flavor.  The fish was very tender, which was nice.  But removing the skin - and thus, no crispy skin on what is normally like a $37 dish - should be a criminal offense.  
Beef Chow Fun:  This was actually pretty good - the beef short rib is rich in flavor and a little goes a long way.   Also decent portion and good chew to the noodle.  That said, the flavor was a touch bland, and no way is this worth a price premium.  
Dip Sum Doughnuts:  These were really good, although I really didn't get any "five spice" flavor.  They just tasted like regular sugar doughnuts (albeit really good sugar doughnuts), so if you do come, you should definitely get these.  Pillowy soft + variety of dipping sauces is a win.  That said, no way are these worth $12(?!) normally.  They aren't revolutionary or mind blowing, they are just good sugar doughnuts.
Candy Bar: This was not very good.  Waaaay too dense and too sweet, with nothing to cut the sweetness or balance the dish in any way.

Space and Pace:  Super modern atmosphere plus giant Buddha.  Having a giant Buddha seems pretty cultural appropriation-y to me, but if you're going to do it, at least remember to appropriate some flavors while you are at it. Smh.  

Service:  Service is very good here - extremely attentive waitstaff (maybe overly so, they come around like every 2 minutes).  All very friendly and accommodating.

text:
4/5 for the two times I've come for overall quality/expediency of food/service

Setting: I came several times as a pair or a larger group of 5 - it's usually bustling and you can also buy the classic Chinese cut meats from the butcher up front

Ambience: Usually bustling, not too loud

Service: Relatively attentive, you get your food quickly

Food:
-3 combo meat platter: Chicken, Duck, BBQ Pork - thinly sliced cuts of meat, a little bit on the colder side the several times I've ordered this, but usually a Go-To staple you can't go wrong with
-Seafood pan-fried noodle: Crispy, fun play on texture with the sauce, a bountiful array of seafood to complement the meat
-Snowpeas: Can't go wrong here either

Tips/Takeaways:
-Would recommend return for take-out or a well-priced Chinese meal with the above dishes I've ordered
-Is comparable to restaurants like M Kee, so far one of the better of the Canto restaurants in Chinatown that I have tried.

text:
My favorite place to get Cantonese roast meats in Philly. The folks who work there are always really nice, kind. The prices are reasonable. Cash only, so plan accordingly.
The roast pig is better than any I've gotten elsewhere. It's soooooo juicy. Other joints tend to overcook this cut. Siu Kee's is alway soft, flavorful without relying on a shitton of five spice. The skin is crispy heaven. $12/lb.
The roast duck is THE meatiest duck being sold, that I've ever found. Again, not subjected to an over abundance of five spice.
My mom had scallion chicken over rice. She said the chicken was nice and soft, the flavor lovely, but she could NOT stop going on about how flavorful the rice was.
It's just a small take out joint, with a limited menu.  But what they have on offer is the best I've had. I've had a lot of Cantonese roast meat joint food, in a lot of places. This is my favorite place to get it.

text:
Sampan serves up decent Asian fusion cuisine, albeit with confusing and unhelpful service policies.

We came here as a large group for restaurant week and got to feast on many items from the menu. Highlights were the crispy rock shrimp, the salt & pepper seafood, and the cheesesteak bao - all very delicious. Decent items were the edamame dumplings and the Korean bbq beef satay. Disappointments were the Peking duck (not authentic at all) and the shrimp pad thai (just not very good). Overall a high variance on quality from one dish to the next, so be very cautious with what you order.

Unfortunately, our experience with service was not positive. They absolutely refuse to sit a group without everyone there, so even though we knew one of our members would be coming later, we needed to wait for her. The staff were not very polite or helpful about it.

Secondly, the ordering process was unnecessarily complicated. Maybe this is a restaurant-week-specific practice, but we were told we needed to order a seven-course meal as an entire table, and that we would all need to eat the same dishes. This was a bit frustrating, since many of us had different preferences and wanted to try competing items on the menu.

Lastly, the restaurant ambiance wasn't quite my jam. It's very dark with weird purple lighting, which makes it feel like you're eating dinner in a club. For a relatively expensive meal, I would've appreciated a nicer environment.

Overall a so-so experience. Given the high price, I don't think I need to return.

text:
This was my first time here based on my friends' recommendation that this is the best dim sum place in Philly. It doesn't disappoint. It is a large, clean restuarant. The prices are reasonable and can be cheap when you split the check with your friends. 

They have traditional dim sum dishes like shrimp shaumai and chicken feet. But it was interesting that their turnip cake had taro in the middle...I wasn't too fond of the taro because it made the turnip cake too dry...

I took a star off because the service was lacking. I don't know if it were because it was a busy Saturday afternoon but still...They never offered us water when we were seated. We actually got water when we finished our meal. Since we sat by the window in a corner, I felt like the servers neglected to come to our table so we literally had to stand up and walk to the carts to pick out our food.

text:
Let me say that this is a very westernized Asian fusion restaurant. If you want really authentic Asian food, there is plenty of other places but Buddakan definitely caters to Americans. 

I went for restaurant week. Honestly the food was pretty good, even if not "traditional" so I don't have any complaints about that. The bbq pork was delicious, maybe one of my favorite pork dishes I've had in a while. My main complaint is the portion sizes- for the price, you really do not get a ton of food. I went for restaurant week lunch and got 4 courses but my party went out to get second lunch after. 

The pork belly bao was alright at best- nothing special but it wasn't bad either. The Kobe beef slider was also pretty good, but again, not incredible anyway and the portion is tiny- I've had real Kobe steak in japan and it was ok a completely different level, the "Kobe beef slider" is basically slightly nicer ground beef. The dip sum donuts are basically fried dough covered in sugar- while the sauces are interesting, it's nothing mind blowing. As I said earlier, the bbq pork is the only thing that stood out. 

Service was okay until we got to dessert- for some reason it took 30 minutes just to make the dessert. We were basically ignored for half an hour while everyone else got their entire meals. 

Overall, food was pretty good but service and portions were not. It was worth going once for the restaurant week deal, but would not return.

text:
I took my wife for the 1st time 9/28/19. I haven't been in years. Nothing has changed: amazing food & reasonable prices. We went on a Saturday eve & showed up at the perfect time, around 7 pm, & sat immediately. By the time we ordered, the line was out the door & remained there. 
Pancakes with the curry dipping sauce is legit addictive. You see trays of it being carried about constantly, it's a MUST order. It's Best of Philly & $4.50. Score!! The beef chow fun...yesssss. Seafood fried rice with scallop, squid &...ack?? I forget! Was it shrimp? Anyway, delicious!!

text: I can't stand behind the price per item of this establishment. It's Italian themed with small plates, at family style prices. Alas the hype makes their business model work. Pizza is good, albeit small pies. The steak is well executed with delicious accoutrements. The pasta offerings were ordered were all mostly disappointing and under seasoned. Finally the drinks. They also need to rework the cocktail portfolio. Martinis should have some garnish and not served in diminutive French champagne glasses to start. Beer selection worked with meal options. I will likely not go back, but they do have a good foundation to work from.

text: Reading Terminal is such a staple place to visit while in the city of Philadelphia.  They have tons of shops inside, mostly food.  Some of the shops inside are great!!!!  It is slightly pricey.   Parking is a nightmare if your driving. I wish they had discount parking or something.   Not enough seating to eat your food. But I know it's a lot of people who visit so I understand. It's definitely worth visiting and trying out some food.  I recommend catching a uber there!

text:
I have eaten at many places in Chinatown since I was young and this restaurant has become one of my go-to restaurants. I went back again a few days ago and ordered the hot pot, soup and dry. The soup is the best thing on their menu, I can't get enough of it! 

There are a lot of options to choose from so everyone can enjoy. The portions are also big but you can share one dish with people, unlike other places that have hot pot. This restaurant has a different hot pot concept than other restaurants, you choose what you want from a piece of paper and then the dish that comes out is all you have, you can't order more items to add to your soup from there. But the price is reasonable! 

The service is not the best but I mostly care for the food.

text:
When they say "small corner hole in the wall" the description is perfectly accurate. You may have to wait for a table but it's worth it. We were the only Europeans in a full house on a Saturday afternoon: a very good sign. A quick survey of tables tells that the soups are the thing to order. We were three. The service was most affable. When an older woman did not understand our English she turned us over to a most helpful young woman who guided us through the very compact menu. We ordered: Rice Noodle Seafood : Excellent, Beef Rice and Egg Noodle, and one non-soup, Seafood Noodle very good but needed a little Sriracha and Hoisin. The prices are incomparable. $8 to $10. 
Excellent choice.

text:
I've never eaten bad Chinese food in Philly, unlike in other major cities with high concentrations of Chinese people. This city is the only one to have a 100% score with me. And Lee How Fook (easy to mess up those words, watch out!) has some goodies available. On my visit, I had to get some roasted duck, and I got a side of vegetable fried rice. As you can see, they gave me some hot sauce, OK, that is legit Chinese food. No complains, better get it while is hot!

Service is friendly, people are friendly, prices are good, parking is a few blocks away, it's all good.

text:
This is one of my favorite dim sum restaurants in Philly.

The place is large and spacious, with tons of room for groups big or small. The servers come around with carts in the traditional dim sum style, so you can pick whatever you want from the selection.

Food quality was all great. The shrimp har gow and the pork shumai were fantastic, as were the bao, the ribs, the meatballs, and the shrimp rice noodles. Nothing disappointed. We all left happy and satisfied.

Lastly, the price was very fair. For a big group of around 10 of us, it was only $10 per person. Obviously, your price may vary if you're all hungry and big eaters. But overall a good value.

Definitely a top notch dim sum eatery in Philly. I'll be back!

text:
i guess this place was okay. we have one in texas and i don't understand the hype. over priced conveyer belt items with even more expensive items on the menu. at the price that we dined at i'd rather go to little sheep for the AYCE menu with a much yummier broth.
i however did like that they brought out a little 'create your own' sauce selection so you can make your own dipping sauce. i'm personally one of those people who prefers to just let the broth season the ingredients themselves, so this wasn't a huge deal for me, but it was still cool.
service was great and we were checked up on often. if you check in on yelp you get a free conveyer belt item. 
definitely go when its busy so you can get fresher items off the conveyer belt; during the time we were sitting there we def saw the same 'sushi' hovering around us for the entire hour.

text:
I was very skeptical of this place after reading the reviews and seeing the overall Yelp rating. Let me tell you, I would give this place a 4.5 if I could. The only reason it's rounded down is bc the ambiance leaves something to be desired, they screwed up once on making our dine-in meal takeaway which led to a looooong wait for our food, and the once or twice where a dish may not have been 100% straight from the wok. Haven't had a terrible experience yet, and we've been here probably a dozen times by now, both for their dim sum and to take advantage of their bogo(!!!) lobster deal (available for dine-in after 6pm, FYI). The staff is starting to recognize us when we arrive!

For the price, this place is aMAZing! I recommend the dim sum and ginger-scallion lobster and their beef chow-fen. As with any authentic Chinese establishments with staff from China, don't expect Michelin-star service (but also, if you know someplace in Philly that provides that kind of service, please let me know so I can plan anniversaries and birthdays). However, they're attentive enough that I've only had to flag someone down once or twice for the bill. 

There's a reason that there's usually a line on the weekends for dim sum, and you'll find people of all ethnicities treated the same here. They try their best with everyone, and the only time I've seen people treated differently is when they've antagonized the staff first. I've come straight out of bed, and also when I've been gussied up for a big-date-type of Saturday. No one has treated me differently for looking like I might smell if you get too close. Maybe you're different, but I love that kind of indiscriminate treatment. 

Big thumbs up, would totally recommend

text:
This is admittedly based on only one experience with E Mei, but I did find aspects of that experience telling, both for good and bad. 

The bad: Mostly I just felt they were a bit pricier than a lot of their local rivals. This came through in the price of my Kung Pao Chicken order to begin with, but then I had to pay for an order of rice to accompany it separately. Considering more often than not places in Chinatown default their platters to come with rice, that felt like a bit of a slap in the face. I wouldn't have minded the slightly higher dish price much on its own, but having to order the rice separately drove it home a bit.

The good: The food was enjoyable. Their kung pao/gong bao came with a healthy amount of chicken, peanuts, and green peppers, as well as dried red chilis and pieces of spring onion for flavoring. I thought it could have been maybe a tad spicier, but it wasn't hurting for flavor. It wasn't so good that I'd say it's definitely my favorite in Chinatown/the city, but it's up there. 

I'd like to give the place another try and sample a larger number of menu items...when I do, you'll know it.

text:
It was a small friendly place. Very convenient to the Franklin institute, free library and Barnes foundation. Prices were slightly higher than Chinatown, BUT, the Dimsum fillings were full of meat and they did not skimp on ingredients. This means we were able to order less but leave just as full. 

I would recommend a trip here.

Notes: 
- Dimsum is made to order
- Soup buns (xiao long bao) could use more soup, but were not bad
- They give a fried pancake/dumpling/something complementary with a $25 or more purchase
- Only one bathroom
- The braised pork flavor was very good, but the noodles used for the ramen are NOT ramen noodles (I would recommend skipping the noodles and just ordering the pork).

text:
You seldom come across a Chinese restaurant which could be as close as it could be in US to its roots, introducing Chengdu! I know it already has 5 star rating overall, but i would like to tell you that each morsel of the respective dish you order is going to be worth it. It is again a self order but served by servers type of restaurant. We wanted to order wontons and dumplings as our starters and they only had that in either veg or pork. Maybe some day they listen to chicken/beef eaters who refrain from pork like me. But that's a different conversation altogether. Anyhow the service was wxcellent in terms of suggestions, serving and overall etiquettes a restaurant should have! Food wise highly highly recommended their hot sauce style dishes with the variety of fish, chicken and beef. This comes along with a bowl of rice, so if you plan to share wirh someone order another bowl orlf rice. We also ordered chicken fried rice, which was yummy and tasted different than any other i have tried; maybe because they use sticky rice overall. Lastly their chengdu burgers are descent appetizers for the prices and i loved shredded beef burger at this place, so you could try it if for the first time. So below are my ratings

Chicken Fried Rice - 4/5
Hot Sauce Style Fish - 5/5
Shredded Beef burger -5/5

text:
i love Han Dynasty! It's really great for large groups because you can order many dishes family size and all the dishes are delicious!!! 
pros: 
-i love the dry pepper style fish. It is so crispy and crunchy, but the fish inside is so soft and tender. it's not too overpowering but the chilis add a nice kick. make sure not to eat the chili peppers though, v spicy LOL 
-the green beans are so good!!! theyre not soggy or not too crunchy. 

Cons: 
-the honey walnut shrimp was pretty expensive with not too many pieces , and a bit too creamy for me. I think some of the dishes are pretty expensive but the portions are very small compared to the price 
-service was a bit slow. It makes sense because there are a lot of people at the restaurant, but we would ask for more water or rice and it would take some time

text: Wow.  This hot pot thing is definitely something.  My first time.  It is very similar in concept to meat fondue which I had as a kid.  Cook delicious things in a pot of boiling soup.  Let cool down.  Dip in great sauce.  Eat.  I really liked the food itself - high quality wagyu beef (cooks in seconds!!), lots of veggies, mushrooms, noodles.  And my level 2 hot soup was indeed loaded with chilis and gave me some great tingles!  Service was very attentive!  My company was also stellar!  But here's the thing:  it was all so chaotic!  And dare I say, almost stressful!  Sure, a lot of it was because it was my first time.  But other stuff could have been made clearer.  What's with the conveyor belt?  It was hard to figure out what's what, how much it costs, etc.  Then there are the cooking times.  Meat was cooked in seconds, noodles took about 5-7 minutes, veggies?, mushrooms?  Then the utensils- do i put the chopsticks in the pot?  Do I ladel?  Why does my brother have a solid ladel and mine is more like a strainer?  Then there is no space for this stuff on the table.  Four hot pots, huge baskets with veggies and massive meat displays...I literally couldn't get to my food at times.  This is not to mention that that pot is boiling, and you get boiling spice level 2 in your lap and your hands and your mouth.  Oh, and the choices of meats (several different cuts of beef, pork lamb etc., and seafood) 10 different mushrooms! Etc etc, also, it's very unclear how much food is in one of the many "combos" (is it enough for the group?).  Oh it's ok,  you can always order more of whatever (just flag someone down,  and then wait for an unknown time). oh and don't forget there are 20 different things on the conveyor belt coming at you!!  Better think fast!!!  Oh, don't overcook that meat!!  Oh god!  I lost the scallop!!  What is that big black thing I just fished out of my pot??  Can I eat it??

text: They have raised all their prices so much that you can't make this your regular hang out. It was very telling went on a Friday at 7 PM there were five open barstools. Every year they have raised their prices so much...not to mention they have extremely pompous attitudes that make the whole experience off putting. I can't tell you how many times I've wanted to go here but in my mind I'm thinking, I don't want to deal with the Pompous attitude's and the increase in pricing. The economy is good and there's many options, this isn't the greatest anymore. Pro tip, make your pricing more competitive and your staff more relatable... or instead do what I know you're going to do... Think you're the greatest, untouchable, and then slowly die on the vine out of existence. That there is the lifespan of the restaurant business... for the unsuccessful anyways.

text:
Manayunk is an interesting place. Half small town, half big city. CoWorking spaces, dog parks, "high-end" thrift stores, plenty of coffee shops and the word "fusion" used more than I am comfortable.  In my experience this correlates to bad parking and high prices.  China Wok though, reminds me of simpler times.  Their decor including the faded, almost blurry posted picture menu, the red and green try-fold paper menus, and boy oh boy, daily Lunch Special pricing. I found this while driving back downtown from Ridge Avenue which has its own plethora of asian food spots - more Thai oriented than Chinese in my estimation. I noticed the yellowed sign and could see the plexiglass "talking booth" from outside. I knew I had to try it. 

Here is the order I placed on 10/11/19:

Lunch Special: 
(Comes with Roast Pork Fried Rice, Can Soda or Wonton Soup)
 
Shrimp Lo Mein
*Alt/Special request: Vegetable Fred rice

Sesame Chicken
*Alt/Special request: Fried hard, extra spicy, extra sesame; Vegetable Fred rice


Quoted Total: $13.50 
**Restaurant only accepts cash. 

I called it at 11:01 am. I remember hearing the chimes from a nearby Cathedral bell. The woman that answered was polite and not at all curt as sometimes is the case when you call during the lunch rush at some places. I asked for delivery (embarrassingly since this place is a ~10 minute walk from my house), gave my addy and ran down my special requests. She didn't immediately rush me off the phone and when I asked for the price she offered confidently.  Great! So far so good!

At 11:37 there was a knock on the door. Note: There was no preceding phone call. This is fine for me but those of you that can't hear the door from elsewhere in the house may want to consider this. I came to the door, pushed forth a $20, offered the tip and received my change. 

::I want to inject here that on a PREVIOUS ENCOUNTER with this driver there had been notable awkwardness when he didn't get a tip. I certainly appreciate tipping but it was definitely not fun being questioned about not offering one.::

I took my food into my office (see pics) and everything was made as I requested. In the bag, soy sauce, napkins, plastic forks. I didn't request any duck sauce, hot sauce or spicy mustard. I did not request chopsticks. The customary "cookies not non-psychics." No extra menus. I prefer reusable everything but this isn't the soapbox for my 60 second elevator pitch on climate change. I received crispy, not crunchy, Sesame Chicken with a dollop of sesame seeds. The chicken itself looked like chicken (heart-eyes). A diverse amount of vegetables were added to the usual humdrum broccoli bouquet. A thoughtful amount of shrimp was added to the Lo Mein. Nothing soggy or swimming in sauce/oil. Good portion size. I enjoy my lo mein cold so after taking a few bites I let it cool and then refrigerated it. 

Everything tasted fresh and was hot; steam rose from the lo mein when I removed the lid. The food wasn't heavy, or salty, or oily. The other reviews of this place are accurate. Getting the cash to patronize this place is far less annoying than receiving bad customer service and waiting two hours for inferior chinese food from other local establishments or the outrageous price of Ubereats and Postmates. 

That's it. No fireworks, no pitchforks.. Just expectations met, which in the days of Yelp and overpriced failed deliveries requiring heated exchanges with chatbots, "expectations met" is a revolutionary act - well worth a reading of the St. Crispins Day speech.

Cuisine: 9/10 
Service: 9/10
Decor: 9/10
Value: 9/10
Overall: 9 out of 10

text: Ninja Bao is a most welcome addition to Suburban Station's concourse.  I love the concept of a ramen, bao, gyoza shop in a busy lunch corridor.  I have been here three times and enjoyed everything I ordered and was offered as a sample.  My favorite so far is the spicy miso ramen (that I just finished and inspired me to write this).  But I plan to eat my way through their menu over the next few weeks!  The service is cordial and fast, both of which I appreciate.  The Chashu pork is delicious but there are other options for the Ramen.  Prices are quite reasonable considering the location and the quantity and quality of the food.  I wish Ninja Bao much success!

text:
Overall, my experience at Dim Sum Garden was great. Dim Sum Garden has always been my favorite soup dumpling place especially because there aren't any good dumplings places where I live. 

Food: The dumplings are filled with a good amount of soup and pairs perfectly with the sauces at the tables. Their prices are quite affordable and good for its portion/quality. I recommend the pork soup dumplings as well as the beef Ho Fun noodles. 

Service: The service was mediocre. We ordered spicy pork soup dumplings, but it never came so we asked the server to remove the dish from our check. Although the servers weren't the friendliest, they worked quickly and efficiently. 

If you're looking for a good Dim Sum place, then I recommend eating here, but don't expect a luxurious experience with the best service. Also, they're cash only!

text: I was so looking forward to try this Plc for this first time, we even waited more than 45minutes on a Monday.  All the meat quality is not bad for the price, shrimp paste is also very good.  Other dishes were average but very disappointed at the quality on a few dishes we ordered.  We got the stir-fried bean curd roll(very oily,not good quality oil used to fry it), watercress(very old and skinny=chewy veggies), fish ball stuffing w/roe(have a very fishy taste), 5 pcs of mid size rock shrimps(I do see some yelpers posted 7 and 8pcs, so quantity is not consistent?).  Also feels weir to share the sauce tray with the other tables but what stands out most for me is the chilly sauce with sunflower seeds in it, it really enhances the flavor of those mediocre dishes.  For the beef I would give it a 4 but for hot pot a 3.

text: OMG! OMG! I like this place! Food is amazing here, and service is perfect! There are two reasons that I like to eat here. First of all, waiters always give us suggestions when we order. Once I remember I ordered too much, then they told us that would be too much for two persons. They are really helping us to save money and preventing wasting of food. Secondly, the price here is very reasonable, you will get a giant crispy chicken with only $8! Furthermore, ma la soup is delicious here and price is very cheap. I ordered a $10 soup, then I got a very giant bowl and good amount of items. There is definitely no reason that I refuse to suggest you guys go to this restaurant. I love it!

text: Good place to get fresh food at a fairly reasonable price. The "Salmon Spot" as us locals affectionately call it is very popular and usually identified by the lines wrapped around the corner. It goes fast though because everyone typically orders the same thing so they make them really fast. They also have produce stores there (Iovine) that sell fruits and veg for good prices, plenty of specialty stores and culture specific boutiques and markets to keep you busy. Great place to walk around too.

text:
This is one of the diamond in the rough finds in Philly. The food can't get anymore authentic than this.

I was browsing on Yelp for restaurants close by and found this gem and made a reservation using the Yelp app. Upon entering, we were promptly seated on the 2nd floor. The ambience is really modern and sleek with their wooden decor and furniture, along with a slight oriental feeling as they had lanterns hanging from the ceiling. Makes for a great place for a dinner date.

My gf and I split two things on the menu: an appetizer and an entree. Beef and Tripe in Chili Oil is served cold and contains peanuts. It is a great way to prepare your taste buds for the spicy food you're about to conquer, hopefully. For the entree, we got the Spicy Aromatic Pot w Fish. This contained bunapi and wood ear mushrooms, onion, bamboo shoots, dry pepper, cauliflower, bell peppers, sesame, potato, and five spices all stir fried with your choice of protein. We were able to get these dishes less spicy, although it was still pretty spicy to make you sweat.

The only down side is that the service is a little on the slow side. It took us a while for us to place our order in with them and have our drinks served to us upon ordering. The items can be on the pricey side, but for what they serve, I think it's worth it.

text:
I had lunch here yesterday and I'm taking coworkers back with me today. The food was so good! The service was incredible too. 

The food: the lunch specials are great prices especially for the quality. The lunch special was around $7. The food is very fresh and also delicious (I highly recommend the bao and chicken gyoza). I wish the portion was a little bigger honestly but it still wasn't bad for center city and the price!

The service: everyone working is very respectful and courteous which is sometimes hard to find in philly during a lunch rush. My wait wasn't even that long (about 10 mins around 12:30pm) but 3 different people thanked me for waiting. The actual space is very small and cozy with just a few tables for seating but it's a great place for to-go orders. The inside is clean and you can tell the family working here cares about their customer service!

text:
I ordered the Pad Thai and a large Tai Chi drink. By far the worst meal I ever had. The Pad Thai did not have any bean sprouts and the sauce does not taste right at all. It was covered in this sweet chili sauce, which is better fitted for spring rolls. On top of that, it was not cooked correctly because there was puddle of sauce at the bottom of the plate making it very soupy. 

The Tai Chi drink is a mix of coffee and black tea, which I did not have a problem with. But, the bubbles were extremely overcooked and tasted mushy. The tea itself was very good, not too sweet and very well balanced. 

My friends ordered the fish ball noodle soup and beef noodle soup. The soups had no flavor and they had to put hot sauce in it to give it some kick.this is definitely a very affordable meal if you are in a pinch. I would not get it if you can make a quick trip to Chinatown, which is only 10 minutes away.

text:
I just met with the owner and had a personal walk-through he spared no expense and if you're familiar with an authentic Chinese karaoke bar with VIP bottle service this is it! Classy appointments throughout the entire space, the biggest VIP rooms hold anywhere from 45 to 50 people (and the average room holds comfortably 12 to 20 people), everything is brand new and was shipped in from China so this place is five stars all the way! 

I will be definitely holding a special birthday, or, holiday party here in near future, even better --- if you want to have an intimate place with friends --- this is the NEWEST classiest spot to do it in Chinatown (@$15-$50pp depending on what you order/size of group it's not that crazy when you cost it out for what you get)...WINNING

text:
Just arrived from Chicago and wanted to grab  a bite before turning in. I generally enjoy Korean-fusion  cuisine and found Sampan to be a decent option. The one thing that stood out for me though was the number of service staff there. The place seem to be teaming with various service personnel, which normally would be okay if there was good service. I sat for a half an hour before someone had the wherewithal to pour me some water and that was not even my waiter, she came 15 minutes later. 

There was no apologies for her tardiness but just a forced smile asking for my order. Perhaps hiring experience wait staff could be more cost effective?

text:
This place is so much fun!

So many food vendors and markets that you could literally spend all day and not try everything there is to offer! It can definitely get crowded, especially on the weekends so highly recommend going early.

Love Miller's Pretzels, Dinic's Roast Pork, and Beiler's Doughnuts, just to name a few.

Parking is available across the street at the parking garage. Take your ticket - not credit card - to get it validated for a discount parking price when you purchase something within the market. Ask the vendor to validate your ticket.

Enjoy!

text:
Solid choice! 

I was skeptical, as a chinese american I am always skeptical of any asian food establishment with double digit price points. 

This place did not disappoint. Spicy, flavorful and plentiful. 

My husband and I ordered the 
beef and tripe in chili oil, (5/5)
Great flavor and cooked just right not chewy at all. The chili oil was legit top level spice

snow pea leaves, and the (5/5) 
Not too oily, perfectly salted and plentiful!

lamb hand pulled noodles (4/5)
One less star because the noodles seemed to have been sitting for a bit so clumps we're stuck together which funny enough my husband likened to a folded up potato chip which he likes so he ate those. Flavor wise on point and again more than enough for two people. 

PROS:
authentic menu and execution 
Flavorful and plentiful 
Friendly and attentive staff

CONS:
Can't think if any other than it gets pretty packed once the clock strikes noon- but obviously a sign of a good place!

text:
GREAT dim sum spot! I've already been there twice in the past week. While I've seen menus with a lot bigger variety of food, this one is the perfect balance between scarce and overwhelming hahaha. There's a little something for everyone.

Next plus -- my favorite part -- the price. It's definitely on the cheaper side of things. Whether you're in a big group or just with a friend or two, you can effectively stuff yourself without really breaking the bank.

For food, I'd recommend the soup dumplings -- I thought they were some of the best I'd ever had. But honestly the food is pretty good in general.

And then finally, the service -- there are a bunch of waiters walking around, and the food comes out very quickly. Not to mention they are super nice and even came to our rescue when we forgot our corkscrew at home (see: wine pictured).

They are stars!

text:
My fiancé and I have frequented almost every dim sum spot in the city and surrounding areas. Unfortunately we weren't super impressed with Nom Wah. We were one of only 3 or so tables when coming in and the service all around was pretty slow. Slow to get drinks, slow to get food, slow to get check, etc. 

The food was overall ok. Nothing terrible, but we've definitely had better. The stand out dish was the vegetarian rice roll which was pretty great. The soup dumplings were pretty dry and the dumpling itself got hard after cooling down a bit. 

Lastly, the price here is definitely higher than other dim sum spots. If the quality matched the price, I'd be ok with a higher bill but it really didn't and you can definitely get better dim sum else where for cheaper.

text:
This review is a couple weeks old so the specials are probably different now, FYI.

OH MAN. This was the most expensive meal I have ever had. Granted, we ate 3.5 courses and each one was delicious. But that bill was a whammy.

We actually planned to go somewhere else for dinner because on this particular Saturday night, Saloon was all booked up at the time we wanted to eat and we couldn't make a reservation. Long story short, we ended up here anyway and it was only 15 minute wait for 2 people. We waited at the downstairs bar and got a round of drinks (wine for me, beer for boo). Lots of nostalgia in that area! It reminded me of my grandmoms house in the 80s with the knick knacks and such - and I mean that as a compliment!!

Our wait was truly about 15 minutes as promised, and then we went on a long walk up the stairs and around the corner to our table. I didn't realize how huge this place was inside so I guess that's why, even with no reservations, they could still seat us around 8pm on a Saturday within 15 minutes? There was going to be live music in the upstairs bar later so that might be worth checking out another time.

Our waitress came over to walk us through the menu and tell us about the specials. Pro tip: bring a notebook and pen because the specials menu is about the same length as the regular menu. She rattled off at least another 10-12 dishes ranging from salads to appetizers to entrees. She really knew her stuff because she did not fumble over a single ingredient. We thought we knew what we wanted from the regular menu by the time we sat down (clams casino, two entrees) but upon hearing the specials we completely changed course (punny!) and ordered almost our entire meal from specials.

We started with (special) salads, which we never do, because the ingredients sounded lovely. My partner had something like an apricot and pecan salad and I ordered a spinach salad wrapped in prosciutto with feta or something. I actually wanted the beet salad but she told us about that one by accident or they were out by the time I ordered. My salad was truly a wrap and in my opinion it could have used half the amount of spinach, but both were overall delicious and full of flavors and textures despite being rabbit food.

I lied, we actually started with the complimentary bread and what appeared to be a pesto dip. Nice way to cleanse the palate for sure!

Then we ordered the (special) appetizer that consisted of two clams casino, two clams some-other-way, two giant prawn boys, and two stuffed poblano peppers. We figured why settle for just the clams casino when we could try a sampler? It was yummy but I wish we had just gone for the casino because the entire appetizer ended up being something like $40-50 by itself and we mostly enjoyed the clams anyway. We were both a little creeped out by the prawns haha.

For our meals! I ordered scallops (another special) because I will never turn down scallops, and my partner ordered the only thing from our meal that was off the main menu - the veal parmigiana. When he ordered, the waitress asked what kind of pasta he would like on the side as if it was included but as it turns out the side of pasta was another $12. I could make an entire pound of pasta and sauce from scratch to feed a family of 4 for $12! *Shock* My scallops were delicious. I didn't like his veal but he enjoyed it. The pasta sauce was flavorful and yummy, always a good indicator for a solid Italian restaurant that doesn't skimp on the staples.

By this time I had seen a neighbor table order dessert and there was a huge tray of desserts brought to them and I heard "cheesecake" so I decided to get wild and top off my meal with some dessert. I ordered the pumpkin cheesecake. It was a perfectly textured/baked slice, but I didn't get a lot of pumpkin flavoring, and I am all about that basic b* fall PSL life so I was, admittedly, a little disappointed. Did it stop me from eating the entire thing? No. 

Then our bill came. We had tried estimating it along the way and knew it would be over $100 but we didn't expect it to be $195 (over $100 per person with tip)!

I left feeling quite satisfied, check shock aside. Everything we ate was delicious, albeit a little pricier than we anticipated. If we come back here I think we will limit ourselves to our normal 2 courses each and we will at least be aware that the specials are also especially priced and not always commiserate with similar-sounding standard-menu counterparts. It would be swell if the restaurant could print the specials so we know the prices and so the servers don't have to rattle them off for 20 minutes at the start of the meal. But, I had a similar experience at another Italian place (Giorgio on Pine) so I guess it's just an ambience thing to shout an entire new menu to me as a patron when I sit down. I can get with it.

But seriously, #noregrets. Definitely try this place!!

text: Emei has the best spicy cuisine in Chinatown (or I can say in Philly). I only buy the sliced beef and stripes from them, because they have the best spicy flavor I love and they gave a full bowl all the time. They rennovated their place but the flavors got better, prices I noticed some raised one dollar more but totally fine and understandable. The spicy chicken now has a better spicy flavor than before, the chilli on the bottom tastes so good that you can save and actually mix with rice or other things to eat! Everything else is still good, or better. I really love spicy and I can eat super hot stuff, so Emei really satisfies my stomach :) There is a good dessert they have after you want to cool down from the spicyness, it is the herbal jelly in brown sugar sauce. They are cold and sweet! (Ps: I really love one little thing: so much scallions and peanuts:)amazing)

text: Looking at the reviews of the past year for this restaurant makes me suspicious that they have been written by competitors vs. ordinary folks!  The food has always, always been decent.  It's a buffet so you cannot expect a plate cooked JUST for you!  The options are amazing with enough choices to feed a "picky" family.  It is true they  have had to cut back on some of the selections - that's to keep the cost in check.  Prices for everything, everywhere have risen [markets, gas, appliances, doctors, etc., etc.] so of course they have had to make difficult choices to keep their prices reasonable.  Sushi selections are more than plentiful at dinner as is the overall choices of food from fish to meat to vegetarian.  Having written this, I plan to go there again tonight - yum yum!

text:
Little Sheep is officially now an AYCE! They revamped the front to a buffet bar where you can pick from small appetizers, rice, noodles, vegetables, seafood, and dipping sauces. It was clean when we went. We did notice that a lot of the originally choices (esp meat and seafood selection) have been erased off the menu but I guess this is the downside of being an AYCE now. 

I really love how they have service cards now (green/red sides) in case you need something or you are good! The price is cheap around $25/person. The broths still taste the same. The free ice cream at the end hit the spot. Taro or black sesame were the choices.

Only cons were that the vegetables weren't washed. I attached a photo of our dirty bok choy!!! Our hotpot stove wasn't turned on and the server never noticed and tried to add our food in for us. We turned the burner on ourselves. Also, it took ages for them to refill our broth at one point even though we flipped the sign to red (need help), we could almost see the 2/3 of our ladle!

text:
Delicious food but poor customer service. 

We got 3 Dan Dan noodles and one was gluten-free (more on that), and a Sichuan beef noodle soup. One of my friends has celiacs disease (can't have any wheat products) and we finally found a place in Philadelphia as new comers that is gluten-free and more affordable. We were SO excited to come here! However, we were honestly disappointed by the customer service. We asked if the dan dan noodles could be made gluten free and the waitress said yes (substitute with rice noodles) but there would be no pork in it. We were a bit confused later on so we asked someone else who seemed like the manager. We asked if there were any side proteins that could be made because we were so hungry!! He could make ZERO accommodations for us. There weren't even any sides that could be made. Cold noodles were the only other options so we stuck with the dan dan noodles. We weren't disappointed in the limited options, but by the delivery of the service. He wasn't really friendly and didn't make us feel helped.

 ***Just because this place is popular for the delicious food does not mean you can make your customers feel disrespected. 

The place is small and there was a bit of a wait. You should make reservations.

text:
This place is always a last resort when I'm craving something soupy and my favorite ramen has too long of a wait. Nan Zhou is pretty quick about getting people seated (if you have a small group). We recently visited this place during prime dinner time on a Friday night and they squeezed us in right away. The restaurant was pretty crowded. We tried the House Special Noodle Soup and the Signature Braised Beef Noodle Soup. You can either choose from hand pulled (thinner) or shaved noodles (thicker). I preferred the hand pulled noodles just because it's less hefty and easier to eat. The portions are huge and the toppings are plentiful. The Signature was very spicy, but satisfying. The House Special had a good variety of meats. The broth is very oily, so I tried to avoid sipping the broth and just ate the contents.

The ambiance is loud and cleanliness could
 use some improvement. Overall, it's a quick, reasonably priced spot when you're craving hand drawn noodle soup. This place is cash only, so plan accordingly.

text:
For a restaurant that has such chic environment, I was not expecting the prices to be so reasonable. It was similar to getting the same items in chinatown! I got the szechuan beef noodle and it was wonderful, I probably wouldve enjoyed it more if it was more spicy but it was still very flavorful. The portion was also just right so I was so satisfied when I finished my food. 

Another thing was great is that the restaurant could actually make gluten free changes to the menu items as I was at the restaurant with a friend who has celiac. So it was nice that she was also able to enjoy that. 

The loss of the star came from the service, while I had such a great time enjoying every bite of my noodles, i wish the man I had spoken to was more polite when we were asking about gluten free options. 

Otherwise, good place for a date, not so much for a group. And definitely make reservations!

text:
If Chick-Fil-A had a fancy, pinky up, step brother this would be it. The customer service at Mulherins is unsettling...they're nice, polite and happy. They smiled, were attentive and constantly checked in with polite words. Like...people shouldn't be this nice. They aren't.. except for here I guess.

Now for the food. They're fancy so they're doing the whole small portions but delicious food thing. AND they're nailing it... ordered the salmon toast and mushroom pizza.

The salmon portions were so small but some of the most flavorful tastes I've had. Very delicious and would recommend. 

The pizzas are normal sized so I'd recommend definitely getting a pizza and then the other things for tasting. 

It tastes so good that the small portions seem insulting with the prices as they are. It's not overly expensive but it ain't cheap. 

I'm going to make this a place I go for special occasions or when the parents visit so they pick up the bill :)

text:
This is a nice cozy place in the heart of Chinatown. You usually see a wide variety of customers and it's always been busy when I went there. The staff are attentive and quick to tend to the tables. The food does take a while to be served so be hungry, but don't be starving.

The food was so delicious I came here twice with two different groups and they each loved it. 

The toothpick lamb was delicious for those that enjoy a slow burn that build up gradually. The lamb doesn't have the typical gamy taste which could also be due to the heavy cumin. So if you like cumin, it is the dish to go with. The cumin was powerful, but balanced with the spices making it flavorful and aromatic. The only thing i personally would change would be the toothpick part. It feels very arbitrary. 

The volcano chicken was good as well. The chicken was stir fried well so it wasn't dry and it had the right combination of flavor. The red onions brought a slight sweetness to the dish. Very well balanced dish, but it wasn't very spicy like the name might indicate.

The soup dumplings here are pretty good. It's not out of this world, but well made and flavorful. I would say these dumplings can easily contend with other very popular places in the city.

All in all, everything is very reasonably priced and the dishes come with rice as well. A great place to just get together and share a couple different dishes. The food is a lot so some people might have to be prepared to go away with a doggy bag, but it's delicious enough to eat those leftovers.

text:
Poor taste and poor service.

My wife and I came here because she has been craving pad Thai. 
After our visit she is still craving pad Thai. 
The portion sizes were huge but the taste was minimal.
The pad Thai was orange, it had no visible vegetables and herbs, and was sweet, not spicy as the menu indicates.
My wife did say the shrimp was cooked perfectly but that was the only positive thing she could say about the dish.

After 2 bites of the pad Thai my wife couldn't stomach anymore so we decided to speak to the waiter. We called for the waiter, literally, we had to call out across the restaurant because every time we needed something he was busy on his phone or watching Avengers on the TV. We expressed the problem to the waiter and asked if we could replace the meal with something different to which he agreed. After looking over the menu again my wife decided she didn't want anything more.

I had the beef with broccoli bento box lunch special. Aside from way too much brown sauce it was ok and a decent price.

We asked for the bill and the waiter brought out a takeaway box and the bill. Before I could say anything more he was gone again. When we finally got the waiter back I asked, "why we were being charged for something we didn't eat?" We were told "because you ordered it. We have to just dump it." To which I replied "yes, but my wife did not eat it. It made her sick to the stomach. We should not have to pay for something we didn't eat." I was then told he could charge half price but not take it off the bill. He said they would replace it with something different but that was all. By this point I was done with giving this place a chance so we ordered something different to takeaway. It wasn't something that I wanted but it was something rather than pay for a dish that made my wife sick.

This place may be called dream house but be assured the dreams here are not very pleasant.
Save your money and your time.

text:
A fun spot for happy hour or modern Asian fusion cuisine. 

Ambiance - 
This place is trendy / upscale - it's a dimly lit, nice restaurant that caters to the after-work and out with friends crowd equally, you will be equally appropriate in a suit and tie or your bar wear. While the restaurant is nice, I will point out that there always seems to be a long line for the bathrooms which I wish they would do something about - while this is par for the course for a bar/night-club it's not really conducive to a restaurant experience. It does get really crowded during Happy Hour. 

Food - 
Much like their sister concept Double Knot, Sampan encourages you to order several tapas-style dishes from their menu which the kitchen brings out to you slowly over the course of your meal. While not every dish was a smash hit, everything we had was pretty good - I highly recommend the Crab Wanton Tacos and the Kung Pao Chicken Wings. This place is better in a group as you'll get to order more dishes and try more of the menu. While we didn't have any dietary restrictions in our group, they made sure to ask at the start of the meal and offer both a gluten free and a vegetarian menu upon request. 

Drink - 
We enjoyed a few cocktails which were good, creative, and reasonably priced for the neighborhood. While I don't know much about Sake, they offer it by the bottle and offer a few different flights which sounds like a fun way to enjoy it. If you're with a group I recommend trying one of the Scorpion Bowls, it's a great deal and is a lot of fun, bringing me back to my fish bowl days. 

Service - 
Getting seated during Happy Hour was a lot less smooth than we would have liked. First of all, the host staff did not explain to us the difference between Dinner and Happy Hour until several prompts from us - the difference being the prices and deals available. Secondly, it took about 5 minutes for us to be seated as the host staff chatted among themselves and disappeared to the back, which would have been fine if we hadn't gotten to the dining room only to discover that it was nearly empty! Table service was good, our waitress was around just enough and was happy to make recommendations - she actually recommended our favorite dish which were the Kung Pao Chicken Wings. 

Value - 
The best value here are the Happy Hour Deals, however the seating for those are limited and they are not offered in the dining room, so it will be a little tough to plan for those. If you're anything like us, you'll go for the happy hour but end up paying full price because the bar area was overflowing with people. Given that it is tapas style, most individual dishes are priced affordably however it does add up. Paying full price, we were 2 people and together spent $100 before tip for 4 drinks and 5 dishes, which honestly isn't bad at all - we walked away stuffed and could have probably gotten by with 4 dishes. I would say go since dinner prices are very reasonable, just don't count on the happy hour deals unless you have time to wait and don't mind being at a crowded bar.

text:
I was very excited to try out this new Chinese hand drawn noodle spot in Mayfair, but it was kind of disappointing. Me and my friend ordered the pork belly noodle soup and there were only 3 pieces of pork belly and the soup was a bit bland. We also tried their chili dumplings for starters and the sauce was very watered down, it literally looked like 4 steamed dumplings sitting in just a muddy red soup. You couldn't even taste the chili/spice. 
The service was ok, they were really nice but it seems like they themselves have trouble working together efficiently. 
But overall, it is a decent place to go to with cheap prices if you are craving some noodles and are in the area.

text: It's no secret that dim sum in University City is few and far between. This was my 2nd or 3rd time at this location for a casual Sunday lunch with my friend. The first time I came here, I remember most of the dishes being spot-on, and I was pleasantly surprised. Price-wise, the dim sum dishes will range from 2-3 times more than what you would pay at a traditional dim sum restaurant in Chinatown or NE Philly. My friend and I ordered their beef scallion pancakes, shrimp cheung fun, shrimp and chive dumplings, and pork and shrimp siu mai. Our server forewarned us that the beef for the beef scallion pancakes would be lukewarm. We didn't quite understand what he meant, so we nodded and agreed to continue the order. Sure enough, it was cold roast beef wrapped in a scallion pancake - we thought this was really odd, because the beef tasted like a cut you would use for pho, along with some pho fixins' and plum sauce in the beef scallion wrap. It was confusing, flavor-wise, and we felt that these tasted better before. The shrimp cheung fun tasted more like a thick rice noodle wrap, so it wasn't authentic. The shrimp and chive dumplings had an abundant filling, fairly crisp exterior, and decent flavor. The pork and shrimp siu mai were also large, in comparison to the typical size you would see at a dim sum restaurant, and my friend liked these the best. Overall, the dim sum is average and the price point is high, so this would not be my go-to for dim sum or Chinese food.

text:
This was my first time doing Hot Pot and it was a nice experience.  We did the waitlist app through yelp so we only had like a 10 minute wait which was good because the place was pretty packed.  You sit down and order your protein.  I do not eat most meat, only seafood, so I did not like that there was not a vegetarian option on the menu.  So I still paid the same price as everyone who got meat but did not receive anything extra.  That was the reason for not giving 5, because I feel there should be an option on the menu that says vegetarian with a slightly lower proce since we are not getting the fresh cut meat the other tables are getting.  

They have a buffet like setup where you can grab your noodles, vegetables, seafood, and other items to add to your hot pot.  I love that they had a great variety of green vegetables and noodles.  I loved the squid ink noodles.

Our waitress was pretty attentive nad very helpful for us being first timers.  I got the vegetable broth which was very good but contained a lot of the inedible peppers.

text:
Dan Dan looks small and unassuming from the outside, but it's larger than it looks and houses a second floor dining area. It is tight quarters, but they can pack it in. As other Yelpers mention, it is overpriced compared to other good Chinese food options. With that said, the food was good and the service satisfactory. 

We were here for lunch and the lunch specials ranged in price from $10.45 - $12.95. Again, a bit higher than you would expect for Chinese lunch options and the portions are adequate, but not very large. 

We ordered the Dan Dan noodles as an appetizer. They were very tasty, but make sure you can bear the heat, because they are spicy. For lunch my table ordered Cumin with Chicken, Dry Pot with Chicken and Garlic Sauce with Pressed Tofu. The Cumin and Garlic sauce were both tasty. The Hot Pot was a bit of a let down, because it was the dish with the highest spiciness level, yet was bland and paled in comparison to the 1-star spice level of the Garlic Sauce dish.

text:
Wow. 

This restaurant is a place everyone should check out. 

The atmosphere: The restaurant is huge. There were two main areas for patrons to eat, a bar, and private rooms along a hallway. The decor was chic and modern with many fantastic pieces of East Asian artwork. 

The food: I mostly had the dim sum and ordered the green beans so I will only comment on those. All I can say is wow. The variety of the dim sum cuisine was great! If you only have been exposed to one kind of dim sum restaurant and dishes, this place has you covered for taking your mouth on a culinary journey! Every morsel of food was hot, fresh and was able to carry its own despite the various dishes on my table. My absolute favorite was the pumpkin tart. You are given 4 adorable coquette style dishes and the red bean inside the soft yet crunchy pumpkin exterior was delicious! I would highly recommend them and the beef scallion pancake! Basically everything. Try the whole menu if you can!

The price: Since this place serves both dim sum dishes and regular dishes, you can cater your food according to how much you are willing to spend. 

Did I say wow yet? Because wow.

text: This is my go-to spot! My family always loved getting their butchered meats, which is always very fresh and tasty. They also have very good meals! Love their rice dishes that come with their butchered meat, as well as their noodles or noodle soup. I'm a fan of their roasted pork (cha siu), roast pig (crispy), and scallion chicken. For my early lunch or breakfast, I like their congee with pork and thousand yr duck egg. Prices here are very much standard and affordable. The amount of food you can get for what you pay is well worth it, sometimes you can split your entrees! It's a small place, but if you decide to eat in, you can definitely get a table if you aren't going on a very, very busy day. This is a place where you can bring family to, it's not super fancy, but great comfort food.

text:
Little Sheep was our go-to place every Friday night for a year, the manager came over every time to greet us, and all of the staff know us well and will come say hi while we're eating. I still crave the broth and kimchi to this moment. Everything was fresh, flavorful and reasonably priced! My boyfriend is the pickiest eater of all time and loved Little Sheep. Unfortunately, they've become an All You Can Eat Buffet and the quality and freshness has dropped drastically. They've eliminated all appetizers from the menu, and cut down on the meats offered. Our half and half broth was brought out with a film of fat on it and tasted awful, it made everything taste like butter was added to the top. The buffet itself was extremely lackluster. Half empty containers down the line, seafood that smelled like it had been sitting - the shrimp tasted funky. The price is not unreasonable if you're content with a standing in line only to reach an empty container or fried rice that's under a heat lamp. 

I thought Little Sheep was a true authentic Hot Pot experience but it seems they've bought into the cheaper market of providing poor ingredients just to save a buck. I will not be going back and am completely dissatisfied with the turn around of this restaurant.  Before, I would have recommended this restaurant to anyone and everyone - pretty sure I actually have- but now? I've told people who talked about going to NOT go. It no longer lives up to the hype of authentic hot pot. A disappointment.

text:
Came here for dinner with a few other friends. The restaurant itself looks very outdated, as many others have expressed. It looks like I walked into a movie scene from a long time ago. It also smells not so great, like what a kitchen with a lot of old oil would smell like. When I walked out, my entire coat smelled like an old Chinese kitchen. Definitely wear something that would not soak up smells when you come here.

The servers first gave us all Chinese menus, even though many people I was with look like they obviously don't understand Chinese. We eventually got some English menus. However, the two menu's contents differ, and even the price differs. The English for some reason has a lot more dishes than the Chinese menu. Moreover, for the items that exist on both the English and Chinese menu, a lot of them have different prices. We found a few dishes that were cheaper in the Chinese menu than when compared to the English menu.

The food itself was just mediocre at best. A lot of the food were extremely salty or just doesn't taste good. Personally not a big fan of this place. You can get a lot better stuff in Chinatown...

text: Quite a nice experience, I was in town for a biomedical conference and we decided to eat here the last night of the conference. The owners were so incredibly friendly and was great to interact with as part of our group is fluent in Cantonese and the other half was not but both were easily communicated. The tea was great and the service was so quick. The quality did not lack however which was impressive to have fresh well cooked food in a short period, IME the quicker the more likely to be dripping with oil or overcooked due to excessive heat but that was not the case so kudos to Ho Sai Gai. I ordered a grilled chicken dish with egg roll and I was most pleased and very affordable. I will order the beef with noodle next time which my colleague from Beijing, China got and it was huge and looked very good. Overall, definitely worth it. Has a nice atmosphere too and again very friendly operators.

text:
My overall experience was okay and the only reason why I'm rating this place a 3 out of 5 is because of the taste of the food.

Atmosphere was good. Very cozy. Dim lit and chill. Servers were quick and easy to communicate with. Prices were reasonable. Crowd was nice. 

Food size: portion was bigger than I expected. Lots of meat (at least for my dish...I ordered the Magic Beef noodles no fungus or mushrooms). The amount of noodles I got was great, it was really a lot, I couldn't even finish it.
We also ordered the crabmeat soup dumplings and it was okay, you get 6 dumplings for like $7-8 but I think Chinatown's dimsum garden might have that beat with the 8-9 juicy and very soupy dumplings they provide. 

Food taste: The noodles were soft and good. The bok choy was fresh and crunchy and tasted good. The meat was tender and had a good amount of fat and muscles that made it good. The only problem was the soup/broth, I think it was very bland. I tried to livin' the taste with the soy sauce and sriracha provided but I feel like that still wasn't enough do anything. 

My friend ordered the Mount Qi noodles(which is supposed to be spicy). From a glipse it was very colorful with the array of vegetables and tofu and I believe she had some beef in it as well. Although she complained that the broth was too sour, she appreciated that it wasn't too spicy. 

Funny thing was as we dined there, a fellow customer went up to pay for tab and offered his feedback. Yes, I eavesdropped. But anyways, I overheard him say the quality of the food ingredients itself (noodles, meat, and vegetables) were really good but his broth was too salty. 

All in all, I would probably give this place one more chance because I want to try their "Beijing Bang" dish which is black bean flavored. Sadly, if that disappoints then I will not be going back.

text:
This is probably the best hot pot place in Philly. It's conveniently located in Chinatown.

I am a hospitality professional and this is hands down one of the most hospitable places I've dined in. The employees here actually care about their establishment. The wait staff was very attentive to my group. You're in need of another drink and/or spoon? They have you covered with your request and a positive attitude. I was fortunate enough to meet the general manager of the Chubby Cattle while I dined in his restaurant. He was one of the most down to earth individuals I've ever met.

I've been to several hot pot restaurants before and the Chubby Cattle's prices are within the acceptable market range. It's not too expensive and not too cheap. I would suggest getting the Waygu Nigiri as an appetizer if you like raw meat. It melts in your mouth and the presentation is pretty cool.

I highly recommend everyone to try this place. This is also a perfect place to bring a date because the restaurant experience is super interactive. 

PS. Make sure you join Fivestars. It's an app for discounts at the Chubby Cattle.

text:
A solid Chinese food option. I have to admit, walking around Chinatown can be overwhelming with the number of options available. Canto House located on a corner, looked approachable and had an English menu on the window with very reasonable prices.

Upon entering, the staff was friendly and I noticed the other patrons were primarily Chinese, which is a good sign. 

I was immediately given a glass of water and some complimentary tea. I ordered the Chicken with Mixed Vegetables, which was really good. It was served in a brown sauce along with a side of rice. For $6.75, I received a very generous portion. For a light eater such as myself, I had leftovers to take home for another meal. 

All in all, a solid inexpensive option for a quick Chinese bite.

text:
So pretty pricey, but had a really good night here. Food was pretty good, and worth the price along with the nice ambiance. 

Everything we got was around $12-$16 so definitely in the the two to three dollar signs. I made a reservation in advance but we got there early enough to not need it. The bar was already pretty full and by the time we left around 7:30 it was packed. 

We got two small plates, a pasta, and a pizza. The hamachi crudo was amazing. The grapefruitand peppercorn made the dish so bright and the basil and pistachio give it such good texture. The fried octopus was also another good one with the pesto, white bean, and arugula.

The pizza. Was. So good. We got the Leslie chow, which had mushrooms, radicchio, taleggio, and Saba. The crust was so wonderfully bubbly and chewy. If you can't tell I'm a crust person, I am haha. The Saba gave it such a wonderful sweetness and paired wonderfully with the umami of the mushrooms and cheese. The radicchio then added a lovely bitter tone. 

Finally, we got the butternut squash with brown butter and sage. The squash filling had a wonderful sweetness. 

Definitely a special occasion place, but I definitely loved all the dishes I got. Definitely coming back to try more pizzas!
