text:
This place is pretty good! Menu is pretty extensive, prices aren't bad, and service was quick.

My friend and I shared the fish dry pot and beef brisket noodle soup. If you like spicy food, I highly recommend the dry  pot. The fish was also crispy and hot. Beef noodle soup was good too but I always prefer spicy food! Portions are good too; we both eat a lot and were quite full afterward.

FYI there's a credit card minimum (I think it was $15) so if you're ordering just one dish, bring cash!

I'll be back again!

text:
I stopped by today to grab some takeout. It's your average strip mall Chinese take out place.  On the upper end of the genre but still not a Jasmine in Glenside or Sang Kee.  Food is solid without any frills.  Prices are very good especially for the combos.  The prices on their menu are not the same as Door Dash so be sure to double check.  For example the sesame chicken combo on Door Dash is $9 and change and is actually $7 there.  

The woman who took my order was extremely nice.  She knew the regulars who cane in and what they like to order.  The kitchen looked very clean.  I got there 5 minutes after opening in a Sunday and they were already busy.  

For the record, we ordered general tso chicken and boneless bbq pork combos.  We also got some wonton soup.  The pork were much larger pieces than Panda Express just down Bustleton but overall about the same amount.  The general tso chicken was still crispy when we got home which cantor said of most take out shops in the area. The wontons were good.  The broth was very light.  I would not say it tasted like dirty water as another reviewer did but it definitely didn't have the stronger flavor found at some Chinese restaurants.  

Overall a good experience but not something I would necessarily go out of my way for.  Definitely a solid choice but if you're willing to travel a bit, there are alternatives that will make you dream of their meals days after your visit

text:
It was a Saturday and we were a group of three that wanted to find something to eat. So we came along Jade Harbor since that was the closest in our path. The inside feels dated and the seating is very tight. We ordered 3 items and 3 soft drinks. The food was not good for the price.  It was the same taste as a regular Chinese takeout except you pay a lot more at Jade Harbor. The quantity was small as well. We paid around $18 per meal. 

5 minutes after we got our meal, they brought fortune cookies, oranges and the bill to us. All of us weren't even close to finishing our meal. 3 minutes later, the waiter kept giving us a dirty look because we weren't hurrying up. Like I get you have people waiting but that's not our fault. It felt like they were suggesting we get the hell out of there. 

So we ate as quick as  possible. We were there probably a max of 20 min or less from the time we entered the restaurant to the time we walked out. The bill said the total was $71.25 including tax and tip. They decided to add $9.30 tip in the bill. So when I went to pay, I decided to not to pay anything extra for the tip. The guy didn't even say thank you or goodbye because I did that.

Based on my experience, I will not be returning to this place. You don't treat your customers like that no matter how busy you get.

text: My wife and I made a drive to this buffet last night really looking forward to a great dinner with our family. We had just taken these children to the circus and they were terribly hungry and feeling restless, ready to have dinner. Our group consisted of my wife and I, a two year old, a six year old, two eight year olds, and a ten year old. I mentioned their ages because the employee didn't accept or believe that our ten year old was actually ten. For some reason we had to prove that our growing ten year old as indeed ten years old and that we weren't trying to pull anything over this lady. As a quiz, she asked us what year she was born, hoping to catch us in some kind of lie. Upset by the question, we still answered honestly and was still turned down by her disbelief. Not only did we face her attempt to charge us an adult price for a ten year old, but she wanted us to pay for our 2 year old as well as if he was at least five. Fed up with this poor customer service, we chose to leave and not give them our business. Very disappointing when in the past I haven't had any problems referring my family and friends to this business. Ruby Buffet will no longer see my family dine there due to this ridiculous and shameful incident.

text: Bing Bing is DAMN good. I came in yesterday with my boyfriend during happy hour. We had two cocktails (Milk Money and Green Fire) which were both DELICIOUS, but seriously expensive. $14 for a cocktail at a relatively casual place is just too much. We tried several food items, all of which were good. The best: Cheesesteak Bao was UNREAL - seriously we had to order another one because it was too good to stop. The Mongolian Beef Dumplings were delicious as well followed by the Turnip Cake and the Brussel Sprouts with Tofu. We really enjoyed everything from start to finish, but I do think it was a bit pricey for the portion sizes/vibe. I also love their fun signage (spotted at both Cheu locations as well). I recommend!

text:
If it was possible to give 0 stars, I would.
The food her is OK. There are some items that are better than others. I have been to this location several times before and never really had any true issues with the customer service. That is, until the other night. I came for dinner seeking a quick meal to feed some picky eating kids. In total it was 2 adults and 4 children ages 2,5,6, and 10. The signage clearly states the prices. It lists adults $14.99, kids 5-10 $7.99. The cashier rings me up and the charges did not seem correct, I asked for a break down of the charges. She tells me 3 adults and 3 kids. I explained, I have 4 kids and they are all 10 or under. She became frustrated with me and began questioning the birthdate of the 10 year old. I felt it was inappropriate to ask that question. Do you need a birth certificate to dine her?  Needless to say due the disrespect and poor customer service, we decided to dine elsewhere. I will not be dining at this establishment ever again.

text:
The google search for this place says "all you need to know" so here it is: this is the best sushi in the city. Period. And I've eaten a lot of sushi in Philly. 
They have amazing rolls that are incredibly fresh and delicious. Everything we tried (I mean EVERYTHING) was good. The atmosphere inside is calming and beautiful - a stark contrast to the busy world of Broad Street outside. 
My husband and I also loved the owner. We went there when they first opened and he came to talk to us about everything: how he used to run a place in Chinatown with his dad, how he gets fish from Japan sometimes, how he found this amazing partnership with the man who makes the sushi (and hoo BOY does he do a good job). 
I worry that people will get deterred by the neon sign outside, thinking this is some average takeout. It's most certainly not. This is high-quality fish, high-quality rolls, and a variety/uniqueness that you won't find in a lot of places. 
This is a date-night type of place with KILLER prices to boot. I just moved out of Philly and I miss this spot all the time. Go here, bring your friends, dress up and bring a nice bottle of wine.
This hidden gem, and the quality it brings, deserves the best.

text:
Shocked this place only has a three star rating. Before coming I read many reviews that said service was bad and the employees were mean so I came in expecting that but I didn't experience any of that! They weren't exactly welcoming but they weren't rude. 

I ordered the regular hot pot with soup with the spice level at "little spicy." First few sips were fine but then it got super spicy so just watch out if you don't like spicy food. I know next time I'll be getting no spice at all. My boyfriend got the highest spice level of dry hot pot and it was definitely hot! The portions here are HUGE. One order of dry hot pot could feed three people. Though I did notice for more "expensive" toppings like oysters, they only gave 2 tiny pieces. 

For a soup hot pot and dry hot pot the bill turned out to around $42. Price depends on how many toppings you put in but for the portions, it's a great deal.

text:
Pricey, but honestly the food is actually really good. 

Things I liked about this place: 
- They make sure to let you know how long each thing cooks when they serve it.
- They ask you if it's your first time doing hot pot and teach you the entire process. Brandon was our server and he was super helpful the entire time. 
- The coconut water straight from the coconut. So good. Don't forget to eat the coconut insides after drinking the water. 

Things I didn't like about my experience:
- They forgot the drinks we ordered. Once we finally realized the tea and coconut was not coming, we had to remind them that we had more that we ordered.
- There were a couple things we asked for, like a spoon for the coconut, that took us reminding a couple waiters to get. 

Overall, the food did make the entire experience worth 4 stars. If we didn't have to keep reminding them about things we wanted / ordered, I would've given 5 stars.

text:
I've had takeout from this place many times but finally had the chance to eat in, so now I get to review the full experience!

First off, you know the Chinese food here is legit because the owner here used to work in the Chinatown restaurant scene. Japanese food is not as legit in the sense that none of the sushi chefs here are Japanese, but the sushi is still fresh and at a more affordable price than nearby Yanako. 

There is also a full bar inside if you don't feel like eating and just want to hang with a couple drinks. Plus, happy hour food and drink specials don't hurt! 

The con to this place is the service. Our server didn't seem to know the menu too well, or just about Chinese/Japanese food in general. When asked how many pieces the shrimp tempura comes with, the server responded the roll comes with 5. We reiterated that we are not ordering the roll, but just the tempura, but he didn't seem to know there was a difference. We ended up having to ask him to ask another server what we meant. 

Overall, a great addition to Main St., and a nice place for a date, a large dinner, or even just to grab a drink with a friend!

i love their hotpot! portions are a bit small for the price but food is always fresh. when they get busy, it can be a little hard to get the waiters attention, but to be fair i think that's just a staffing issue.

only "bad" experience was the first time i went, the host guy just completely ignored me. like didn't say a word to me until he called my name from the waitlist i put on through yelp.

i like all the food i've gotten for hotpot (mostly meats and veggies), but their raw beef sushi is not so great. i got their wagyu nigiri and the meat was still frozen :/

overall, a great dinner! also, definitely utilize their yelp waitlist. it's so easy and simple, & you don't have to wait super long once you get to the restaurant!

text: Lots of variety & options in one place, but can become extremely crowded which is not really conducive to eating a nice and relaxing meal...often have to wait/hunt for a seat/table. Parking offered at a discount or free at nearby garage...gotta check w them...I forget exact terms. At the end of the day the Dutch merchant puts many if the bakery items for sale. People literally wait in LONG lines for many if the merchants soooo something to be said for the demand...especially for the Amish Dutch food and Bieler's doughnuts.

text:
1. This place is not that cheap given that it's a crowded, cash only place. I could get close to twice as much food for the same price over at Ting Wong, and the places in Chinatown that do cost more than Dim Sum Garden typically have MUCH better atmospheres (yes, I am willing to pay a premium to restaurants that don't stacked me like sardines in an awkwardly long, semi-claustrophobic restaurant layout).

2. But even if I'm not getting a crazy large portion size or a nice dining experience, all that could have been forgiven if the food blew me away, but this certainly did not. Maybe it's due to all the hype screwing up my expectations, but I found the soup dumplings very average. I've had thinner wrappers and more flavorful soup at my favorite places back home in Chicago. They did at least pass the "better than frozen Trader Joe's soup dumplings" test (it's embarrassing how many restaurants can't even manage that). Most everything we ordered was average, from the beef chow fun to the siu mai.

3. Tips: The best thing we got were the beef pot stickers, the filling was very dense and flavorful, not diluted with water or breadcrumbs (although if you're like my parents who prefer fluffy fillings, what I described might not be a good thing.) The worst thing we got were the scallion pancakes. Zero scallion taste, zero layers (yes, a good scallion pancake should have thin layers, it's not supposed to be heavy like a pita), and zero crisp, it might as well have been a steamed lump of dough.

4. Overall, I've gotten cheaper food at some places and better food at others (and a rare few that manage both) while attending school in Philly. If Dim Sum Garden is average all around and ridiculously crowded/overhyped to boot, I don't see any reason to come back

text:
There's like, a 20% surcharge on their grubhub prices which I didn't realize was there until I dined in last week for the first time, so I recommend NOT USING GRUBHUB for Bai Wei. Even for a cash/venmo only restaurant, 20% is a little insane. A dish I paid $18 for on grubhub was only $15 on the menu, and the fish I got on Wednesday that cost me $16 at the restaurant is listed at $20 on grubhub! And that's not counting if you then pay for delivery and tip your delivery driver.

But anyway, on to the food. The first time I got sizzling Japanese tofu and shrimp off grubhub, it looked nothing like another reviewer's picture, the shrimp were tiny "medium" sized shrimp barely the size of a nickel (why grocery stores call those medium shrimp and then have to go up to large, extra large, and then jumbo, I'll never understand, marketing, I guess), there were some diced carrots and onions which were undercooked, and the entire dish was orange and tasted of, what I guess I'd call "shrimp blood". Now, my mom uses fresh head-on shrimp in her pork steamed buns  and it's great, but when she tried to do the same trying out a chiang fun recipe, it was an orange disaster. In a dish that's more mild such as tofu, using head-on shrimp is more disaster territory than a good idea, just stick with headless frozen shrimp please. Japanese tofu is always tasty though, no matter how bad you screw up the rest of the dish, so I still ate the whole thing.

But because TT Skewer and I are forever starcrossed (that's another story), I decided to give Bai Wei another chance, and I'm glad I did (and not just because I caught the grubhub thing). I got fish fillet in spicy sauce (水煮鱼 and the server had to verify I wanted the spicy dish and not literally boiled fish, which was topkek). And now, the only restaurant I've ever had this at served it with tofu and peanuts which is about as far from traditional as you can get, so my perception of this dish is way out of whack. Bai Wei does it more typically with cabbage and bean sprouts and it was equally good and I felt healthy getting some vegetables in.

The server did not stop by at all during my meal because I was all set with a gigantic pot of tea and it's typical in China to flag down waiters rather than wait for them to come to you (my parents HATE it when servers pop by to ask how we're doing), but within a few minutes of finishing eating and pulling out my phone, a server came by to ask if I was finished, so I assume they're relatively attentive and quick to respond, so just don't be shy you'll be fine at Bai Wei. 

The white furniture and elevated dining area is also pretty cute, so I'd dine in again sometime, just not grubhub, never mix grubhub and this place.

text:
Booking experience feels like that it has a artificial demand. Open table had bookings either at 5:30 or 9:15. My wife called and got table for 7:0pm on Friday night. When we reached the entire middle table was empty with at least 25 seats. Never filled during our dinner till 9:00pm

Appetizer's were good and server customized menu by replacing pork with chicken and /or veggie options.

Good drinks options but main course options for veggie and chicken eaters were very limited.

Compare to the food we got and the bill we received, feels like not a great value for the money. It was bit expensive 

Sound level in the restaurant was high, not a quite place 

I would give 5 star for the service, would give 2 star for the food choices and cost.

Overall experience was okay. Can visit one time

Take a train if you are going from suburban of Philly, parking is a nightmare

text:
So first things first, this isn't Mongolian hot pot. The style of hotpot that prevails in Northwestern China and Mongolia is nothing like this. This is basically Sichuan-style hotpot.

Not a problem in my book, both are excellent. I just find this "rebranding" of geographic origin in East Asia annoying. Why is "Mongolian" the hot thing whereas authentic Sichuan, Hubei, or Shandong cuisine are impossible to find?

[/RANT]

Moving on... this is pretty good hot pot. Their soup stock (bone broth) is good enough to push a bit of the flavor through to the final product and the seasonings (the additions that provide the spice) are also custom-blended and quite good.

The meats are excellent, including scratch-made meatballs.

This being hotpot, there's not much more to be said, but this is well worth the price. I have no idea how/if they make money on it, really.

text: Bing Bing was very good, but I wouldn't call it extraordinary. The food was definitely unique and delicious. And the service was great! I wish the prices weren't as expensive, because we did find them to be somewhat high, but it can be justified to be equivocal to the quality of food and service. We ordered the pork soup dumplings and caterpillar bread for appetizers. The pork soup dumplings were pretty average, but the caterpillar bread was bread filled with bbq pork and had caramelized honey on the bottom-- it was super different and delicious! We also ordered Dan Dan Noodles and Chicken & Guac Rice. The Dan Dan noodles weren't the best I've had, but they were still really good and the ingredients were all very fresh. The rice was good, but I wish it wasn't as mushy... it might've been better if the rice was toasted beforehand to give somewhat of a crunch. Overall, we wouldn't put it at the top of our list, but it is worth trying. I have heard wonderful things about their happy hour!

text:
Here's the deal:

Food is good. For the price you pay, you're getting a really good hot pot meal. However, IF YOU ARE ALLERGIC TO PEANUTS, do not come here! They use chopped peanuts with their spicy soup base and do not have an allergy warning on their menu or website. They will also tell you that people with peanut allergies have brought this concern up with them and since no one has had a bad reaction so far, you won't either.

Food - 5/5
Service - 0/5

text:
This restaurant, located in the lobby of the Sheraton Hotel, isn't obvious to see from the street.  Also, on a recent visit, the Hotel entrance closest to the Restaurant was closed, I assume for renovations, and I had to enter from the main hotel entrance and walk around the lobby. Upon entering, the staff members were friendly, as always.  The decor is quite nice, with plenty of seating. It was crowded on a Friday night but we were still able to be seated, and they have bar seating in case it got even busier. 

Their Peking Duck roll appetizer is wonderful. I love the flavor of Peking Duck, but rarely want that as my entire appetizer. So this gives a little taste of that flavor, wrapped up in a pancake, and is just the right size.

Their Wonton soup is delicious as well. It is the more Authentic style (Smaller, round, wrinkled wontons rather than the big fat folded kind you see at cheaper take out places). 

I had the house special pan-fried noodles that were served with shrimp, chicken, and pork. The noodles were perfectly executed.  Crispy, but with just enough sauce to make them chewable, without being overbearing. the meats and shrimp were nicely done as well.  On previous visits, I have tried their Pho and other dishes.  Their Lo Mein is nice too, in that it's not the heavy fatter noodles one often sees. It looks like the same style as the pan-fried. They just are (presumably) boiled so they are not crispy.  

Pricing is higher than a typical Chinese restaurant, but so is the quality. I would not call this place a value restaurant. It is better than average quality, at higher than average pricing.  It is easier to drive and park here than it is to go to Chinatown. So I don't mind the premium pricing. 

The service was spot on. There was a slightly longer than usual wait when wanting to pay the check, but that may have been due to the crowd.

text:
Absolutely delicious! I've been looking for a go-to asian take out spot here in philly, and I think I might have found it! All of the food was absolutely amazing. The delivery price is a bit high. I wish they were on PostMates. 

Here's what I ordered: 

Egg drop soup: 10/10 -- perfect in my opinion. No frills. Classic egg drop soup. 

Pork Dumplings: 9/10 -- these are HUGE and delicious. The order comes with six and they are super filling. I might recommend ordering the ones in chili sauce. Although these were absolutely delicious, I did wind up dipping them in the sauce that came with my dan dan noodles. If EMei gave you three different sauces with these dumplings, it would be the PERFECT appetizer. 

Dan Dan Noodles (with beef)-- 10/10 super cheap and absolutely amazing. The noodles came separate from the sauce which turned out to be a great thing since we ordered way too much food. I wound up reheating the dan dan noodles the next day and they were still perfect.

Singapore Noodles -- 9/10. Delicious and a whopping portion. As Singapore noodles should, the dish was flavored with curry and served with bell peppers, onion, shrimp, beef, and chicken. The flavor was perfect, but I do think the bell peppers could have been cooked a little more. I also think the shrimp was frozen because they were all identical, slimy, and flavorless. Luckily the other flavors of the dish combatted the not so awesome shrimp. 

Overall, I 100% recommend this place. My favorite Chinese in Philly thus far.

text: Great dim sum. Even my parents (Chinese immigrants) agreed that the food was pretty authentic. Prices appear to be a tad more expensive compared to other places. We enjoyed all the dishes (siu mai, dumplings, soup dumplings, scallion pancakes, vegetable tofu soup, sticky rice in banana leaf, etc). However, I personally do not like egg tarts or pumpkin tarts much (as an American-born Chinese person, I enjoy American desserts more and find a lot of sweet Chinese desserts to be somewhat weird to my palate!). I also actually did not like the turnip cake, which was surprising; I liked it at other places, but here, it tasted weird and too hard (and the accompanying sauce was too sweet/weird for me). Maybe it was just a miss, or they made the turnip cake differently from other places (I'd prefer other places' recipe!).

text:
Ocean Harmony (karoake lounge in Chinatown) seemed to expand now to also include Good Harvest - restaurant with new hotpot / soup / broth options. The taste is great, but note that it's on the pricier side. 

Atmosphere: Very clean and new set-up with hotpot stoves. It's not your traditional hotpot where you add in your own ingredients into a steaming pot, however. They essentially continue to cook your entrees on a heated plate in the center of the table. Quite spacious, with interior seating of ~30-35 on the first floor.

Food: We ordered the steamed duck pot - the flavor was amazing, with a mix of leek and garlic. However, I thought the duck was a bit dry and didn't carry the flavor well. The particular entree we ordered also was 60% garlic, and not as much duck and vegetables as we would've liked - if there were more vegetables added, I would've enjoyed it more. For $30, you're better off ordering duck elsewhere in Chinatown, that can likely be just as flavorful (just not steamed in a pot). The Good Harvest menu offers a bunch of steamed / stir fried pot options, but they keep the Ocean Harmony menu downstairs too for other dishes (e.g., snow pea leaves, chicken w/ broccoli). 

Overall: 3.5/5 - an interesting new addition of stir fried & steamed pots to Ocean Harmony, but a bit too pricey for the amount of food you're getting. Might come back to have friends try this dinner option, but I likely won't be back on my own.

text:
Not my first time here, but I always enjoy my experience here :) the soup base is so good - very flavorful and I enjoy drinking the soup just as it is. There's also lots of soup variety to choose from compared to other hot pot places. Of course the best part of the meal is the wagyu beef!!! The BEST beef I've ever had for hot pot, it literally melts in your mouth. The conveyor belt makes it fun too :)

Overall, love going to this place. The only downsides are the wait times and the food can be pricey if you're looking to order a lot of food.

text: Run and run fast, the website is totally incorrect when trying to find out about this place. Let's begin on the website they advertise a drink called a pineapple express which can not even be made due to the ingredients not being available, can so one say update. Next your website talks about Sushi, also it's in your name of what Tango is sadly and sorry to say they no longer have Sushi at Tango karaoke and sushi bar.  I was part of a party that had gotten a karaoke room found out that the bill was consolidated food and drink, i've had bad experiences with this.  So I went to the bar to order a couple more drinks and the price was different from the first time ordered I ask the bartender why he said there's an upcharge because you are with the group. I just think that to be the most underhanded business tactic in the world. They stated that they have hookah, but they didn't state that the hookah can't be used in the karaoke room you would have to go to the upstairs potion of their establishment.  I was a little disturbed by all of this because it was a monday and they were not busy, but i understand why they where not busy. I don't see this place lasting thru 2020. Food portions need to be enlarged for the price,  2 shrimp rolls   for $12 The decor or ambiance was void of being, really an embarrassment for a center city location.  would have thought I was at the corner bar.

text:
My wife and I came in. I've been wanting to try Chubby Cattle for a while, but its always been a long wait when we've wanted to come. We still waited roughly about 45 minutes to eat. 

We had the Wagyu Brisket, Meat combo, tofu skin, bok choy, enoki mushrooms, soft tofu and fried tofu. The Wagyu Brisket was complimentary for the long wait. My wife had the oxtail tomato soup. I had the House Hellish Spicy Pot (Medium).

For the price compared to Hippot and Little Sheep the meats were much better quality wise. 

Our server, David was also very helpful and explained to us how the broth was made. I was surprised how spicy the House Spicy Soup was. Next time I would do the entry level.

Overall it was a good experience and we will be back. Just make sure to book an hour ahead of time.

text:
My friends and I came to Spice C for a quick dinner while in Chinatown and had a great meal! To start, we shared an order of seaweed salad which was yummy. 

I was feeling lazy and wanted to stick to a classic, so I got the Combo with a half portion of the Sesame Tofu and a vegetable spring roll. It was a huge portion (I can't imagine what the full portion size is!) for an amazing price. The sauce on the tofu was sweet and sour - super delicious. 

They have an enormous section of vegetarian options - I can't wait to come back and try some of the other dishes like noodle soups and stir fries.

text:
FOund this restaurant after doing a search for best peking duck restaurants in Chinatown and gave it a try.  We had the peking duck dinner special - the soup, duck and veggies were all great and very reasonably priced. And also appreciated the complimentary tea.
As mentioned by other reviewers, the restaurant is not fancy or modern, but the food is great, the prices are great and the servers were very accommodating. We will definitely go back!

Also they took our credit card without any issue so maybe it depends on how much you spend, but it wasn't cash only for the peking duck dinners for 2 special.

text:
Food: Great authentic dim sum! I always make sure to ask if there are 'ladies with carts' when I'm recommended a new dim sum restaurant because I believe these places are definitely more authentic. Great variety of dishes and everything is hot!

Cost: Typical dim sum cost. No too worried about the cost here being a deterrent for people to come and enjoy some dim sum.

Environment: A very large restaurant- no issues accommodating large or small parties! 

Service: There are plenty of people circulating with the carts so don't worry about having to wait in order to get more dishes if you're hungry! I didn't have to flag anyone down during our meal here and once we were done with all our dishes it seemed like there was someone always near by for us to grab some more food!

Uniqueness: A great and authentic dim sum restaurant- if you're around the area and craving for some dim sum, definitely stop here and help yourselves!

text: I ordered their Durian and Mango cake for my uncle's birthday yesterday and when we cut the cake, there was zero to no durian inside and instead, the cake is slathered​ in layers and layers of whipped cream. All the thick white layers in the cake are whipped cream; there were no yellow pieces of durian inside. If I wanted a regular birthday cake then I would've just bought a cake from an American bakery at​ a cheaper price. I asked for extra durian and less whipped cream in the cake and they said okay but it would have to cost more. I got a whipped cream cake for $60!! That is ridiculous because what I got is completely different from what they told me. Not to mention, when I talked to their staff over the phone, they kept giving excuses and denying what they promised about the order yesterday. After arguing with me (a CUSTOMER), and giving attitude, I received a half-hearted apology. And what was their excuse? It was that mango and durian are expensive. Mangoes are $1 for 2 in supermarkets. I'm pretty sure they can afford MANGOES. I understand durians are expensive, hence why I was willing to pay EXTRA for it but instead, got cheated out of my money. I am incredibly disappointed. Never coming back here again. You lost your business for both the cake and the customer service.

text:
My fiancee and I recently had Han Dynasty cater our engagement party. We couldn't have asked for a more positive experience. From the beginning, Nick, our point of contact, was extremely communicative and accommodating in helping create a menu for the party. We initially shopped around different restaurants due to my fiancee being vegan. Nick and the rest of the team at Han Dynasty were so quick to craft a vegan menu that was not only the perfect amount for the 50 people who attended the party, but delicious and extremely affordable. And they were BY FAR the quickest to respond and friendliest. Every single person at the party, vegan or not, could not stop talking about how delicious the food was. Nick arrived with the food at the location of the party at the exact time he said he would and helped set up quickly and then emailed us the next day to check in and make sure everything went smoothly, and even congratulated us on our engagement.

We are extremely grateful for Nick and the rest of the team at Han Dynasty and will recommend them for any future party and event. 
Thank you guys so much!

text:
This place was excellent! Loved eating here with my (Chinese immigrant) parents and my boyfriend :). There were lots of other Chinese families eating here on a busy Saturday night, which I always take as a good sign for a Chinese restaurant in America (speaking as a Twinkie ;)). Every table was occupied at 7:30 pm-8:30pm. We came in around 7 and waited 20-25 minutes to get a table for a table for 4. This restaurant was very clean.

This place is cash only/Venmo/Alipay. For a big and higher end Chinese restaurant, it's kind of annoying they don't take credit cards, but maybe this'll change in the future.

The service was excellent. The waiter refilled our Longjing Tea pot ($5) at least 3-4 times and the restaurant used high quality tea; despite the ongoing 20+ minute wait for tables after 7:30 pm, we never felt rushed during our meal and the service was quick when we received our food. 

This restaurant has excellent authentic/traditional tasting xiao long bao soup dumplings - I would argue they were as good tasting as the ones you find at Nan Xiang in Flushing NY! My boyfriend happily devoured the XLB. The pan-fried pork soup dumplings were great texture-wise (there's a bit of an extra "crunch" at the bottom of them), but only good/okay taste-wise (the meat filling is more savory-tasting than slightly sweet/salty like at some other Shanghai-cuisine restaurants - also, I didn't really taste much of the "soup" that was supposed to be in these (but the dough was a little thicker/heartier like in regular bao-zi, so maybe it just absorbed the soup). The vinegar/ginger that came with the XLB was great.

We also had a more traditional dish, pickled cabbage soup with tilapia ($28), that was fantastic! The soup came with a whole fish that was de-scaled. The broth had a rich, creamy texture with a deep flavor that clearly showed they used fresh, live fish in their soup and it was a huge portion for the 4 of us. This was my favorite dish in terms of flavor/depth and my Caucasian boyfriend (who can sometimes be hesitant/not-super-adventurous when it comes to Chinese food) was pleasantly surprised and even enjoyed this soup - he ate a huge portion of it.

The salt/pepper double delight fried squid & shrimp dish was also great - the batter was light and crunchy and not too heavy/oily, so I didn't feel like we were eating ourselves into a greasy food coma like some other restaurants that serve this dish. We also had the eggplant with garlic sauce and this dish was also made well - a little sweeter and not spicy enough for my own personal taste, but the texture of the eggplant was firm/cooked well and it was a good-sized portion for the 4 of us. Pretty reasonably priced meal for the 4 of us that came out to approximately $102 with tax & 18% tip with 1 tea pot, 2 XLB orders, 1 pan-fried XLB dish, 1 huge multi-portion fish soup, 1 veggie dish and 1 protein dish.

I would definitely come here again! Thanks for the awesome dinner with my family and boyfriend :D

text:
We visited today, food was good, service left a lot to be desired. We were given a table near the door, despite other tables inside being available, had to ask and insist for the table inside before the hostess finally agreed to it. Roti kanai, spring rolls, basil chicken were good. One dish was completely different than expected, thought it would be a curry dish, it wasn't. The waitress repeatedly said, I told you it would be fried. We said, the issue was not that the chicken was fried, but that the presentation of fried chicken and sauce separately served was not at all what we expected, we should have been told that this was just non flavored fried chicken with sauce on the side. They did not offer any other item, we were charged 16.99 for this dish. We were ok paying for this, thinking, this was lesson learned and we would be more careful in learning beforehand how the food would be presented. 
Gratuity of 23% was added even before I could sign the receipt! When I asked why, I was told it's gratuity. I asked again, the manager then said, oh so you want to leave custom tip? I said, yes! It's beyond shameful that a thriving restaurant like Penang would charge a 20% plus gratuity for a party of 4, especially where the customer was clearly dissatisfied with a high priced dish. The manager then argued with me that I did not leave enough tip, I told him tip was not mandatory and I felt it was enough given the service. They had no standards set for the service which clearly could have been better, but love how they have standards for a 20% plus pre added tip. We are done, never spending our money on this place again.

text:
I only had a short amount of time for lunch while at my conference, so I was glad that Nan Zhou was close by. I had frequented this restaurant ten years ago, so I was glad to see that they were very much still in business and had excellent success. 

I ordered the dish I always did, the Noodle Soup with Duck. The soup was a solid broth, although not as flavorful as I remember. It could have been due to the extremely busy nature of lunch. The noodles were deliciously fresh, and made the soup much more appetizing. 

Overall the cost, and the fairly rapid delivery made this a great lunch spot. Next time I'm in town I'll try some of the other small plates as well.

text:
Food Delicious.  Service Outstanding.  Ambiance Wonderful. If you can bear the slightly higher prices for smaller food portions, WM Mulherin's is a home run for dinner with friends, date night, or a special occasion. 

We recently had dinner here with friends on a Tuesday night.  The place was packed and we still waited about 10 minutes for our table, even though we had a reservation.  Reservations seem to be a must regardless of the day you visit.

The restaurant is very dimly lit making it a little hard to read the menu. We shared our food by ordering the Wood Oven Cauliflower, Broccoli Rabe, Leslie Chow Pizza, Cappelacci di Zucca, Halibut Plate, and the Purple Sweet Potato Mousse.

The Best:  We loved the Cauliflower.  It was so flavorful and delicious. The Leslie Chow Pizza was very unique but had a great savory taste to it. The Halibut was cooked to perfection. 

Good:  The Broccoli Rabe was good, but I found it way too salty. The Purple Sweet Potato Mousse was very unique. 

Just Ok:  The Cappelacci di Zucca was my least favorite.  It was oddly sweet and the portion size was tiny

text:
Really awesome hotpot place! They had a TON of different options for customized dry pot, whole fish pots, and multitudes of options for authentic Chinese cuisine They even offer Americanized dishes, but what clearly shines is their various options for hot pot. 

We only got a customizable pot but were able to fill it with everything we wanted. Their add-ins have attached prices and you have to hit a $30 minimum. We hit just around there and were both pretty satisfied; they also offer bowls of rice! You can also adjust the spice level to your liking; we got 2/3 for enough Szechuan kick but enough were you can taste the food. Our favorite picks were the scallops and king oyster mushroom.

We'll definitely be back to try the hanging pork belly and the whole fish pot!

text: I cannot speak about the delivery problems that some yelpers have mentioned, but we have picked up orders here several times, and the food is always good. The quantities are crazy and the prices very reasonable. I don't know how they do it. Last night we got a quart of wonderful shrimp lo mein for under $10, and it is enough for two or three dinners. Eight large steamed dumplings also excellent, as was the hot and sour soup. All for about $20. Amazing! I don't understand how anyone could complain about this food and the prices, although I agree with the one person who said that all of the photos of the owner all over the wall are weird. Two or three would have made the point, but then again, we have a narcissistic megalomaniac for president, so I guess the owner of this restaurant might as well have an entire wall plastered with photos of himself.

text:

text:
3.5/5

My sister who lives in Philly says nothing but good things about Dim Sum Garden so my boyfriend and I decided to stop by while visiting from out of town. 

It was not the dining experience we had hoped for. Don't get me wrong the food is absolutely delicious (will get to that soon) but their service is lacking in all areas. 

Upon arrival, we had to wait INSIDE the restaurant for about 20-30 minutes. It is almost the year 2020 and they do not use a reservation or texting system that alerts you when your table is ready. If the owner doesn't want to take reservations..fine. But it is absolutely ridiculous to have customers form a line inside, while HOVERING around tables where customers are trying to enjoy a meal, all for waiting to be seated.
Fortunately, we were seated towards the back of the restaurant. I might have felt claustrophobic if I was sitting in the front. 

Service (2/5): Their service needs a lot of work. The whole establishment seemed to be disorganized as we were not assigned to one waiter throughout the night. Our food came out during random times and did not see a single person with a smile on their face. Also, when I placed another order of the soup dumplings the waiter seemed annoyed and said it would come out in 30 mins. Fast-foward to 15 minutes later and our dumpling came out at room temperature (not boiling hot like our first order). It was apparent that it was another party's dish that was served to us. 

Food (4/5): Food was delicious and filling! We ordered the Scallion Pancake, Shanghai Crabmeat and Pork Soup Dumpling, Shanghai Steamed Pork Soup Dumplings, and the Diced Chicken with Chili Pepper. My favorite was the crabmeat and pork soup dumplings and the chili pepper chicken. They were so delicious and full of flavor and spice. 

Overall, the price point is very affordable but comes at a cost with the poor service. Would I come back again? Only if it requires a zero minute wait time.

text:
I don't normally complain about wait times or what order my food comes in, but I ordered four skewers and sweet potato fries as an appetizer. I got one skewer around 35 minutes after ordering, two more around 40 minutes after, and then the last skewer and my "appetizer" almost 50 minutes after I ordered! And this was around 8PM on a weeknight, the restaurant was not busy, but there was a table of four already seated and a couple takeout/delivery orders so it's not like they had to restart the grill for just me either. If you take out the grill start time, I've gotten faster food even from backyard barbecues! And I wouldn't have even minded a similar wait time if I'd gotten my appetizer first and then had all my skewers come out together, but no, food came out slow and completely haphazardly. On top of that, what sounded like, I don't know, rapid random morse code beeping was carrying over their speaker system, so it was all around a bad dine in experience.

The skewers might seem decently priced at a couple bucks but the portions are minuscule! The bacon wrapped enoki skewer amounted to one strip of bacon and less than a quarter of a package of mushrooms, which is probably something like 20 cents worth of ingredients. Yeah, I know restaurants have labor and rent costs, but come on, four measly rice sticks $1.50? Chuan Kee is the first restaurant where I've spent over $15 and left hungry, and that was with the sweet potato fries doing all the heavy lifting.

The food itself tasted okay (although they used the same sweet and spicy sauce on everything I ordered, so not much variety) except the lamb skewer, which was incredibly tough and gamey and one of the worst things I've ever had, which took what was an otherwise 2.5* meal down to a 1.

text:
Anyone who likes dim sum knows that Saturday afternoon is synonymous with a cacophony of crowds and dim sum carts chaos. This was not the case at Nom Wah Tea Parlour. The understated, relaxed ambiance combined with good eats at reasonable prices were welcome surprises. 

I decided to try Nom Wah at a friend's recommendation and was not disappointed.

Most of the dining room was filled but it was not like you would have to be too close/right next to other diners. Some of you may think that because it wasn't super-crowded on a Saturday afternoon, it probably isn't good. And you would be missing out. Because the dishes were delicious. I ordered a lot of the usual suspects/favorites including all things shrimp - shrimp dumplings, shrimp rice noodle crepes, and pan fried shrimp and vegetable dumplings. I particularly enjoyed the shrimp and pea leaves dumplings dish, which is not as commonly offered in my home city (DC), as well as vegan options such as the scallion and cilantro rice noodle crepe and vegetable dumplings. My server was helpful and good about refilling the tea. 

As I was leaving, I noticed the sign outside that notes that Nom Wah was established in 1920. 100 years is no easy feat and I look forward to returning whenever I visit Philly again.

Note: My approach for my reviews is based on a combination of whether the food tasted delicious, the ambiance, service, and also what I expect for the area. I'm not from NYC, SF, LA, or Asia, but have experienced lovely food from all of those places, as well as bad dishes. The effect of awarding a local restaurant a lower rating solely because they cannot compare to restaurants in areas that have higher Asian/Asian descent populations can be more damaging to an otherwise good local business than we expect.

text:
What a fun Thanksgiving experience! No one was quite in the mood for turkey and sides for a week and all the cleaning and time that prep entails, so we decided to hop to Chima! I'd never been here before so I didn't have any expectations, so I think I was easily amused. The "deluxe salad bar" was neat and you can tell there's a lot of effort put into the non-meat. I thought it was also nice that they included some more traditional Thanksgiving options even though I didn't have any myself (except the cranberry sauce; that was good!).

The meats were kind of slow to move around the room and the selection seemed pretty limited considering what their menu has as offerings, but maybe that was on purpose. In any case, I really liked the pork sausages and the lamb! If cinnamon-coated pineapple comes around to your table, promptly pull the person towards your plate and plead for at least 2 slices down the column because that was probably the highlight of the meal for me. Oh and the deep-fried bananas.

I have to say the wait staff was AMAZING and we never felt like we were forgotten about...except for the meat, anyway.

Also, maybe just don't get a sangria even if it is the size of your head...

Three stars mostly for the price vs value.

text:
It's possible that my expectations were set too high for some late night chinatown hot pot / BBQ. i have always been a huge fan of Chubby Cattle, but they close early and I ended up here instead. The place is on the newer side, but the renovations were quick and only on the surface. Before I get into the food, I will point out how the place was near closing and the floors had already been recently mopped. I'm not really one to pick on something like this, but the layer of slime and grease on the floor was enough to level a sober human. 

Anyway, the place smelled great, the sauce station was next level, and evening everything LOOKED amazing. I can't say if the hot pot may have been better, but we did the BBQ. The price was reasonable--about $30 a person for more than one party could possible consume. But here is the rub: the orange glow of the grill itself was so deceiving. Our first grill seemed like it wouldn't cook our food if we sat there all day, so the waitress moved us to a different table. It was the SAME EXACT PROBLEM! The grill only appeared to be hot. 

On top of this lukewarm grill, we put everything from galbi to pork belly to  strip steak and rib eye. It just didn't really even cook. Then, the idea that raw chicken wings could even cook on a grill like this is preposterous. Plus, imagine having raw chicken touching all the other mostly cooked food on the grill. 

Needless to say, I consumed very little food, and left very hungry. I would avoid this place.

text: My wife and I came in for dinner. We were pretty excited to come in looking at the pictures. It was about a 20 minute wait which is standard most hot pot places we've been to. While we were sitting there my wife had seen the pictures of the Bubble tea on the screen. We had asked the hostess about the Brown sugar milk tea on the screen. She said we had to walk to the store a little further down. Why would you display bubble tea of you don't have it there? It made absolutely no sense. We ordered our food and the waiter brought us lamb  instead of the beef we ordered and we didn't realize it. and my wife almost threw up. We aren't lamb eaters at all which is why we didn't order it. we ordered the tom yum soup base and the oxtail with tomato soup. It was very bland. The sauce bar was average at best. The meats just didn't taste as fresh or as good as other places we've been to. The music they played was more that you would hear if you went to a club not a hot pot place. We probably won't be back for sub par service and bland food. For the price I would definately recommend going to other hot pot places in the city.

text:
As a student who lives on campus, Dim Sum House used to be my go to for when I craved asian food and dim sum and felt okay to splurge a little. The more I come here though, my experience becomes a little worse every time; I'm not one to be too critical with service but it's the main complaint I have.

Pros:
- ambiance is great! nice decor, clean, has fun stuff like pool tables
- open late to 1am (used to be 2am)
- generally accommodating for large groups 
- food isn't bad tasting

Cons:
- the distance from the kitchen to the main dining area is probably a ~1min walk, more work for the servers and slower delivery
- I went to late night and they seemed to be generally understaffed for waiters and chefs
- The servers don't seem to have a system or tables they're in charge of? I always need to flag/wave down a waiter after waiting like 30 min to order
- Food in general is hit or miss with portion size/quality for price (soup dumplings have zero soup in them in the pic below :( )
- food is catered more towards "americanized" palette

I always have a soft spot for dim sum house, but they should optimize their service maybe and it could make everything more efficient!!

text:
This is always one of the first places I bring friends and family who visit my boyfriend and me in Philly.  Whether you want to go for ice cream, cookies, Chinese Food, Italian, whatever your craving is, Reading Terminal Market has it.  You won't be disappointed.  It's usually pretty crowded, so expect not a lot of room around you when exploring the market.  

In terms of food, I've tried peking duck rolls from one of the Chinese stands, they're fantastic & affordable.  The ice cream parlor is great too.  I enjoy going to the stores in the back corner where there are a bunch of kitchen gadgets.  I have yet to try the famous donuts that there's always a line for, but I will one of these days!  I highly recommend.  Tons of food options, perfect place to buy a gift for the holidays.

text:
The quality of this place keeps on going downhill. First it was the service taking a dip, then the food, and now the ambiance. 

Whenever I walk into the restaurant, it smells. It's a mixture of fish and chemicals. The smell gets worse as you walk deeper into the restaurant. It really makes we question the freshness of the sushi and fish they have displayed at the counter. 

I always get the BBQ rib noodle soup and I swear each time there's less and less meat. This time, I only had 3 small pieces of meat. 1 bowl is $10, I expect there is be more meat in this!! It's very disappointing. 

I will not be back for dinner nor their lunch specials. There are so many more places and options in University City for soupy noodles in the similar price range.

text: We ordered lunch delivery to an office and are disappointed by the serving sizes for the price tag. $22 for Char Grilled Beef that was half (or less) the amount of beef compared to the photo advertised on the delivery service website. Other items were also small portions for the price, but the beef was ridiculously small. It was also overcooked. We stopped ordering from here a few years ago, because they would put 2 (yes, just 2) shrimp in the pad thai. We decided to give them another try today and see they haven't changed. Skimpy on everything but greens. Tea Smoked Ribs are delicious, but honestly not worth eating here just for those. We spent over $200 on this food order. If you MUST order lunch here, just get the Bento Boxes. That's the only thing that has value for price.

text: So many better places to go for Pan-Asian. Came here for dinner....was (as usual) rushed. We ordered 5 things and they came out within 10 minutes of ordering. That's fine for fast food...but we are supposed to spend some time at a a restaurant in this price range. Impression is...they want you in and out as soon as possible and they want to turn the table. For the price, go to Chinatown and you can get interesting takes on Asian food for a fraction of the price and not be rushed out of the restaurant.As with many Schulson restaurants they had multiple servers/ vultures standing around trying to swipe up your plates the minute they sensed you might be done. honestly, the entire feeling was " can we get you in and out of here within a nanosecond"?" They would do better to focus on the overall experience and less on the transaction.

text:
Best authentic dim sum place in Philly (that's worth the price). My family usually brings me here. Today I brought some friends.  

They have the traditional carts and dim sum is $ (as it should be!) I honestly hate going to places that sell $7 for 4 crystal shrimps.

I went with a party of 3- total was $65 for all of us. We ate for around 1 hr and had around 15-17 options. Ribs are my favorite to get with a side of Congee with the 1,000 yr old egg. 

The variety is vast (dumplings, fried shrimp, tofu, jellies, pastries, veggies, soups etc). Place opens at 10 but I suggest coming around 10:30 for 1) seats because the place gets filled fast on weekends and 2) more options. If you come to early there might not be as many foods ready

text:
This place was AMAZING!!!! The food was so flavorful and delicious. My wife and I ordered the Dan Dan noodles which had a wonderful chew and great tasting peanut kind of sauce with minced beef. We also ordered the shrimp fried rice(plently for 2-4 people), the garlic sauce lamb, scallion pancakes, and spring rolls. Honestly, all this was way too much food but I will happily eat these left overs. This place is sooooo reasonably priced I couldn't believe how low the bill was for that much food.

We had two very friendly and attentive servers, Kathy and Victoria.

I would recommend making a reservation and I have full confidence you're going to enjoy whatever you order here. This is now one of my "Must Have" places when I come to Philly.

text:
Looking for a staple Dim Sum place? This is it!! 

Very cozy, chill place with a bar and super cool wine bottle decor. I came here on a Friday night with a friend  and the place was not crowded at all! Nice and speedy staff who were very attentive and polite. 

The food here was GOOD for the prices that they had. Between my friend and I, we ordered 9 dishes and our total was only $37!!! (we didn't order any drinks). 

There were many options on the menu but not as many as you would find at other local dim sum places. They did have gluten free options on the menu which were marked with an X and some veggie options as well. 

I would suggest to take public transportation here since this place is located in Chinatown and parking is really tricky. You COULD find meter parking but that would be an inconvenience.

text: My parents and I used to order from Johnny Chang's all the time for many years over the phone and one day I ordered something that was probably very inexpensive to make as it only involved egg and rice and my husband called to say he would run behind by a couple of minutes and they told him not to worry that someone will be there. He came there to pick up my food and no one was there. I called back the next day about it and I asked if I would be able to have my same order given I paid about $5 for something that probably cost them pennies but instead of being accommodating to a long time customer that they've never had issues with before, they took a stance of not accommodating my request over the phone. Quite disappointed in their customer service as I've been a patron of theirs for many years and with having had one issue they were willing to just throw it all away over something so small.

text:
The food at the restaurant is delicious, fresh and made on site. But my review is aimed at their catering service.
We were hosting a dinner for 35 people for our son's rehearsal dinner in South Philly. He asked for Dim Sum. We investigated a few places, including our normal go-to (another spot in Chinatown). None had a dedicated catering process, and this was too important to leave to chance. We hadn't been to Dim Sum Garden in a few years, but thought we'd try it. We were overjoyed with the quality and taste, and more to our delight, it had a catering operation. We were also able to order regular menu items not on the catering menu.
On a Monday we ordered the food, and it was delivered the following Friday. The food was warm, fresh and delicious. The delivery was right on time, and the delivery person was very helpful in setting the food up for us. Everybody raved about it, and it made our special dinner an event to remember. The price represented a good value for the amount and quality of the food.

text:
Initially wanted to experience the individual hotpot and conveyor belt, but with a group of 6 we had to share one big pot (the typical way). Their sauce tray was huge and hotpot isn't complete without this. Their menu had plenty soup base options (multiple vegetarian options too), meats, carbs, and veggies to fit a large group's needs. Split pot for broth was an option.

Food was good. Wait during prime time could be super long. Price is steep (I prefer ayce when it comes to hotpot). Service was decent during the meal, but they kind of forgot about us when it came to the check. Presentation of food is cute. I would come again if I had a smaller group to experience the individual hotpot and conveyor small plates.

text: We were pleasantly surprised and enjoyed our dinner and drinks!  The bartender takes pride in his craft of making drinks.  I had the Philly Love which was amazing.  Bartender also altered it for another patron with Tequila instead of Vodka.  We had an nice conversation with the bartender and enjoyed watching him make his specialty drinks!  The dinner was excellent and reasonably priced!  The wonton soup was enough for two.  My husband had the General Tso's and I had the Chicken Pad Thai which was awesome!  The staff was very nice and accommodating!  I definitely recommend this restaurant and will be returning when I am back in Philly!

text: Cash Only!!!! The noodles are pretty tasty. I got the chicken with wide noodles and honestly I prefer the small ones instead of the wide ones. The wide noodles were a little messy but that's pulled noodles for ya. The portion is okay. I felt full. The birth was light and refreshing but I wish it was more. There was a good amount of mustard greens in the soup. They ppl quickly seated me as well and the indoor decor was standard. It's more a 3 stars for the food I ordered versus what the whole place represents .  I've had better hand pulled noodles for the same price.

text:

Uni is not on the menu.  $18 for lunch and $24 for dinner.

My mistake.  This review is for the restaurant in College Park, MD.

text:
Little sheep is now AYCE all day! I think it was $25.99 per person, same price for lunch and dinner. Lunch is 12-3 and they close for a couple hours until 5:30-10. Each table shares one pot and you can choose 2 flavors. Our table chose the half/half original and spicy broth. None of us thought the spicy broth was spicy.. at all! But you can choose extra spicy, so if I come back, I'd probably do that. I have to be honest and say I prefer the broths at nine ting better (along with the fact you get your own pot incase you feel weird sharing), but this was a good change. The spicy broth has spices I'm not too fond of like cardamom and cumin so keep that in mind. 

As far as meat, you use the card at the table that says "I'm all good" or "I need help!" to signal to the staff if you need to order more meat or a beverage. There are 5 kinds of meats you can choose from, 2 lamb choices, 2 beef choices, and pork belly. We had the aged lamb which was fine, it pretty much tasted like beef after being cooked in the broth. There's fatty beef which was my personal favorite and marinated garlic beef which I thought I'd like more than I actually did. The marinated garlic beef became weird in texture after being cooked, a bit too soft. Pork belly of course was good as well. 

There are also seafood options like crab, shrimp, and octopus where the "buffet" is. Plus fish balls--BEWARE!!!! the fishball with roe will explode when you bite it and the molten roe will severely burn your tongue (don't as me how I know...). Also tofu skins, any vegetable you like, and a small cooked section with UNEXPECTEDLY GOOD CHICKEN WINGS!! Seriously don't overlook em- they don't appear great but were so good. There's also a small but sufficient sauce bar if you need it. 

We spent about 2+ hours which is one of the things I love about hotpot. You can hang out with friends eating for a long time and enjoy your time together.

text:
TLDR: Good quality, authentic Chinese/ Taiwanese food for decent portions and reasonable prices in Center City!

***********************
As my friends and I put it as we were leaving, this is a restaurant that we would feel comfortable bringing our Chinese parents to/ the best Chinese/ Taiwanese food we have had without needing to order in Chinese.

I usually have different expectations of food authenticity and price efficiency for Chinese/ Taiwanese restaurants outside of a Chinatown or not a family-run business. However, I will say I was pleasantly surprised, so I applaud the owners for sticking true to their roots in DanDan's menu, cooking, and portion sizes.

The menu has dish names in both English and Chinese. For starters, we got the crispy spicy cucumbers, scallion pancakes, and wonton in chili oil. For entrees, we got the dan dan noodles, three cup chicken, dry spicy fish (unsure if that is the exact wording of the name on the menu), twice cooked pork (I think that is the English name for hui guo ruo 回鍋肉?) and garlic eggplant. Out food came with 2 medium-sized bowls of rice. The scallion pancakes were kind of small (only ten small pieces), but the eggplant portion size was pretty large. Again, I was pleasantly surprised by all the flavoring! Not that I'm by any means an expert on Chinese/ Taiwanese food and its authenticity, but this was definitely the most authentic food I've had in Philly outside of Chinatown, and for reasonable prices too.

The inside vibe is dark and ambient, great vibe for a date night or fun casual dinner with friends! It's a little small, so if you're coming with a bigger group, definitely call ahead. We were seated right away, but also I think we got lucky and there wasnt much foot traffic, from it being a rainy, cold night.

Overall, good Chinese food for good price, especially if you share everything with your group! My group of 7 went family style, and everything we ordered was enough for us to all feel full. However, if I wanted Chinese food, I'd still go to Chinatown for guaranteed good Chinese food in larger portion sizes and for less money.

text:
Food was good for the most part.  The seafood mixto and flank steak were well worth the price.

The octopus was overfried and tasted a little burnt.  The mushrooms were excellent.

The messinessi was good but a little chef boyardee-ish.  Good thing I happen to like chef boyardee.

However the francobolli comes in a portion that is enough to feed a guinea pig, not a full grown human being - so be wary when ordering if you're hungry.  It is definitely appetizer sized (actually the appetizers were bigger).  What little was there happened to be delicious.

Best deals are the pizzas in my opinion but there are better authentic Italian pizzas in Philly and jersey.  

Overall a bit overpriced for the food quality - which was a bit inconsistent.  Great atmosphere though with nice decor.

text:
Ambience: Where to start off. This place is utterly amazing. This is place is so freaking amazing. Very cozy, you can smell the aromas of the soup bases just right out of the restaurant. Next thing you know you're sitting down and downing the amazing broths. There are about 15 to 16 tables. The lights and the design of this place is on point. Such a modern yet comforting vibe.

Food: Now down to business...for appetizers we got the wagyu yukke and uni nagiri. Both just amazing. Uni nagiri is something to get when coming to this place. They place the dish under this smoke encased glass. So that the smokey-ness encases the sushi and uni. Just absolutely melts in your mouth. As for the wagyu yukke very interesting appetizer. Came out with a raw egg and minced wagyu accompanied by nori sheets. Very interesting but light as an appetizer should be. For entrees we got two soup bases, the original and hellish spicy pot. And boy should I tell you the hellish spicy pot is no joke. We got it at the lowest level of spicy-ness and it is no fricken joke. We got the hot pots accompanied with the wagyu combo platter, vegetable combo platter, purple yam noodles, green tea noodles, tripe, and Kobe Bimbap. The Kobe bimbap was so worth it. Very flavorful and they mix it in a stone bowl right in the table for you. The noodles are both worth getting as they're unique to the taste and powerful in flavor. 

Service: We were greeted by the handsome David "Vee". He was extremely polite and explained to us what hot pot was and how to eat hot pot. Extremely helpful and attentive. So thank you David "Vee". 

Overall an awesome experience. Very cool experience. It is a bit pricey but totally worth it. As all together with what we got came out to 143$. But again so worth it. We'll definitely be back.

text:
SO GOOD
I have so many great things to say about this restaurant -
1. Nearly everything is vegan, and all of it is vegetarian.
2. Prices are very reasonable, especially for how big the portions are.
3. Service was quick, clean, and our waitress was so kind and helpful (made amazing recommendations!)
4. Simple parking if u have a car.
5. And most importantly, delicious food.
I seriously recommend everyone come to this place for some great Chinese dishes and dim sum, I promise it will not disappoint!
We got fried cashew tofu, sesame noodles, DIY "pork" bao buns, scallion pancakes, bbq seitan skewers, steamed veg dumplings, soup dumplings, "pork" buns, shumai dumplings, and bbq roast "meat".
My faves were 1. The bao buns, 2. The seitan skewers, and 3. The sesame noodles. But literally EVERYTHING was awesome :)
I will most certainly become a regular at this place!

text:
New Leaf is a newer Asian fusion restaurant in Manayunk and probably the best one on Main St. They have a full bar which is unique for it being an Asian spot.

I've been here twice and had a pleasant experience each time. They offer many options including sushi, Japanese and Chinese entrees. At my most recent visit, I ordered the Spicy Tuna and Philadelphia roll and both were delicious! Each roll was around $7 which is priced fairly. I also ordered 2 glasses of Sauvignon Blanc which tasted pretty good for it being a house wine. A glass of wine is about $6-7 which is definitely cheaper than most restaurants. 

Service is fast, friendly and attentive. Food comes out quick and is neatly plated. The interior is big, simple and clean. I would definitely recommend going here if you're in the area! I look forward to trying their entrees next time.

text:
A few friends and I came to Little Sheep "Mongolian" Hot Pot for a dinner. The restaurant is in Chinatown on Arch St. Parking is a hit or miss; the areas in front of the restaurant and around the corner are always tough to find parking, but if you go a block over in front of the Convention Center/Reading Terminal, there are usually more parking spots (though can still be full). We were able to contact the restaurant ahead of time and place our name on the list, but we still had a short wait. Walking into the restaurant was quite amazing because you can smell the wonderful aromatics from the broths right away. You see the buffet and the vast amount of ingredients you cannot wait to put into your hot pot. 

After being seated, we choose the broths and the meats. I'm not really sure how this is "Mongolian" since it seems like a normal Asian/Chinese hot pot to me. Plus, most of the employees speak Chinese (some can ONLY speak Chinese, which is tough). We ended up doing the half-half, and the spicy broth was really amazing (lots of Sichuan peppers). and was very tasty It's pretty much all-you-can-eat, which is pretty awesome for any party size. The buffet consists mostly of the non-meat options (veggies, tofu, etc.), but includes seafood (ie fish balls) and some cooked foods (rice, fried dumplings, chicken wings). Trust me, you'll become full rather quickly. They don't have a bar, but it's BYOB and we brought a bottle of wine, which they provided wine glasses with no fee. Finally, price is decent for an AYCE hot pot buffet (~$23/person without tip/tax).

text:
A bunch of us Asian folks (originally from Asia) have voted that this is the best place to get Dimsum in Philadelphia. 
For dimsum lunch, they push carts around and you just pick what you want to eat. All great options, big variety, tasty.
Service is not too great because the staffs don't speak too much English (and we don't speak Chinese) but that doesn't matter because you can just point to what looks good on the cart and they'll mark it on your bill. Not too pricey, either. We usually end up paying around 20$ per person.
Definitely recommended for dimsum. They don't serve dimsum for dinner I think.

text:
This is one of the flashiest places in Chinatown. Usually when you walk past it, it's packed. The interior decor looks nice, very upscale. So my friends and I decided to come here for their birthday.

I am going to start off with the appetizer. The Baby Oyster Omelette was good. The omelette was nicely made and oysters were alright. Overall well seasoned and the soy based sauce accompanying it went well. It gave a slight sweet note to the dish.

For the entree I got the Sambal Sotong. This is a squid dish and I was intrigued. I love squid and spicy food is my jam. Despite how it looks, it isn't really spicy. The disappointment comes with squid. Personally, texture is a very important to me. Squid has a soft body, but there is still a resistance to them. Sadly, in whatever way this squid was cooked, it lost whatever texture it had. The squid was a soft as if I was eating tofu. Also these dishes doesn't come with rice and you had to pay a ridiculous amount for a small bowl of rice.

Overall, the experience didn't hold up to the appearance. Everything looked very pretty, but the flavors did not match with the aesthetics or the price. Having to pay for a bowl of rice for an entree dish is disappointing and even more so when the food isn't good enough to be eaten alone. Without the rice it would've been a soft mess. Maybe others would have luck with other dishes, but so far it was mediocre for all 8 of us at the table each a different dish.

text:
Location is great. We watched a movie at Landmark and wanted to find a restaurant close by. Buddakan is right around the corner! They have really good reviews so we decided to give it a try. I personally would rate it a 3 star because I like more authentic Asian food. I gave it a 4 because there's really nothing to complain. The only con is they are a little too pricey for the portions they offer. Also the lighting is a little dark for me, but it can be perfect for a date night. Let's talk about the food:
Peking duck - A definite recommend. Boneless duck with extra crispy skins is all you expect from a good Peking duck dish. They didn't disappoint. 
Dim sum sampler - Dim sums are cute. Not enough for 4 people to eat but can be a good starter for 2 people dinner. 
Jumbo shrimp - delicious but very small portion. 
Fried rice - Average. 
Curry cauliflower - a bit too salty but tastes pretty good.

text:
I'm a bit biased, because where I'm from there isn't a great hotpot place, so keep that in mind. However, my partner and I LOVED this place. The soups were delicious, the meats seemed fresh, the mushroom basket was aplenty, and the watercress was the single most solid choice we made. It's a bit pricey, but honestly would come back here over and over just for that soup and that tray of ingredients to make sauce. It has *almost* everything I usually use to make my family's hotpot sauce, so I was stoked. 

The ambiance was great, and the service was quick and courteous. Super cozy for a trendier place, and just the right noise level for the type of place it is. We both basically raved about our meals and came out bursting with fullness.

text:
What's more traditional at Christmas - when the kids are away - than Asian food?

Never had hot pot before, but the reviews were so compelling, we had to try. And we are adding our strong endorsement to all those that brought us here. The service was great - our server, Brandon, took time to explain everything and answer our questions, both at the outset and over the course of our meal.

We tried the Wagyu nigiri to start - OMG! It was phenomenal - the smoke-infused treat was overwhelming. 

My wife had the original broth and I had the Hellish. I tried a taste of my broth after it heated up - just a dip of a stick. WOW, that was spicy and I started to worry that the spice would overwhelm the cooked foods. Next, the beef combo. Three different cuts and each had a clearly distinctive flavor - and those flavors completely survived the Hellish broth. If you like spice, you don't have to worry about not appreciating the flavors of the cooked food. Next, fish balls and, again, incredibly flavorful.

We were still interested in trying more even though we'd consumed a pound of beef plus other items. So, a meatball sampler and orders of shrimp and scallops. You might think that these more subtle flavors would be overpowered by the well-used broths, but they weren't. The scallops were completely and wonderfully distinctive, as were the other items, but good scallops are so sweet and mild, I was amazed by how well they tasted.

Yes, pretty pricey, but we had a terrific, 2-hour meal and will absolutely be back.

This place lives up to its name and the awards they display. I got the beef brisket noodle soup. The hand made noodles were great and went down easily.  The beef brisket had a great flavor and the soup well seasoned. The marinated egg was alright, the flavor wasn't really there and it was very overdone.

When I came back the second time I got the House Special Noodle Soup, scallion pancakes, and pork and chive dumplings.

The house special soup is great. Defiantly a must have, they load it up with literally everything and the flavor is immaculate. 
The pork and chive dumplings are good, nothing too special. 
The scallion pancakes were delicious though. It's a bit thicker and smaller than other places, but it was just as good. The thickness allows for a balance between the crispiness of the outside and softness of the inside. Delicious none the less.

Overall this is a must visit place with a great variety of noodles with a great price. The staff are attentive and the food comes out fast.

text: I've been going to Danny Wok for years for all my large party orders. Stopped there on Christmas for a pan of wing dings and I was HIGHLY upset. The wing dings were a fraction of the normal size that I had been getting for yours. They were some of the smallest wings I've ever seen in my life. As much as I love the chicken I can't see paying the price for such small pieces of chicken. They were like chicken nugget size wing dings. I have a party in a week and now I'm in a crunch to try and find another place with decent size tasty wings.

text:
Get the damn soup dumplings. period. 

They're unparalleled to most, and you won't even want to bother with anything else on the menu -- you'll just want to save more room to stuff additional dumplings in your face. My fav is the spicy pork. 

To be honest, in reading other reviews, it sounds like the rest of the menu might fall short anyway...

The lines will be LONG, so don't wait until you're hangry to check this place out. Also consider placing a takeout order (and eat it IMMEDIATELY) or trying to snag a seat at the bar. This experience isn't going to be an incredible dining one -- it's going to be about the deliciousness you'll experience at a great price.

The wait staff here best accommodates smaller groups - I would stick to a smaller party.

Take a bubble tea to go.

text: I was here on a Friday night with a 730 reservation, but upon arriving there were quite a few tables available so it might not have been necessary. (All of that to say, this could be a "walk-in" place if you find yourself walking around center city on the weekend wanting some decent food). We started off with the pancake and curry sauce and I have to say, that curry sauce was DELICIOUS. I wanted it on everything (I'll explain more later). It was creamy and peanut-y and the pancakes were crispy and not greasy at all. So good. I ordered the satay with tofu because I was looking forward to more delicious peanut sauce but that was not the case. When I think of satay, I think peanut, but this didn't really have much of a peanut flavor. It wasn't bad...it just didn't taste spicy and peanuty-y. The prices are good the service is good and the place is decent. Our bill would have been on the lower side for a meal in center-city on a Friday night if it were not for the bottle of sake that we ordered.  It was worth it and we were feeling pretty good by the end of our meal. This place is a bit more of a casual spot. They were very gracious with a Yelp 10% check-in discount even after our tab was already totaled. It was an ok experience. (I should have poured that peanut-curry sauce over my tofu.)

text: If you are in the area and have the time, go at least once. There is always a large selection of high quality food of all types. I passed by one of the butcher stalls, where the meats cost twice the price I have paid elsewhere.
