text: 4 star food. 1 star service. Keep in mind you're here for the tasty food and reasonable prices. Staff don't care if you haven't dined in before. When ordering read the entire menu item, not by number, or they'll reprimand you. If you ask for water or anything other than hot tea, specify how many or you'll only receive the amount of glasses one waiter can carry. You may be asked if x is enough and if you say yes and ask for more later, they will complain that you said  x was enough drinks for you earlier. Tried to kill with kindness, but waiter was still sour, arrogant entire meal. Restaurant tip reflects service. If you don't care for 1 star service, order take out and save your money on the tip.

text:
I LOVE this place!!! Wow. The food is incredible. It's authentic, it's fresh, it's flavorful and it's sooo quick. You get your food in a few minutes! The won ton soup was perfect. It was just right. The fried noodles were fresh and crispy. I can't say enough about how much I enjoyed the food. 

The drinks were also very good. I had a martini and for being a restaurant, it was pretty darn good. Not to mention their prices are very fair. 

The atmosphere is nice. It's bright, cozy and warm. It's a fun place for groups or a cute date night. It's not intimate at all but you're getting the experience, it's not the place where you ask your new boyfriend what he thinks about gentrification. It's fun, it's noisy and it's good food. 

Just come here and enjoy it. It's worth it for sure.

text:
Love this no frills Shanghainese street food place. Soup dumplings (xiao long bao) are authentic, the scallion pancakes are tasty without being dense, and fried dumplings are great too. I think they had the usual noodles and fried rice and such on the menu, but we really just came for their famous soup dumplings so didn't look too much into the other stuff. The name may be a bit misleading, because this is definitely not a Cantonese style dim sum place with the ladies that pushes carts of goodies around. Dishes are made to order. The best part? The price! Snacks for 4 people cost $20.

The service is as expected at most Chinese restaurants. Seats are crowded. Table slightly dirty and literally wiped as we were sitting down. Water cups looked old and maybe dirty. Bathroom was a bit run down and messy too. For these reasons, took away a star, but for sure would still come back for the amazing food.

text:
Pricey but absolutely worth it. I have been here a couple of times either with friends or family it's great for sharing.

Fish hotpot is a must. When I went with a friend we shared the hotpot combo where there's a specific # of options you have to include for a ~$35 hotpot. With family, we go for the stripped bass- there's 3 options on spice level but if you can't handle spice like my brother I recommend getting a garlic base. 

The hotpot itself comes in neat "chest like" pot or moon shaped hanging pot. The interior is very modern and I really like how they have outlets at the seats! Big plus since my phone is always dying. 

The menu is very vast - very, very vast. I'll be coming a couple dozen more times until I get to every dish offered here.

text:
Im not so sure why there are so many highly rated reviews. (I am personally on the fence between 2/3*.) Possibly because they offer bonuses/deals and require proof of a high rating on Yelp to enroll in their rewards program.

Let's start with the wait time.
We reserved a spot through Yelp which stated 2 hour wait. We arrive the time stated for the reservation only to be told it would be an additional 30 minute wait. After deciding to go to their bar/lounge located upstairs to wait it out we eventually get called down to experience a much worse wait of another 20-25 minutes. Making it worse because now we are standing in a small space having to endure the wonderful smells and seeing what appeared to be delicious foods.
The ambience of the place is pretty cool aside from the very loud music making it pretty impossible to hear the unintelligible speedy chat from the waitress. Also, there are two restrooms, one of which I believe was out of order while there 

Now for the average food, a couple things to be aware of and the terrible aftermath of the meal.

We went with a classic house broth and the lowest level of spice with a Spicy house broth. We only ordered a couple of seafood pieces and four vegetable options. Of which nothing to rave about. If going with seafood I would suggest the platter, as the portion size seemed adequate and the presentation looks wonderful with animal ice sculpture as the centerpiece. (We did try out the Wagyu brisket and it was phenomenal.)
We ordered green tea noodles that were tasty but the dish has a very small amount of noodles and if memory recalls the shobu that were decent.
Now on to the disappointing broths. The classic was very average and the spicy will most likely ruin your day. The two of us love spicy food but this is not enjoyable. Mixing the two had it bearable. I feel bad for the couple seated behind us who were unintentionally given the spiciest level and most likely could not consume after hearing his quote of "this is literally the spiciest thing I have ever eaten!" followed by other remarks. They should put some type of warning here.

A couple things to be aware of and keep in mind.
- If you are accustomed to endless servings that come with the all you can eat hot pot places...this is not it.
- When the assortment of garnishes are placed on the table be prepared to take what you intend on using, because they will shortly return to take it away.
- They do not have spoons. You will be drinking the broth from the bowl.

On to the aftermath. We left and took a short walk back to our place where I soon rushed into the bathroom where I found myself stuck for quite a long time. I do not want to go into too much detail here but I will say that if you are seeking a cleanse this would probably be the least enjoyable option to choose from!!

On a side note. It was appreciated that they offered two free dishes from a list they wrote out because of the long wait time. One of the choices being a salmon sushi roll that was tiny and bland.

If it was not for my company who happens to be the most amazing women in the world, knows how to make the best of a situation, and shared her beautiful smile through this experience... I would have been very disappointed, a bit upset, and partly offended by this NYE meal.

P.S. The cost was $75.00 (with a $15 bottle of Soju) and additional $25.00 for two cocktails and a shot while awating.

text: Went in on a slow Thursday night. Sat instantly and was immediately brought waters. Our drink order was taken and arrived extremely quickly. It was my first time at hot pot so I got the run down from our waiter about how you cook your own meat in broth. My party and I ordered all three levels of spicy broth (Entry, Medium, and Numbing). We also ordered wagyu brisket, angus prime, lamb shank, glass noodles and udon noodles. They provide a soy sauce and fresh herbs and spices to customize it. The broth took no time arrive and the dumplings were first out follow by the meats and the noodles. Everything was very good. Broths were very spicy and everything cooked extremely well. The meats were beautifully sliced and very good. I felt the wagyu wasn't worth price for hot pot. Loved the glass noodles and the soy sauce mixture. The lamb shanks were delicious and definitely the best part of my meal. I will definitely be back again!

text:
Leaving this review because I have to to sign up for their rewards. Quynh was our server and she was great. We've been here a few times and perhaps the novelty has worn off. Conveyer was fairly sparse, maybe because it was a Thursday night. Prices have gone up as evidenced by the stickers placed over old prices. Pricing was a little deceptive as ordering of the conveyer was actually cheaper, $0.25/piece for certain items, than directly ordering from the server.
Overall it was a decent meal, quality slightly better than some AYCE hotpots. Premium pricing is for the experience, atmosphere, and overpriced higher quality cuts. I'm sure we'll be back. Maybe a 3.5 star review is more accurate.

text:
I came here for dinner with my date. The menu was pretty extensive. We got the Thai calamari, spicy cucumbers, and ahi tuna dumplings to start, which were delicious. The calamari and dumplings surprisingly weren't extremely greasy for fried dishes. I have to say that the plates on which the appetizers were served weren't practical. The small base of the plates/bowls almost cause our food to fall all over the table.

I got the green curry chicken as entree which has some hint of green curry taste in it, but the base was more creamy than expected. It did help satisfy my green curry cravings, but I've had better green curry elsewhere.

The price was good for the quantity/quality of the food we got, especially for a downtown restaurant. I'll definitely return to try their other dishes.

text:
GLOWS:

They answer their phone. We asked about a table for five so when we arrived we were seated promptly.

Hayden did a GREAT job making sure our party (most not familiar with Malaysian cuisine) knew what we were ordering before we got it. (All except one item, which I kind wish he had in retrospect.) 

Reasonable prices.

GROWS:
Those wings are whack. I'm actually mad so many reviews made sure to mention them. They're whack.

The spare ribs were waaaaay to hard to eat. I get deep fried, but they were barely edible. And then the refused to remake, exchange, or refund them. That bothers me A LOT. 

I get that they were trying to bring out the food as it was prepared and therefore it was warm, but the person in my party who ordered the overcooked spare ribs was waiting a whole extra 20 minutes for them while the rest of us had all been given our food. 

OVERALL: Meh, I guess I just expected more from the reviews. It was basic.

text:
Good Harvest is very much similar to Jade Harbor and Tai Lake, but with a fancier interior. Both Jade Harbor and Tai Lake's interior design is pretty outdated. But of course, better design means higher menu prices. If I'm correct, some of their items are 20% or 30% higher than JH and TL.

I took my mom here to celebrate her birthday. When we enter around 11:30pm, it was only 1 other set of customers dinning in, I was a bit shocked. Jade Harbor and Tai Lake are pretty packed at this time of night. It didn't stop me from dinning in though. 

We order Scallion pancake, Crispy Seafood Rolls, Spicy  Beef appetizer, Braised Scallops with Mixed Vegetables, Salt and Pepper Frogs, BBQ Squab, and Snail in wine sauce. We fell in love with the Scallion pancake, we got a total of 3 orders lol. Only con is their sauce, it is not the sweet sauce that we are used to, but since I like it without the sauce, it will do for me. Crispy Seafood rolls are perfectly fried, crunchy exterior and soft on the inside. Spicy Beef appetizer is seasoned very well. Hubby enjoy the Braised Scallops very much. Bbq Squab were a bit overcooked, if u like ur meat well done, these will be perfect. Salt and pepper Frogs and snails were both sauteed very well too. 

Our waiter made our experience pretty awkward. He kept staring at my hubby. I understand it is Chinatown but it is America, STARING is RUDE!!

text:
Judging by the nightly lines to get into this place, it's no secret that Dim Sum Garden is a winner and easily the king of Philadelphia Chinatown dim sum. I'd had their basic steamed soup dumplings a time or two before and found them to be some of the best in the city, but over the weekend I sat down with a couple of friends and shared a slightly broader range of items at the bar. 

I wouldn't call our order ambitious by any means, but we had steamed soup dumplings, pan-fried soup dumplings, shrimp egg rolls, shrimp dumplings, and chicken on a stick. All of them connected. 

The two types of soup dumplings were the highlights and left my friends split on which they preferred; I was no help in deciding a favorite because I played it safe and said I prefer different ones on different days, which is absolutely true. They don't do anything out of the ordinary with their soup dumplings, they just deliver the goods the way they're supposed to taste. In China that's to be expected in my experience, but in Philly soup dumplings of both kinds are a more hit-and-miss affair (my girlfriend finds the fried ones to be as close to the ideal she formed on a trip to Shanghai with me a couple of years ago as any she's had in the States).

The shrimp dumplings they serve here are the delicate, partly translucent kind with big meaty shrimp pieces inside. They made a nice variation on dumplings from their soupy pork counterparts. Again, they're just classic shrimp dumplings done the way they're meant to be. I guess I won't go on much further because as I think about it, that's the kind of bland but sincere comment I have for most of the stuff we ate. The Spring Rolls with Shrimp were crisp and airy, but they were there and gone so fast, arriving as they did at peak feeding frenzy time, that I wish we'd at least doubled our order; they're only $5.80, so I'm not going to complain about the price, but do be warned - it's a small order. The chicken on a stick (which is closer to SE Asian satay than the Chinese meat skewers from my time over there) was a more substantial order (four sticks) at a similar price, but they also left the least impression on me. Then again, I let my friends have a larger portion of those in favor of getting an extra fried soup dumpling, so maybe that factors in.

There's still plenty I want to try here. In terms of dim sum, I expect good things from the spicy soup dumplings, pumpkin cakes, and fried beef dumplings. But I now really want to try their more standard, full-plate dishes because they've proven that they do dim sum well enough to excite me for their Kung Pao, eggplant, hot pots, etc. 

(bonus: they're right next to the also masterful Nan Zhou Pulled Noodles, thus making the best restaurant neighbor pairing in Chinatown!)

text:
Sang Kee Peking Duck House is a old school Chinatown favorite spot
 Located at the end of Chinatown near the wall, it's a very popular and busy restaurant. I go there often, mostly for take out and it's always crowded and busy.
My favorites are: roast pork (make sure you ask for the duck juice to accompany it), the duck rolls (tortilla like bread with roast duck, scallions and hoisen sauce) duck noodle soup with scallions and ginger, nearly every noodle dish and of course the Peking duck which is displayed proudly in the window.
Service is fast and everything you need to add on like sauces, chopsticks and utensils are on display. Prices are reasonable and they'll get you on your way in a hurry.

text: Not sure what everyone is raving about this place for ... I personally enjoyed the experience but the waiting time and the price just kills it as there are other options in chinatown. Would I come back again? I would seriously have to think about it. Although we put our name on the waitlist over an hour and a half before we got there, we still had to wait an additional hour to be seated. The bright side to all of this is that they have plenty of seating area in the second floor for waiting and the staff was super friendly. Most people come here for the Wagyu beef which is good but like I said, to me it just tastes like meat (sorry, my tastes buds can't tell the difference between great and good quality). You get your own hot pot and can order your dishes through the waiter and grab side dishes from the conveyor belt. Overall great experience but a bit on the pricey side.

text:
So far the best hot pot in Chinatown Philly. The food are much better quality than the all you can eat, and honestly it comes out to be the same price per person as anywhere else. 
I like that it is individual pots so I can choose my own broth flavor. I've tried the tomato oxtail broth, original and spicy. My favorite is the original. The tomato oxtail broth kinda has a sour taste to it, but it definitely taste better after a few minutes when everything is simmering. The spicy was level 6 and OH MY its spicy! 
I think you cant go wrong the original, it is so yummy!
I also had their uni rolls..not the best uni, I suggest to skip that and save your money. They are mostly known for their hotpot so dont do the sushi here

text:
I went to the graffiti bar during happy hour. I ordered the kimchi fried rice (very good), the pork potstickers (very very good) and the korean beef satay which was good as well, but I was disappointed that I they only give one beef stick. I'm not sure if the happy hour portions are less than the normal portions. I couldn't believe that the one beef stick was $5 and I hope the full priced portion is more sticks of beef. 
The staff was friendly, especially the food runners that introduce each dish by saying "good evening, here is your blah blah blah". The bartender's service could definitely use some work tho. There were 3 of them behind the bar and a tall white guy was the person specifically serving me. Outside of getting my food and drink orders, he never came back to check on me. Never asked if my food was ok, never asked if I needed anything additional, which I did. The three of them were chatting behind the bar and I had to keep finding a moment to interrupt them to ask for soy sauce and then a fork. I also intended to order another beef satay and another cocktail, but I'm not a customer thats going to keep looking around for my server or waiting for them to stop talking so I can ask for something I need. They all pretended to barely see me staring at them, patiently waiting for my bill. My food was all gone, plates stacked and pushed to the side and they still didn't come back to me on their own, I had to wait for them to stop talking to interrupt and ask for my bill

text:
I highly recommend this hotpot and think the extra cost (several dollars more expensive than Nine-ting) is justified in the higher quality of the meat and vegetables, the AYCE buffet style and the delicious taste! My pet peeve with some hot pot places is that you can't control the quantity of food servers bring to you. Here, I could get a single mushroom or a couple bites of tofu, which ensures no food waste. I thought the meat (the only thing that is brought out by servers) was tender and juicy and the hotpot broth (original and spicy), were a cut above the rest. I can actually taste the difference between the beef and lamb, which sometimes is sliced so thin at other places it's hard to tell. The sauce selection is not as extensive as other places, but has the basics. There was no wait time on an weekday afternoon. 

They also have a soft serve machine with cantaloupe and honeydew flavors, which aren't my jam, but others may enjoy.

text:
Walked in on a Friday night for takeout. They were pretty empty but so nice! Not sure if it is the same owners of isushi which was in the spot previously or new ownership, but had picked up from isushi before so wanted to try it out.

Got the shrimp dumpling soup from the kitchen menu, and sashimi appetizer + spicy salmon tartare from sushi menu. All was great, reasonably priced and what I was hoping for. Fish tasted fresh which is obviously important.

Standouts would be the shrimp dumplings in the soup and the salmon tartare.

Will be back soon. Want to see them do well!

text:
Here are a few of the many reasons why I always come here for lunch/dinner whenever I am in Philly: 

1. The noodles are simply delicious. The portions may not be huge but you will leave full-filled and happy. My favorites are the Mapo Tofu Noodle and the Szechuan Cold Noodle. 
2. The price is incredibly reasonable, about $8-9/dish. AND you can now pay using venmo! 
3. The service is impressively fast and no-nonsense. 
4. It's BYOB.

text:

text:
Very disappointed! 
Had dinner here tonight with a large group. We were given an option to do the regular menu for $50 or the restaurant week menu for $35. The restaurant week menu had a limited amnt of meats and did not include dessert so we opted for the $50 menu. Towards the end I look at the menu and realize that we were never served half of the meats from the $50 menu - no filet, no bacon wrapped filet, no ribs!  We proceed to mention to waitress and she says that she can speak to the chef and they can bring those meats out. At this point we are all stuffed and pretty much ready to leave. So, we proceed to tell her that we don't want anymore meat, but think it makes sense to do some type of discount since all the meats never made it to our table. She makes a comment about the fact that we didn't mention it earlier so we kindly explain that we didn't even realize until looking at the menu again. She says she can talk to the manager. The manager states that he spoke with the staff and they confirmed that they brought all the meats and that our party of 15 is basically lying. He proceeds to say that we were probably "distracted" and didn't see when the meats were being served at our table. He also accuses us of not knowing what filet looks like and says that they are not serving the bacon wrapped filet anymore. When I get back to the table  after talking with Manager Mauro we see the guys walking around with bacon wrapped filet!
After a few minutes he comes over and says "What do you want me to do?" Ummm, you're the manager.... figure it out!!!! He brings over $25 gift cards and says we can use them next time. We decline and say that we would rather see a discount tonight because we don't know if we'll be back. He asks if we ordered desserts and we say that you can cancel the desserts and just discount our check, which he seems to agree to and leaves. 
Manager Mauro never returns! The waiter brings out some of the desserts and we get charged the 50$ pp price, plus  $$$ for sparkling water and coffee and tax and tips.... so the $35 buffet ends up costing us almost $80 pp! 
I usually don't write reviews and never complain and I've been to Chima multiple times, but I will not be back again. I felt cheated and ripped off and the worst was the Manager accusing our party of 15 of not noticing the meats and not knowing what they look like! Look at the camera footage Mauro...they never came to our table with those meats! 

Beware! Pay attention to what you are getting! ESPECIALLY during Restaurant Week!!!

The fried noodle dishes were pretty typical, but I found the rice noodles (ho fun) to be not as smooth as it could be. Good food, solid delivery. Didn't have the wow factor I would have expected given the other reviews.

text:
This restaurant is a hidden gem in China Town, you must be on the look out otherwise you can easily walk past it as I have many many many times. 

Came here on a Saturday night with family being seeing a comedy show around the corner. There was a wait and unfortunately due to the small capacity of the restaurants front end you have to wait outside which isn't ideal when it's cold, but the wait was too long. 

After being seated we were greeted and given tea. The menu is pretty expansive and offers many many items to choose. I ended up ordering the Beef Noddle Soup and the Garlic Chicken and Eggplant. Both plates were large, easy to share, and tasted so delicious. I would say though go for the Spicy Beef Noodle Soup, it's not that spicy and definitely adds more flavor. Also the prices are excellent for the quality and quantity of food you receive. 

This place has now become a go-to place for me to grab their Spicy Beef Noodle soup to-go on my way home.

text:
A great spot in the Museum District/Spring Garden neighborhood for some tasty Chinese food! Living around the area, I come here more often than places in Chinatown, as the food is delicious and the travel time is nonexistent. I highly recommend checking this place out, as they also offer a free choice of dimsum when you spend  $25 or more. 

The dimsum is delicious! I love the pork bbq ribs, which are so tender and flavorful. Also I would recommend getting the scallion pancake, the cha shao bao, and the soup dumplings! It's hard to find a dimsum place that also offers soup dumplings, which is one of the reasons that I always come back. The food is decently priced, and you will definitely be full by the end of it. 

On non-dimsum plates, the noodle soups are quite delicious. I've tried the Taiwanese noodle soup, which is perfectly spicy and extremely delicious! Their mapo tofu is also pretty good, although the size is definitely the main reason to order this. 

The place is BYO and the service is extremely friendly. I will definitely continue to come back  here!

text:
Unit Su Vege has tasty, fully vegetarian (mostly vegan) Chinese food. 

I had dinner with some friends, and let my foodie friend order for the group of us. We had mapo tofu (really delicious, though didn't have the Szechuan peppercorn numbing zing), green beans (fantastic), some kind of Chinese broccoli in a white sauce dish that was just fine, and a couple of orders of dumplings (soup dumplings and steamed dumplings - which, alas, tasted basically the same, but were both good). Prices and portion size were good, and they weren't busy at all on a weeknight evening. They have a nice variety of teas for $1 person, too.

The menu is huge, and if I lived in Philly I'd definitely be back to try more options.

text:
Went here with a group of 8 for restaurant week at 5:30 on a Thursday night and we stayed for 2+ hours. They will hold your reservation for 15 minutes, and if your entire party is not there, your reservation will be cancelled and you get put on the waitlist. This happened to us, but our wait was less than 5 minutes, once everyone arrived. They offer valet for $11 plus tip, but the parking garage around the corner (although it can be tough to navigate through) was only $12.

They offer both a full menu with all the meats, sides, and a dessert, and a restaurant week menu with select meats and no dessert. They warned that if they saw meat sharing they would charge both for the full menu price. There's a salad bar with some greens, bread, soup, cheese, deli meats, etc. I would go easy on these items but would recommend grabbing a couple of these just to have a break from all the meat. 

If you're like me and don't really care too much about what kind of meat you eat, I'd recommend saving the extra money and getting the restaurant week menu. I wouldn't think of going here during anytime but restaurant week. You still get a great selection and great experience! (And after a while, I can't even distinguish what cut I'm eating lol)

The staff and service were amazing. Our side dishes and drinks were constantly being refilled. They'd offer us new plates and asked us we had any requests for particular meat selections. When we'd leave the table, they'd pick up our napkins and refold them. If there were scrapes of food on the table, they cleaned it up. 

As far as the sides that come with the meal, I absolutely love their mashed potatoes. I easily ate 5 bowls. It's a great compliment to the meat, but can also be enjoyed alone. 

We came here as a birthday celebration and when they served desert, they also gave us a delicious tiramisu with a birthday candle!

text:
Omg! So philly is having their restaurant week the same time I'm out here for a quick weekend getaway! I had the pleasure of booking this restaurant for dinner, and let me just say, i was not disappointed. For $35 they offer you a 7 course meal. It's called their tasting menu, and almost everything was delicious! 

I ordered the Pork Bao Buns, general tso chicken soup dumplings, mushroom and roast pork lo mein, Korean bbq skewers, steak, crab wonton tacos,,and pan seared scallops. 

 The best to me was the Crab Wonton Tacos! They were crispy, the crab was perfect. For this price  point everything was amazing. They finished it off with mini ice cream cones   2 banana choColate, and 2 raspberry vanilla! Omg! Food heaven. Definitely tRy this spot if  you're in philly. It's a cool vibe. Also we had the dragon bowl with vodka and it did exactly what it was supposed to do. Check pics below

text: With all the great food options in Chinatown, I feel like this Szechuan place gets overlooked a lot. Their menu is reasonably priced, the service is pretty fantastic compared to others in the area, and the food is authentic, plentiful, and flavorful. They had our Szechuan staples of fish filet in hot chili oil and braised pork belly over picked veggies. Both were among the best versions I have had for either dish. There was an abundance of fish and pork belly to last us at least two meals and quality wasn't sacrificed at all! I highly recommend this place if you are looking to satisfy your Szechuan cravings.

text:
Oh Lord.

My friend Tim was in town and wanted to 'walk around' Chinatown. Why, I don't know, but part of being a friend is acquiescing to requests like this, so I met him at 9th and Arch and we proceeded to do as he wished-walk around. Of course, all this perambulation makes a man thirsty as well as hungry. David's Mai Lai Wah, which I heretofore knew nothing about, was right across the street when we both commented on our growling bellies, so we stepped inside. 

When we entered, the place was empty save for 2 tables and even then, we stood in the entry way for more than 10 minutes until someone acknowledged us and pointed to a table. We sat, were given menus, then we sat some more. 

The cocktail menu is odd to say the least, with things on it like 'Bee Feater' and 'AB Solute.' Quirky spelling aside, a lot of classic cocktails are priced at $6.50 here, which is about half of what you'd usually pay in almost any Philly bar.  We wanted some booze, we were ready to eat. Still we sat. 

Finally a curt older waiter came and asked what we wanted to drink. I ordered a Manhattan and Tim asked for a martini. We were not asked what kind of liquor we wanted nor did the waiter pay any attention when we said we were ready to order food. Hmmm....

Another 20 minutes passed, the place was still only 2 tables full plus us, and no drinks nor anyone inquiring as to what we wanted to eat. 

At last our drinks came but again, when I said (politely) we wanted to order food, I was ignored.

The drinks. Oh, those drinks. Tim took a big swig of his martini and started to cough. I teased him about being a light weight until he made me taste his cocktail. I sipped and looked at him with raised eyebrows. "I know. Right?!," he said. "This must be some kind of industrial cleaner, not booze. It will probably kill us." With trepidation, I tasted my Manhattan and got a mouthful of what tasted like very cold cherry Robitussin. Since I'd done the honors for Tim, I made him taste my drink. Even through all his Botox, he screwed up his face when it hit his taste buds. I suggested we ask for the check and go elsewhere for food, since we knew we would not finish these abominable drinks and felt certain that no one was going to take our dinner order. 

We tried catching the eye of several servers to no avail and finally Tim went to the register with cash, saying we wanted to pay. By now, the front of the restaurant was clogged with people waiting to be seated. The woman at the counter looked through Tim and did not take his money. He pressed a male server into helping him and was told that this server did not know what he had. Tim named the drinks and the man walked away.

He sat down again, suggested we just leave money on the table and go and said he needed the Gents before we headed out. While Tim was performing his ablutions, I again tried to get someone to give us a check and held up both credit card and cash as I attempted to get someone's attention. No dice.

Tim came back a little pale and I asked if he had a bad bathroom experience. He said the toilet was dirty but what bothered him were the dead fish floating in the over crowded, dirty seafood tank in the back, being eaten by live fish. 

At that point, we put 2 tens on the table and pretty much fought our way through the throng of people at the door who were still not seated. I wanted to shout out, 'Abandon hope, all ye who enter here,' but felt that would just be in bad taste. 

I will AB Solutely never darken David's door way again.

text:
My friend and I opted for Nom Wah because we knew that the original New York version is famous. The dim sum here was a bit of a mixed bag. Ranking of favorite dishes:

Steamed pork spare ribs - honestly, you can't mess dim sum spare ribs up. Ranking this the highest because I'm biased and I love meat more than carbs.

Rice roll with fried dough - This one is carbs-overload (my friend loves rice rolls). It's more of a sweet than savory dish, as it comes drizzled with a sweet soy sauce. 

Cilantro and scallion rice roll - More rice rolls. I personally would've preferred the shrimp rice roll, but this one was also good. The rice paper itself was thick and soft. 

Steamed Chinese broccoli - Not even a dim sum dish. We just wanted to pretend to be healthy lol. 

Xiaolongbao - The above dishes were all standard dim sum quality, but I genuinely didn't enjoy eating the xiaolongbao. When it came out, we could already tell that the skin was way too dry, so they were probably standing out way too long. As a result, it was hard to peel the dumplings off the steamer, so a lot of the juice spilled out. Overall, the meat wasn't as flavorful as we would've liked. 

The restaurant wasn't busy during Saturday lunch hour. We came around noon and there were still a few empty tables. The price here is very reasonable, though. Between the two of us, we spent about $35.

text:
Huge venue! Great service, plenty of seating for large and small groups. Ideal location for business, right by campus.

Parking is minimal, street parking mostly. I would walk if you can. 

Lots of choices, variety of proteins. Definitely need to come back multiple times to try different things. We got the garlic sauce with chicken which I was not a fan of but portion sizes were good. Meant to be shared/family style. Also got the salt and pepper shrimp which was to die for but like most places it was a tiny portion. We killed this dish and wanted more! Not overly salted which is always good. Finally the wonton soup was a light refreshing soup. May have  added a bit too much black pepper as out daughter was not able to eat the actual soup but she enjoyed the wontons.

Overall, definitely wil  be back to try more of their dishes. We did get dessert too, their Mochi which comes from a prepackaged  place so it was standard nothing to rave about.

Only complaint were the prices of some of the dishes. Yes the portions were large, but not large enough to be charging what they charged!

Will be back, happy eating!

text:
Average Cantonese food and dim sum in Philly

Food: 3, Value: 3, Service: 4, Atmosphere: 4.5

I'm from a Cantonese family so I always try to find great Cantonese food wherever I go. We decided to  try this place on our weekend trip to Philly. The atmosphere is nicer than most traditional Cantonese places and service was quick, however our server was not familiar with the menu and did not understand the Cantonese names of the dim sum when I tried to order. Overall everything we ordered was just average. Here is my specific thoughts of the food:

Ho Fun - decently done, but did not have much flavor. Not enough meat. Had to add quite a bit of soy sauce to get adequate taste

Pork belly with mustard greens - very thin slices of pork belly and small portions. Don't be fooled, underneath the pork belly is a pile of mustard greens not pork. The buns are soft, but did not seem home made.

Dim Sum - just average. Tried a few different things. The noodles and wrapping were a little thick and the meat filling lacked flavor.

Overall, nothing special, but a nice restaurant atmosphere.

text: I'm so excited I finally found a dim sum place within 20 minutes of the city! We live pretty closeby to Chinatown, but unfortunately, all of the places there have let us down. Whether it's the unbelievable waits, the awful service, the incredibly limited parking situation, the just average food, it's just always a hassle. Even Wokano out near Washington Ave has really started to let me down. We found this place on New Years Day...and WOW, were we impressed (for Philly dimsum!) It was about a 17 minute drive from our place in Old City which is really not bad. There's a huge parking lot and a chinese supermarket next door with a boba shop inside. For the amount of people they had to deal with on Near Years Day, I was genuinely impressed with how organized they were and how quickly they were able to get everyone in and out. The dimsum carts came around quickly, nothing ran out (for some reason everything is ALWAYS out at Wokano), and everything was actually really delicious. The chili oil on the tables were SUPER yummy and actually spicy. They even had the piggy custard buns, and they were not just amazing for the cute appearance, but for the taste as well!! Prices were really good too. For a group of 6 that ordered way too much and left REALLY REALLY full, we paid $14pp including tip and tax. If that isn't a great deal, I don't know what is. Looking forward to making this our new dimsum place!!

text:
This cute little restaurant in the middle of china town is definitely one to check out. 

We got seats for four right away on a Wednesday night. We ordered a variety of things.... they were offering a special "BOGO" for certain meats, and we chose two portions of the pork belly as well as the wagyu variety platter with three kinds of beef.

I also chose the miso broth base. A vegetarian from our group got the mushroom. One variety vegetable platter was plenty for the four of us. 

The broth unfortunately took about ten minutes to boil. So as our various items came out for us we began to lose table space. They brought over a small metal table to help, which it did a lot. 

Once we were cooking it was great. Our server told us how long to cook each item that came out. 

The soup dumplings took a  while to cook! So make sure you throw those little adorable dumplings in right away. They were really great. 

Service was great, and it was a lot of food for a  relatively low price. If you're looking for a hot pot restaurant definitely head here!

text:
I had been craving dim sum for some time and glad I was able to find this place in a familiar neighborhood.  Parking can be tough in that area so if you can order delivery, that would be the less stressful option.  The establishment is a store front space.  You enter at the register where they lead you to the sitting/eating area towards the back or order to go.

The menu has all the popular dim sum dishes (shrimp dumplings, sticky rice, chicken wings, pork bao, and moree).  I've tried the majority of items and they were really good.  Just thinking about them now has me craving their food.

The food comes out warm and timely so no long wait.  The prices are good therefore this is the place for your dim sum fix!

text:
We met a couple here for dinner on a Tuesday. Right in the heart of Chinatown, Chubby Cattle offers a large selection of different Waygu cuts of beef, many accompaniments, and different vegetables cooked hotpot style at the table.

There was no wait when we arrived, but Chubby Cattle has the wait list available via Yelp which is fantastic. We all ordered different broths, my girlfriend ordering the Miso Tonkatsu (definitely recommended - super delicious, dense, and my favorite of the ones I tried), and I ordered the house which had a decent taste but did lack a big punch in flavor.

They bring a caddie out with all different "toppings" like garlic, scallion, etc., to make your own dipping sauce for the meats. We ordered the brisket, the waygu sampler, soup dumplings, and the vegetable sampler. The meat was all delicious, beautifully displayed, and tender. The vegetables kind of lacked variety in the sample and were mostly large, leafy greens that didn't break down well when cooked. The soup dumplings came out frozen and were colorful, apparently each color representing a different flavor that the dough was made of, although they didn't taste too different from one another.

The food all tasted delicious, the set up and the idea of the restaurant is fun, interactive, and you get to try a bunch of different things for a decent price. Definitely worth checking out. I'll be here again at some time.

text: We came here last night. Five stars for the service, which was the best part of our experience. I liked the more upscale hotpot experience, but is it that much better than Little Sheep?? Not for the price point. The wagyu foie gras was a bit gimmicky for $18. It was flame torched just before serving, which made it difficult to taste the actual flavor of the beef. If I'm paying for sashimi style meat, why add smoky flavors? The tiger shrimp and mussels also did not look fresh at all, maybe they were leftover from Chinese New Year? The veggies were of excellent quality. We ordered a few of the nicer meats and found the brisket to be the best in terms of flavor.  One thing I really wish they had was a better soup base. For a pretty expensive meal, I should not go home feeling like I just had wayyy to much msg. I don't mind small amounts of msg in food, but this was too much. Found myself chugging water even the next day, with that weird msg aftertaste in my mouth.  If they're providing an upscale experience, they should have a good bone broth without msg, otherwise they are not different enough from the other cheap hot pot places in Chinatown.

text:
Good Szechuan food outside of Chinatown! My friend lives nearby and really likes this place, and she's absolutely right. The food is solid--spicy, authentic, and decently authentic. We got the dan dan noodles, wontons in chili oil, pork belly with sweet garlic chili oil, and spicy beef hand-ripped noodles. Everything was wonderful, but our personal favorites were the dan dan noodles (my husband still thinks about this) and the spicy beef hand-ripped noodles, which had the most tender morsels of beef and delicate noodles. I can see either one making a deeply satisfying meal for one. We're moderate chili lovers and thought the food had a pleasant amount of heat, but if you live for the burn, you might want to ask them to make it spicier. 

The restaurant is trendy with a nice romantic ambience if that's what you're into. Prices are reasonable for the area, and portions are large. The three of us split 2 apps and 2 noodle dishes, which was plenty of food and the total only came to around $40 before tax and tip. 

This is the kind of place Chinese-American yuppies bring their parents, and I want to clarify that that is a good thing. As a Chinese-American yuppie myself, there's something to be said for a place where you can simultaneously impress your parents, eat good food, and not feel bad about the fact that you can't actually speak Chinese. Well done, Dan Dan.

text: I normally come to this place whenever I'm craving skewers since it's pretty good here. However, I think it's a bit overpriced. You could easily spend over $30 from skewers here and the portions are small, but they had this happy hour where every Monday it's $1 for certain skewers from 2pm-6pm? Anyways my friends and I came here on a Monday and they told us that they're not doing it anymore for some reason when the signs were still up for the happy hour(funny thing is that this happy hour thing seems to change whenever the waitress feels like it). So we got around 20 skewers for 3 people and a stir fried instant noodle dish. Mind you 20 skewers arent a lot since the portions are small and the ramen dish we got were $8 for God's sake. Its literally instant noodles with a few pieces of spam, greens, and eggs. With $8 you could get a legit bowl of noddles anywhere else in chinatown. The total came out be like $56(including tip) which is ridiculous we just got freaking skewers and a small dish of stir fried instant noodles. And I would say the service isn't that great, we sat down and the waitress didn't offer us water much later even though we were the only table there and she even asked us if we needed water? Like don't restaurants usually just bring it to the table? Anyways she never came to check on us to see if we needed anything else or even water the entire time we were there and the place was literally empty while being on her phone. Overall, I was disappointed with this place this time coming here with my friend who I just recommended it to.

text:
My wife and I were piqued and intrigued to scope up Chubby Cattle, so we stopped by last night for our first ever Hot Pot experience.  We were not disappointed.  Positively or Negatively, this is best experienced with more than one person and table space is at a premium, but we enjoyed our experience and will be back!

Before I get into my pros/cons, a little bit of a primer for the uninitiated (which was us until last night).  Hot pot, or hotpot, also known as steamboat, is a Chinese cooking method, prepared with a simmering pot of soup stock at the dining table, containing a variety of East Asian foodstuffs and ingredients. (Per Wikipedia).  

We began by ordering out hot pot base, which include a number of broth options.  Previous yelpers warned for extremely spicy options, so we opted for the house and beautiful tomato soups - they were both delicious broths and both my wife and I found the house broth to be a flavorful experience - especially with the dumplings and noodles!

They bring out the soups, instruct you on how to heat them ("have you dined with us before?") in a very non-judgmental way and then you are left to order any number of items to dunk and cook in your broths once they boil.  Food items are delivered a la carte with cooking instructions (times) and some items can just be left in the broth for minutes while you eagerly engage in others.  We found the experience fun and delicious, although we found presentation often got in the way of simply placing lots of food items at the table.  Overall, it was more an experience than just a meal!

Pros:

The star of the show was the beef.  Beautifully marbled Wagyu beef not only stars on the menu, but is advertised/displayed throughout the restaurant.  And with good reason, it's truly a decadent and delicious experience, with a well-distributed fat content that basically balances the fat content in an ideal manner.  Basically, the Japanese have mastered beef and it's served in bit size hot pot cooked slices for you to enjoy.  We tried the Wagyu Brisket and Rib-eye and we not disappointed.  We enjoyed the Rib-Eye slightly more as it was a more sustainable bite, but both were excellent.

The housemade flour items were delicious.  Our server recommended the green tea noodles and we also tried the dumplings which were both freshly made and flavorful.  The dumplings in particular were a beautiful rainbow of colored doughs that included some very fresh raw meat which required a 10 minute cook time.

Additionally, the seafood combo we tried was both beautiful and plentiful, including fine easily cooked lobster, shrimp and slices of various white fish.   Well worth the price of admission and not a disappointment.  

Another excellent experience was the sauce making - you begin by making a sauce to enjoy your various options - featuring any number of delicious accouterments.  But decide quickly as it needs to be removed from the table somewhat fast.  We found the fried tofu was the ideal vehicle (it's tofu, so of course) for consuming and tasting the sauce as we altered it.  

Finally, our server Angel was truly excellent - one of the best service experiences I've ever had.  He was fast, attentive, experienced and knowledgeable of the menu.  He was capable of explaining all of what we were trying, what was worth the experience and making other recommendations.  

Cons:

It's certainly pricey.  The menu is essentially a la carte and best enjoyed in a group setting to try a number of items.  Most "dishes" come with many pieces for a table of 2-5 to enjoy several of and it's clearly constructed as such.  For the price, the quality was high, which seems to be the theme of Chubby Cattle

Is this a con?  Things are served very quickly and we ran out of room fast!  

The beer list was far from extensive (some standard Asian beers along with Heineken and Corona) and they did not have any Soju which was a little disappointing.   If they've got a liquor license, they may wish to up there game.

Perhaps we ordered poorly, but our vegetables were lackluster and I wouldn't spend too much time on that part of the menu.  I actually found the veggies in the broth to be far more enjoyable.

Conclusion:  Our first Hot Pot experience was a truly positive and enjoyable one.  With individual pots, a large and expansive menu with a wait staff that is extremely knowledgeable, we were not disappointed.  There's so much on the menu that we want to try, primarily different broths and other house made options (purple yam noodles?).  It seems like one could go on for weeks trying everything the menu at Chubby Cattle has to offer.  We'll be excited to come back and bring our friends to try such a fun experience!

text:
Disclaimer: The 3 stars has NOTHING to do with the food. My go to order for my family and I is the salt and pepper shrimp, salt and pepper chicken and chicken fried rice nothing else and the salt and pepper shrimp are my ABSOLUTE fav meal I usually eat an order to myself. I could probably eat them everyday if I wasn't concerned about high salt content. 
Anyways, my 3 stars are solely because the customer service is horrible I thought at first it was a cultural thing you know, the strictness and short flat temperament of the staff but now I just think they're mean. One time in 2019 they were closed for a while and I felt like every time I went for food they were closed so once I caught them open and went in I attempted to have small talk with a waiter asking "hey you guys have been closed for a while what happened?" And I was bluntly told "you have break right?!" So rude in my opinion I was excited to be a patron again just to be put in my place I guess you can say. We are nothing more than cash flow to them and I feel bad saying this because I'll continue to be a customer because of that salt and pepper recipe  So for the maybe more sensitive folk who want to feel valued where they spend money BEWARE the chances of a friendly interaction are little to none staff wise. 
Oh and they stay open late so this is an after the club hit. Maybe the late nights aggravate them idk.

text:

Always great to find a vegan chinese food place! text:
Good Harvest is another really unique restaurant in Chinatown with dishes that I am sure you wouldn't be able to find in many other places.  I ordered three dishes: the dungeness crab over sticky rice, the taro and duck casserole, and the frog congee.  This was my first time having dungeness crab and frog, so I was really excited for how they were going to taste.

I will say right off the bat, be prepared for high market prices of the seafood here - the dungeness crab was $58 and we also inquired about a few other seafood dishes at market price and found them all to be pretty eye-watering. My partner and I were given restaurant credit in exchange for a review of the restaurant, and so if it were not for that, we may not have tried it. I'm so glad we did however though - the crab on top of the perfectly cooked sticky rice was such a treat. 

I'm originally a Marylander, so I do have a bit of bias for cooking crabs smothered in Old Bay, and I do honestly believe the dungeness could have used some salt and seasoning.  If I were eating it without the sticky rice, I would have probably liked it less but regardless, it was still steamed to perfection and delicious. The duck and taro casserole was not what I expected at all - it was stewed in a kind of savory gravy but it was good overall and great with our white rice we were given with it.

The frog congee was also great - frog tastes more or less like stringy chicken, but the huge vat of congee was very much welcome on this super cold night. We took plenty of leftovers home and were really satisfied with our meal. Service was super attentive, and every time our side plates got a little bit dirty, servers were there to whisk them away for new clean ones.  The restaurant was pretty empty, and we came on a Thursday night.  It seems though that they can accommodate very large parties easily, and I would definitely bring more people here to try more of their dishes (especially the plentiful hot casserole pot options they have).

text:
Like real-life ninjas, Ninja Bao is hidden in plain sight, but it is a formidable foe for against hunger and expectations. FYI - Ninja Bao is underground in the Septa station, just a few stores adjacent to the Dunkin Donut.

Must get: chicken katsu bwa bun, free gyoza
Meh: roast pork bun, pork ramen
Missed out: dessert bao

As a native-born northern Chinese, I am very particular with baozi, or steamed buns stuffed with vegetables or meats. So you can imagine that my simultaneous hesitance and excitement when I heard about the new baozi shop. In short, it's fun, fairly well priced, salty and sweet. Unlike traditional baozi, ninja bao are steamed in similar manner, but also fried at the bottom to get that crispy bottom. While I was not too crazy about this cooking style, I was very surprised by how hot the bao remained, even after a long period of wait time while digging into other dishes. As for the actual inner content, the roast pork bun is very similar to the cha siu bao (or the sweet and savory, aka barbecue pork bun) that you can find at dim sums, however, given that I don't like bbq pork buns...it wasn't my favorite by default. The chicken and corn bao was actually quite a pleasant surprise as chicken is uncommonly utilized in Chinese steamed dishes (dumplings or baozi), but I found the overall combination of the ingredients to be a sweet and salty delight.

The bwa bun, or one-sided bun, is beautifully packaged and definitely the star of the restaurant. Of the options, the best is definitely the chicken katsu, as the chicken is incredibly juicy but crunchy and worked best with rest of the fillings. That being said, I think these buns utilize too much sugar (visible layers of crystalized sugar on the bases) and thousand island dressing that definitely reminds you that you're eating something non-traditional. My biggest disappointment is the roast pork, which was way too fatty. In fact, for the pork bun and pork ramen, we had to throw it away because it was too fat to eat and enjoy. While the fatty pork made the broth of the ramen reach greater heights, I was highly disappointed when I had to throw away the generous chunks of meat away.

Overall, this was a fun and unique establishment to visit, especially if you're traveling via Septa. The service is very friendly, almost too friendly, and you get a free gyoza on arrival, so it's definitely worth a visit.

Food: 3 stars
Service: 4 stars (very fast)
Ambiance: 3 stars (I like the decorations, but would have liked the Disney film Bao to be played in its entirety on the TV, not just the trailer played on repeat)
Price: 4 stars

Such good food! Authentic but also some modern dishes as well. Good sized portions, plenty to choose from for any palette. Service was quick, not the friendliest as it's all business, in and out. 

Venue is large, has down and upstairs. This place is known for its duck but we wanted to try other things. Nothing disappointed us. Even the smoothies were delicious. Prices were decent and expected for Chinatown. Wonton soup was plenty, the shrimp with honey walnut was amazing. We also got a lo mein dish which was okay. 

We will definitely be back for more meals! Horrendous parking as it is in china town. There is street parking for cheap if you can find any,  otherwise it's $15 to park in the lot across the street. Plan ahead and make  it a day trip so the parking is worth it!

Happy eating!

text:
Yelp, you've never steered me wrong! Sampan is a home run, it's as simple as that. The look inside is cool and vibey without being stuff or pretentious. The happy hour specials are fantastic! $4 beer and wine, plus 20 dishes ranging from $3-$5. There wasn't an average bite in the lot!
Korean BBQ Beef Satay was delicious. Sweet tender beef paired perfectly with the sour, spicy kimchee.
Edamame Dumplings with sake broth were soft pillows of soy bean heaven, swimming in love. 
The Pork Banh Mi was flawlessly executed, combining most-yet-crunchy bread with sweet charred pork, tangy slaw and spicy pickled carrots. But regardless of all other praise, the night belongs to the Chicken Bao Bun. I can't rave enough about it. Perfect flavor. Perfect texture combination. Perfect price ($5.). If I wasn't already married and if it was legal, I might ask this Bun to marry me. It's that friggen' good!  
I came in and sat solo at the bar and loved every minute of my experience here. The staff is great, the patrons were courteous and friendly, and I walked out stuffed, buzzed and happy for $35!
If you're in Downtown Philly, this is THE SPOT

text: My friend and I were looking for a new place to tryout for dinner in Chinatown since we had been eating for almost every restaurants in Chinatown. When we saw this place, we checked on google and it was a franchise restaurant, so we had to give it a try. We ordered the combination pot with crispy fish/short ribs (half and half in one dish) and salt& pepper squids. There were very few pieces of fish, the rest were vegetables and peppers.  The squids were covered with too much batter.  The three dishes were pretty salty even we ate it with plain white rice. The more we ate it, it's just getting more salty. When our check came up a total of almost $70. It's on a pricey side of just 2 orders with 3 dishes and for 2 small bowls of plain rice.

text:
Full disclosure: My wife and I were invited to have dinner at Good Harvest, gratis, and were asked to write a full and unbiased review.

They offer a good rendition of modern Chinese fare, centered on skillets and dry pots. It didn't completely blow me away but was skillfully executed.

Our first impression on walking in was that we'd walked into a mid-market restaurant in a well-off part of Beijing. They nailed the currently-fashionable modernist decor common in restaurants in China to a tee. Service was fast and responsive, though it seems their marketing consultant didn't make sure instructions were left for frontline staff on how to handle this promotional offer, which took a minute to sort out.

We ordered a yellow-braised chicken pot and a ying-yang pot split between flounder and blue crab.

The former is a style of cooking common in Northern China; chicken and vegetables are braised with spices and then splashed with water, covered, and left to steam for a while. Theirs was spot-on; not as heavily salted as some others but that's all to the good. It's not the best we've ever had but it is the best we've seen locally.

The seafood pot was less impressive; it was good, just not amazingly authentic or breathtakingly innovative. China has a way of cooking white fish such that it comes out awesomely tender and juicy, which they nailed, but it was a bit blander than we expected, perhaps because we didn't specify a spice level.

The crab was also good; chunked up, lightly breaded, and deep fried in the Chinese style. The upshot is that it's possible to eat the softer bits of shell when it's done this way; the underside of the carapace and the thicker parts of the legs are edible.

Their naan/flatbreads were a perfect rendition of China's imitation of the original Indian; my wife loves banana flatbread so she was overjoyed and ate the whole thing.

We didn't pay much attention to prices but they seemed reasonable from what I recall.

Overall, we were happy with it; Good Harvest is good enough that it would survive in the cutthroat mid-market segment in China, so it certainly deserves to here in Philly.

text:
Nine Ting is great for Korean BBQ! A little bit on the pricey side--I notice the pictures on Yelp was a bit outdated. When I went, we ended up paying $29.99 per person.

There wasn't as many banchan as I was expected (we got kimchi, seaweed, peanuts, one more we didnt really touch), but the kimchi  really was spectacular!! We had to ask for another portion of it twice. 

The seafood pancake is very good, just be careful not to eat it too quickly while you're waiting for your food to be cooking, as it can fill you up quick. I usually eat it by itself since the sauce for it can be too sweet (it was like honey!).

There was this lovely waitress who wasn't even assigned to our table, but she totally made our day! She was very kind and visited us at the right times to ask if we needed anything. Didn't bother us or hang too close constantly. Near the tail end of our time, we were somewhat full but still wanted some seafood and the sausages (super good!!), so I asked her if she could bring them out but in small portions--and she did!! It was so kind of her to accommodate us! 

Overall, it was a good albeit pricey experience for bbq with your friends! Other stuff to recommend: mix your soy sauce with the garlic and add scallions and vinegar; the pumpkins are sooo delish! A little bit crispy from grilling but the inside is soft and sweet!!

text:
I am shocked!!! First time yelp has pointed us in the wrong direction. This is as gentrified as food can get, as far from asian cuisine as you need. Just an overall disappointing night.

The food was all bland and subpar. We were here for our anniversary cause of the reviews and ratings but man did this hit us hard. Lemongrass coconut soup had no taste of lemongrass, not sure if this was purposeful for the palette of the neighborhood? But it was not good. The pork belly in chili sauce was not tender, it was tough, and lacked depth. It was basically store bought chili poured over pork belly and mixed. Finally the salt and pepper shrimp/squid was so tough and the batter was so mushy. There was barely any salt and pepper flavor. And it was placed on a huge pile of greens, even though there was only a handful of protein. 

The price is way overpriced for the portion size, flavors, and overall experience. We could've gone to Chinatown for half the price and better flavors, we wanted to eXplore and that was our fault. Beware!

Only street parking if you can find any so best to walk, bus, uber. Best of luck, happy eating. We definitely will not be back.

text:
we waited 2.5 hours and honestly, not worth the wait by any means.

the service was great, nice and helpful waiters. 

the food... 
wagyu nigiri - this isn't worth it for the price. i hate that it's not slightly seared, it's ice cold and honestly made my stomach feel funny

bibimbap - we got the wagyu beef bibimbap, it was OK. nothing crazy but had good flavors and was yummy

hot pot - the entry level spicy is SPICY (trust me) stick with that or the medium broth if you're feeling daring. we got a couple of the wagyu beef options and honestly, i can't tell the difference in hot pot between wagyu beef and regular beef. maybe it's just me but i don't think the price point is worth it.
even the vegetables are priced a little higher than most hot pot placed.
the rainbow noodle portion is smalllll. it's a good amount for 2 people but that's it. 

overall, this place is definitely pricier than most and i don't think it's worth it but if you feel more comfortable purchasing wagyu beef i think then it's the place for you

text:
Must try: Tuna Pizza, Lobster Spring Rolls, General Tso Dumplings, Edamame Dumplings, and Lobster Fried Rice!

Why: Unique flavors and dishes! I loved everything we ordered. Tuna Pizza and Lobster Spring Rolls were our appetizers. My friend who doesn't eat raw fish actually loved the Tuna Pizza. There were actually large pieces of lobster in the spring rolls. General Tao Dumplings were tasty and not steaming hot where you burn your mouth. The Edamame Dumplings were actually served cold, which was surprising but they were delicious. The Lobster Fried Rice was also great and was my last bite to end dinner. 

Notes: Pricey, yes! However, this modern Asian cuisine was quite an experience. We came at 7:30pm on a Wednesday night and were seated right away without a reservation. You walk in the dim lit restaurant and immediately see a huge golden buddha statue. The service was incredible from the hostess to the waiter. They were very attentive.

text:
I love this place! This is such a cute spot for date night or dinner with friends. It's mostly dim sum (small plates), but there are regular sized entrees. I only come for the dim sum ‍ Pretty much everything I've tried off the dim sum menu I've enjoyed. Everything is cooked to order, packed with flavor, and good portion sizes (for sharing). Also, the prices are not bad. It's not cheap, but not expensive either.

This is what I've had in preference order:

Mongolian beef dumplings
Cheesesteak Bao
Charred long bean salad
Seafood dumplings
Scarlet dumplings 

I have not had the below items (because I don't eat pork) but my boyfriend enjoyed the following (in preference order):

Pork soup dumplings 
Caterpillar bread 

As far as the service is concerned: it's always good, but I'm going to be honest no one is cheerful and jumping for joy to serve you. In my experience everyone has always been cordial and made sure our order was taken in a timely manner, our water was refilled, and they check in a couple of times. No syrup laid on though. 

This is def one of my fave spots in the city!

text: Imagine being able to get some of the tastiest roast duck in the city for a low price . You can make this a reality by visiting Sui Kee Duck House located at the Southern  Entrance of Philadelphia Chinatown on North 10th Street . This takeout place offered a whole roast duck for $22 . The rice and  vegetables on the side a buck per side . This Fowl had quite crispy skin . The dark meat is  moist surrounded by a sliver of fat creating a slippery succulent sensation with each bite . If you feel the need for more flavor the sauce on the side gives this bird a savory that is something to quack about . In addition to Duck they also sell roasted chicken & pork including cuts like pig ears . The service was friendly and efficient. You can take your duck home whole or cut up .

text:
Stopped in for a quick lunch.

We had the scallion pancakes, shrimp dumpling, pork soup dumplings, and noodles with scallion sauce.

The scallion pancakes were crispy and not greasy at all.  The noodles were thick and covered in sauce.  Definately a dish to share.  The shrimp dumplings were delicately steamed and bursting with filling.  Lastly the soup dumplings were filled with hot broth that pretty much warms your soul and your left with a huge piece of pork filling.

Everything came out hot and fresh.  I especially love how you can see the kitchen quickly pumping out fresh made dumplings. The portions are fair for the price and we spent about $25 on these dishes and still had enough to bring home as leftovers.

The only thing I dont like is they are cash only but have a really nice looking electronic pos system and a tablet.  I get it's the businesses preference but if you have the tech (not just a manual cash register in which case I totally understand) why not use it to its fullest.

text:
I was bringing my mother in law out for dim sum and this place had more vegetarian options than most of the other restaurants in Chinatown so we decided to give it a try. I went to their NYC location and loved it there so had high hopes for this one. The food and service was just ok, while the prices were higher than average. Tea is $1.50 per person but they won't allow you to have different types of tea? So odd. Tea is usually charged by the pot so for 3 people It costs $4.50 for tea and we still couldn't choose more than 1 Kind. I liked that they took reservations on a Saturday afternoon, which is unheard of in other dim sum restaurants in chinatown. 

All of their dim sum dishes are just ok, other places in the area have better variations. The one exception was the snow pea and shrimp dim sum, that was delightful. I tried their famous OG egg roll and it was just ok, nothing to write home about. It tasted good but wasn't amazing. My mother in law ordered the pan fried crispy noodles and it was really just stir fried noodles. The vegetarian dim sum was tasty per my mother in law. 

I would say if you are really jonesing for dim sum and don't want to wait an hour on a weekend in Chinatown, then try here. If not, check out the numerous other options Chinatown and the Northeast have.

text: This place is definitely a hidden gem.  You will be happily surprised after you walk through the very modest entrance.  It is beautiful inside.  I work nearby and picked this place for my monthly lunch with my coworkers.  The have a great lunch special menu.  We ordered the scallion pancakes and they were delicious!  And more than enough for the 3 of us (honestly, we struggled to finish them but did bc we knew we couldn't pack them to-go).  I ordered the shrimp lo mein with a side of chili oil.  It was done perfectly.  You need to come here.  The service was fast and the prices are great.

text:
My girlfriend and I decided to try this place out for post-Valentines day lunch. We had intended on eating at Dim Sum garden next door but given that the line was too long to comprehend we decided to opt for a shorter line Nan Zhou. 
-cash/Venmo/wechat 
-relatively affordable (dumplings, 2 soups ~$27) 
-fast service 
Those would be my main highlights of this visit. As far as taste goes, if you like meat, the soups had plenty of it. The soups were not terrible but also wasn't anything spectacular. We weren't able to finish all of the meat in our soups so I would say the portion size is pretty good. 

Conclusion,
If there was a 3.5 star option I would have chosen this instead. Service was fast, food was affordable but I do feel like the taste wasn't anything exceptional. This is a casual "where-have-we-not-gone-in-a-while lunch"

text: Totally regret walking into this shabby place where foods are insanely overpriced and not worth the wait time. I ordered combo A set, which basically is a small bucket of flavored soup with some teeny tiny pieces of beef tripe, two pinky-sized shrimps, spam {which is definitely not listed. guess it came as a substitute for cabbage??? the server did not notify that ahead nor did she try to ask for our understanding with a sorry, maybe!}along with other cheap veggies like seaweed knot, fried tofu, and shirataki (konjac) noodle in a very stingy amount. If this is not a joke, tell me what it is. Definitely not coming back here even if they decide to increase the portion size or lower the price. That's how bad food tastes in this place. What a total rip off!

text:
Every time I visit Chinatown in Philly, I always want to try a different Chinese dim sum place because I feel like I can get some authentic food for a good price. After some research, I ended up trying out this place. Location is kind of away from everything else but it wasn't a far walk from my hotel. Kind of spacious inside unlike some other Chinese restaurants I've tried in Chinatown. 

I was one of the first customers of the day and got some pork soup dumpling, wonton soup, and sliced pork dish with rice. All of the food was decent, not particularly better than other places I've tried. Read a lot of other good reviews about it so I wanted to give it a try but it wasn't like wow this was one of the best places I've tried but it was certainly good enough for me to want to return. The price is pretty good but the portions weren't that large- which is fine for me because I don't usually eat too much. Either way, thinking about the convenience, speed, dining experience, quality, quantity, and price, I'd say other people should give this place a try too. I'd definitely come back if I am in the area.

text: We were a large group and we went at 4pm when it opened.  Based on the hype, we were expecting great Asian fusion.  Some of the dishes were very good: the edamame dumplings in particular were unique and the pork belly bao was good.  But the rest of our food was just so-so or outright terrible.  For example, the crispy calamari salad was incredibly salty and over dressed.  Same with the Pad Thai noodles with shrimp: the seasoning was just okay but ridiculously salty, like they splashed fish sauce over the whole dish at the end for good measure.  The chicken and ginger dumplings were rubbery and dense and had an unpleasant smell.  The whole duck was good, although, again, the plum sauce was beyond salty.  I am not one of those salt-averse diners.  I love spicy cuisine and eat out a lot.  But Buddakan is way way overrated.  For a quarter of the price, you could go to a decent authentic Chinese restaurant.  The ambiance of the place is way too dark.  Hard to read the menu or even see what you are eating.  And they pipe in this loud, relentless, bass-heavy Asian techno music that makes it hard to ignore.  So, overall, Buddakan is over-priced, completely mediocre-to-bad Asian fusion.  Some dishes were indeed excellent but the large portion of our dinner was awful.  Atmosphere was frustrating with the music and poor lighting, although the giant Buddha was impressive.  This restaurant definitely has "corporate" by design written all over it.  The food has no soul.

text:
Amazing food for an amazing price. I've been to Penang countless times because they serve large portions of delicious food for a very reasonable price.

I always order the beef noodles and the roti canai! That is more than enough for dinner and some leftovers to take home. 

The roti canai is made fresh to order! It is just the right amount of crispy and flaky to pair with the chicken curry dip. You cannot go wrong with ordering this appetizer! 

As for the beef stir fry noodles, you will get a plate bigger than your face! If you were to order one plate and two appetizers, it would be the perfect amount of food for two. 

Besides the food, there is the decors! The place has a boat like vibe with the hostess dresses in a qipao. You have the option of ice water or hot tea! Get the tea, and they will bring you a mini kettle.

text:
Dim Sum Garden has huge soup dumplings!! Love love love their soup dumplings here. Was my second time here, first time I went for a late lunch/early midweek dinner around 4pm and it was dead. This time we arrived at 2pm, and it was much busier. We didn't wait long at all for a table or for food. Staff here turns around tables quickly. Good value for the prices here too. 

Note, this place is cash only, there is an ATM at the front door if you forget cash.

text:
Finally reopened and we are pleased.Just as we thought to try this place out last fall they closed for post fire repairs,remodeling.Saturday nite the 15th was only their second day in operation,and while they told me they were still smoothing out a few rough spots I never noticed. It was busy that evening and I sat at the bar.The guests to my right and left indicated that they were enjoying their meals and made a few suggestions. The bar tender Mitzi was also very helpful.I started with the scallion pancakes,they were very good,followed by the spicy soup dumplings,Mitzi recommended them and they were delicious.For a small entree I had the Double Cooked ,with pork , it comes with a bowl of rice and I have to say it was fantastic.I drank TsingTao with the three courses and was pleasantly full.The beer and wine list is adequate and suites the menu. Mitzi recommended the Egg Custard Bun for dessert and that was a mistake,MY mistake it was wonderful but I barley had room for it.
The menu is a picture book with brief narratives,a separate price sheet is provided so you can keep track of the courses you order.The nice thing was that the food when presented looked exactly like the pictures.
We are already planning our next visit,and its close to home so no,drive,Huber or taxi needed!
Try it you may like it !!

text:
Food: I got the Char Siu Pan Fried Noodles. The portion size was HUGE. I honestly don't think this was meant for one person... it took a lot of time and willpower to finish it. In terms of taste, it wasn't too bad. The noodles were fine and there was a decent amount of meat and broccoli. The flavors didn't really jump out to me though, and it got a little tiring after a bit. 

Service/Environment: The service wasn't too bad; my order took the longest out of our party of six, but it wasn't excruciatingly long. The restaurant was kind of small, but we didn't really have any issues with finding a place to sit. 

Price: For the amount of food that you're getting, it was pretty cheap. I was barely able to finish my dish, and didn't spend more than $13 for it. 

Overall: Not a bad place, though I would probably look around for other restaurants in the area before coming here. If you want to eat a lot for a fairly cheap price, this might be somewhere you want to consider.

text:
I love this place! This is such a cute spot for date night or dinner with friends. It's mostly dim sum (small plates), but there are regular sized entrees. I only come for the dim sum ‍ Pretty much everything I've tried off the dim sum menu I've enjoyed. Everything is cooked to order, packed with flavor, and good portion sizes (for sharing). Also, the prices are not bad. It's not cheap, but not expensive either.

This is what I've had in preference order:

Mongolian beef dumplings
Cheesesteak Bao
Charred long bean salad
Seafood dumplings
Scarlet dumplings 

I have not had the below items (because I don't eat pork) but my boyfriend enjoyed the following (in preference order):

Pork soup dumplings 
Caterpillar bread 

As far as the service is concerned: it's always good, but I'm going to be honest no one is cheerful and jumping for joy to serve you. In my experience everyone has always been cordial and made sure our order was taken in a timely manner, our water was refilled, and they check in a couple of times. No syrup laid on though. 

This is def one of my fave spots in the city!

text:
Great happy hour!! 
Came in and had a drink (Strawberry Smash) as well as happy hour cucumbers and dan dan noodles.
You cannot beat the price of the food as well as the portions. It was very tasty. The cucumber was crisp, sweet, salty and spicy. Very well balanced, and only four bucks! The pork dan dan noodles were amazing. Only five bucks, and could feed 3-4 people for a nice snack. The drink was delicious. Not overly sweet, with fresh strawberries. 
Cocktails not on the happy hour menu are slightly overpriced in my opinion. But the food was excellent.
