text: I lived in the neighborhood for over ten years. It was good and it seemed pretty clean. As time went on, that seemed to change. Their prices went up. They have more restrictions like the atm minimum, the main space has gone downhill, they mainly deal with take out, and the young people they have dealing with the customers are just plain rude. All the while I'll see the the owner's son showing up to work in a nice Mercedes SUV. Clean the f-ing bathroom!? There bathroom is filthy. They have cockroach traps out in plain site in the bathroom. And they have an aquarium right inside the entry that has could give James Cameron's underwater explorations a run for his money. Not surprisingly they were closed down last year for health code violations. It wasn't long that they were back at it again. I'd stay away from this place if you want to maintain your health. It was alright while it lasted but the owner and his family needs to put some time and money back into this place and have some effing respect for their community and customers!

text: They serve different types of soup with rich flavor. Be warned that some of them are really spicy. The soup is authentic so becareful with the spiciness if you are not mala lovers (i think its called 'Red' something). Food here is nice, especially for some hotpot dishes that are marinated really well even small pieces of meat are rich of flavor. Price wise, it is not cheap. However, generally speaking, hot pot restaurants are more expensive compared to other cuisine. So, the bigger the group, the better, as you can share diverse food and the cost. Tiny restaurant feel cozy and great atmosphere, service was good. We'll be back :)
categories: Hot Pot, Restaurants, Chinese

text: I come here all the time. I like their Singapore noodles, shrimp broccoli, dumplings and wings. The place inside doesn't look clean, that's what you should expected from most Chinese takeout restaurants anyway. However, the lady is so friendly and nice. Last time I didn't have enough coin for another 20cents she lets me go. She said I always come here and she remembered me. Their prices are so cheap and they gave you so much food. An order of Singapore noodles can feed the whole family of 4 people. The best Singapore noodles ever!!!

text:
I was so hungry for Chinese food- but my hair was wet- no makeup and impatient- so I stopped here. THE WORST! For starters the woman at the window seemed unable to explain the platters, costs, etc. There's qalways something wrong I think when they say- drive around and I'll tell you your total. 
But it would still have been okay if the food was decent.  It was not.
Despite my sudden Chinese urge- the food was practically inedible and the portions so sparse I thought when I got home it must have been a mistake.
Way too little food for the 13.95 I paid for one beef broccoli, one eggroll and a Sprite. The beef broccoli was much less than a cup- tons of rice- and worst of all the very flavors seemed infused in everything!  Too much ginger and sesame oil!  Little by way of any other flavor. The roll dumped on top of the whole deal which was truly laughable- the size of it.
Below is what was left after I consumed 2 pieces of Broccoli and around half of an eggroll!

text:
Everything A5 Wagyu? What? Not sure if that's 100% true, but what I am 100% sure about is that their beef is boss. The flavors are amazing and make the wait worth it. The waiting can be ridiculous, so plan ahead especially if you have a large group. I got on the waitlist on Yelp, but still waited like an hour for a party of 3! Be strategic.

If you're not a hot pot fan, there are rice dishes you can get instead, which is what I did. Your bill can rack up fast because of the high prices--it makes sense if they're using that A5 Wagyu for everything. Items I got that you should definitely not miss out on:

1) Aburi Wagyu Foie Gras Nigiri - awesome smoky presentation and the beef melts in your mouth
2) Foir Gras Truffle Kobe Bibimbap - mixed tableside in a stone pot

I tried some other menu items, but the above 2 items were the highlights of my meal. I'm trying to eat less red meat, but that rule goes out the window when I'm at delicious restaurants like Chubby Cattle.

text:
Mixed feelings about this place - in many ways, the space and decor seems like an ideal place for hosting large events, especially if you want a festive Chinese feel to it. On the other hand, I think their pricing seems questionable, and I felt rather duped during my dining experience here. 

For starters, their food is meh. But what was worse is that for the dinner event being hosted at the Asian Palace, the meal was advertised as an 8-course meal (you think wow!) and then you find out it's really more like 4 large dishes that they bring out one at a time (what in the world). They included cut up oranges as part of their 8 courses for "dessert" (um, excuse me?). One of the "courses" was rice, and another "course" was rice crackers (o.o). Many of us at the table were definitely still hungry by the end of the meal. 

Oh another funny part of the story, dumplings were supposed to be served as part of the "course menu" and somehow it just got skipped. At the end of the meal, when our table asked why we had never got dumplings, they said sorry there isn't any left (I think maybe two or three other tables had gotten dumplings earlier on). We were not happy as we were still hungry, and then all of a sudden the server was like, "actually wait, let me check" and goes back to the kitchen. Literally 2 minutes later, they come out with multiple plates and plates of hot steaming dumplings for the different tables. Were they just lying to us before? Clearly they had cooked and ready but was just going to bypass it for some unbeknownst reason. 

I personally had a great evening with friends, as the dinner event was hosted through a school program, but the cost + food + service left much wanting in my opinion.

text:
Jane G's rebranded to Dim Sum House and reopened on Valentine's Day, 2020. This review is a bit belated as I went about 10 days ago, the day after the grand re-opening. 

The interior looks largely the same, while the menu got a total makeover. Gone are the $35 unlimited hot pot and Sichuan dishes, replaced by dim sum. I would have liked to see a few more traditional dishes, but it had most of the major stuff catering to a Rittenhouse crowd. (The prices were in Rittenhouse dollars as well.)

We ordered a few different dishes: hot and sour soup, turnip cake, scallion pancakes, Brussels sprouts (why were these on a dim sum menu?), fried dumplings, crab and pork soup dumplings, and pork belly with mustard greens, which came with a side of rice. 

I knocked off a star because while most dishes were good, the turnip cake was a total miss - quite a bit overdone. I didn't find anything particularly memorable that I would come back for. We did experience quite a few issues with ordering as the kitchen had run out of a few items due to reopening the day before; I completely understand but the issue was that our server (while very nice) was not prepared with this info and had to keep coming back to us to let us know the kitchen was missing something, after we had already ordered. 

Overall, Dim Sum House has a few kinks to work out but it is nice to have them reopen with an Asian option in the neighborhood.

text: There are so many options to choose from food-wise from Reading Terminal Market, and it is hard to distinguish between good food and great food there. Sang Kee Peking Duck would fall under the good food category. The food itself came out very quickly, and the staff was very efficient in fulfilling a very long and hungry line of people's orders. Though the food was a little cold upon receiving it, the dish itself was flavorful and filling. The roast duck is the namesake of the restaurant and it does not disappoint. It is dense, greasy, tasty, traditional goodness and worth trying. Also, the prices are fair and you can get a decently portioned meal for under $10.

text:
Located conveniently in Chinatown, there's so many options at this restaurant! We were seated promptly and were brought complimentary hot tea, which warmed us up from the cold weather outside. 

I ordered the spicy braised beef noodle soup with shaved noodles. We also ordered steamed pork and chives dumplings and the house combination noodle soup with shaved noodles. 

I LOVED the shaved noodles! The server recommended we pick that one if we liked chewier noodles. The broth was very flavorful and had an abundant amount of noodles, veggies, and meat. The broth wasn't as spicy as I thought it would be, but it was still good. The house combo noodle soup had a lot of meat so if you like meat, definitely get this one. My favorite were the meatballs in this dish, they were so soft and tender. 

The pork and chives dumplings were super plump and their filling tasted delicious paired with the sauce. 

I'd highly recommend this place to anyone looking to eat authentic Chinese noodles at a very, very reasonable cost! Price was low and the portions were huge. 

One odd thing was the method of payments, be prepared to bring cash or if you have Venmo/Wechat then that works but they don't take card.

text:
Solid meals every time! 

I love how affordable and yummy it is here :) My friends and I often default to this spot when we're in Chinatown for a number of reasons. 1) it's accommodating of larger groups (fits up to around 12 on their main large round tables) and smaller groups alike. 2) They're open from breakfast till late evening, so you could literately eat any meal there. 3) You get a solid meal for $8. It used to be cash only, but I think they take card if you order more than $15 or something (may want to verify this though!). 4) They offer great take-out and service is fast for sit-down, even though they're not always the most attentive. You're not going for a high class experience but their service suits the casual everyday occasions. Also very helpful if you can actually speak Chinese as the servers are more comfortable in Chinese (so I love going with my Chinese-speaking friends). 5) They have plenty of simple yet yummy dishes, but also offer enough options that you can try something new. The classic options would be your choice of two meats over rice or noodle. My most consistent order is probably roast pig and duck over noodle.

Pro tip: there's an actual difference between roast pork and roast pig. The roast pig has a crispy skin layer and juicy meat, while the roast pork is more seasoned and has a slight chewy texture.

text:
It's called a Duck House so of course we had to get the duck! We came in for an early Sunday lunch and were seated promptly. We were given complimentary hot tea.

We ordered the duck wonton noodle soup and the charsiu pork and roasted duck rice plate. Everything tasted delicious! The duck wonton noodle soup tasted rich and warm and the noodles were super soft. The wontons were plentiful as well. 

As for the charsiu and roasted duck rice plate, this hit the spot. The charsiu pork and duck were perfectly cooked and seasoned. The duck skin was glistening and crispy and had a ton of meat. The rice plate also had some Chinese broccoli. 

We saw another table get the duck roll so we also got that but I wouldn't recommend it since it's about almost half the price of a 1/4 duck plate. It was good, but I wished it had more veggies in it... It just wasn't worth it in my opinion.

I would highly recommend getting any of the duck dishes and maybe a side order of just the duck! The duck is so meaty and cooked to perfection, you won't be disappointed!

text:
Came here [finally] for restaurant week after being in Philly for over 25 years.   I honestly adored the presentation but was seriously underwhelmed by the flavor.   Here's what I had:

-Chicken & Ginger Dumplings
Sesame soy dipping sauce
-Wok Cashew Chicken
Plum wine sauce
-Chocolate Mint Cake
Devil's food cake, mint ganache, lemongrass sauce

The dumplings were the best of the trio.  The cashew chicken was extremely flavorless and I was quite surprised.   The mint cake had nice flavor balance but it didn't seem to pull together well for me.

I'm going to give them another try in hopes that I change my mind but there are so many wonderful Asian restaurants with GREAT food and economical prices it's hard to settle for something that's just "okay," even if it's a totally posh ambiance.

text:
We went around 6-7 on a Thursday and it seemed not really busy so if you ever want to come here with seating I recommend a weekday. They sat us really quickly and the waiter was super nice and kept checking up. 

I ordered the roast duck and roast pig we ordered were considered appetizers but they gave us such LARGE portions. The roast pork skin was so crispy and juicy I highly recommend it. We also ordered the roasted duck with noodles and wontons. I didn't think they'd give us so much duck in the noodles so next time I won't order duck appetizer since they gave so much. The short rib pan friend noodles were SOO crispy and the sauce was perfect. The dish itself was very large and I think it can be shared with at 4 people max. The cost of all of the food was so super reasonable for the amount and taste. The total was under $40 for two with tax. For the amount you get and the price I would definitely come back because it tasted so good.

text: My friend is a huge fan of Nom Wah and brought me here tonight. It was yummy! We each ordered a soup and shared several plates: the cilantro scallion rice rolls, stuffed eggplant, pork sui mai. The cilantro scallion rice rolls and pork sui mai were my favorites! The baby bok choy in my soup was fresh and wonderful. Really, all the food was fresh and tasty. The servings were all decent sizes and filling. The service was good and the bathroom and restaurant were clean. I will definitely return! Oh, and the prices were great! Less than $35 for our meal and tip! Awesome!

text:
A nice spot for a well-made, upscale meal! 

Ambiance: 
Wm Mulerhin's manages to create an upscale, rustic atmosphere that makes you feel like you're dining in a wealthy relative's cabin as opposed to a restaurant. The roaring fire-place and leather couches in the dining room that are often filled with bar patrons make you forget that you're right under the El in Fishtown. The whole thing feels very upscale and cozy, albeit a bit loud with the proximity of the tables and the fact that there is not a clear distinction between the bar and dining room. 

Food: 
I'll start by saying I've never eaten anything bad here - everything they made is well executed and has come out flawless every time. Their kitchen definitely knows what they're doing and holds themselves to a high standard which shows the caliber of the restaurant and the attention to detail. The first time I came here several months ago I struggled to find something I liked on the menu - though now they've updated to feature a lot more dishes that I enjoy. My advice is to check out the menu ahead of time to make sure there are dishes that call out to you - while they do a great job of cooking not all of the dishes match my personal tastes. As this is an Italian restaurant, they offer a lot of seafood options and it seems to me there are several vegetarian and vegan options available as well. 

Stand-outs for me are the brocolli rabe appetizer and the hanger and eggs for brunch - I don't normally like over easy eggs but they do them so well here I have to order it. 

Drinks: 
Much like the kitchen - the bar here knows what they're doing and their cocktails are spot on in terms of balance and flavor. You can't go wrong here ordering a cocktail you like. The selection of beer and wine are standard Italian fare. They do not seem to have an extensive wine cellar or wine by the bottle offerings which may deter some folks, though I'm sure all of their wine by the glass can be purchased by the bottle as well even though not explicitly quoted on the menu. 

Service:
While it's clear the servers here are pulled from top notch establishments and have knowledge of the menu, the overall service lacks the refinement of a five-star establishment. My drinks tend to sit empty here for several minutes before being topped off and the little touches such as being offered spreads for my croissant or a steak knife are lacking unless I explicitly ask. For some of you this won't bother you, but I was a bit disappointed as having to go back and forth with the wait-staff can throw off the pace of a meal a good bit. That said - the service is definitely good and friendly. 

Value:
Why 4 stars? Everything is good here and well-made, however Wm Mulerhins lacks the magic to make this a 5 star experience. While I've never had a bad experience I've also never felt compelled to rave about this place to my friends either or to bring guests from out of town - it's kind of just a nice spot to eat when I don't feel like going to Center City. Some dishes are better value than others, but ultimately it's comparable if a little bit less than center city prices which is fine for what they offer and the neighborhood. I would say go value-wise, but for the reasons described not a place that I would use for a special occasion.

text: This restaurant should be rated among Philadelphia's best. These are fresh noodles, made on the premises using a centuries old method. The soup broths are exquisite. Service is quick and efficient. The noodles can be long and thin (it's fascinating to watch them make them) - called "la mien," or thick - sliced from the dough "dou shou mien" (fascinating to watch the chef slice them into the broth). Prices are modest - my wife and I eat there often, and generally pay less than $20 - for both of us! I've seen some of the Pho restaurants and some of the new age ramen joints given high ratings by the local media. In my opinion they don't compare. This is the real deal - try it!
name_x: Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House

text:
My family and I had a reservation on Christmas Day for 7 people. The place was PACKED at 6pm. 
The ambience was hip and it seemed like a great place to hang out with friends.

Service was ok for a super busy night. 

Food: Everything is family style so order according to how hungry everyone at your table is.

General Tso Soup Dumpling: I love soup dumplings. This was... ok. I wouldn't get it again and pay for it myself, but if someone else got it/paid for it, I wouldn't mind eating it. 

Shrimp Dumpling: The traditional har gow is 20000x better. I get that this is a fusion place, so I shouldn't complain too much. 

Beef Chow Fun: The best dish we got. Can't really screw this one up. The beef was tender and the noodles were perfectly chewy (not overcooked). 

Lobster Fried Rice: It was ok. Yea, that's all I have to say. 

Peking Duck: Another dish that you can't really screw up. Loved the crispy skin and the sauces that came with. 

Dim Sum sampler: Two each of chicken & ginger, shrimp, pork, edamame dumplings. The edamame was.... interesting. It's a paste consistency .... like red bean paste buns. 


So as you can probably guess, my experience of the food was meh. The price was just waaaay to expensive for the quality of the food. I think they charge more for the experience and the hip ambience. Would not come again if it was my own money. And if someone else was paying, I'd suggest few other places first. Go for the ambience, the drinks, and the "young" vibe, not for the food.

text:
Sichuanese food has really taken off in recent years, gaining popularity beyond Chinatown, but Sichuanese stalwart E Mei remains one of the best, most authentic options in Philly. 

There are dishes that you can't find elsewhere, like the salty egg yolk tofu with shrimp (咸蛋黄虾仁豆腐), an addictive combination of rich egg yolk with silky tofu in a sunny yellow dish. There are the staple Sichuanese dishes, like the wonderfully crunchy Chongqing spicy chicken (重庆辣子鸡, sometimes called "dry pepper chicken"), the dan dan noodles (担担面, much more authentic than the peanut buttery versions found at more Americanized joints), and whole fish in hot bean paste (豆瓣鲜鱼), which is one of the tastier renditions of the dish I've had in a while, though I would have liked it served over a warming candle to prevent the sauce from congealing. 

Large portions of generally delicious food coupled with attentive service and clean, modern decor (with maybe the comfiest dining chairs I've ever encountered in Chinatown) make the dining experience at E Mei worth the higher price tag.

text:
We are quite happy with the whole experience at Chubby Cattle. Our server Angel was nice, professional, and he was easy going but proficient. Yes, the price was hefty, but considering it was a meal largely consisted with wagyu beef, it was actually reasonable for the amount of food they serve. There was good variety of sides, although I wish they would offer more veggies on the conveyor belt. 

One thing to note is that they offer buy 1 get 1 with a review written. This review was written because of the deal, but I was probably going to write a review anyways. They did not specify how we want to write the review, and I was honest with what I wrote.

text: A little run down but so much fun! We went here for my birthday and got a private Karaoke room and it was amazing! The staff was incredible and super accommodating. They allowed us to bring our own cake which was so nice! There is a call button in the room to order food and drinks. I was shocked at how affordable it was for the number of people we had and amount of time we spent there! I already can't wait to go back again! If you are looking for a fun place to celebrate or just a great night out with friends definitely check it out. The private rooms are a huge plus and so much fun to just let lose around your friends!

text:
This review is for an Uber Eats order which I have had massive trouble with. I highly, highly, highly recommend you do not use Uber Eats (The prices of the menu are higher then the normal prices on the restaurants menu and they will actually charge you even if the Uber Eats delivery person cancels your order).

That being said the review detailed below is unbiased from the Uber Eats delivery that took place for this order and is soley based on the food.

Steamed Pork Soup Dumplings - These were decent I would rate slighly below Dim Sum Garden quality which is the barometer that all Dim Sum is measured by in my opinion. Comes with not soy sauce but a sweeter verison of soy sauce I want to say.

Shanghai Shumai - Well this item was very different. Had rice in it and a sticky like substance - first time I have tried this item and I appreciate the dish but I would not get again. The color of the food dye or whatever is in the item makes the Shumai appear blood red.

Shrimp Lo Mein - A fair amount of shrimp. The noodles to me tasted thicker and more starchy then other Lo Mein dishes I am used to however it is not oily / greasy like most places that serve Lo Mein so it's a catch 22 depending on your preference. For the record I did enjoy this lo mein quite a bit but cannot indulge in such a high carb item often. 

I will give them another chance and visit in person but perhaps my taste buds are just changing and I can't deal with the sodium in these types of foods.

text: I came here with a group of friends back during restaurant week in the fall. I had heard a lot of good things about it but frankly, the food was quite underwhelming. I also had terrible luck and managed to order the things on the menu with the smallest portion sizes. I had the yellowtail sashimi and the honey walnut shrimp. The sashimi was nothing special and a little salty for my taste. The shrimp was good, but you only get 6 of them so it was not filling at all for the steep price. I was honestly very excited to have the Dip Sum donuts for dessert as I had heard a lot about them. The donuts themselves were a little hard and quite dense, so I didn't really enjoy them.

text:
Been here a few times. I think this place was alright. It is definitely authentic, where they still push the carts around. Definitely able to get the dishes you can get in Hong Kong (my parents are HKers, I lived in HK for 2 years). Nowadays, HK dim sum has become so fancy. This restaurant is not that kind of place. This kind of dim sum takes you to the classic shrimp dumpling, siu mai, spareribs, sticky rice, turnip cake, etc. They also have classic native HK dim sum dishes like chinese donut wrapper in rice sheets, various congee, and bean curd chicken/mushroom wraps (dunno what they are called in english).  While you can get all of these dishes, I think they lack in quality. It's missing the freshness that you would get as compared to another place. The rice sheets are too thick and the shrimp dumpling has too thick of skin. Some of the fried items are not as fresh when I get them, and sometimes tastes like they were fried twice after not being sold the day before (or earlier that day). 

I speak to the workers in Cantonese, but the service has not been bad when I've gone. Always been able to sit down pretty quickly. They accept credit card there, but I think they charge a fee for it (which I never know about). Overall, the price of it was not too bad. It may be a little bit more costly, but for the variety that me and a friend had, it was only $15/person. 

I will check out other places and will continue to update the ranking of this dim sum place compared to the others in Philly.

text: I ordered Panda Express through Postmates on Saturday. I was planning to order a medium orange chicken, but it was actually slightly cheaper to order 2 smalls. I also ordered some fried rice. All together the food cost $15 and change, and didn't include the deli and tip. I personally thought that was high for Chinese food. Anyway, the food came quickly and was really good! The chicken could have used a bit more sauce, it was a little on the dry side, but still crunchy and flavorful! The fried rice was perfect after I added some kikoman! Overall, food was very good, just pricey for fast food Chinese.

text:
Food: Three words: authentic, delicious, fulfilling. We got their MaLa (Spicy Peppercorn) flavor Catfish Fish-Pot with add-ons. Although this restaurant is definitely more expensive than your local eats, it is worth the experience and affordable to share with friends. Their MaLa flavor is genuine in that it doesn't taste like the instant hot-pot MaLa paste. There's plenty of peppercorn to give your mouth a numb, tingling sensation. The catfish was fried crispy on the outside edges, and yet tender on the inside. One order comes with 2-3 servings of rice, however additional servings/refills cost $2 each, which is the same price per add-ons. Pickled radish/edamame are served as side dishes.

Service: The service wasn't on par with the food's excellence. The servers were impatient and submissive upon placing orders and refused to give us proper seatings upon request considering it was not a busy night. 

Atmosphere: The interior is beautiful and clean. Seatings offer booth or chair-table sets, with the back reserved for larger parties.

text:
Well, well, well...a new restaurant in Rittenhouse area and let me tell you something one of their dishes blew me away. 

Shrimp Siu Mai - $12 for eight extremely well portioned Shrimp with a Pea on top, thats right a Pea. I mean it works!! I believe this is defined as one of the Cantonese big three staple items and my god it blew me away like no other. Please if you are a fan of Shrimp get this item ASAP!!

Beef-Stuffed Scallion Pancakes - Three servings of this dish and it is quite good. Fried all be it but different and not bad. My one qualm is no sauces were given to me in my entire order but I am assuming was by mistake you can't deliver these two items without sauces and expect to get five stars???

Shanghai Wonton Soup - $8.00 wonton soup. I knew I was getting ripped off when I ordered this but really wanted soup. DO NOT GET THIS. You will be disappointed. Not even good, was a very big let down but I think the restaurant knows what its doing and making a great profit on people that really want soup as this is the cheapest verison of wonton soup they offer.

Eggplant Garlic Sauce - I literally own a mug that says give me eggplant or give me death so one of the things I can do is critique eggplant dishes. This dish has a wonderful amount of spice, not too much but bordering on too much spice for the casual diner. I really enjoyed this dish but it was not great when reheated.

Based all my first experience here I would defintely be up for a visit once the COVID-19 Pandemic is over....I am just hopping it is BYOB as this order cost me over $51 for one person worth of take out.

As always people SYOY!!!

text:
Sampan is my go-to spot for happy hours and hanging out! The foods and drinks that are offered during happy hours are so fairly price and taste great! You have to come when it opens otherwise, it gets full super quick especially at the graffiti bar.

I usually get a specialty cocktail which varies throughout each week. My favorite happy hour foods are the edamame dumplings, kimchi fried rice, pork bao, and chicken wings. There are some misses such as the tofu taco, Brussels sprouts were a bit salty. This time I have to say the foods are a bit oily but would totally come back again!

text:
During this time of social distancing, I've been digging back into my archives to find places I haven't reviewed yet that may offer takeout, and I can't believe I haven't reviewed Nom Wah yet. This review is long overdue: I absolutely adore Nom Wah.  In my opinion, it's the best dim sum place in the city. Every time I've gone, I've gotten stellar service. Most of the time, my party gets seated right away but I know on the weekends obviously this place can get a little busy so I'd make a reservation.

My usual order is the scallion pancakes, the steamed lotus leaf rice, turnip cakes, pork soup dumplings, pork siu mai, and I try to order a couple of new things to try every time I visit too. Last time, I ordered to try the tofu skin rolls and curry dumplings (unfortunately no picture of the lotus leaf rice and curry dumplings, I was way too excited to wait and I just dug into those!)

Everything is such high quality, served piping hot, and just really delicious. I feel like I can order anything off the menu and it won't disappoint.  I've taken countless friends here, and no one has ever had a bad experience.  Unfortunately this place is not a cart dim sum place, you check off what you'd like to order a la carte. Everything is reasonably priced I'd say, and if you are craving dim sum during this time, I would highly recommend you give them a call and try to get something for takeout / delivery.

text: The food is delicious. They give out very good portions at affordable prices.  The wonton soup is very good and has big meaty wontons, and lots of pork slices, in a hearty broth. text:
My fiance and are fans of Buddakan in regular times, but they really impressed us two weeks ago with the quality of their COVID-19 dinner delivery.  Like lower-end Asian fare, the meal travels and reheats well -- but unlike lower-end Asian fare, Buddakan's delivery dinner feels luxurious and special even without being in the restaurant's cool space.  We ordered lobster fried rice, cashew chicken, dumplings, and spring rolls and agreed it was easily one of the best takeout/delivery meals we've enjoyed since Philadelphia shut down in mid-March.

The only downsides were one of the longest wait times (over an hour) and highest price tags (over $100) we've experienced while the shutdown order has been in effect.  But, as we millennials like to say: #worthit.

text:
I came back and they raised the price on the Shangai wonton soup now its over $9 and the best thing I had ordered from them the Shrimp Siu Mai got slashed from an order of 8 pieces to only 4?? Whammy and not the good kind.

That being said they just have some unique items on there menu that I will be back to try. Like the Shrimp Cheung Fun, I never heard of such a thing and now must try on my next round from this space.

Spicy Shrimp Dumplings- too spicy for me. I thought it was interesting the dumpling was orange colored no doubt for the heat it brought.

Chicken Shiitake Dumplings - I couldn't really taste the Shittake in it but these pretty above average and would recommend.

Dan Dan Noodles- Ahh, whats there to say about Dan Dan Noodles...I do not get this item often but you can get it tailored by a spice level from 1 to 5 when ordering it and it was okay. I order about once every few years and this one had a ton of peanut oil on it and very tiny minced beef.

text:
Very nice decor and modern. It's defiantly a place that you can't miss as you walk around Chinatown. The staff are attentive and the food comes out in a reasonable time.

When you order food from here I feel like it could be very much a miss or hit depending on your palate. The shrimp, double cooked pork, and dumplings were amazing! Savory with just the right amount of sauce to not overpower or make the food slimy. The stir fried radish with egg can be a pretty big miss for some. They use the yolk of salted eggs to make it creating a very meat and savory flavor with a slight gritty texture.

Overall for me it was a decent meal. Very filling and lots of food. The price wasn't too bad either. A great place to come and try out once in a while.

text:
If you're looking for solid, budget-friendly takeout Chinese food, this is your spot. Especially during the current covid-19 crisis - they have takeout and delivery available with easy and safe pickup.

Over the past few years, I have been there somewhere between 10 and 20 times, and I've always been happy with my order. The restaurant itself is not in the greatest condition, so I recommend takeout or delivery. They have a very user friendly website for ordering, which I appreciate for ease, especially right now.

Yes, this place isn't fancy, but the food is consistently good, they have great prices, and they are reliable in the sense that my orders are always correct and made on time.

I recommend the wonton soup, chicken and broccoli, any of the lo mein, and the fried chicken wings. My boyfriend loves these even though they are most definitely not Chinese food :)

I will keep supporting this business knowing they are working hard to make good, affordable food, especially during this time!

text: We ordered the sauteed baby bok choi, stir-fried baby shrimp ho fun, and roast duck over rice.  They all cost about $13, which is high for these items compared to a typical Chinatown restaurant.  I hoped that the price would suggest that the items would be above-average, but they were below-average.  The duck was dry and flavorless, the baby bok choi didn't have enough sauce, and the shrimp noodles were monolithic and boring.  While beggars can't be choosers during COVID-19, I miss getting quality Cantonese food from Sang Kee Duck House, Shing Kee, and Ting Wong.

text:
Outside: Classic Downtown Restaurant
Inside: Traditional Chinese Hot Pot
Food: Hot Pot Buffet
Service: Pretty Chinese
Price: $25pp - AYCE

Little Sheep is a chain out of China that does Mongolian style hot pot. If you don't know what that is, it's basically Chinese fondue. You order your dishes raw and then cook them in communally shared pots of broth - with some variation on flavors available.

I love hot pot, and Little Sheep delivers. It is not 100% authentic but it is also not the westernized kind of Chinese food you may be used to so if you are unfamiliar with hot pot, come in with an open mind. If you expect general tso's chicken and crab rangoons you are likely to be disappointed.

The buffet consists of lots of food, mostly veggies and tofu that you can add to your pot but you will also have a chance to order specialty meats to be delivered (raw) to your table. Try everything. Especially the fish balls stuffed with roe. Absolutely delicious!

Now, you may have seen that I mentioned the service was "pretty Chinese" let me explain that in China you do not get the same kind of service as in America. The waitresses don't check in on you and ask how things are or if you need a drink refill. In china, when you want service, you literally just shout "WAITRESS!!!" and a server comes to your table. Little sheep is perhaps a hair more attentive than this but be prepared to flag someone down when you want something. 

There is a lot of great food in Philly, especially in this part of Philly and Little Sheep is a great experience. But $25 feels a little pricey to me. I've also been to this location on several occasions and found that when they switched to the buffet style, the selection and quality suffered a bit. That isn't to say the place isn't fantastic, it IS! But as someone who went there before the change, I preferred ordering everything from the table and the change causes me to rate a star lower.

If you've never had hot pot, Little Sheep is a great place to try it for the first time. And if you have, it's still a great place to get your fix. Check this place out. You won't be disappointed.

text:
M Kee is my favorite traditional spot to eat in Chinatown compared to the other traditional restaurants around. The food selection has everything you're looking for in one spot. It always tastes great and also is a bit less costly compared to other restaurants with the same items. This spot doesn't have anything special or fancy about it. Just straight up amazing traditional Chinese food. 

My top picks would be the Crispy roast pork, Roast duck noodle soup, Roast pork pan fried noodles and the Walnut Shrimp.

text:
I happen to give this place a try since I had called a couple of my normal Chinese takeout locations and they weren't picking up. (Closed during the COVID-19 pandemic?)
     It was quick to order over the phone, and while not a large order, they said it would only be 10 minutes for pickup.
     I got there later than I had expected, but they were ready and friendly. They're set up so you don't have to walk in right now, just a table at the door where they set up the interaction. The woman at the counter put on a mask and gloves (disposable, so she's changing out gloves each time) to bring my order and change.
     Food was your typical Chinese takeout. I'll admit I was starving and went right through my shrimp with broccoli combo platter. My wife had chicken lo mein which seemed a little under seasoned, but better to be able to add soy sauce/seasoning/salt then being too salty to start. Pan fried pork dumplings were good as well as my wonton soup. Though I left my egg roll until last, it wasn't greasy. I also got a beef and broccoli combo to have for lunch today.
     Basic Chinese takeout, quick service, and fairly reasonable prices.

text:
Solid Philly dim sum tucked into Chinatown! I definitely can't say it's the best dim sum I've ever had in my entire life, but it's enjoyable and the prices are fair. Service was standard, and the restaurant itself has a homey vibe to it. Keep in mind it's cash only, but they do have an ATM inside. I was seated immediately on a walk-in basis on a Monday morning. I also did takeout on another occasion.

I had the Shanghai crabmeat and pork soup dumplings, Yeung Chow fried rice and shrimp dumplings. The soup dumplings were probably my favorite, because the broth was quite flavorful. The shrimp dumplings were solid, not necessarily better than the next dim sum spot's; they're just standard. The fried rice was also not standout but not bad. 

Overall a very safe place to go to for dim sum on the east coast.

The food is so greasy yet the portion is so freaking small. I can even get a bigger chicken pot if I go to any other restaurant for half the price. 
This place is robbing the customers. DO NOT TRUST other reviews, because the restaurant gave MONEY TO INFLUENCERS to get good reviews. But the food tastes so greasy and costs so much.

text:
The first couple of times I went to Sang Kee I was disappointed. I'd lived in China for five years and fallen in love with Beijing/Peking Duck in that time. When I moved back, this was presented to me as the spot to go for said dish. And they do carry it, which is more than I can say for the majority of roast duck spots in Philly Chinatown, which roast it normally, but then primarily serve it on rice platters or, at best, in bao buns. Sang Kee does it right in that regard - you get dozens of thin slices of duck, spring onion stalks, sweet bean sauce, and wraps/"pancakes" to use as your delivery method, taco style. It mildly disappointed me that they don't give cucumber stalks along with the spring onion, but my main issue was the wraps - they're so much larger and starchier than basically any others I've ever had! And so, while I was happy it had introduced some of my friends to the idea of the dish, I always rolled my eyes a bit like the pain-in-the-rear China snob I am when they spoke highly of Sang Kee.

Well, fast forward to a couple of weeks ago, when they re-opened for takeout after a brief Covid closing. After noticing what killer business local roast duck rival Siu Kee had been doing selling just duck platters during the early days of the quarantine, I was outright fiending for roast duck. And then I saw that Sang Kee was reopening and took it for a sign. 

My girlfriend and I ordered a whole-duck Peking Duck platter and I requested in the order that they include the carcass so I could make some soup with it. 

The first good development/sign was that they were cool with my request, so the value of the meal immediately at least doubled. 

The second was pretty basic - I enjoyed the Peking duck! I'm sure part of it had to do with me not expecting a petite wrap anymore and having adjusted expectations, but the fact remains that if it hadn't all tasted good together, I wouldn't have just said I enjoyed the meal. And I wouldn't have made this a 4-star review. The dish is just such a killer use of duck that as long as the meat and sauce are done right, it would be hard not to like it. I got more than one meal out of just the proper Peking duck part of the meal, too.

The fact that I was able to make a soup, which was possibly my driving factor in wanting duck at that point, locked in the fact that I am very glad that Sang Kee is open again. I now clearly see that I was too harsh on them in the past, and now I'm looking forward to seeing what they can do with more standard Chinese platters.

text: Been shopping at Reading Terminal since I was a kid.  Great for high-qualify, affordable groceries, meat, fish, as well as a panoply of prepared foods, gifts, etc.  As soon as I cross the threshold I feel happy!  I love to go early on the weekends to beat the crowds, as it can get very busy.  Plenty of seating so you can pause for a snack and some people watching.

text:
Very hit and miss depending on what you order.

I always end up at this spot when going through China Town. I believe this is the case as there is ample seating and they had an extensive menu in the past. For delivery they do not offer all of there menu options at this time.

Roti Canai - I really love this item and only have tried it twice in my life. You are looking at $5.00 anymore and I think your getting hosed as the naan bread does not cost alot for the portion size they give you and it comes with a very small container of sauce with two pieces of chicken and one potato in the sauce.

Seafood Lo Mein - I was not planning on ordering this but the menu states : Squid, scallops, shrimp, and vegetables in Lo Mein for $13. Well, There are about 2-3 Shrimps and the tail is still on them in Lo Mein? Really dude... There is also maybe 2 1/2 baby sized scallops, also some minced squid. The Lo Mein was different however, the noodles were very light / thin and not the normal Lo Mein I was expecting. It worked for the dish but I would not come back to order this item as it did not meet my expectations.

House Special Squid - If I saw a picture of this item before ordering it online I would have not ordered it. Back in the day this location literally had items on the menu that said ask your server if you would like as they had some interesting items that are local favorites from localities in Maylasia, Thai Land, and Cambodia. I was expecting something more unique then small pieces of squid and minced squid in an abundance of sauce. But sometimes we take chances in life right and learn from it.

What I have learned from my experience is next time I am in China Town to try another location. As always people SYOY!!!

text: I've never had Panda express pre-covid so I wasn't sure what to expect, but I was thoroughly happy with my first experience.  For our date night, we went for the family meal. This includes 2 sides with 3 entrees for $35. The entrees were just what you'd expect. The chow mein on the other hand, was chewier than it probably should have been/tasted of flour but I'm a sicko and loved it. Overall, I think it was a good value for the food you got, considering all the boxes were filled to the brim and the fact that they were even offering takeout at a time like this is a huge plus in my book. I'll be back for more.

text:
I loved everything I ate from here especially the rabbit in chili oil and peanuts. The flavors were so amazing that after I finished the rabbit pieces, I saved the remaining peanuts, green onions, and chili oil to put on various other leftovers from my fridge including rice and ramen. This dish does require some work as rabbits have a bunch of tiny little bones, but just like shellfish, the work is worth it as this is easily one of my favorite restaurant-made dishes! The dan dan noodles were also amazing and the portions are extremely fair for the price. My order of dan dan noodles lasted me three meals and they consistently remained the same high level of quality despite being refrigerated and reheated a couple of times.
The staff is kind and our order was made in a timely manner. I plan to come back for more soon.

text: In terms of lunch buffet, this Chinese spot has all of the classics that you'll want in a normal fashion. Buns, dumplings, egg rolls, soups, rice, noodles, sushi- and this one even specializes in seafood, which is what I see a lot of bigger groups coming in for. I personally don't eat the seafood much, so my favorite things to get here are the crab rangoons, soups, and sushi- all of which make the price worth it. Typical style for all of the food, and the sushi isn't stellar, but has all of the parts you'd want. Compared to corner store chinese spots, you'll get similar flavors and textures, maybe a little bit less crispy since it's sitting for longer. Don't come for the pizza or American food section.

text:
I went here with high expectations and was very disappointed. Once I walked in I immediately said to myself, this is one of the most try hard hipstery places I have been to. Everything about this place falls in line with the word "trendy".

The food may be asian inspired but misses the mark on every dish. The food is presented great but is way too salty and over seasoned (Mongolian Dumplings/Brussell Sprouts/Dan Dan Noodles). It doesn't taste like asian food, it is very much an American take.

For having dim sum in the name, the prices are outrageous for the portions and the taste. Everything here is about presentation and to catch your eye but I would rather have better tasting food than be stuck in an instagram trap. If you want quality and affordable dim sum go to Chinatown.

text:
I love me some dan dan noodles. While I have never actually sat down and eaten at the restaurant (or tried their HH, which looks amazing), I love getting takeout / delivery from Dan Dan. While it is pricey (as noted from some of the other reviews), their Dan Dan noodles can be made vegetarian and never fail to make my tongue burn from the spiciness and my stomach happy. 

In comparison to Su Xing House (which is down the street), Dan Dan definitely gives you a more "restaurant" quality vibe, while Su Xing House always gives me a more homemade feel (with much cheaper options).

One piece of advice - skip the scallion pancakes! They are very, very oily. While their other vegetarian dishes are adequate (e.g., mapo tofu), I'd always recommend an order of their namesake Dan Dan noodles.

text: HIGHLY RECOMMEND. Seriously, the food is SO GOOD. I ordered here twice in three days because I was blown away. They are cash only, but you can order on your phone using card or Apple Pay through the BeyondMenu app. I got the general tso chicken and this place is my fav in Philly. I used to like Master Wok in Liberty Place but Michael's food is cheaper (best lunch special), fresher, tastier, and a better value. Also really appreciate that they staple the containers shut so that your food won't spill out and love that they include a fortune cookie with my purchase. Try this place next time you're craving Chinese you won't regret it!!

text:
An update on my previous review! COVID-19 has rocked the city but this place definitely comes through! Their tables are situated outside and they are actually shaded due to the building! So when we got there at 6:30 on a Thursday night, it was cool and breezy and Perfect.

The staff are friendly and hope you weren't waiting for the table and sitting down. The tables are numbered so it's easy to identify. And if you wear your mask you can certainly go inside and use the restroom. Other than that, no one enters. Besides the staff

The food here is delicious and a small bit on the pricey side but it's worth it for the location, scenery, and atmosphere.

We fancy the caterpillar bread, the cheesesteak bao, the Dan Dan noodles, and the Koji beef. 
They also told us the pork soup dumplings, even though they weren't on the menu, were an option so of course we got those too! Overall, the portion sizes are pretty small for their appetizers but their meals are definitely plentiful. 
Drinks were delicious and served at a good temperature.

text: First time having Lau Kee for lunch the other day. I ordered the Scallion pancake and Shrimp dumpling noodles. Fast food and reasonable price. My noodles were good and got big shrimps in my dumpling. However, the scallion pancake was okay.. I would avoid that. It was oily and not flaky.

text: Updated review. I wrote one a few months ago and got a response from Anthony Cheung, a manager. You can read his comment below. I'm not sure if he's the owner or the owner's son. But they should get someone else to handle Public relations. While theyre at it, they should hire someone to help oversee health and safety.  This A hole replies by apologizing for it not being up to my standards and and that it's just basically my own opinion. He ends by saying that reviews like mine make a difference on small businesses. And I agree, good and bad reviews SHOULD HAVE AN IMPACT. You really should VALUE your customers' opinions. You basically put it back on me and I've seen you do it with other negative reviews. How about instead of wasting everyone's time with your insincere comments, you spend the time cleaning up your place? Dude, your bathroom is still the bathroom straight out of trainspotting. And you should care about your place!!

text:
First time at Xi'an Sizzling Woks and I'm not impressed. I have never been to any Chinese restaurant that does not include rice with a "rice dish" especially when that dish cost 16.00. I found this to be so unacceptable that I refused to add the rice to my order and instead went home and made my own. That should never happen. 

As for the food I ordered, it left much to be desired. I have had this dish many times in many places. Whether they call it Chongqing Chicken, La Zi Ji or simply Chicken with dry hot peppers you should expect certain elements to be present. Crispy chunks of fried chicken, a heaping pile of peppers, sliced scallions and garlic and sesame seeds. I got chicken and peppers but the rest was noticeably absent and very much missed. The chicken was prepared nicely enough but the flavor was not consistent across each bite. Some morsels were a little salty while others had a more sweet taste which I somehow preferred. The spring rolls were good but that is simply not enough. This is definitely a one and done for me.

text: Finally after 3 years of wanting to visit this restaurant I got the opportunity to do so. I asked for the 3 meat combo but instead of white rice I wanted pork fried rice, I was told the menu is not interchangeable that I had to buy separate. I then ordered pork fried rice and the 3 meats (soy chicken, bbq ribs and crispy pork). The rice was delicious but the meat was colder than a witch's tit. The bbq pork had a good flavor. The soy chicken I found a bit salty. The crispy pork, well there was nothing crispy about it and was way too salty. Now for the price, the fried rice was $8.50 for a generous portion but the meat I was told was $16.50, which total should of been $25. I paid $30 cash and got $1.50 in return. (Pickup order) Tips? (Nonexistent) Taxes? I don't know what I do know is that NEVER AGAIN!! No love for Ting Wong. Overrated and (sneakily) Overpriced.

text: What an incredible little restaurant!  Outstanding dishes!  I got Kung Pao with the peanuts.  It was a gigantic serving, excellent flavor, well presented, and a VERY reasonably priced dinner at about $13.95 or less, as I recall.  This was the weekend before July 4, 2020.  My sister had something equally delicious.  And extra rice free for the asking!  Attentive and friendly service, as well, right in the heart of old town.  We were first advised to go to China Town and we made our way there walking.  Lots of restaurants -- all were takeout -- we saw one chain restaurant with patio seating.  Unless you want take out, don't bother with Philly's China Town during corona shut down.  Much easier to hang out in old town and go to Han Dynasty for a delicious meal with excellent service.  They have some great Chinese beer also, are open pretty late, and did not rush us at all.  Super Chinese food restaurant in old town Philadelphia!  Signed, A happy out-of-state customer.

text:
So I'm not sure if this shows, but my first review was posted prematurely as it was just notes. This is supposed to be the proper, fully formed sentences review.

Right off the bat we noticed that the service was better than the price point demanded. Not just our server, but the entire staff. This was made doubly evident by the way they have handled the covid-mandated social distancing. They really did a spectacular job of being considerate. I would even say they brought a new level of professionalism to it. If you were ever going to risk outdoor dining during this time, this is the restaurant to do it at. So many little touches that I would never have even thought of were changed to their process to make it feel safe and comfortable.

Cocktails were ordered first: a Sister Francis and a Just Drink It. The former was nice but nothing remarkable. The latter was excellent and recommended. The price point on both were fair.

First course was the crispy octopus. I've never had octopus breaded this way, and the pesto plus white bean puree really brought it together. Make sure you get some arugula on your bites as it perfectly accents.

Second course was pasta. Cavatelli and Maloreddus. This is where the night really took off. The Maloreddus was simply fantastic, a traditional tasting dish kicked up by the saffron and fennel. Really I will get this every time I come here from now on. The cavatelli was in some ways the best dish of the night. It was so unique, so well made, so unlike any other pasta dish I've ever had. A lovely combination of unami, savory, an earthy flavors. Even visually the dish was uniquely appealing, as the pasta was a dark, nearly squid ink black color. Portion sizes were enough that they could be your entree, but they were just a smidge less than normal pasta portions at a more traditional Italian place. In other words, you can (and should) get them as well as an entree.

Our main course was the pork chop and the half brick chicken. Both were fantastic. I felt that the descriptions of both dishes did not do them justice. They were both superb.

text:
tl;dr outdoor dining done right, offering farm-to-table offerings with an Italian bent

Restaurants across Philly are taking the plunge into outdoor dining. While admittedly some are fish out of water, Wm. Mulherin's Sons goes out of its way to amp up its outdoor experience. Half in the sun and half in the shade, the block of sidewalk against the north wall of the restaurant-hotel is dolled up with area rugs and a pop playlist. The space is smattered with two- and four-seater metal black tables and wooden-and-metal folding chairs, each separated from one another by many light-decorated plants. Opt for a table on the building side of the block to avoid the sun as best as possible.

My partner and I decided to brave the suffocating summer humidity to take a break from our homemade meals. Upon our waitress's recommendations we opted for the Whipped Sheep's Milk Ricotta, the Fried Soft Shell Crab, and the Leslie Chow pizza, complemented by the Birds, Bees & Italians and the I Dare Youse cocktails.

The ricotta itself tasted like a savory whipped cream with strong notes of mint, balanced out by the salty and olive oily Foccacia, which tasted particularly of grilled rosemary. The crab was battered in a light coat of cornmeal, sitting atop a zucchini slaw and incredibly flavorful garlic aioli. Finally, our pizza, while vegetarian, carried a  generous load of mushrooms with a balsamic-like drizzle. I was most pleasantly surprised that the crispy thin crust held up despite being loaded with toppings.

For just about $100, we shared a decently large meal and drinks -- a fair enough price by Philly standards. I've been meaning to give Wm. Mulherin's Sons a whirl for some time, but I've never quite followed through until now. Now, I'm kicking myself for not having gone earlier -- and I can't wait to get back.

text:
Sadly this was my first meal following months of quarantine. Although the accommodations made for COVID-19 were on point the food left much to be desired. 

We got two orders of pork soup dumplings, a caterpillar bread, and dan dan noodles to share. The soup dumplings were the best of the trio and had a lot of soup in each dumping. The vinegar and ginger sauce on the side could have come with a few more slices of ginger and although the soup was plenty it did not have a rich pork flavor. These came 4 for $9 when other places in Philly will give you 6 or 8 soup dumplings for the same price.

The caterpillar bread was disappointing for the price, $10 for a bit of pulled pork in bread with honey drizzled on the plate. The dan dan noodles were okay but the beef was a bit salty for my taste and the noodles were too hard/chewy. 

Overall if you are looking for dim sum there are a lot better places to go in Philly that have more variety, better prices and more traditional dishes done right.

text:
This place is always take-out only so the current COVID-19 pandemic did almost nothing to affect the customer experience. The only barrier (literally) was that when you step inside the landing, there are large cardboard boxes barricading the way towards the food counter, so you have to stick your head through and shout at the lady to get her attention if she's not in the front. This leaves little room for customers to line up inside - I guess this is intentional for social distancing purposes. Don't be turned off if she's a little cold with customers, you definitely don't come here for polite customer service, but she is very straightforward with answering questions.

*Combination Box: These are generally $9 each right now. It comes with a pint-sized portion of white rice (extra rice is possible for extra $$) topped with steamed Chinese veggies (usually something like yu choy / choy sum) and your choice of meat. When we came, there was no more roast pig, so we opted for ginger scallion chicken and roast duck. No regrets there, this place lives up to its name of being a Duck House! Beautifully flavored savory roast duck with great texture. The ginger scallion chicken is very generously flavored, almost on the salty side, but still delicious. The pieces are on the smaller more chewy side which seems more traditional, and not the typical chunky white American chicken breast cut of chicken. 
*Honey BBQ Pork Belly:  This as well as the roast pig normally costs $15/lb as a side dish, so we ordered it just as a side. She only had two thirds of a pound left so we took it all. It's char siu flavor, super authentic, not too sweet (I don't like it too sweet anyway). 

Our party of four got full enough off of three combination boxes plus the side order of 2/3 lb of honey BBQ pork belly. I'm so looking forward to coming here again and trying the roast pig if they have it available, because so far based on the poultry and the BBQ pork belly, I'm so sold.

text:
This place is one of my favorite places to eat in Chinatown. It hits my cravings every time. There hasn't been one dish that I've ordered that I wasn't fond of. I've taken many friends and family members here whenever they've visited. 

Food is reasonably priced, authentic, and delicious. What more can you ask for? I love the soup dumplings. They're not the best I've had, but still pretty high up there! Definitely recommend. 10/10. 

If you're going with a large group I recommend heading there earlier than you want to eat because the lines get packed. 

Btw, this review is based on my experiences at the restaurant prior to quarantine and covid. I'm not entirely sure how they're managing business as of now. They do take out orders though which I will probably do some day soon.

text: We came in and ordered a few items. We got the crab and pork soup dumplings, spicy pork soup dumplings, Napa and pork fried dumplings, beef fried dumplings and general tso's chicken. I noticed that the menu prices did not match what I was charged. When I asked why my receipt had higher prices I was casually told the menu is old so the prices are a dollar to 2 dollars more for many items. I know business is tough so I didn't push the issue too much. I just paid and walked to a few other places while I waited to pick up my food. The food was all good and I'm only giving a 4 out of 5 for the mismatch in menu prices and what I was actually charged.

text: Meh.  Didn't love it here. Although, I will say I'm not a huge fan of Asian fusion. And I classify any Asian restaurant as fusion unless it is a noodle stand that just has a vat of broth for beef noodle soup and I'm sitting on plastic chairs eating with stainless steal chopsticks, sweating my bum off. Sampan had the plastic chairs and sweating part down but the food was underwhelming and overpriced. We got the beef short rib with Lo Mein. The beef was tender although very salty and really difficult to eat. The Chilean Sea Bass was ok, I have definitely had better. The broccoli and fried rice was average. Our experience may have been better if our waiter wasn't also really awkward, and a little standoffish. Just my humble opinion.

text: Honestly for a Chinese takeout restaurant, the sushi isn't half bad! The delivery did take a longer time than expected but the wait for food was worth it. I got the cali roll, spicy shrimp roll and shrimp tempura roll with a miso soup. It did add up to around $20-25 which is an overall good price compared to other sushi restaurants. Sushi rolls are jam packed with rice and the various ingredients. The shrimp tempura roll was huge! I don't know whose mouth would be big enough for one piece to fit. Anyways, if you want good sushi without breaking the bank, order from here and I recommend ordering for the sushi lunch which is 3 rolls for $12.

text:
Who doesn't love this place? Such a huge building with plenty of food and shopping choices; perhaps too many choices? Here, You can get literally every type of cuisine you could possibly imagine. And it's all good! 
I've only been here a few times recently when in town and it's usually a cheesesteak, but last time it was Hershel's for corned beef and pastrami. (Separate
Review coming later). 
Parking can be a problem near here if driving, so finding a meter or affordable garage is difficult at lunchtime. We were lucky to find a mater spot after circling the block a few times. 
No indoor dining with Covid restrictions in place, but hopefully it'll get back to normal soon. 
If you've never been here, you must visit and enjoy the overwhelming vastness of the building and the plethora of cuisines. Definitely a must-visit while in Philly.

text: JIAN BING ALERT!! I've been searching high and low for a Jianbing in Philly ever since I studied abroad in Shanghai last year. Thankful to have stumbled upon a very outdated blog post on the internet that mentioned an old restaurant used to make these, but the name was different back then. Luckily Delightful Garden has kept them on their menu. Decently priced for about $5 a piece, these are super close to what I had in Beijing (not the Shanghai crispy style with millet) but does the job. Please go here and try the most underrated street food item that people in America don't know about!

text:
This is the first restaurant I visited since the lock downs started in March. Granted, I've been to Sampan many times over the past 5 years for happy hour and dinner since moving back home but revisiting any familiar place during COVID, with all the changes and restrictions, makes the experience strange and new. 

A close friend who I also had not seen since March made a reservation (no just walking up and claiming a table) so we could have an after work happy hour. We both arrived, masked, just a few minutes before 3 while the masked hostess outdoors was setting up her station with paper menus and hand sanitizer. She showed us to a table for 2 set up against the outside wall of Sampan. Tables were all 6 feet apart and a portion of the street in front of the restaurant was also cordoned off and made into a dining area. Again, tables were correctly distanced. 

Our table was on a distinct tilt; not bad enough so that eating implements and food rolled off but significant enough that we were not 100% comfortable. On the other hand, it was preferable to sitting in the street as regular, Friday Philly traffic rolled noisily and closely by.  

All tables were bare for easy cleaning between patrons. Our server, masked and gloved, took our order and chatted happily with us about being very glad to be back to work again. We told her we were utterly sick of our own cooking and, in Nick's case, delivered food. The atmosphere here was noisy (sirens, motorbikes, raised voices, horns honking) but festive. Not everyone (other than Sampan staff) we saw was wearing a mask. Of course, those seated and enjoying their food and drink were sans mask, but that was to be expected. 

Nick and I ordered what we usually would have had in pre-COVID days-the house special cocktail (a cranberry/vodka spritzer on this day-very weak), happy hour priced edamame dumplings, crab rangoon, beef skewers, kim chee fried rice, roasted brussels sprouts and roasted shisito peppers. By now, we had several masked servers attending our table, thus the food was coming out rather quickly, crowding our small, tilty table top. 

Happy hour prices have not changed and you'll still get a solid meal if the happy hour bites are going to be your dinner. No shame in that at all. The fried rice was not quite as we remembered; still a very plentiful serving but seeming a bit underseasoned, lackluster and very light on the kim chee. Like what I find at almost every restaurant that offers shisito peppers, these were more soggy than fried/lightly charred; as well, they were served in an oddish way-a big bowl heaped with peppers (making them MORE soggy as they sat and steamed together) with the 'dipping' sauce smeared on one side of the bowl in a thin swathe. This made the peppers hard to 'dip' so we wound up using first a knife, then our fingers, (since it was just the 2 of us) to retrieve some sauce for our peppers. That finger thing isn't something I'd do if I were to eat with a group, though. Regular plates and utensils were used for serving, but chopsticks and napkins were disposable. 

We ate, had several drinks, caught up on the doings and not doings of each other's post-COVID lives and people watched. Not everyone who had a reservation was masked and patrons who were walking around-heading to or returning from the restroom, meeting other members of their party-were usually not masked, either. There also seemed to be a line of people either waiting for their reservation time, or seeing if they could get a spot. There was absolutely no social distancing in the line, most of those waiting were not masked and some of the people were actively hanging onto/leaning on each other. Sure-probably lovers and/or good friends (one would hope)-but still...

Between the traffic and the din of people at last let out of long confinement, lots of unmasked patrons passing our table, the noise level that was fairly high, plus the tilt of the table all made it hard to relax in spite of having quaffed several adult beverages. As a result, we cut our time short, got the check which arrived quickly, paid, tipped generously and headed off to our respective destinations. 

Would I go back? Probably not for awhile. I'm curious to try other outdoor dining situations, like Salty's, K'Far, Zahav's patio and BarBombon's charming looking alley seating. Heck, even a take out picnic in Rittenhouse Square would tickle me. 

Sampan certainly seemed to be doing everything right; maybe this was (for us) like once again dancing or dating for the first time in a long time-awkward and strange, but hopefully something that will become better and easier with time.

text: Seating ended much earlier than the end time of the restaurant so we took it to go. So I was told that the Dan Dan Noodles were something I had to try. I am not usually a fan of Dan Dan noodles but the kick on this one was great. Mix it a little with the white rice and you can mellow out the heat a little. The salt and pepper shrimp was good albeit portion was a little small for its dinner price. The scallion pancakes and the dip was great! I had the bok choy and the black mushrooms as well. Great flavor and texture.

text:

The food actually has a hint of spice or heat when it says it will and the food has always been tasty, delivery has been fast and I'm always eating everything. It's typical American Chinese food.

text:
Merrian-Webster dictionary defines the term "eating out" as eating away from home, especially at a restaurant. Philly's own Sampan passed this test with flying colors, serving their customers with food, away from their home. I chose this restaurant to temporarily fulfill my immense and everlasting hunger because of its ability to unite artisan mainland China cuisine with the popular Japanese dish,すし or sushi.
     Per usual, my experience eating out was an emotional roller coaster. Although I had made a 6:45 reservation, my team and I endured a 15 and a half minute wait before being helped to a table on a quaint side street. The chairs they used were comparable to the street itself, but once my rump went totally numb, I found the city noise created a pleasant ambience for my meal.
    Although the staff treated us with the utmost respect and compassion, the flimsy paper menus missed the mark for me, I also would've loved to see some more kid friendly options such as General Tsos Chicken Nuggets and French fry fried rice. After perusing the menu's extensive and expensive choices I went with the Kimchi fried rice, yellowtail sushami, toro roll, blue crab sushi, General Tsos soup dumplings, A-5 Kobe beef (RIP), and a strawberry lemonade. The yellowtail really hit the spot for me, as the southern tang coupled with the tropical fish fostered a cultural paradigm in my mouth. That, along with my soup dumplings, fried rice, and the homeless man harassing the families across the street were the clear highlights of my meal. 
     Although the prices were somewhat egregious, this restaurant inspires greatness with its high end Asian cuisine which I hope will be a catalyst for the city of Philadelphia as a whole. All in all, Sampan provided me with a unforgettable experience that will sit with me for a lifetime.

Final rating: 67/89

Signed, Yours Truly...Tom

text:
My wife and I wanted quality Chinese food for takeout, and Mustard Greens didn't disappoint.  I had their wanton soup, and the broth was healthy and seemingly saltless. The wantons themselves were compact and relied more the filling than the dough.
My wife had spring rolls,  and they were light and flavorful without the excessive grease some lower tier restaurants depend on.
We shared a chicken and broccoli dish that used the sauce only slightly. The broccoli tasted freshly cooked and crisp, as though it had been just as soon as we had ordered it. The brown rice was cooked perfectly.
The prices were appropriate for the quality if the food, and the owners were cordial and professional.  We look forward to getting back for more takeout; it goes without saying that we look forward to dining in, too.

text:
Pho Ha is our go to place when half of my family wants pho while the other half wants broken rice, bun bo hue (only available on the weekends), summer rolls, etc. The only reason why it isn't at the top of my list for pho is because whenever I get brisket, it's always pretty fatty compared to other places. Otherwise, their pho is legit. I usually get pho dac biet, but their chicken pho is really good too. 

For those that aren't in the mood for pho, there are other options. My dad really likes their broken rice with grilled pork. I've gotten their bun bo hue before, but it was just ok- not memorable. For drinks/dessert, I'm a fan of che ba mau (coconut milk, red bean, mung bean, and pandan jelly)!

**This review is based off my preCOVID experiences. I was in the shopping center recently and it looks like they had a recent makeover. Not sure if it's the same owners or not but their new menu looks pretty extensive. Prices seem a bit high but that may be due to COVID. Will have to check them out the next time my parents are in town...

text:
Minute rice and a Costco microwavable meal are better than this. I was skeptical of the rather mixed reviews and decided to order take-out with my family, and I can say it was objectively awful. The Chicken with Eggplant in Garlic Sauce essentially tasted like straight soy sauce, it was saltier than the Dead Sea. I couldn't taste any chicken, eggplant, or garlic. The Sweet and Sour Chicken was small pieces of soggy chicken with no sauce. The sauce was effectively sugar-water on the side. The Vegetarian Fried Vermicelli was apparently decent. 

To add insult to injury, when I was handed my final receipt (AFTER I had paid), I noticed I was charged a credit card processing fee which was not included on the website (I asked them to confirm this) and was not listed on the initial receipt. Furthermore, I found out that if you place an order over the phone, some items will come with rice for free, but this is not the case if an order is placed through the website. 

Between the mediocre food and the annoying price "games," I strongly recommend to obtain your daily nutrition elsewhere.

text:
Covid-19 Outdoor Dining Review

The outdoor dining area, although right on the street is made inviting by several planter benches with colorful vinca flowers.  Our server wore a mask and gloves, despite the heat, and was very friendly and professional.  

Dan Dan is a bit overpriced and portions are small compared to other good Chinese food options.  We were here for lunch, although they do not offer lunch specials.  It was a standard menu.  We ordered the Ginger Scallion Chicken and the Scallion Pancakes.  Both items were really good. 

In the past , we have ordered the Dan Dan noodles. They were very tasty, but make sure you can bear the heat, because they are spicy. I've also had the Cumin with Chicken, Dry Pot with Chicken and Garlic Sauce with Pressed Tofu. The Cumin and Garlic sauce were both tasty. The Hot Pot was a bit of a let down, because it was the dish with the highest spiciness level, yet was bland and paled in comparison to the 1-star spice level of the Garlic Sauce dish.

This is definitely a more touristy attraction which higher price points for the food and potential gifts, but definitely should not be overlooked.

text:
The food here is good and cheap. Before covid the prices were so low they were practically giving it away. 

I've been ordering the salt fish fried rice for twenty years, this is my go to order.

Roti cani has been rotated out of my usual rotation because the roti does not hold up well for takeout. I can't wait to come back here for a big steamy plate of roti cani when restaurants in Philly welcome patrons back inside.

text:
Honestly such a great spot with outdoor dining experience for pandemic needs! Here's the scope:

Yes, hotpot outdoors with gas grills (fire guards for wind). They try to warm up soup ahead of time as it does take a long while to start boiling. Ours took 45 min.. after soup was in front of us.

Amazing selection of items for AYCE, love how they start with smaller portion of items and giving more during reorder, allows us to try new things and eat a selection. The soup bases are really good too, including a tom yum and special mushroom broth. Sad the live crab was on the menu included in dinner ($24.95) but they did not have it.

Really good service and also offers a seafood boil like environment. Would have wanted to try it but did not see a combined option for order plus only have one stomach. 

I think the price is reasonable! The food is great and fresh with plenty of seafood options. Yum!! Beware of the tables outdoors as they have holes and so hot soup may drip on you if you're not careful. Ahh! I will definitely be back here!!

I LOVE this place! It's so fun to visit during a stroll in the city. This place is the best because it's like a giant food court. There's such a variety of foods you can choose from, and they're all delicious! I could truly spend a whole day here sampling from every kiosk!
