text:
I really think Panda Garden is a good, solid pick for Chinese American food when you're craving it.

They have a huge variety of a lot of classic Chinese American takeout on their menu.  My partner and I ordered it off of seamless, and we really enjoyed everything we got. The price isn't terrible, and the portions are super generous and fed us for another whole meal. 

We ordered the sweet and sour chicken, sesame chicken, walnut shrimp, and Szechuan style pork along with an appetizer of two egg rolls and crab wontons.  The sesame chicken and the walnut shrimp were my two personal faves, and they really packed the takeout container with a ton of meat rather than filling it up with filler veggies. Everything tasted delicious and as expected, and really hit the spot for fulfilling our takeout craving. The order came with two generous portions of white rice, and we weren't charged extra for it.

The only two downsides to the meal were that the dipping sauce with the sweet and source pork was super watered down for some reason? And not as flavorful as I was expecting, and then also our order through Seamless was almost an hour late from the projected time we got, even when we ordered ahead of time. So just be prepared that this place gets super busy on a weekend night at prime dinner time!

text:
So many wonderful Chinese places to eat in Chinatown and the greater Philly area, but I'm glad we stumbled across Dim Sum Garden tonight. 

We understood this place can be really busy so we budgeted in enough time but were then happy to find that there were a couple small tables when we walked up for dinner. 

For the two of us we ordered 2 roast pork buns, an order of steamed pork soup dumplings (8 count), 6 pan fried spicy pork soup dumplings and a fried rice. Our eyes were bigger than our stomachs as we ended taking the fried rice to-go. 

With the one exception being that the roast pork buns were a little dried out and hard, the food was fantastic! Everything tasted amazing, came out piping hot, and the wait staff were attentive and making sure everything g was to our satisfaction and our waters were topped off. 

Great experience, excellent food and very reasonable prices. 

Pro tip: Cash only so come prepared with greenbacks.

text: Current best duck house in Philly. They've been there forever. Very small, take out only. Wonderful selection. Duck giblets or beef tendon in 5 spice, slow steamed duck wings, duck tongues, roast pork and pork belly and more. The duck itself is the least fatty roast duck I have found. Prices are typical, low for the organ meats. Ting Wong is great and you can sit when there isn't a pandemic on, but Siu Kee is a much more nuanced kitchen.

text:
*THIS PLACE HAS OUTDOOR SEATING* despite what Yelp says on their front page. 

Best noodle house in town. I love this spot and this is the place I go to every time I'm in the city. They DO NOT take cash so bring cash. I hear from other Yelpers that they take venmo, which I was not advised by the waitress but they do not take credit card. 

I got the House Special noodle soup and it is delicious. The aroma of the broth is so strong that you can smell it even while sitting inside. It's not spicy at all but if you want to add a little chili oil to it, just ask for it and they'll give you some condiments. They add some pickled green mustard to it and some Chinese broccoli, which gives it a nice little balance. The best thing in it is the meatballs. I gave some to my sister and she loved it so much that I gave her the rest of mine.

My sister got the dried noodle, which was also very good. The only thing is that its just a tad bit oily but the portion size is really great for the price. 

Best noodles in town. I would recommend this if you're in Philly and looking for a nice soup dish.
name_x: Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House

text: Saw this place on DoorDash and decided to give them a try. Picked up pork house bao, scallion pancakes, fried dumplings, and spring rolls. The bao was pretty good, first time I ever had it in general. Soft, warm, sticky bun with a moist, soft, flavorful pork coated in minced peanuts with some cilantro. Pancakes were crispy, thick, and chewy. Dumplings were so packed with filling they were open along the edges but were good, crispy with a moderately thin skin and the pork with chives flavorful. Spring rolls were fairly run of the mill. Overall, the dumplings were great, bao was good, pancakes okay, and spring rolls passable. I would try it again, interested by the noodle dishes. Should said it's a bit pricey.

text: M Kee has done a great job during Covid. The extensive menu is posted outside on the window and is great value. We always get half a duck ($12) and usually also get the wonton soup and 1 new thing to try. The wonton soup is delicious, with shrimp and pork inside. We have also had the beef he fen (stir fried flat noodles) which reminds me of home. It's a great place to get your Cantonese take out fix without the dine in prices. They take orders outside and are prompt so you aren't waiting too long even when there is a line. You can also order delivery from Chowbus. The pricing is a bit higher and the delivery fee is a little annoying, but it's the only platform that brings Chinatown (and especially this restaurant) to your front door.

text: As a NYer, this place is like your Big Wong on Mott so you definitely can compare their dishes. Came to get lunch before we left and I ordered my usual, roast pork and soy sauce chicken over rice. There was a line of people who were ordering so I definitely felt confident that this is a good spot. First, they were quick with the orders given the amount of people who ordered ahead and after me. Waited maybe 2-3 minutes before it was ready. I think they give more meat compared to Big Wong buttt, when the lady told me the price of my lunch I was taken aback a little. She looked at me at said $10.80 and I thought she got my order mixed up so I confirmed if that was my order and she said yes. I did not have a problem paying that or maybe I haven't ordered from a fast casual chinese place in a while since the pandemic started but 10.80 felt a little steep. I understand that prices went up, just didnt realize what I was used to paying $7/8 in NY would cost me almost 3 bucks more. Anyway, the food itself was prettty darn good. When I watched the man cutting my roast pork, I was a little nervous because the piece looked like it was on the leaner side and I like half lean/half fatty roast pork but nope, the pieces I got were reallly tender, very flavorful and just really good. The chicken was also marinated nicely so they was flavor to it. The orders were so big, I must've at close to half at first and I was already stuffed. I finished the rest on my own a few hours later and felt very satisfied. Would recommend this spot!

text:
Quarantine Post

They have limited seating but hot pot is alive again! First impression, the food is extremely high quality and their fish balls are homemade as well as noodles. They are going for the niche and quality food. They also have a promotion of buy 1 get 1 for select meat orders, a la carte. Honest, the homemade colorful noodles are pretty but impossible to eat. Very chewy regardless of how long you cook it. The fish balls are a MUST try, very delicious, we got the combo first and then ordered separately. The food selection is plentiful and our party of 5 had a wonderful time. They also have multiple different soup bases with individual pots. They sent us a sauce tray, the options were very dry not very sauce like however, they have a homemade sauce thats delicious!

I would recommend this place but keep in mind its bougie and really going for quality and may not be comparable in price to an AYCE for example. Still, loved the experience, would recommend!

text:
I've been to Ochatto many times pre-COVID. I have never really had any big problems coming here. My go-to order is kani salad, duck roll, and beef noodle soup. They actually have my favorite kani salad around, and the other dishes are great too! No complaints. The staff has also always been friendly to me.

The reason I give it 4 stars is because it's a little overpriced. For example, the portion for the duck rolls is super tiny but it's $8. 

Another reason is that my friend used to work here as a sushi chef and he warned me to never eat the sushi here. Unsettling, but since I don't order any raw fish from here and since my food has always been good, his warning did not scare me. For everyone else, BEWARE.

text:
BAIT-AND-SWITCH
BE CAREFUL ORDERING GRILLED FISH.
I ordered a $30 Grilled fish in Chongqing Style under Chef's Specials, and I was expecting a "Grilled Fish" like everyone else's posts. However, the "Grilled Fish" I got looks more likely a Hot Pot Fish Filet (from the photo on yelp) that only costs $16.95. Out of my curiosity, I called the restaurant and asked if I receive the right order, and I was told the restaurant "modify" their recipe because they couldn't find whole fish anymore. So I asked about the vegetables in this dish because they also looked very different than their photo online and was told they use "seasonal ingredients." 

It's not about the money I paid because I always overpay tips to all services during the Pandemic. I understand COVID is a tough time for all the restaurants, and I would be completely fine if they said to me upfront. However, the way they handled my question made me feel like I got cheated as a customer. I probably wouldn't revisit in the future.

text: A staple restaurant in Chinatown Philadelphia. I've been a customer for over 40 years. Their food is consistently good, the prices are very reasonable, portions are well above average, and the staff is very friendly and hospitable. The establishment is always clean. Whether you're taking it, or eating in, as I did pre-Covid, the food is always good. Chicken with mixed vegetables, with soup, sweet and sour, egg drop (all the soups are delicious), shrimp and lobster sauce, every variety of fried rice, lo mein- it's all delicious. .

text: This is a nice hotpot place, but the value to price ratio is a bit sad, especially with the meats. We got some pork belly, and it was literally so paper thin I could eat it all in one bite LOL even though it was $6.99. This place specializes in meats but I honestly can't really tell the difference between a nice wagyu and regular beef but that's probably my fault! Service was also a little disappointing as my soup base was never refilled, and I had to ask multiple times/different waiters for different items. Overall it was a good experience, just quite pricey! Tip is to definitely join the waitlist on Yelp!!

The place is HORRIBLE. The food is okay but there are a lot of items on the menu they do not have. And there is an unexpected rise in price for all-you-can-eat. Previous lunch is 17.95 per person and right now is 24.

The manager named Leon seems like a lunatic. We found a fly on our Angus beef and then the waiter reported to this manager Leon. He came here and started to scold and blame us for not being careful enough when placing the beef in the hotpot. He said they need to obey the city protocol to open the door and that's why there are flies everywhere in the dining room and it is not their responsibility if the flies get into our hot pot. Then Leon asked us is there anything else we need. We were totally uncomfortable at that time and did not want anything and then he was like we were so rude and impolite just because we did not want anything anymore. 

Everyone, please be careful of this Leon and the flies.

text:
Outside: Hidden Downtown Gem
Inside: Traditional Chinese Noodle House
Food: Mostly Chinese Noodle Dishes
Service: Remarkably Fast
Price: $10-20 pp

Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House is delicious, fairly priced, and authentic. That should be all you need to know to check it out right now!

For more details, read on:

NZHDNH serves a great variety of Chinese noodle dishes (many in soup, some dry) and assorted appetizers and side dishes (dumplings and veggie dishes primarily) and everything is fantastic.

The dumplings are plump and flavorful.
The veggies are perfectly prepared.
The dry noodle dishes are filling and flavorful.
The soups are divine.

I've sampled each of the following items:
Scallion Pancake
Shredded Kelp in Sauce
Cold Shredded Potatoes
Barbeque Lamb Stick
Marinated Duck
Braised Sliced Beef Noodle Soup
Beef Brisket Noodle Soup
Roast Duck Noodle Soup
Beef Tendon Noodle Soup
Ox Tail Noodle Soup
Lamb Noodle Soup
Noodle w. Peanut Sauce
Sesame Cold Noodles
Szechuan Cold Noodle
Boy Choy w. Fresh Garlic
Coconut Chicken Curry Dumpling
Mixed Veg Dumpling

And literally everything was savory, delicious and something I would order again (assuming I wasn't actively trying to order literally everything on the menu).

The place has an unassuming front, and often a wait when a convention is in town, but wait or not, this place is worth it.

Philly's Chinatown has no shortage of great food but this might be the best place of them all. Hidden a little bit off the main drag, and not offering the standard Americanized Chinese food many places are known for may make it easy to overlook but that would be a mistake.

As someone who has lived in China and is constantly on the lookout for good, fresh, delicious Chinese cuisine I have found a lot of places in Philly that are good. Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House is great. 

While you wont find you traditional American Chinese staples here (no genreal tso's, no pork fried rice) you will find a wide variety of savory and comforting foods. There should be something on this menu for everyone and even the least adventurous among you shouldn't balk at a noodle soup with sliced brisket. And I do recommend the noodle soups as the best of the best in a menu of nothing but great options.

For the most adventurous you can try something more traditional like ox tail or beef tendon. 

Regardless, order a noodle soup, add a splash of the vinegar on the table and spoonful of the ground chili in oil. And bask in comfort as the warms flows through you and soothes your soul with every bite.

What are you waiting for? Go give this place a try.

text: My family decided to try this restaurant for the first time today, so we ordered delivery. It will be our last. We all decided to try the specialty chicken, KenShin Chicken. It had great reviews. We didn't agree. The chicken was super dry and stringy and the some of the vegetables were overly soft and soggy while others were totally raw. The portion sizes were inconsistent among the containers. I did enjoy the flavor of the sauce, what there was of it. I had requested extra, but had the same minuscule amount as everyone else. The spring rolls were okay, but not worth the price. The rangoons were very bland. We gave them two stars instead of one because we liked the packaging on the side items. It definitely was not worth the totally overpriced bill that we paid. Do yourself a favor and eat elsewhere.

text: Their lunch menu is delicious and very reasonably priced. We ordered a Chicken Terriyaki Bento box that came with shrimp and vegetable tempura, a California roll, veggies, rice and a salad. We also ordered two Maki Lunch special. The Maki special allows you to pick two Maki rolls and their list to choose from is substantial and far beyond basic. We ordered a peppered tuna avocado roll, spicy crab with avocado roll, seared tuna roll and the spicy crab cream cheese roll. The Maki special also comes with miso soup or a salad. We got one of each. Every single thing we ordered was delicious and fresh. I highly recommend and will definitely return!

text: If I could give this a 6/5 stars I would. Nan Zhou is one of the most delicious restaurants I've been to period. The pork soy sauce noodles are flavorful, chewy, so well seasoned, and ridiculously affordable. The diced cucumbers were salty, garlicky, and so so tasty (definitely not bland or sesame oil heavy like at other restaurants). The dumplings (we had the pork and chive) were generously filled, and the dough was ridiculously chewy (in the best way). The scallion pancakes (at under 4 bucks mind you) were flaky, tasty, and the sauce they were served with was great. Their house chili oil is flowery and spicy and rich and makes star dishes even better. I went to this place several times during my stay in Philadelphia because the food was SO good and SO affordable that I couldn't believe that it wasn't just a very lucky one off (it was not). Each time delivered delicious food at an affordable price. Please come here if you like awesome food. By the way, the fried mini buns are a great surprise on the appetizer menu (don't be fooled by the lettuce bed they are served on; they are NOT savory)

text:
Let me tell you something. i first got introduced to dry pot (mala xiang guo) at this NYC spot called Mala project. and i've been hooked ever since! but being back in philly, i needed a place just as good or even better, and chushang is the SPOT. 

food: i've never gotten the soup, but i always get the dry pot with my favorite things: potato glass noodle (a MUST), few meats, fish cakes, sweet potato (also a must)and a bunch of veggies + cilantro. i'll always be an avid fan of Mala Project, but chu shang's portion seriously outshines!!! it may seem like the cost is racking up with each ingredient, but they do not give sparingly! super large portions, and super strong flavor. 
it can be salty, so please don't forget to eat your rice!

the space: it's a fairly large space, just a normal chinatown area in my opinion. nothing is special about the inside, you're really just here for the food!

text:
We came here highly recommended by a friend.   We had a reservation and were seated at a table that might have barely made 20"s in width.   It was tight and cramped and very close to a large beam that obstructed view as well as made it even tighter to sit.   After asking our waiter to move to a better seat we were told there were none available.  After speaking to 2 managers, Kris and Yolanda, we were told we could not be accommodated because we were a couple of two when right across from us was a couple of two that had a conveniently larger seating area and they arrived 20 mins after we did.  As well as the several empty booths that were available and never used.  At 9:30 pm we were told there were incoming reservations, unknowing that the last reservation is taken at 9:45 pm. 
    As a business professional in the customer service industry and my spouse being a doctor that deals with people daily, we were less than pleased with the lack of understanding and courtesy.  Our waiter was great but I really feel the management dropped the ball in what was supposed to be a great Friday evening out.  $300 later I have to say I was not impressed and would likely not come back to this restaurant.  
    Its more than just food.  Appearance, punctuality, courtesy, and understanding go a long way in the customer service industry and I came here with very high hopes and was severely let down.
    Our meal... Honestly for what we spent $$$  I would have rather ordered chinese takeout and watched netflix and chilled.   
    The cost would have mattered not if we were treated like our comfort mattered in what we thought was an upscale restaurant.   
    Respectfully,
Lennie L. Corbett

text:
RULE OF THUMB: You can tell a lot about a Chinese Restaurant based on the amount of sauce packets they provide.

It's a simple concept: If the restaurant skimps on sauce packets in an effort to cut costs, this usually translates to other cost cutting measures. Most often in the form of poor service and food quality.

You can imagine my immediate disappointment when my latest order contained just 3 packets of both soy and duck sauce. This was an order for 4 people. 

This used to be one of my "go-to's" so it pains me to say that the food quality and service has plunged to the point that I will not be returning. Hopefully, a decision maker at the establishment reads this and makes this place what it used to be. Because if they did, I would come back

text:
Overall a very decently priced spot with food that hits the spot!! Also, they only take cash or Venmo in store! 

We ordered:
Braised Beef Noodle Soup (4.5/5): The soup was flavorful and the beef was quite soft! Wasn't the best noodle soup I've ever had but for $9 it tastes amazing when hungry :)
Spicy and Sour Chicken Noodles (4.5/5): Pro tip for all the nut based sauces (peanut or sesame), add vinegar!! If you like vinegar you will appreciate the addition, it's so good! This dish is basically like the peanut noodles but they add chicken, cucumber, and lettuce.
Hot Milk Tea: I can't believe a cup was only $1.75, it tasted pretty good! 

Service was nice and quick too, would recommend this place if you're looking for a cheap, quick meal.

text:
Just got delivery from Mandarin Palace for the first time tonight as our usual place was closed and it was recommended on the NextDoor app. I have to say that I am extremely disappointed for many reasons:

For reference we got the Moo Shu Chicken, an egg roll, and General Tso's Chicken

1. The General Tso wasn't very good, cost nearly $15 for a very small amount, and we were charged an extra $1.50 for subbing brown rice which made the dish very expensive 

2. There was an option to order from a few different platforms online and each had different menu items listed and drastically different prices so I decided to call

3. When I called I wasn't given a total or estimated delivery time 

4. The Moo Shu was absolutely terrible (see photo). I had to add salt AND soy sauce to the dish to make it edible. It also had A LOT of egg and very very very little chicken. It also was lacking in mushrooms, which I love. It was basically egg and cabbage (again little chicken and mushrooms). I am honestly very upset and disappointed. 

On a positive note the delivery came pretty quickly and the Moo Shu came with both rice and pancakes. 

Overall we will 100% never order from here again.

We had the soup dumplings, rice cake and the taiwanese fried chicken. The fried chicken is a big portion and a must try, really well seasoned and delicious. The rice cake was good, a little under seasoned and oilu but still good. I do recommend trying their soup dumplings while they are hot, we waited a little too long and they were stale. I am excited fo be back, prices are reasonable and food is good! 

They are using styrofoam plates and cups currently so doesnt look as nice but maybe more sanitary?

text:
I've only ordered take out/delivery from Spring Chinese Restaurant twice, but from what I can tell it's a pretty solid spot. 

The first time, I ordered the shrimp fried rice and chicken wings and the Kung Po Triple Crown. The shrimp fried rice and wings were amazing! I legit could not get enough of it even as I was eating it. Even thinking about it now, I just might order it again today. I asked for it to be spicy because I really like spicy food. It wasn't as spicy as I wanted (I have a ridiculous spice tolerance so it was probably okay for most people) so I added some of my own pepper myself. The Kung Po Triple Crown was okay. Also had to make adjustment to it with my pepper and I wish there was a lot more protein in it. I definitely enjoyed the shrimp fried rice more, hence why I stuck to that the second time I ordered from them. 

The portion sizes are also incredibly generous. With those two meals, I was able to eat lunch and dinner for like 2-3 days. Probably would have lasted even longer if I hadn't overstuffed myself the first day with the shrimp fried rice and wings. 

For the price and the portion size (and delicious food), I'll definitely be ordering from them again.

text:
Well...I should have read my previous review to refresh my memory before ordering last night.

American Dream Roll - I was expecting this to be gourmet from all the premium ingredients in the roll and the price. Far, far, below my expectations.

Kao Pao Shrimp - So listen to this folks you pay $15.50 and need to pay $5.00 which is a discount from the $7.00 they charge for fried rice! To simplify you get NO RICE for $15.50 order for Kao Pao Shrimp!! This dish is also a bit too spicy to enjoy and not worth the money.

Miso Soup - $5.50 for a quart of Miso Soup...really??

INGRAIN IN MY BRAIN DO NOT ORDER FROM THIS SPOT AGAIN. 

Also, they do not read any special requests I wrote please make the Philadelphia roll with just avocado and cream cheese and they disregarded, I even wrote I would pay extra if it cost more to put avocado in it instead of Salmon. I mean I am only spending $59.00 on this order but okay I hear you loud and clear now Mandarin Palace just like you heard my request for my roll.

Hogwash!! If you ask me....Next!

text: To sum it up, great flavor, good portions and hits the spot but a little overpriced. We got the dry pepper chicken which is nothing like the ones you might expect from a Szechuan place like Han Dynasty. It wasn't crispy but it was really flavorful and we enjoyed it a lot. The Mongolian lamb was okay, the meat was a little tough and not worth the money in our opinion. All the veggies and flavor overall was good though. Last thing we got was hot & sour soup, and that was exactly what we wanted and expected flavor wise.

text: I am highly disappointed. This restaurant has a great reputation. I usually go to Jasmine Asian Bistro in Glenside. I absolutely love that restaurant but they were closed on Mondays. I remembered about CIN CIN in chestnut hill. I've never eaten there but heard great things so I ordered takeout. I ordered a large shrimp and broccoli and 1 spring roll. When I picked it up, the cost was $21.40. I've never spent that much in an order like this but didn't mind because I thought it would be tasty. I got home and opened my package. I was so disappointed with the food. The food was not fresh. It tasted as if it was reheated after sitting out. My spring roll was oily too. My daughter and myself tried to eat it but couldn't. Maybe this was a bad night for them but I certainly will never go back. If it is a Monday, I would rather go to the other Chinese restaurant down the street. I've eaten there and the food was tasty and more affordable.

text:
XLB, Xiao Long Bao was the main reason I chose this restaurant for dinner one night while in town. It was cold that evening and I wanted to eat that soup dumping and a few other dim sum dishes.

While they may not be the best XLB but they were pretty good. 

My other favorite dish was garlic snow pea leaves.   I could just have this green and white rice, and be happy. 豆苗 is my favorite leafy green and I memorized Chinese characters so I know to always spot this dish wherever I go at a Chinese restaurant around the world. 

Be sure to leave room fit desert as they have egg tarts on their dim sum menu. Actually we got so full, we took these egg tarts back to the hotel.  Naturally I ate both of them 2 hours later. Of that really completed my night. Good egg tarts finish my day right.

Reasonable price for the volume of food in each dish.  

Great friendly service. I loved the clean and nice decor inside too.

I would come back if I lived in the area

text:
This place is great for the value! It's classic Americanized Chinese food, which I tend to crave sometimes. I ordered the General Tsao's dinner box, which came with the vegetable fried rice, wonton soup, and a spring roll. The quantity was good for $9.50, and it was enough to make two meals out of it.

The spring roll, wonton soup, and rice were typical, not too special, but decent. The chicken was the best part, the perfect texture and with a lot of sauce. Would recommend for a quick meal or if you're craving american chinese food.

text:
(Painted picture) It was a dark stormy day, not a dim sum in sight... called ahead to Nom Wah and just to our delight they were open! Since we called ahead they sat us right away only us and said no more customers. Felt great as if we had it all to ourselves which we did. (Brief history) apparently is the first tea parlor/dim sum house in philadelphia. Tea was great, all day dim sum even greater! 
Decor: authentic, homie, bar type vibe, it was an interesting mix but def welcoming to say the least. 
Service: Well... nothing can beat being the only ones allowed in. Ofcourse in defense there was a curfew and we made it just in time for the cut off. But also service was friendly and quick! Cooperating with the new norm- masks were worn upon entering and being seated, off while seated/eating, back on upon exiting. 
Food: I don't need to explain, just know it's good! Jk jk def gotta come for the xioa long bao! I wasn't much of a fan for the chicken feet, but the shrimp shumai was definitely a must buy too. 
Price: affordable, cheap, def get your bang for your buck.

text: Let me start my saying this is a really decent attempt at Center City style Chinese up in the NE. For reference I only had the hand drawn noodle soup, pork soup rumblings and pan fried pork dumplings. The pork soup dumplings were pretty identical to center city's Dim Sum Garden but much smaller. I was a little disappointed in the pricing knowing what I get in CC for the same price. They were tasty just smaller and overpriced. The pan fried pork dumplings were good but fried a little too long for my liking as they were crispy as if they were deep fried. The soup however is where the home run was hit and the reason I have it 4 stars instead of 3. The soup was absolutely delicious and reveled the noodle house on rave street. The pork ballet was good but fatty so I would recommend the chicken honestly. They did put the chili sauce in it and the burst of heat was amazing. I would go back just for the soup.

text: These Chinese devours come from @newleafmanayunk . Their service is really great. Their team of servers are very attentive and they check back within 5 to 10 minutes to see if everything is still OK at your table. They are bathrooms are exceptionally clean; And they do offer both indoor and outdoor dining. Our food came out pretty fast which was really good. Here is their crispy calamari, along with their Tom Yum seafood soup; and their seafood delight dish that came with shrimp, scallop, salmon, snow peas, mushroom in light black bean sauce! The calamari was really good especially with the duck sauce. The Tom Yum soup was very filling and tasteful. And the seafood delight was simply amazing with the black bean sauce; I really enjoyed it. If you're ever in Manayunk and want some really good affordable Chinese cuisine please check out @newleafmanayunk and tell'em SHIMMY sent you! #food #foodie #foodphotography #foodblogger #foodstagram #philly #philadelphia #soup #tomyumsoup #shrimp #calamari #duck #scallops #water #snowpeas #salmon

text:
I love coming to Ocean Harbor! This is the place to go to for the most authentic dim sum experience in Philly. They have ladies pushing carts and a nice, chatty atmosphere. Wait times are usually between 15-20min but could be longer so make sure you walk in and ask the host how long it'll take. 

The menu has a variety of classic dim sum dishes like steamed shrimp dumplings and siu mai but also have heavier dishes like stir fry beef and Peking duck. The service is very fast and no nonsense; typical of what you'd expect from a dim sum place. Their prices are also very affordable; less than half the price of Dim Sum Garden so I definitely recommend trying here at least once!

text:
Meh. We tried to order through the website but it kept redirecting us because it said the site was not safe, or we reached a 404 Error. Then we ordered through Yelp, which was easy enough. We received a notification that our order was being prepared but no notification that it was finished, so that I had call to verify that it was done. I told the person on the phone that we hadn't received any verification but it was already an hour when the wait said 20-40 minutes. She made a point to argue that she pushed the button to say the order was done, but honestly she could have just noted that whatever system they're using isn't talking to the Yelp system. If you order from yelp just take note that may happen to you.
Anyway. The food is mediocre for the price. We got two Bento boxes and some appetizers which was plenty for a family of four, but the quality wasn't fantastic. I'd have been happy if we spent half as much. The top foods were the Age Tofu and the Shumai shrimp dumplings--very good, great texture, fresh. In the Bento, the tempura was fine. Otherwise, the teriyaki chicken and fish were dry and the california rolls weren't flavorful. I would consider this the "fast food" of local Japanese fare, but there are other local places with higher quality for the same price.

text: So glad to have found MKee today!!! I've been dying to find authentic salt and pepper pork chop for a few months now since we moved to Philly and I can't believe I finally found it at MKee. This is one of my bf's favorite chinese dishes and he approves. The pork chop was very tender and pretty crispy; it probably would've been even better if I ate it right away. Beef chow fun was delicious as well, tasted just like the ones I had from china. Both dishes were not salty. Portions were very generous with really reasonable prices; best value of any chinese restaurants. The menu has so many traditional dishes that I like and can't wait to try other dishes. They are only doing takeout right now and orders were made fast.

text:
Moving in the middle of a pandemic isn't easy. After a long flight from across the country, being frustrated with TSA and people not knowing how to wear masks properly, I wanted something that was comforting and familiar. Luckily, Han Dynasty was close by and made me feel better after a long and arduous day. 

I had been here once before for a conference, but getting the experience living in the city is quite different. For now, it's either pick up or delivery, and it was nice to see that they were very cautious, and only allow people wearing masks to pick up food. I ordered some of the usual sichuan dishes, such as mapo tofu, water boiled beef, twice cooked pork, and string beans. After sampling almost every sichuan restaurant in my previous city of Houston, I can say that Han Dynasty can stand with the best. The mapo tofu has a wonderful texture, it wasn't broken up, and actually uses the right style of tofu. Water boiled beef had a great flavor, just enough sichuan peppercorn, and wasn't too greasy. The twice cooked pork was also really good, but it was half leeks and less meat than I would expect. String beans were cooked perfectly, just how I like it.

The price isn't terrible for the location, but it is more expensive than I am used to. Then again, I am new to the city so my needle has to probably change a bit. If you're already familiar with the dishes and are ordering online, it can be a bit confusing, since they go by "style". I would have also liked to have some more rice with my food. I ordered 4 dishes and only got 2 little to go containers of rice, which felt a bit skimpy.

Overall, this is going to probably be my new local. The flavor is great, resonably priced, and does an excellent job of protecting their customers and staff.

PS, if you haven't yet, the owner is featured on Munchies video by Vice.

text:
Ordered take out from Dan Dan after seeing high ratings on Uber Eats and we were not disappointed! We ordered around 6PM on a Friday night, and our order was set to be ready by 6:45PM so really quick turnaround. We did deliver, and our delivery guy followed directions and left our order outside our door, which worked out very well. For eats, we both ordered the dan dan noodles as our main (felt like we couldn't not get them!) and split the scallion pancakes as an app. The scallion pancakes were OK - they were very greasy so must have been fried in lots of oil. That being said, they were tasty but that might have been a byproduct of the heavy deep fry. They were served with soy sauce, which was a nice touch, but we couldn't get past the grease. On the other hand, the dan dan noodles were very nicely done. They were coded as a 3/5 spice, but boy, were they spicy! Our noses were both running the entire time. The flavors of the dish were very good though - the sauce was strong and rich, but not over powering the noodles themselves, which were nicely done and clearly homemade. The minced pork meshed well with the overall dish, but the minced nature made the meat get a little lost in the noodles, which was disappointing. Outside of that, there appeared to be a few green onions and bean sprouts mixed in as well, but some extra veggies would have added to the dish too. But overall, we did really enjoy the dan dan and could tell it was a much elevated dish from traditional lo mein. The price of the dish was extremely reasonable (~$10 on UberEats), but the portions were HUGE! We split one dish between the two of us and were incredibly full after. So definitely worth the price!
We enjoyed our takeout meal from Dan Dan, and we were overall pleased with our selections. We will probably opt for a less greasy app next time, and we will explore other (less spicy) noodle and entree options too to give the entire menu a chance. But this is a great spot for dan dan noodles, just be prepared for spice when you go in!

text: Mom's cooking but with a twist! I ordered the Set 1 with fried chicken. It came with ginger rice and it tasted just like the one my mom used to made when I was little. You can get the steamed chicken, which is more traditional, or the fried one, which was perfect. The meat was juicy and flavorful, the batter stayed crispy even when I got home. The sauce was the perfect amount of hot, sour and sweet! I whished there was a tiny more pickled veggies though. The price was 9,99 and included a canned soda and a chicken broth with white radish. Very good! Service was great, the girl working there was very friendly and welcoming. I will definitely come back since I live near by.

text: LaTao is a huge hot pot factory near the U Penn campus. The all-you-can-eat lunch special was a great value. We shared a big pot split into three sections of different broths. We could order any raw ingredients from the menu and particularly enjoyed the beef (duh, a must-have), the quail eggs, the fish balls, the dumplings, and the noodles. I even tried pig brain, which wasn't that remarkable but certainly unique! The wait staff was a bit sub-par, as they would occasionally forget items or bring only small quantities of the things we ordered (perhaps to be expected for an all-you-can-eat). But we still enjoyed the feast and left satisfied. Overall a fun experience next time you're in the mood to boil your own food!

text:
You just can't go wrong at Buddakan!

You walk in, and it is just this huge open room, with high ceilings (they need it to fit the 10ft. buddha statue - which is really cool.) Lots of tables and energy in the restaurant. 

Their menu is HUGE, and really fairly priced for their appetizers, dim sum, noodles, etc. The portions are great too, you'll likely have leftovers. Their main entrees a little pricey, but you can easily avoid them if you aren't looking to spend a ton of money and get a few smaller plates. The flavors though are poppin' on every meal.

Desserts and drinks are must gets - worth the indulgence. They have really cool Asian influences to them.

text:
Food is decent and incredibly cheap. Perfect place to grab a small, affordable meal. They have a bunch of pre-made goodies for purchase. Since everything was so cheap, I couldn't help but over order. 

I got the fried rice noodles with vegetable, Vietnamese noodle roll, sweet tofu dessert, and a mango passionfruit green tea all for takeout. Still couldn't believe how affordable this place was. 

Fried rice noodles were decent although a bit cold. It wasn't a big deal since I could just pop it in the microwave. For less than $3 you really can't complain. The container might look small, but the lady really packed a lot of noodles in there. As for the Vietnamese noodle rolls, I was sad that they didn't have Vietnamese ham on top like the advertised photo. Maybe they just ran out? Well nonetheless, it was pretty good and for the price it's an amazing value. 

Sweet tofu was delicious and it satisfied my cravings. Sweet tofu is a childhood favorite of mine and it's been years since I've had any. So glad I found a place I can come back to grab some more. As for drinks, their options were a bit more limited. They didn't have oolong tea, but they asked if I liked fruit tea. Their mango passionfruit green tea is pretty good. It's sweet and very refreshing. 

Since I live pretty close, I will be making another visit in the near future to try some of their other promising snacks.

text:
Happy Wok is a great neighborhood Chinese restaurant. They make all of my favorite dishes I remember from my childhood. 
Some Chinese food items are better in the hood than in Chinatown. For example, egg foo young, chinese style BBQ spareribs, yat mein, sparerib tips to name a few. 
I always order the chicken egg foo young and the best part is the gravy, rich and flavorful, I can't get enough of it. I also love the BBQ ribs and I must have extra chinese mustard with it.
I really like the pan fried dumplings, just right with the crisp outter dough and a gooey pork filling. 
I also enjoy the pork yat mein which has the aforementioned delicious gravy, tender slices of roast pork, noodles and chopped raw onions.
The people at the Happy Wok are indeed..... happy and polite. So far everything i have ordered is correct, never had a problem, delivery is fast and courteous and the driver is like an old friend stopping over for a visit.  Prices are very reasonable and I can't wait to explore more of the menu.

text:
Oh RTM, how do I love thee!


My wife and I have been here multiple times!  We love strolling through the aisles, looking at everything that is for sale. Seeing if they have anything new!

On our most recent trip (during covid), it was sadly very depressing...  We went on the Friday after Thanksgiving.  About 20% of the shops were closed...  There was no indoor seating...  If you did manage to find a chair that wasnt removed, security came along fast to move you along...  My wife is 8 months pregnant, so they let her be for the most part.

So since the last trip was a little dismal, I will post what we have come to love about this place.  We LOVE the cookies from the PA General Store.  OMG soooooooo amazing!  Soft and chewy.... such a delight.  After the first time we only bought 2 cookies, now we know to get 2-3 dozen! hahahaha!

I am a huge fan of Corned Beef and Pastrami, but as a NYer, we know Jewish style is the best!  Places by us are $30-40 per lb, or 20+ a sandwich, but good ol Hershels is a normal price!  $10 per sandwich, and $14 per lb!  Its worth it to drive down lol!

Since we arent locals, the produce isnt that big for us, but we love getting spices and seasonings from the Head Nut and the Herbiary.

We also love getting unique items from Amys place!  Highly recommend!

They also have several butchers that you can get fresh meats from.  We really love getting sausages and so many other items like steaks and sometimes fish.  Dont forget a cooler!

They also have about 10 stores that are direct from Lancaster Amish country!    Fresh butter, fresh eggs, fresh produce!  Make sure that you stop at Beilers for a donut and cake!  Millers also does amazing pretzels!  Make sure that you like butter.

If there is something that you are looking for, and do not know where to get it, 99% of the time, you can find everything that you need here!

text:
These are the BEST noodles in Chinatown!! 

I have been here many times for their noodles, and they have never disappointed. Recently, I ordered the peanut noodles, egg tomato noodles, and the braised sliced beef noodle soup. These three dishes complimented each other really well with the varying flavors and noodle textures.  For takeout, you have the option to keep noodles and soups separated so the noodles keep their texture. 

Peanut noodles: peanutty with a slight soy sauce flavor, the texture of the hand drawn noodles is great. This dish is even better with some chilli oil and vinegar. Make sure to ask for it if you're ordering takeout! For the price, you must get these! I always order with handdrawn noodles.

Egg tomato noodles: the sauce was very flavorful, with woodear and scallion as well. I like these with both the handdrawn and shaved noodles.

Braised sliced beef noodle soup: like all their noodle soups, very flavorful. This one was slightly spicy and came with radishes. Noodles came with shanghai choy and cilantro.

Would 100% that everyone eat here if they're in Philly!

text:
CinCin is the kind of restaurant that when you're hiking the Tour du Mont Blanc, and pausing on some alp to chat with another couple you've just met, and it turns out they're from the Philly area, they'll say that they come to CinCin every Sunday night for dinner.  The place has that kind of well-deserved loyalty and reputation. 

We did a recent takeout order. If you haven't been there, they have a very good COVID compliant pickup arrangement. In fact, the riskiest thing is probably driving into and out of the fairly small parking lot. It is, however, very convenient.

We started with an order of pan fried dumplings (note, the printed menu does not specify, but these are meat dumplings), which were rated very high by a Deputy Yelper in the household. Eggplant in hot garlic sauce (not super-spicy, just right) was excellent with perfected cooked Asian eggplants. The Tofu in Black Bean sauce was a bit plain, but satisfying just the same - tofu with a fried-chewy texture, and the accompanying veggies perfectly al dente. Deputy Yelper described their Szechuan Pepper Basil Lamb as "fabulous." 

The really nice details: yes, brown rice. Also, if you want leftovers, their serving size sets you up very nicely. I'd say that the typical vegetable or poultry order ($12-$13) is really two adult servings. Some other entrees are priced a little higher, but this is a very affordable menu overall taking into account serving size. They included enough mustard, soy and duck sauce packets for small army, plus numerous teabags. Nice touch for a takeout order.  And, as you guessed, fortune cookies with some pretty funky fortunes - and not at all stale!

text:
This a my go-to local restaurant for sushi delivery. The rolls are well priced. I love how they package their take-out rolls too, I've never had any issues with them falling apart or anything. I feel the price for the quality is just a steal as I've never had a bad sushi experience. 

Also, do yourself a favor and add their Avocado Salad in your cart. It's a juicy yummy salad with basically a full avocado in it! Best part is it's so cheap.

However, I will say I'm not a huge fan of their other Chinese food. The chicken teriyaki with veggies and rice is always pretty good, but beware sometimes the chicken is dry. The best add on though is they have a small fried rice which is lightly fried for line $2! Also stay away from the hot and sour soup as it's mediocre.

text:
This was my first time at the Philly location; however, I've been to the Atlantic City location (which closed permanently due to COVID unfortunately) quite a few times. I never had a bad experience and the food/service was always excellent in AC, so I expected no different from this location.

When I first arrived, I was relieved to see the semi-enclosed booths for the outdoor seating. I had made reservations in advance, so I figured my party would get one of these booths. INSTEAD, we were seated in the open-air on the sidewalk, which was quite cold and uncomfortable. Somehow it didn't sit right with me that we were paying the same price as the more comfortable patrons while being completely out in the elements, despite having a reservation. It was especially bothersome when other parties seated on the sidewalk were being offered to move into a booth. I just don't believe you should have to sit entirely outside if you made a reservation. That should be reserved for last minute walk-in's.

The service also left much to be desired for. I do empathize with the difficulties of serving tables during COVID with outdoor dining, but our server first dropped my boyfriend's beer and promised to bring another free of charge, which took at least 30 minutes. Meanwhile, he was favoring other tables and giving them better service. It almost seemed like he was ignoring us and didn't even come back to check with us. After we'd already FINISHED our entrees, he told us "your dinner will be out shortly" which speaks volumes on his lack of awareness of our needs. I did want to order dessert and another drink, but everything was taking so long that I didn't even want to bother and by that point, we just wanted to get out of there.

The food was pretty mediocre aside from the spare ribs and edamame dumplings. I would not return to this location or recommend it to anyone.

text:
My friend and I ordered from here and each got our own Lo Mein (chicken and beef), and we split Happy Family, Won Ton Soup, and Egg Rolls.

The egg rolls were pretty good, Won Ton was good (also there seemed to be more than some other places), and Happy Family was fine but wasn't as flavorful as expected. The Lo Meins, however, were kinda bland and had very little meat. The lack of meat can't be due to COVID since the Happy Family had plenty of it so perhaps it was a mistake.

The service was great, though. Delivery was quick so the food was hot. Prices are fair. We even got 2 extra egg rolls, which was cool because I'm poor and love good egg rolls.

text: It's very frustrating when a restaurant is inconsistent with customers. Especially when they're willing to support local business to be turning out in 30 degree weather and snow ridden streets just to grab dinner. Long story short I dine here frequently but that will no longer be the case. I always order the tuna and sub the cold noodles (not a fan of cold noodles) for the curried Cauliflower. This evening the staff refused to fulfill my request of subbing that item even though I've had it like that in the past and their only resolution was to say "we're not sure why that was allowed before" but were willing to sub me mashed potato's or regular cauliflower. So you can see my frustration with the story changing, first I was told no substitutions were allowed, then told "well you can sub but only for these items" and for reference the mashed potato's and curried cauliflower cost the same price under the sides. The lack of customer service here is unacceptable.

text:
Got take out from here last weekend during COVID. Except for one large issue, a delicious meal!

Big menu with easy online ordering. Lots of delicious options that run the gamut of usual Chinese food as well as random specialties that I haven't seen elsewhere. Ordered the food and it was ready in a jiff which was great. 

Had the pan fried pork dumplings which were nice and crispy on the outside and delicious on the inside. The dipping sauce was a bit bitter for my taste but good regardless. Got the wonton soup which was an unfortunate occurrence. Several of the soups say "Contains Pork," or "Contains Shrimp." The one I ordered didn't say anything, including what was inside I suppose. I specifically wrote "Allergic to shellfish" in the comments section but sure enough, they were full of shrimp. My friend was therefore unable to eat them, so I had the joy of finishing them. Delicious again with a good helping of wontons. I just wish they had read the comments, or explained things better on the website. For entrees with had Snow Pea Leaves with Garlic which were fantastic! A huge helping, nice and tender, and full of flavor. Also had the chicken with string beans which again was excellent. Not too oily or heavy. A nice sauce to go on the rice which was great and the string beans were perfectly cooked. 

Delicious food, quick service, good helpings, reasonable prices, easy ordering. I just wish they read my comments regarding shellfish allergies and my friends chances of death...

text:
After trying their delicious duck a few months ago, we returned today to pick up take-out dishes and several items of BBQ items. The BBQ meat items were about 30% less weight than what we were charged. The meats costs $16 per lb.

We ordered 3 lbs of roast pork, and 1 lb of crispy skin pork.
The receipt indicated 3.1 and 1.43 lb respectively.
We put the meats in zip lock bags for freezing, then decided to weigh them as they felt lighter than expected.
The actual weight was 2.2lb and 1.07 lb.
That came to an overcharge of about 1.26 lb, equivalence of $20.

So watch out when you are there.

I give them a rating of 2 as the food tastes good, but with the cheating of weight, that is unethical.

text:
Atmosphere: Chubby Cattle was our first stop for food during our visit to Philly, which was pre-COVID lockdowns. The restaurant had a very young and vibrant environment. The seats had their own outlets, and there was a conveyor belt with a variety of small dishes/ingredients for your hotpot.

Service: We had made a reservation before arriving at Chubby Cattle. Since we arrived early, we had to wait about another 40 minutes. The staff was kind enough to give us a coupon for a free choice of meat. From the online reservation to being seated, it took a total of 1 hour and 40 minutes (on a Friday night). We definitely liked the online waitlist and would recommend signing up early as possible! The service was friendly and helped us explain their menu/portions. 

Food: We first ordered the House Original and House Hellist Spicy Pot (entry level spicy) as our soup bases. We loved that we could design our own hot pot sauce from a wide range of ingredients! From the conveyor belt, we got seaweed salad and rice cakes, and we also ordered udon noodles to enjoy with our soup. For our meats, we ordered the Beef Combo, which includes brisket, angus prime ribeye, and Australian Wagyu short rib, and got a pork belly from the coupon we got earlier. Overall the food was fantastic! However, we preferred the House Original over the Spicy because it paired better with the meats and udon noodles. While the conveyor belt has some nice selections, meat is definitely the way to go (we especially recommend the pork and ribeye, which was very soft!). 

Overall: Chubby Cattle has such a great balance of food and experience. Although a bit pricey, Chubby Cattle is definitely worth a visit for their delicious hot pot and amazing meats! Would undoubtedly come again!

text:
Went to Han Dynasty my visit to Philly back in August. I wasn't sure about Philly's Asian cuisine being that I had never had it there before but they did not disappoint at all. Had the cumin style chicken and rice and it was very good. A bit more spicy than I thought it would be but still fairly very good. 

Good outdoor dining area away from direct sunlight in a subtle but mildly busy restaurant area. Very good service and affordable. I recommend it for anyone visiting in that location or live in the area.

text:
Reliable, good prices, my go-to. I eat here quite often. The food is always fresh with good portion sizes for the price. It also comes quickly. Avoid the egg rolls though they are quite greasy.

Update 1/7/20
Ordered my usual and a few others:
Let's break this down

Tempura appetizer- weird, bland mixture of very long fried shrimp, and veggies.
Edamame- overcooked, hard, dry, not edible. I threw it away. 
California roll- avocado was not fresh, overall tasted bad but i managed to eat after drowning in spicy mayo 
House fried rice- tasted odd, onions undercooked but might be salvageable if i add soy sauce and mirin.

I'm a little upset. I'll probably think twice about ordering again.

Reordered 1/21/21 breakdown:
 Overall this restaurant is a good go-to that isn't too expensive. Generally their fried food (other than fried rice) is not super good. Their fresh food like sushi normally tasty.

text:
I ordered take-out due to the whole COVID restriction. My family and I just arrived at our hotel nearby and were hungry from our long trip. The only restaurant decently open was this so we decided to order. 

We ordered our usual Chinese dishes. We got the crispy chow mein, orange chicken, beef soup and their combination fried rice which all came out to $66. I personally think the prices are a bit steep for the amount of food they gave. The sauce for the crispy noodles weren't enough. The orange chicken was pretty good. The beef noodles were decent. And fried rice was well... you can't mess that up. 

The service was great however! Lady said the little wonton noodle toppers that are usually placed on top of congee were on the house, LOL. I MEAN... thanks? There was no other purpose but to eat them like a snack I guess. 

Parking's on a narrow, crowded street. Be careful for other cars passing by or you can say goodbye to your side mirror!

The soups at this place aren't made, they are crafted, and the prices are cheap, cheap, CHEAP for the quality you get. I will be first in line to eat in when this place opens back up!

text: I have heard a lot of praises for bing bing so I decided to give it a try myself. One I was very impressive by how warm I was sitting outside and it was 40 degrees outside. Two the staff was extremely friendly and welcoming. However, I was very disappointed by the food. It felt like an half-hearted attempt at asian fusion. In my opinion, to be a great fusion restaurant, whatever elements or twigs added to the traditional dishes must add something to them. That was not how I felt at all. It felt like someone who's not super familiar with those traditional dishes just randomly pile an array of condiments on top of each other for novelty. I would say the outcome is mediocre at best. Given the price and taste of items we ordered, I was not impressive. We go the caterpillar bread, lamb dumplings, turnip cakes, brussels sprouts and duck noodle soup. The turn cakes didn't taste like turnips at all. The Brussels sprouts are really salty and not much else. The duck noodle soup is good but nothing super interesting and overpriced. This is a place for people who have never had dim sum before. Regardless of how many disclaimer the place might give, I am giving my money and patronage somewhere else; especially since businesses in Chinatown have suffered much from COVID and xenophobia, I feel my resources and attention should be directed there instead.

text:
I've been here multiple times pre-covid and their udon is great! I get the BBQ Eel or Seafood Sautéed Udon and it's savory goodness. Their jasmine bubble tea is also really good and I like their bubble tea reward system; I always carry around the punchcard in my wallet. 

Their dinner bento box is also really worth it. You get a variety of food including sushi, protein of choice, and tempura for a pretty good price. I've had the filet mignon option a couple times. 

I haven't really tried many of their sushi, but my friends who have all say it's pretty good!

text: I got their Dan Dan Noodles and Chicken and Broccoli. It was okay for its pricing and quality combined. The Dan Dan Noodles was not what I was expecting, but the taste was not bad. It was spicy, but I didn't enjoy the numbing feeling of the spice. I would get again though because it was none the less pretty tasty. As for the chicken and broccoli... I wouldn't get it again. I didn't realized they didn't have lunch specials anymore, so I got the entrée, and it cost about $14. The serving size was small for what it costs, and it did not come with rice. It's worth it during lunch special, but not on its own.

text:
I cannot think of any negatives about this special place to balance out my review. Simply stellar. They've really figured out a way to make enjoyable dining possible during covid. They have pods that are really quite warm -- I was even debating taking my winter jacket off. It's nice to be sitting out on the streets too, as there's some solid people watching available in center city. The wait staff is also incredibly attentive. Obviously the food is tapas style, and we didn't regret ordering any of our plates. As a pescatarian, I especially recommend the salmon skewers (so very flavorful) and shrimp pad Thai! The Brussel sprouts are consistently the star of the show, too. Thanks Sampan for all that you do!

UPDATE (visited again for happy hour):

Sampan's happy hour absolutely broke the 5-star scale for me. Can I give it at least 6 stars?? I was blown away by how much high quality food & drink we got for such a reasonable price. A huge bowl of fried rice for only $5?  You must be pulling my leg! The scorpion bowls are phenomenal and the right amount alcoholic for a lil evening fun! 
Our waitress was super kind and made sure we were able to place orders before the 5 o'clock happy hour deadline/ the cheaper plates expired! 
I have never been so anxious to return to a restaurant in my life!

text:
I love it here. While the decor may seem simple, the dishes are anything but that. I've been here for both dine in and takeout and had great experiences. Every dish I've tried was delicious and the portion sizes are large for the price. 

My favorites are Xian Lian Pi and Pickled Pepper Woodear. The Xian Lian Pi is such a large serving for a great price and always fills me up. The Woodear is a cold dish that perfectly complements the Lian Pi. For a larger meal, the Fish Fillet with Tofu is amazing and I highly recommend.

text:
Ordered vegetable lo mein and asked for a few shrimp thrown in. Also ordered a vegetable spring roll. About $14 total. Very happy with this meal. Basic, uncomplicated lo mein done right. Not too salty, not too greasy, but nicely flavorful. There must have been 10 to 12 shrimp, more than I expected. I think they had been lightly breaded and fried too - a nice way to do it. Plenty of food for the price. Also, friendly and quick service. 
After a couple days of work on the road, I needed comfort food and satisfaction. 100% I can kick back and rest now! I'll come back when I'm here again.

text:
Amazing noodles, cannot go wrong with any dish that Nan Zhou serves! I was in Philadelphia with my boyfriend for 3 days and we went to Nan Zhou for 2 of our dinners because we were that obsessed with how good and flavorful their food was!!

I'd highly recommend the spicy beef noodle soup and shrimp stir fried noodles--the taste was fantastic and I honestly can't think of ever having stir fried noodles better than the ones I had at Nan Zhou. We're so obsessed with the place and sad that we don't live in Philly. I'm sure we'd be eating here every other meal. 

Definitely check Nan Zhou out, the food is also very affordable and you get your money's worth, no doubt. If you're a noodle person like me, you'll probably have a great experience here.

text:
Solid and affordable Thai style restaurant located in the heart of Chinatown. I did not expect a simple chicken and rice dish to be so deliciously made! I got their Set 1 with a boiled styled chicken dish. It came with a bowl of soup, bottle of water (or soda, you can choose) and a few cucumbers as a side.

As someone who does not like ginger, I was in love with the ginger rice that came with the chicken! The ginger taste is there but it was very light and flavored nicely in the rice. It was not overwhelming at all!! I got the boiled style chicken which is 100% recommended especially if you like super juicy and soft chicken. The two dipping sauces were ginger oil and a lightly spicy sauce that gave that extra OOMPH to the entire dish. Price and portions of the dish only cost 9.99 which is an excellent and very affordable dinner option.

text: My meal at this charming brand new restaurant may be the very best Chinese dinner I have ever eaten. The flavors in the non-hot dishes are delicate and interesting. Nothing is masked in soy sauce or MSG. The menu is not huge, but all dishes we had were fresh and delicious. The fish soup and the complimentary dumplings were especially flavorful. The spring rolls have fresh mushrooms in them. The service is excellent. The decor is modern and handsome. If I'm in Philly again I will seek it out. Price is reasonable, a bargain for the quality of the food.

text:
Visited during a brief visit to Philadelphia. Yes it's a chain restaurant, but the concept is unique and worth trying.

First you pick your soup base, there are several choices. I went with the entry level hot. Next you pick your protein. Wagyu beef is available at multiple price levels, (from F! To WTF!) alongside a few other choices. You are also presented with a basket of ingtedients to make your own dipping sauce - garlic, fresh ground chiles, scallions, etc. While your soup simmers in front of you, a refrigerated conveyor belt that runs past every table provides a parade of ingredients you can grab - vegetables, Tofu, seafood, raw eggs, more. Every color coded plate has a different price. We figured out how to poach the eggs in our soup ladles, really changed the flavor of the soup in a positive way.  Be careful with the "sponge tofu", if this soaked in your spicy broth it will deliver a blast of hot temperature AND hot spicy broth directly to the back of your throat.

This was a fun time, we got in around 5.30 PM on a week day with no reservation.  Even with expensive beef and multiple ingredient plates, our check was less than $50 for a 1.5 hour meal.

text:
So most people know this as a decent Brazilian steakhouse that is a great place to bring a date vs group of people vs family for a nice hefty meal to celebrate something... Or to come during Restaurant week, which the restaurant always participates in... More recently, I've discovered an amazing thing about this place, it's happy hour! It happens almost every day and their caipirinhas are great! Cheap and strong! Also with a decent happy hour food menu that won't burn your wallet. 

Rating: 8/10
Pros: Great happy hour, decent meats, Restaurant week! Also great location and staff
Cons: Brazilian steakhouse price

text:
Tried to order some dim sum for takeout while driving back from Berwyn back to NJ.  Called my usual location Ocean Harbor but nobody answered the phone.  The next choice was Dim Sum Garden, but the lady answered the phone was rude and did not want to take my order just said all cash payment.  Nom Wah was my third choice with credit card accepted.
I ordered Shrimp Dumpling, Shrimp Rice Rolls, Rice Roll with Fried Dough (2x), Steam Bean Curd Skin and Sticky Rice with Lotus Leaf.
The price was high $35.64 with just 6 orders.
Well, here is the verdict:  Steam Bean Curd Skin was salty and once of the Stick Rice with Lotus Leaf tasted sour.  The other selections were decent but nothing really delicious!

text:

Reasonably priced as well. Just right, and competitive in the Chinatown area. Would return if I wanted this style off old again and in Chinatown

only complaint is the drinks. we got the fish bowl one time but they didn't have the bowl so we just got it in a jar. there were at most 3 drinks in there and you barely get any buzz from it. quite deceiving when they put it in a bowl and you thought you're getting a lot of alc with $25

text:
F'delicious food. The staff was courteous and friendly. The lights were dim and the music good.  You can see the bustling kitchen, kind of like a Hell's Kitchen set up. Overall had a good experience. I would recommend this place at least once. 

ZEN-GRIA:    8/10
Pros: Tasted good, not bad for $11
Cons: Ordinary 

PASSION FRUIT LEMONADE:    8/10
Pros: Tasted good
Cons: Plain, nothing to see here keep it moving

TUNA PIZZA:    10/10
Pros: Appetizing, colorful dish, the garnishing made it pop. I would recommend this dish.
Cons: Was it worth $17? That's up for debate

DIM SUM SAMPLER: 9/10
Pros: Tasty af. Sechuan pork & edamame dumplings were the best of the bunch. Put that chilli soy dipping sauce wit'em to take it up a notch.
Cons: $21 for 8 pieces hmmm that's tough

CRAB FRIED RICE: 8/10
Pros: Scrumptious, has an escargots tinge taste to it. 
Cons: Portion size lacking for the price. Meal was forgettable.

KOREAN BEEF FRIED RICE: 9/10
Pros: An inviting dish. Garnishing game was on point. The sunny side up egg was a good compliment. Well seasoned, tasted great.
Cons: Nothing I could think of.


BBQ PORK TENDERLOIN: 9/10
Pros: Very delicious, savory af. The green sauce across the meat was a good touch. I think the onion ring that came with it was the crunchiest onion ring I ever had. Another recommendation in my book.
Cons: None

text: I've been so tired of lackluster Dan Dan noodles living on the Main Line. These were not just "la" but "mala." The Szechuan peppercorns were numbing allowing the extreme heat from the peppers to easily slide through the lips. Not TOO oily (people need to understand chili oil is essential to this cuisine.) The shredded beef with long peppers was brilliantly "feathered" with cornstarch making the tough but flavorful round tender with the classic texture only the Chinese seem to be able to achieve.  Portions were enormous, especially for the price. Dan Dans would easily serve three as an app. I took 2/3 home, as I'm stuffed. Waitstaff spoke fluent English (which  was lucky, as they didn't understand a word of my less-than-fluent Mandarin. Masks/shields worn by staff (and many Asian customers.) It was quite crowded at 7:30 on this July 4th. They were very nice accommodating me as a single.

text:
Came here last weds for brunch with my brother. They have a normal chinese american food menu as well as the dim sum menu, but we only had dim sum. Dim sum menu was divided into shanghai and cantonese sections. 

We ordered the beef stuffed scallion pancake, honey vinegar spare ribs, pork and shrimp siu mai, shrimp stuffed eggplant, and sticky rice banana leaf. 

Favourite dish was the shrimp stuffed eggplant and least favourite was the siu mai. It wasnt bad by any means, it just tasted a bit too fatty/oily for ky preference and I wish the shrimp flavour was stronger. Other items we ordered were pretty good as well, better than what I've had in Baltimore but not as good as some in NYC. 
Overall a pretty good dim sum place with decent and well priced food, but not the best I've had.

text:
Honestly I expected better from dim sum in Chinatown. I definitely think this place was slightly over priced and was disappointed by the mediocre quality of the food. Some options weren't bad but others were really lacking in flavor and didn't really taste like authentic dim sum.

Shrimp and pork shumai: 3/5 not bad pretty standard but nothing special
BBQ pork bun (cha siu): 1/5 one of the worst, lacking in flavor and randomly had yam in the middle 
Pan fried soup dumplings: these were actually the best had a good amount of soup in the middle and didn't taste bad

Overall would not come again. Wasn't horrible but overall pretty mediocre. Luckily ordered over the phone so I quickly picked it up when I got there since there was a huge line out the door even though the food really isn't that great here.

text:
If I ever move to Philadelphia, I would buy a place near the Reading Terminal Market and never cook again.  I would also die early from atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease.

Now, I haven't been to a lot of public markets like this, and more memorable ones for me have bee in Australia (such as the night market in Cairns and the Queen Victoria Market in Melbourne).  Some of the domestic ones, like Quincy Market and Boston Market, seems very touristy.  To be certain, Reading Terminal attracts its fair share of out-of-towners like us, but unlike Quincy Market there's still a sense that it's a place where locals come.  Maybe I'm wrong about that, but as compared to our subsequent experience in Boston just a week later, Reading Terminal was far less crowded, though still bustling with activity.

There are so many good things to eat here, and I wish I could remember all of the places we visited to get little bites here and there.  Cannoli, poutine, a big ol' freshly baked biscuit with jam, fresh fruit from the grocer, a pastry called a pig ear, and much more - all of it was good.  I wish we had more time to eat our way through the entire market.  There's so much variety, and overall prices were quite reasonable, at least when it comes to the little snacks that we were picking up at every other stall.

I just did a Google search for the best public markets in the US and this place consistently ranks at the top of any list.  Definitely a must-visit place in Philadelphia, and a lot of more interesting than lining up to look at the Liberty Bell.

text:
We first visited Buddakan over ten years ago during our last trip to Philadelphia. We weirdly had fond memories of the Buddakan's chocolate sorbet , so we put it on our list for our return visit.

Working backwards, the chocolate sorbet is still really good and probably the best part of our meal. We should have ordered less food and ordered two sorbets instead of sharing one serving at the end :-/

For our main course, we had the barbeque lamb chops and lobster fried rice. We started with the  tuna tartare spring rolls, pork, and shrimp dumplings. To summarize, the food I would rank it comparatively to a PF Chang's restaurant. Nothing was inedible, but it was all forgettable (except for the chocolate sorbet ;- ) ).  To be fair, the cilantro salad (served with the lamb chops) had a nice kick. Frankly, we would have been more satisfied with a double serving of the cilantro salad, instead of something else.

For drinks, we had a peach lemonade, Szechuan sour, and glass of shiraz. All were fine, but once again, not terribly memorable.

Our server worked very hard and was attentive. She was aware of our lactose allergy and mentioned it as we were seated, which is better than the Michelin star restaurant we dined at two nights ago! Therefore, we have no criticisms of the service.

The total price for the dinner including tax, tip and a 20+% tip for our server was $213. The bottom line of trading off quality with price is that it just wasn't a great value for us. We likely will not return, but we will always have the good memories of the chocolate sorbet!

text:
This is one of my new favorite gems in Philly. (Warning: love letter ahead)

It's a cozy space so when we went for breakfast on a Saturday morning all the tables were taken - we were prepared to wait, but they cleared off a table just so we could sit right away!! (At this point, my heart was already full.)

I had never had siphon coffee before, so the owner's son (we never got his name but with my creepy detective skills, I think his name is Lawrence) told us all about how the process works while we watched him brew it right in front of us (it looks like a chemistry experiment!). I got the sumiyaki and my friend got the Jamaican blue coffee and Lawrence gave us the extras from both so that we could try each other's. Looking at the coffee, you can tell it's going to be the smoothest coffee you've ever had. I'm not even a regular coffee drinker, and when I do I usually have a latte, but I was able to drink the siphon coffee black (probably because it was also accompanied by a cute little chocolate-dipped shortbread cookie that is from the same Greek place they've been getting them from for the last 30 years). It's pricey but well worth it!

We also ordered the beef tomato rice which was like tomato egg rice (the ultimate classic Chinese comfort food) with corn/peas/carrots, beef, and ketchup. So so cozy. We also got the popular dumpling sampler; they were all plump and juicy and everything I wanted.

There was delicious homemade chili oil as well, which is a labor of love by Lawrence's brother who grinds the peppers himself and has to arm himself with goggles/gloves when he makes it. You can take some home for about $4 a container - do it and thank me later.

My friend and I were enjoying our morning slowly so by the end of the meal we had talked to Lawrence quite a bit. After we got the check he even gave us a slice of the cheesecake (I LOVE cheesecake so to say I was excited is an understatement) which was accompanied by coffee jelly and espresso beans. The cheesecake was smooth, creamy, and not too sweet. It was made by his brother who came up with a recipe from lots of Youtube research and taste testing by a friend who is also a cheesecake aficionado. 

The hospitality I experienced here reminded me of why I love Philly so much, and you can see how much pride the Ray family has in their cafe and how much care and intentionality was involved in the food/drinks from beginning to end (even in selecting the dishes/utensils). I hope it stays around for many many more years to come, and next time I'm in town it'll be my first stop!

text: Strictly Dumpling came here and raved about this place so I had high expectations. We ordered the salty tofu, sesame paste, Chinese sausage bun, and veggie bun. Portions were sizable and the price is amazingly low. The salty tofu had all the components I was looking for but it was weirdly bland and needed more salt or seasoning. The sesame paste was on point and had a depth of sesame flavor that I can never seem to get at American establishments. The buns were ok - I was disappointed to see how little filling was in both, and both needed more salt or seasoning.

text:
If you like great handmade noodles, you will LOVE this place. Got the dandan noodles to share with my partner, and I am actually not much of an Asian cuisine person, but they were absolutely fantastic. You can taste the care that was taken in making them in-house by hand, along with the sauce ingredients. A must-go for anyone, and their food prices are exceptional considering the noodles are well enough to share for 2 people (we did so and still left with leftovers).

That being said, don't waste your money on alcoholic drinks. Their cocktails were expensive and super small portions. But given that this is not a bar and the food was super exceptional and a place I will look forward to coming back to when I visit the city in the future, still 100% recommend.

text:
I heard a lot of great things about this place and want to give it another try but we were pretty underwhelmed by our first visit. 

The double Margherita pizza was a very good start to the meal. We followed that with two pastas and the wood fired pork chop. 

The Ferratini al frutti di mare was everyone's least favorite, it was very heavy on the marjoram and tasted very floral which was an odd flavor combo with the seafood. The pastas are small portions and the four of us left half of it on the plate. The carbonara was ok, the pasta seemed a little undercooked and it wasn't very flavorful. 

The wood fired pork chop was very tender and tasted good, but the sides of green beans and spinach were kind of bland and didn't add anything to the dish. 

The service was great, our server was attentive and gave good recommendations on the amount of food to order. 

Portions were small for the price point and quality.
