text:
Wow! I was blown away by this place - I really wasn't expecting much because I'm pretty picky about dimsum, but these dishes were reasonably priced and delicious. We got the 

Scallion pancakes (5/5): Thick but still crispy. I also thought the flavor was really spot on! Sometimes these can just taste greasy, but that wasn't the case here

Fried rice (5/5): Very standard fried rice, but well done! It had egg, onions, and chicken. Looked a bit plain at first because they don't add soy sauce, but the flavor was all there regardless! I also thought it was a great size.

Roasted pork bun: (3.5/5): I loved the buns! Fluffy dough and sweet pork, but I was sad about how much fat was in the first two buns. The first two probably had 60% fat and 40% lean meat inside, but the last one was absolutely perfect. Not a single piece of fat, just well-cooked, high quality meat.

Pork Soup Dumplings: (4/5) These were really good, the only reason I couldn't have given these 5/5 are because I've had Joe's dumplings in NY and those will always be the best to me! I also thought that there wasn't that much soup in some of them. Otherwise they were perfect though.

text:
I expected more from Sampan based on the hype and high ratings. Overall, the food was subpar and overly priced.

Edamame Dumpling - Average. I've had better dumpling from the frozen foods section at the Asian Supermarket.

Spicy Tuna Roll - Your average spicy tuna roll that's available at any sushi restaurant.

Pork Bao - Overcooked, overly salty meat. Bao was dry. 

Crispy Brussel Sprout - Tasty! Probably my favorite dish out of what we ordered.

Chicken Tikka Satay - The menu says it comes with yogurt, which was not brought out. The order comes with ONE stick of dry, under-seasoned chicken. 

General Tso Soup Dumpling - Think of a soup dumpling, but half its size, with a sprinkle of general tso flavor on it. 

Hamachi Ceviche - Delicious, but extremely small serving size. 

Ming Mule - Made perfectly!

Kantoi Road - Too sweet. Was expecting a stronger tamarind flavor.

text:
Amazing hot pot. The best I've had in Chinatown. Really fresh ingredients all around - we got both the beef combo and the seafood combo, and was impressed by the quality. The seafood platter even came out with an ice sculpture! Maybe a bit over the top, but still a nice touch.

We also ordered two servings of the noodles - very colorful, I think the flavors were purple yam, a vegetable one, and something else. We ordered a couple more things and the bill came to $50/pp ($200 total including tip, split between 4 people). To be honest I could have probably eaten a lot more because the food was so yummy, but we wanted bubble tea for dessert so I disciplined myself to stop. Plus, $50/pp is not cheap when the other hot pot we've had before averaged around $30/pp.

Our waitress was very helpful in giving us guidance on what to order, and kept us updated on the progress of our food coming out if we had been waiting for awhile. We ordered the heaven/hell hot pot with the tomato oxtail broth and the entry-level spicy (not spicy at all in my opinion but the 3 friends I was with said it was spicy enough for them). Our friends at the other table ordered the medium-level spicy and they said their mouths were burning, lol. 

My mouth is watering as I'm recalling our experience and how delicious all the food was. The price is worth the experience and quality of food.

text:
My wife and I found this place via Yelp (though being in Chinatown... there are lots of great options) and we were quickly seated in this fast-paced restaurant. Menus were the same as folding takeout menus and were quickly dropped off. I ordered pork noodles in a sauce (similar to Dan Dan noodles) and my wife had several dumplings and pastries, along with a bubble tea. Food came quickly, though each dish came out individually as it was prepared.

My noodles were great, and with the addition of chili oil were very springy and chewy. Since water refills were not a guaranteed thing, I went easy on the hot oil. My wife's dumplings were tasty, and the red bean bun reminded me of a croissant stuffed with the bean paste... not your typical item, but nice. Prices were reasonable. This isn't the place to stop by for a long, quiet meal but if you want good food quickly (and then need to exit quickly) it is a fine option.

text:
We needed a quick bite to eat and Canto House was still opened at around 5pm as other restaurants were in the process of closing. The menu was posted outside as the space inside to order was tight. Every order came with jasmine rice (which doesn't happen all the time!) and a side of greens 

Order: 
-BBQ pork rice: Really, really good. The pork was tender. In addition, the sauce added additional sweetness to the meat and the rice. The pork was thinly sliced so there was "more" to enjoy.
-Stir fry green bean and beef rice: Also very yummy! The beef was really tender. The green beans had the wonderful wok hay. The sauce was also very good. 

The portions were very good especially for the price. I think we paid less than $20 in total.

text:
Okay, as an Asian person, I was pretty impressed.  The food was good, pricey, yes, but very good. And it was beautifully plated to give off a "wow" factor for a few of the dishes. 

And it was pretty high quality!  Ingredients such as the steak were fresh and well-prepared, with "medium" being a true "medium," no more and no less. 

The two things I enjoyed most about Buddakan were the ambiance - it was a great environment to eat, mingle, and have fun - not too pretentious, but just upscale enough and the diversity of food choices - menu items ranged from the low $10s to $40-$50 depending on what you ordered, so you could get away with just doing small plates and not breaking the bank. 

I heard somewhere that this was the first Buddakan (feel free to fact check me) before they moved onto NYC (Chelsea market?) and my experience here confirmed that the food scene in Philadelphia truly punches above its weight. Not too pricey, extremely high quality. 

Finally, our server introduced herself and was pleasant and polite. Very knowledgeable and not too obtrusive. 

The standouts were the miso black cod and steak dishes (photos!)

text:
I always find time to visit here when I'm in town. I enjoy the history, the variety of shoppes, and the whole atmosphere of this marketplace. I can see why Reading Terminal Market has been in business for so long. Some of my favourite spots here are the tea shoppe, the beeswax candle shoppe, the General Store, the Mushroom shoppe, and Flying Monkey for their gluten free options. As a New Yorker I come here to stock up on items I cannot find near me, and it's also significantly more affordable. 

My only advice is to not visit during the Philadelphia Flower Show, because that's when the Market gets mobbed with tourists! This is especially true about the Donut Shoppe-my first visit to the Flower Show back in 2015, and my first trip to Philly. All I wanted to do was explore the Market, but there was a long line, a good kilometer (0.6 mile), wrapped around the outside of the building! Why? 'Cuz tourists wanted those famous donuts, that's why! XD:   But that's good for business so I'm not complaining 'bout that!

My only complaint is that (like many places in Center City Philadelphia) it closes too early (at 18:00 or 6pm) most days of the week (based on memory).  Otherwise I enjoy visiting and shopping in what feels like my eccentric Amish grandmother's farm stand.

text:
Went in for an authentic lunch.  Was greeted promptly and asked the waiter for a lunch recommendation.  After some back and forth he recommended the dry bamboo shoot with beef brisket.  He mention the menu price was wrong and it'd be ~25% more than the listed price.

It came out within minutes.  I mean suspiciously fast, like someone sent it back or they just have a big vat of it in the back and it's not made to order.  Didn't seem like it was the house specialty nor did anyone else in the restaurant have this at their table.  The dish was three measly pieces of beef with more fat than actual meat.  Didn't eat much of the rice and left hungry and disappointed.

text:
I went to Buddakan during restaurant week with two friends, and the three of us had quite different experiences with the food, so i would say your experience can really depend on what you order.
Given that it was restaurant week aka fixed price, if you opt for the "fancier dish" with more expensive ingredients, then naturally the portion size would be much smaller.
That being said, the food was quite good. The restaurant was very busy, as expected on a Saturday lunch during restaurant week. Make sure you have a reservation or you'll have to wait for a long time. Might come back for restaurant week but i think ordering normally may end up with a bill higher than i would like.

text:
I pretty much find Tom's Dim Sum to be a more convenient Dim Sum Garden - it has the same offerings of buns and dumplings while being less crowded and accepting credit card. I ordered pork soup dumplings, pan-fried Shanghai pork dumplings, and fried pork and cabbage dumplings to share with one other person. The server mistakenly brought us chive dumplings instead of cabbage since she might have misheard me, but I like them too and honestly didn't mind. Service was otherwise fast and effective, but not overly friendly as expected at a Chinese spot. 

The chive dumplings were plump and had nice chewy homemade wraps, and the pan-fried dumplings were super juicy. The soup dumplings more of the traditional style from what I know, being bigger and thicker-skinned than the little fancy Din Tai Fung style. I find that makes them easier to pick up without breaking, and the soup inside was thick and meaty. Overall it was an affordable and filling meal, though if my stomach had more room I would've ordered a veggie dish to balance out all the carbs and meat. 

I see a number of comments complaining that this place doesn't have the carts and deep-fried stuff typical of some other dim sum spots - that's because this is Shanghai-style dim sum, not Cantonese dim sum! Please do some research before publicly criticizing a small business like this!

text:
This place is awesome. Their sushi is good, and they actually put effort into their vegan dishes! My partner is able to choose from several different mock meats (get the mock chicken with garlic sauce, trust me). It's really nice that we are BOTH able to enjoy Chinese food despite food restrictions. Prices are about on par with other Chinese food places.

The staff is very friendly and polite, and online ordering through their website is always a breeze. The best part is that they have CRAZY fast delivery times within East Falls - every time we ordered, they got there in less than half an hour. It's awesome. We moved out of the area, but we will sorely miss our dear Shan Chaun.

text:
This place is the absolute best! We have been going for a long time (just after they relocated to their current spot), but it's gotten so popular and busy the past couple years. There would always be people lined up inside the restaurant waiting for a table.

Pretty much everything they have is delicious, and the best part is that because it's dim sum, you can try so many different items. The soup dumplings are the one thing you MUST get, though! They are the specialty here. Once you've stuffed yourself with so much delicious food, you will be surprised at how affordable the bill is. Especially if you're going with a bunch of people and sharing, this can actually be a very cheap meal for the incredible quality of food you get.

text:
So I get takeout for lunch here occasionally. I've found their food to always be fresh, delicious, and their portions to be reasonable for the lunch special price. Until today. Today I decided to try the jumbo shrimp with angel hair pasta. The price was $11, a little more than what I normally get but there was good news in GA so I was feeling celebratory. I was expecting a small portion of shrimp. It's a lunch special, after all, but the entire dish was small. And when I say small, I mean smaller than the pint sized soup I also got. I was incredibly disappointed in the amount of food for the price. Compared to the other dish I ordered, the four flavor beef, it was less than half the volume. 

I actually really love CinCin. I'm hoping this poor rating will get their attention and they will make this right. If they do, I'll post a follow up and adjust my rating.

text: Jane G's has a really great outdoor seating set up, efficiently utilizing the sidewalk space to build several booths that are made cozy with overhead heaters. I dined there with two others tonight and really enjoyed the dumpling variety! We had soup dumplings, truffle edamame dumplings, chicken shiitake dumplings, and wontons in soup. We did order non-dumpling items as well (string beans, three cup chicken, pork buns (controversial q - is a bun a dumpling?), and scallion pancakes. All items were cooked well, super tasty, and reasonably priced. Our waiter was very friendly as well. I am glad that this neighborhood staple is persevering in the pandemic!

text:
Found this spot by accident and made a mental note to try them out the next time I was craving neighborhood chinese food. 

Tonight was the night! Ordered fried dumplings, which appeared homemade. The flavors were good albeit a bit greasy for my liking. Next time I'll get them boiled and drown them in that delicious house dumpling sauce. That was the star. It had tang, spice and savory sweetness. Perfect combo to drown those morsels in.

Also ordered shrimp in lobster sauce and it was excellent. The shrimp were larger than I expected and the sauce with the pork fried rice was bomb.

This was pretty good quality at exceptional prices. I will definitely order again!

text:
This is a small restaurant so space is limited preCovid no dining in. The restaurant is clean and you can see the cook. I love to watch them make my food. 

I've been here several times since moving to Brewerytown and I love it. The meat and vegetables are fresh so that's a plus for sure. My food is hot whether I order and pickup or have it delivered.  There's never a lot of people inside and that's great considering the times we live in. 

The lady that takes the order is very professional and keeps you updated on your order. Every time I pickup she's there so I like to give her a tip because she deserves it probably more. 

Overall I come here for authentic Chinese food and if you're like me and you want tasty, quality and presentation of food is important than this is the place for you. 

Btw the prices are not high at all.

text:
So happy this place was open for indoor dining!
I've been craving dim sum for awhile and didn't feel like eating outside in the cold. This was our first time here and I loved the selection of dim sum on the menu. They even had a page just for vegan options which my vegan + vegetarian friend really appreciated :)
We came in for lunch and it wasn't that busy so we felt very safe. The staff wore masks and glasses and took down our order. The only disappointing thing was that some of the items on the menu I wanted to try they didn't have but it's fine!! There was so many things we got instead.
We got a variety of items from shrimp shumai, pork/shrimp shumai, pork+crab soup dumplings, pan fried pork soup dumplings, scallion pancakes, vegetable steamed dumplings, crystal shrimp dumplings, pork belly + mustard greens and vegetable tofu soup. 
My favs were both the shumais! Both were stuffed with pork and shrimp and were juicy/delicious. I did like the pork and shrimp soup dumplings but the broth wasn't as flavorful as I would like. Scallion pancakes were nice and flaky (yum!). The pan fried pork soup dumplings were okay I didn't like how it was doughy but it tasted good inside.
We got a beautiful pot of tea with jasmine tea. We got tons of food and prices weren't bad either! We all got to take food home since we ordered so much. I would love to come back here again when my next dim sum craving hits!

text:

Spring Roll - Nothing special
Duck Samosa - Idk what I was thinking, this is not an Indian restaurant 
Calamari Salad - Chewy Calamari
Crispy Rock Shrimp - Inconsistent flavor profile

I won't be returning anytime soon, hopefully Doubleknot doesn't fall victim to the same fate

text:
Look. I'm reviewing this place during the soft opening week. So I can't judge everything. 

But I can judge the food taste based on what I had while checking out the new casino. 

The space is nice. That's to be expected. 

I tried the spicy tuna roll and the pork and shrimp dumplings. I took it out to my car to eat right away instead of inside so I still got it pretty fresh. 

I will say the tuna roll wasn't bad. It was fresh. It wasn't terribly spicy. I ate that happily. It won't confuse me with any higher priced sushi specialist places in the city but pretty good is a win here. 

The dumplings were decent but not spectacular. Definitely overpriced for the amount and quality you get in return. 

Nothing here would make me give up a trip to Chinatown to come here instead. But if I happened to be here, I'd probably go for the tuna roll again to nibble on.

text:
I ordered a single sampler (dumplings, roll, side) through the curbside kitchen app for $13.95, a day in advance. Unfortunately at the pick up time,  they were out of the crispy edamame side so I got truffle fries instead. 

The dumplings were hot and greasy. Most of the fillings were juicy. There were two drier fillings but those had decent flavor. There were a couple dumplings with spots of hard dough which was slightly unpleasant. The green dumplings were tasty but there was too much dough compared to the filling.

The Mac and cheese egg roll sounds like a fun concept. However, the pasta was close to mushy and the filling was much drier than I expected. There was a good cheese flavor, but I really missed the saucy-ness of Mac and cheese. It was okay to try once but I would not order again. 

The truffle fries were the best part of the sampler. Crispy, salty, and a bit of crunch from the scallion. 

It is a filling portion size for approx $14. If you're actually craving dumplings - you can find better tasting dumplings elsewhere for that price or less. But if you're hungry and looking for a greasy food truck vibe - this is a fair pick for a meal.

text:
Just came here for dine in last Friday and had a great experience!

COVID setup is great outside. One use menus, everyone was wearing masks and the warmth was quite reasonable in the outdoor cubicles. 

Pretty big menu which made it a bit hard to decide, but something for everyone with lots of staple Chinese dishes. We had two carafes of sake for drinks. Would have been nice to have warm sake in the cold weather but that wasn't an option. We had pork soup dumplings and vegetarian dumplings for an appetizer. Delicious and served quickly with a nice sauce on the side. We ordered about 7 dishes total and we asked them to come out as they were ready but in retrospect that was a mistake. Things came out very quickly and filled up the table. Especially in the cold weather this made things a bit cold, so make sure you tell them to bring them out slowly. 

Dan Dan noodles were excellent as well. Not too spicy but still with a nice kick of flavor. Also had pork belly with mustard greens which came with some bok choy as well. Meat was delicious and tender and came with supplies to make little bao buns which were nice. Eggs and tomatoes were simple and well done as was the garlic eggplant. Last was the snow pea leaves which were again, very simply but done very well. 

Prices were higher than China town but quality was just as good, so I suppose to be expected of a Rittenhouse restaurant. If you're looking for China Town type food but with a slightly nicer atmosphere, definitely recommend checking them out!

text:
Solid Chinese food for a great price. I was in the mood of what I consider the American "classic" Chinese food - egg roll, general tso's- the whole comfort food experience. 

I ordered delivery and had no issues as far as ordering or delivery. Food arrived on time with everything we asked for! 

We ordered the Dumpling soup - this was unexpectedly my favorite. It had the SLIGHTEST kick to the broth and the dumpling were definitely homemade. We also ordered sesame chicken and chicken with garlic sauce with fried rice on the side. All the chickens were great - highly recommend the chicken with garlic sauce - it's a little spicy but nothing overwhelming and is with peppers and broccolis, really tasty.  The platter combos also came with fried rice and egg rolls. The fried rice was not my favorite, but still good. (Everyone has a different palette!) The egg rolls were exactly as expected and what we wanted. 

Overall great experience and would order again.

text: New Leaf 2 on Main St deserves more then 5 stars! Excellent quality, goodbye mystery meat, hello white meat! I've been a local to the area for 20 years and see lots to restaurants come and go from this spot, New Leaf 2 is here to stay, great  customer service and 20-30 min wait times, can't be beat. This is a GEM that "yunkers" will be glad to have stick around!

text:
small sampler plates that are a great price especially during happy hour!
-Edamame Dumpling: made up of truffle, pea shoots, and sake broth, this was definitely surprisingly really good. The inside has mushy pea shoots and a distinct truffle flavor, wrapped in delicate dumpling wrapper and soaked in an aromatic broth
-Pork Bao: definitely the best small plate. I personally love pork belly and the shallot and mint added such a distinct flavor. The bun was also extremely fluffy and the flavor of the pork was oh so delicious
-Kim Chee Fried Rice: Can never go wrong with this! The poached egg was really amazing and mixed in well with the rice and I LOVE those baby shrimps. Perfect tempura crunch things on the top as well
-Crispy Brussel Sprout: the puffed rice was good and I love Brussel sprouts, but they over did it on the sauce and it was a bit too salty
-Kobe Sliders: were a bit disappointing; the best part was honestly the toasted-to-perfection buns
-Wagyu Beef Satay: also a bit disappointing; wasn't bad, but I expected some higher quality wagyu and the portion was also wayyy too small. It is what it is though

text: I have ordered several times from here and havent had a dish that I didnt like. I usually order from home stir fry or chef special section. All dishes are authentic and actually have distinct taste. Szechuan style is pretty  spicy if thats what you're looking for; I have asked for less spice before and they were able to accommodate it. Slightly on the pricey side but the quality is definitely good and quantity is generous for Philly.

text: Ordered a delivery of the famous spicy pork soup dumplings and fish in spicy sauce. The soup dumplings tasted much better in the restaurant then by delivery as was getting cold. text: Good service but I'm not really sure where the hype for this place came from. I read tons of good reviews but when I went there, it was just an overpriced gentrified dim sum house. None of it tasted like dim sum... they serve the dishes on asian plates and in steamers to give it that asian aesthetic feel but the food was not satisfying at all. Everything we got was really sweet (maybe that was the Jewish twist?) and lacked flavor. My party of 5 and I were quite disappointed. Am I shocked to find an over glorified and gentrified dim sum house in the middle of philly?? Nah. I just expected the flavors to maybe be there with all the hype. I hope people that come here don't actually think this is what dim sum is supposed to taste like. If you're going to be a fusion, maybe make it more clear you're a fusion and not a dim sum place.

text: Not impressed at all.  It's just overpriced Chinese food.  I was really looking forward to liking this place after recommendation.  There's no way basic bland eggrolls should be $4 each. It was not only gummy but they left big slices of orange peels in it I had to pick out. Too many onions in rice.  I don't see myself ordering again.

text: Every table had guests, not one table was skipped to follow social distancing guidelines. The servers forgot to bring some of the food we ordered and didn't check back on us. We had to flag them down twice ask for our drinks and the missing food. The food itself was not tasty and overpriced. The rice was extremely too salty and the vegetable dumplings were flavorless. To make matters worse, there was a roach walking on the wall! Please don't waste your time going here. Extremely disappointing.

text:
I'm thinking my review could be a solid 3.5 , the restaurant is better than three stars but definitely not four stars. 

We started with appetizers, i ordered the crab rangoon (fried perfectly but way too much cream cheese and barely any crab) , my husband ordered cheesesteak egg rolls (blasphemy I know but he loves a cheesesteak egg roll and enjoyed them) For the main course I ordered shrimp mei fun, it was surprisingly delicious . My husband had the general tso chicken, he also enjoyed the meal . I also had a glass of wine (cupcake rose $10 a glass ) to toast and my husband had a cocktail (a little larger than a shot) I think it was called a crawling tiger, the meal was $85 before the tip. I have to agree with the other reviewer, the food is overpriced.

text: As a new restaurant in a casino it's expected for them to work out some kinks.  But I can reassure you that they put thought and care into everything.  The ambiance is trendy and modern with neon lights and geisha wall art.  The price is high but that's expected for being in the casino.  We ordered here twice and both times we ordered the Crispy Chilean Sea bass!  OMG!  Delicious!  Crispy perfection with a sweet and tangy sauce.  Also, the Sashimi martini was fresh and definitely a great appetizer.  Service was incredible!

text: Is it me or is dim sum hard to find even in Chinatown? Well the good news is that Ocean Harbor sells all your classic dim sum dishes at a very, very affordable price. The best part is that they offer dim sum takeout ALL DAY. No dine in service available at this time even with the indoor dining ban lifted. My personal favorite was their siu mai. For what you pay, you really can't complain. I will be back in the near future for more affordable dim sum. Make sure to call ahead and place your orders!

text:
So the reason I'm giving a 3 instead of a 4 is because I thought the food was just ok.

The part that got me was that the food was so salty and there was a lot of rice. When I bite into the roll, it's just... rice. A good roll should have a nice ratio of rice and sauce and crunch (none of these had crunch even though the description mentions crunch) and fish. I was extremely full eating half of my order but just from... rice. 

Another thing that bothered me was that I LOVE wasabi. I eat as much wasabi as a Japanese person probably. I like to have at least a tip of a chopstick amount of wasabi per sushi roll, but when I got my order, I received a LOT of soy sauce but only about 2 bean size amounts of wasabi (if you look at my photos, you can barely see the wasabi). It's one thing to give too much, but to barely have enough wasabi for my order was disappointing. 

On top of it all, these rolls aren't cheap. I got 3 rolls for $42 on Grubhub. For the price I pay, I expect better quality. And I've eaten a lot of sushi in my life so when I don't like something that means I really don't like it. 

The reason I give 3 stars is because the overall flavors are ok and they're quick with my order. But the biggest factors that make it a 3 and not a 4 or 5 are mentioned above. 

Would I come here again? It's hard to say. Was this just a bad day for them? Was their original chef somewhere else? These are things to consider, but experience today was subpar to say the least.

text:
Saloon is an amazing experience. Everything about it is just so old school and traditional Italian. From the menu offerings to the actual decor (big wooden bar that spans a sizeable part of the restaurant as soon as you walk in, lots of dark and rich tones in the furniture, and of course the food being served on multiple floors just fills the building with the irresistible Italian cuisine aroma.)

It is in the heart of South Philly, always crowded with great people. Love the energy in this restaurant. 

You are going to spend some decent money here, it can be a bit pricey if you are just seeking Italian food, but in my opinion, it is all worth it!

Service was fantastic but could not make up for the lackluster food. The broth was mediocre. The watercress came wilted. It's good that they allowed me to send it back. Also the minced garlic wasn't fresh and was soaked in some sort of liquid. This meal cost over $50 for one person making it a poor value.

text:
I come for HH here once or twice a month and never can get enough of this place. One of the best spots in town for HH. The menu is well priced and very extensive. HH portions are big enough. 
I am a vegan and can always find few items for myself. They usually are willing to customize some of their items for my needs, as well. The staff here is very polite and well-trained! Very nice and professional floor management, as well. 
For some reason every time my friends and I try to pick a place for a HH, we always land here. 
FYI Reservation is made through resy and HH is outside, but the place has covered booths and heaters.

text:
Best noodles in Philly. I've ordered from Nan Zhou a handful of times in the last few months, and they never disappoint. If you're looking for savory and authentic Chinese noodles at a very reasonable price, definitely get Nan Zhou.

We ordered the
Szechuan Cold Noodle with Original Hand-Pulled Style noodles
Noodle with Peanut Sauce with Original Hand-Pulled Style noodles
Tomato with Egg on Noodles with Shaved Style noodles

These dishes definitely gave us a good variety of flavor, and the portions are fantastic;  You can't go wrong with these dishes -- especially if you add their chili oil. The noodle texture in all dishes were perfect; the hand-pulled noodles are very long and have a good, springy bite. The shaved style noodles are thick and chewy and go great with the tomato egg and some of their soups.

Overall, I'd strongly recommend Nan Zhou and I'm excited to get it again!

text: We went on a Tuesday night for dinner and ate outside in the private chalets. The outdoor seating was extremely warm (no jackets necessary) and felt very safe, they did a great job with the setup. We did go on a night on which there were only 3 other tables outside, but the service was great. The servers were extremely polite and quick. We ordered the general tso's soup dumplings, the chicken and ginger dumplings, slow roasted short rib, wasabi crusted filet, and the whole peking duck. The soup dumplings and the wasabi filet were great and had amazing flavor. The peking duck was good too, the skin was crispy and it came with hoisin sauce and small wraps. The chicken dumplings were okay, nothing special. Same with the slow roasted short rib, we were told it was a new addition to the menu but it wasn't very good. Overall, the price is a little high for the type of food they serve, but it is definitely a good option for asian fusion.

text: Went to try Luk Fu for my birthday, I've been waiting to try it since Live opened up so I was excited to go. The service was great and VERY attentive, but the food was just average. We had the shrimp and pork dumplings and cheesesteak spring rolls, both were good but would have liked a bit more than 4 dumplings and 3 spring rolls. As for the main entrees I had the General Tso's Chicken, which was good, but just average at best. I asked if I could get fried rice instead of the white rice, but was told no so that was a downer. The rest of the party had the Pepper Steak which once again was good, but average and the portion size could have been WAY bigger; finally we also had the Fat Beef Pho which was good, but the beef was WAY too fatty even though our waiter said it wasn't too fatty and just the name. Honestly I would say the overall experience was just average and if I want Chinese food next time I'm down at Live, I would stick with the Sangkee in the food court for probably half the price for regular Chinese food, if you want noodles this place would be a good choice for you at Live. If you are willing to take the ride down Broad St toward Chinatown, I'd say go there for better food and at a fraction of the cost.

text:
Chubby Cattle has to be one of my top favorite hot pot places to date! Their service and dishes are of high quality whenever I visit. They offer a great selection of fresh meats and we opted for the Wagyu Beef Platter. You just need a quick dip in the broth to enjoy the fattiness of the wagyu. When I say, it melts in your mouth, I am not lying! Not to mention their noodles are handmade as well. Definitely recommend the Noodle Combo so you have the opportunity to try the tomato, purple yam, and green tea noodle. And let's not forget about the Wagyu Uni Nigiri. That stuff melts like butter the second you taste it. I have never had something this yummy before! 

If you haven't tried Chubby Cattle yet, you're missing out. This place may be pricey, but their quality is what you're coming for!

text:
I'm a long-time resident of Philadelphia and have heard many things about Dim Sum Garden. My Asian friends call it "Americanized", my non-Asian friends say it's the best Chinese food they've had in town; all of if which is true. After biting the bullet and trying the place out, I've come to fall somewhere in the middle of these thoughts. 

Dim Sum Garden is a great place for foodies looking to dip their toes in Chinese cuisine. The menu and English-speaking staff make it much more approachable than other authentic establishments in the area and is a huge haven for those who don't speak Cantonese or Mandarin but, would really like some dim sum. As a Chinese American and someone who grew up on dim sum, the quality and flavor of the food was nowhere near the caliber of any of the dim sum establishments nearby.  The food had little to no seasoning and the prices were far greater than they should be. The only thing on the menu that I think is okay is the soup dumplings; everything else is better elsewhere.

It's also important to note that this establishment does not follow CDC guidelines. The entire restaurant was packed at full capacity, no seats were reserved to provide social distancing, staff had masks covering only their mouth, and there was no protocol at all to keep food from being contaminated. In fact, some waiters placed other's people food on our table as they were they serving.

text:
Szechuan is one of my favorite cuisines - and EMei will now be a staple in my diet.   

Before we get into specific dishes, my feedback overall is: if you are used to spicy food / if you order 8-10 at Han, make sure you specify you want spicy. The food was DELICIOUS and it had great  Szechuan peppercorn / chili oil flavoring, but I would have liked everything a bit spicer. I didn't specify any spice level as I wanted to try as-is for my first time. 

Must order:
Dan Dan - really great flavor. The noodles are much thinner than what I'm used to from other dan dan recipes, and it's a totally different flavor. Less nutty flavored and more Szechuan peppercorn. Really delicious. 

Cumin Beef - My fiance got this and I was only allowed to steal one bite because he enjoyed it so much. The beef seems to be seared / dry fried in a delicious cumin flavoring. I usually get cumin chicken and I might be a convert to cumin beef moving forward. Very flavorful + great portion! 

Thinly sliced beef in hot & spicy sauce - ( This is a similar dish to the Hot Sauce Beef from han, just with a different name). This is what I ordered and first off the portions are HUGE - I got THREE meals out of this. It came piping hot that I burnt my entire tongue off- just the way I like it! Now the flavor profile...was so, so amazing. Tons of raw garlic and napa cabbage and meat in the most delicious sauce. It had that lovely numbing effect that I love about Szechuan Peppercorns. I enjoyed every bite, of all 3 meals I got from this.  The only thing I didn't love was it came with a big pile of cilantro stems + leaves on top (not a big cilantro fan) but luckily I was able to remove the whole pile easily before diving in. 

If you want steamed rice for either entree dish it costs extra, which I also thought was odd, but it was only $1. 

Hot & Sour Soup - This was the best hot & sour soup I've had. And it was only $2. I will be dreaming of this soup for days to come.  

As for the restaurant ambiance, the place is so clean, cute, and classy! I loved the teapot, tea cups, & complimentary Green tea itself, and loved the whole feng shui of the dining area. The service was stellar & everyone was so nice as well! 

Can't wait to come back!

I will never order here again, I want my money and my tip back. This is ridiculous.

text:
This place is the go-to spot for dumplings and bao in Philadelphia. Albeit, I have not tried that many places, but if there were something better I am sure I would have heard about it by now. You cannot go wrong with this place as the food is delicious and the prices are more than reasonable. 

Food 4.5/5: our group ordered the vegetable dumplings, the Mapo Tofu, and the vegetable Bao. These three items packed a punch of flavor and authenticity that cannot be put into words. We were hoping that the food would be a little more spicy as we enjoy the spice, however they were able to give us some sriracha on the side to help with that. The reason why it doesn't get a 5/5 is because we had also ordered bubble tea, which you should avoid at this location. The bubble tea did not taste as good as we had hoped and they forget to include the tapioca pearls (but they re-made it for us and included it the second time). For vegetarians, this is a good spot because of the numerous options that they have. 

Service 5/5
The service is also great  as we came at noon on a Thursday. Therefore, we didn't have to wait and we were able to seat ourselves inside. You can tell the staff work very hard because they were constantly moving around bringing food and water to different tables. Our server was great, we did not catch his name however. 

Ambience 3/5
Honestly, not much to say for ambience. Beside for the Asian food and the chopsticks, I couldn't tell I was in an Asian restaurant. It was clean and quite so I cannot complain. The bathrooms are kept tidy, but not perfectly clean. 

Tips:
This place does not take card so you have to pay with cash. This was a little inconvenient because that meant we had to use their atm in the restaurant which charged an additional fee. 

Parking- your best bet is to park on the streets in Chinatown. There is usually 2-3 hour parking across the neighborhood. We had an easy time finding parking but we also came in the middle of the day, so I am not sure what parking at night would be like.

text: I grew up in NYC so I love all the dim sum options. I was craving it when I was in the city and heard about this place since they have one in Chinatown in NY as well. I decided to dine in, they have hand sanitizer at the entrance and tables were spread out. There was no one else dining in at that time. I got shrimp rice roll, the rice roll with chinese donut, the cha siu bao, shrimp crystal dumplings. The rice rolls had a strange texture, a little too delicate. The chinese donut was too crunchy. The bao was expensive but it was very tasty. The shrimp dumplings were good, but the skin was a little thicker than others. I also got the pork shumai and sticky rice in lotus leaf to go. Those were pretty good even eaten the next day. Overall I was not impressed, especially for the price, I've honestly had better dimsum from some of the other bakeries in chinatown that are not dimsum restaurants.

text: I ordered from Chowbus here, and the order was prepared quickly. Unfortunately, the flavor of the dishes left more to be desired. The only great dish I had here was the cold gluten - must get! Everything else - The scallion noodle and shanghai noodle were both a tad too oily and a bit bland - felt like it needed a little something more. The sauce in the sesame noodle was a bit too heavy handed with the peanut butter/sesame and could've used some diluting. I'm grateful that they have an option for vegetable dumplings, which was filled with a good portion of filling - however, this definitely lacked some flavor and needed a dipping sauce to complete it. However, great thing is that it's a good price for a good portion size and vegetarian options are available.

text:
The food here is so good!!! Everything I've tried has been phenomenal. I haven't been there to dine in (I  only discovered it during Covid) but I have ordered take out several times. I like that I  can order right from their website. 
The scallion pancakes are really good. They have a chewier texture than most and that's something that I like. 
I've tried the steamed sliced pork belly with with Chinese pickle and it blew me away. The pork was so tender and the flavor was incredible. I probably would not have picked that off the menu but my friend wanted to try and it was a good call! 
The cold chicken with bone in spicy sauce is nice and spicy. A lot of chili oil in that dish that I  saved and used for other things because I couldn't let that deliciousness go to waste. 
The chongqing chicken is probably the best I've had. Crispy and spicy. Lots of red peppers but more chicken than peppers which is nice. A lot of times when you order that dish from other restaurants it's deceiving because the portion ends up being mostly peppers. 
I got the sister dish to that which is the fried fish fillet with dry red pepper. This was also amazing, but I probably prefer the chicken. 
They also have American Chinese food as well. I must admit, I love sweet and sour pork. I cant help it! Sometimes I  just get a craving and I did get it from here and it was exactly what I needed. 
This place has become my go to for good Chinese. I cant wait to be able to dine in. I want to try their frog legs!! 
Also delivery ordered straight from their website has been reliable and fast. The prices are a little higher than the average Chinese restaurant, but this is not an average restaurant. You get what you pay for. This is high quality, delicious Chinese food. I dont think the prices are unjustified. Well, well worth it.

text:
We ate here outdoor at the tail end of covid (March 2021). Unfortunately, even though we had a reservation, we were seated on the sidewalk instead of in one of the cool booths in the structure they created during covid. 
We went for happy hour and our server was really great in allowing us to order multiple drinks before happy hour ended. However, the food was just alright and didn't match expectations
Kimchi Fried Rice: this was the best thing we had. It was a good happy hour deal as you do get a lot of rice with a lot of shrimp in it.
Brussel Sprouts: decent but seemed a tad burnt to me
-Kobe hot dog bites: these were meh. The hot dog itself was good but it was just topped with a dab of mustard and the buns were pretty boring (didn't seem toasted or anything).

The only thing we got that wasn't on happy hour were the general tsos soup dumplings which were actually really good and flavorful! But seemed a little overpriced for the 4 that you get.

Overall the service was good and the fried rice was a good deal on happy hour but nothing really blew us away.

text: I love Reading Terminal Market. It has something for everyone and is a culinary delight. My only drawback is mostnof the items are over priced but that's to be expected in center city. I also don't like that police officers take up most of the parking around the buildings so it could be problematic on a busy day. However if you are new to Philly the Reading Terminal will be a good philly gem to visit and hang out with locals from all walks.

text:
You cannot miss in the RTM. If you like donuts, I highly recommend Beiler's - it's definitely our favorite. But you really cannot go wrong with eating anywhere in here. I've tried a ton of places and have never been disappointed.

text:

text:
Took me a while to find a true Vegetarian Chinese restaurant after my favorite one closed down 2 yrs ago.

They have decent prices and portion sizes. Their noodles honestly can serve 2 and all of their appetizers are, well, quite appetizing.

I recommend picking 3 appetizers instead of just 1 entree. Be prepared to wait upto an hour for your food to be ready, but it's worth it. The workers are also very nice and accommodating.

text:
The spicy fish was not as spicy and numbing as I would like from Szechuan restaurant. The string beans is nicely seasoned. It's good for the price but not good enough for me to go back. 

水煮魚完全沒有麻辣，味道很淡，勾芡很重，魚片吃不出鮮味，不會在點一次。

text:
Finally came back to Sampan for happy hour after three years. They have excellent value food and drinks during happy hour. 

Highly recommend: satay beef, kimchi fried rice (good portions, has lots of shrimp, and very flavorful)
Good but not mind-blowing: edamame dumplings
Meh: chicken satay (rather bland)

My friend tried the Thai punch and loved it. 

So glad they took strict covid precautions and offered outdoors seating. 

Overall great value for happy hour! Hoping to try their other small plates in the future when I visit Philly.

text:
*WOULD RECOMMEND FOR HOTPOT*

If you're looking for a decent all you can get hotpot and/or kbbq place for a good value in Philly Chinatown, this place for you! They have a large selection of meat, seafood, vegetables, and noodles that you can get for both, though I think the selection for hotpot is larger and better than Kbbq. You use your phone to scan the QR code to get the list of all ingredients you can get and just tell the waiter whatever you want, and of course you can order as you go as well. 

*DINNER*
Hotpot - I've had their kimchi broth, original broth, and tomato broth, and so far, my favorite is the tomato (sweet, savory, and sour). I love their selection of fishballs and seafood (they even have crab!) Their meat is fresh, did not come out frozen unlike other places I've been, lean and not as fat (though personally, I prefer fattier cuts). I don't think you can really go wrong with hotpot.

Kbbq - Their selection is a bit more limited than Kbbq, but definitely have the classic bulgogi, galbi, pork belly, as well as unique meats like duck and pork chop. The meats was fresh. Personally I wasn't the biggest fan of bbq because I think the seasoning were all the same. Plus the meat like pork belly were all thinly sliced and i prefer thicker pieces for fattier meats like that.

*VERDICT*
I would go back again for hotpot for sure

text:
This spot offers outdoor and indoor seating now. The interior is beautiful and well designed. The staff was attentive and fast.

The food was pretty good. The first thing we got were the dumplings. The dumpling filling itself seems like pork and was alright. Could've done with tiny but more seasoning and something like chives would've been nice. That chili oil it was in was amazing though. It gave a nice amount of heat with a hint of sweetness to cut through it all. Absolutely delicious chili oil.

The Taiwanese pork belly burger (on a lotus bun) left me a little mixed. The pork belly was bursting with flavorful and paired well with the garnishes. The crumbled peanuts didn't feel like it added too much, maybe if they were roasted peanuts it might have been better. The main reason I had some reservations on this dish was because of the bun. Usually they are soft and airy, but this one was a bit tough. If the bun was better this dish would have been amazing!!

The dry pepper chicken was pretty good. It wasn't as spicy as I thought it would be and less spicy than the noodles we got. The chicken was super crispy and absorbs the flavors really well. It does get a bit too overwhelming with the saltiness the more you eat.

The noodles were pretty good. The sliced braised beef shined on top of this mountain of long noodles. Every bite into the soft braised beef bursted with flavor. I only wish the noodles were slightly shorter or cut in half cause they are really long and could be a bit messy if you slip. The chili oil that these noodles are in was alright. Some heat and as with some Sichuan dishes numbing heat. There wasn't too much flavor with the chili oil, but it was spicier than the chicken. Still my favorite chili oil was in the dumplings.

All in all a great place to try different spicy dishes. Everything was well worth the price and they give some great portions. Certainly worth trying out.

text: This is hands down the best dining experience I've had in Philadelphia in the 6 years I've lived here. From the drinks to the unique food options to the impeccable service, it was a delight from start to finish. If you want to feel like royalty for a few hours, come here. The cost is worth it. Also, if you're a vegetarian like me, you will not be disappointed. Be sure to ask for the tofu buns. They are not on the menu but they make them special for vegetarian diners and they were divine. I am so happy I took my boyfriend here for his birthday - it was a night to remember!! They have very safe and cozy outdoor seating and do temperature checks. I can't wait to dine inside and see the interior that everyone raves about once I feel safe doing so. Go Buddakan!!

text:
The first time I had Han Dynasty was pre-Covid years ago and the food was really great. Last night we ordered takeout via Grubhub and it was ready for pickup in 10 minutes. So a star or 2 for being ready so fast! 

We ordered Dan Dan noodles, Chicken Dumplings,  House Special Fried Rice and Spring Rolls. 

Dan Dan and House Special Fried Rice are always winners for me. They have the only Fried rice that doesn't require you to douse it in soy sauce. So good and flavorful! Now those spring rolls? I'll pass on buying those again. They were super small. I mean they could fit in a kid's hand and bland. Not worth the $5 price tag..Nor were the Dumplings. The small box had 4 dumplings for $8 and just weren't very good.  

I won't count them out but the experience of dining in here is just so much better. Food tends to lose its luster once its thrown into takeout containers. Sigh.

text:
A small spot in Chinatown that serves an amazing Three Treasure Rice with very nice and hardworking employees.

The Three Treasure Rice comes in those styrofoam boxes filled with rice, some veggies, two types of their delicious ducks, and roasted pork that just melts in your mouth. This also comes with a soup. These glistening jewels bursts with flavor and leave you stuffed. The only slight down side is that the duck skin isn't as crispy as I'd like, but still delicious. All the flavor and juices gets soaked into the rice and vegetables making them a rich and soaked with flavor.

The whole roasted duck itself fills up two containers is just as delicious. The same downside is that the duck skin isn't as crispy as I'd like it to be. The crispy skin can really make it break a good roasted duck, but the great flavors make up for it a little.  I love that they give you a cup of sauce for each half or container, sometimes places only give you one.

It's a great place to grab lunch or get some duck for dinner or an event. It's well worth the price and I can't wait to go back for more.

text:
(Four stars means "I would make a special trip just to eat there again".)

I did not know there was a Sichuan restaurant in this neighborhood.  We were very excited to go and we were not disappointed.  The menu has many dishes I have never tried before, not just Americanized dishes.  I got twice-cooked pork belly, which is stir fried with leeks My companion got a beautiful dish of spicy shredded beef and dried Sichuan peppers, scallions, Sichuan peppercorns, and garlic.  We also bought a bottle of water and a carton of soy milk.  Total cost was around $30, and we brought half the food home to eat later.  I plan to certainly return.

They have a 5% discount for cash

Caution: the web site claims they have outdoor seating.  They have outdoor seating for exactly *two* people.

text:
Called in takeout for dinner for the first time with my brother. It was quick - 20min and it was done. Dine-in isn't an option yet - when we pulled up, there was a line of a few people. They've got a table set up at the front door to provide you with your order. It's definitely a COVID-safe experience.

We both ordered the Maki Combo which came with soup and salad - the soup was the best we'd had from any place we've gotten sushi - it had a healthy amount of tofu and seaweed. He ordered the crunchy spicy salmon, spicy crunchy tuna, and the screaming 1. He really liked the crunchy spicy tuna and salmon; he wasn't as big of a fan of the screaming 1 as the avocado was overwhelming. I ordered the crunchy spicy salmon, salmon avocado, and screaming 2. I really enjoyed the crunch spicy salmon but not as much the others with avocado - the avocado was overwhelming; next time I'll probably stick with the crunch spicy rolls. OH and our order did come with fortune cookies which I'm a sucker for.

I've been looking for a reasonably priced sushi place and found that through Lucky Star. Overall, it wasn't the best sushi we've had but it was good. For the attached picture, the lighting wasn't great so you can't tell but the sushi's colors were vibrant.

text:
Buddakan is a nice Asian fusion restaurant in Philadelphia's Old City, right near Independence Hall.

The cuisine is an Americanized Chinese-Japanese-Korean fusion, offering items such as dumplings, tuna sashimi pizza, calamari salad, bibimbap, black pepper beef, pan-seared sea bass, spare ribs, and more. The black pepper beef was by far my favorite with tender beef chunks in a sweet and savory sauce. The other items we tried were ok but not remarkable.

We are outdoors on the sidewalk which was perfect for a day with good weather. The indoor dining feels more upscale, with dim lighting and a giant golden Buddha statue overshadowing the main room. The service was friendly and prompt.

Overall a fine experience. For the slightly upscale price, the quality of the dishes could've been better. But feel free to check it out and try for yourself if this style of cuisine appeals to you!

text:
Pho and ramen get all of the noodle-soup hype, but Chinese beef noodle soup needs more love and Nan Zhou is the place to get it. Beef noodle soup is a relatively simple dish without any crazy toppings or spices (unless you order the one spicy version), with a deeply meaty broth and chewy handmade noodles. No sucker punches or fancy colors here, just a warm hug in your belly. Beef noodle soup is literally served as fast food in China, and I wish there was a Nan Zhou type place in every neighborhood over here!

For every noodle dish, you're offered the choice between hand-drawn (thinner and ramen-like) or shaved (broad and fat like chow fun) noodles; everyone I know has their preference but I ALWAYS get hand-drawn. I used to get literally the simplest of the soups - sliced beef noodle soup - but now go for the House Special soup that comes with a variety of meats, including some remarkably delicious meatballs. On hotter days, the Szechuan and Sesame Cold Noodles are more refreshing and feature the same yummy noodles. The signature noodle dishes are big and affordable, but if you somehow have more room, the dumplings and pig ears (spicy, chewy, and meaty) are great appetizers to share.

For a homely Chinatown spot, the dining area is actually quite nice and spacious. However, as a homely Chinatown spot, they only take cash and more recently Venmo (though you might need to get up to ask to Venmo), so come prepared. I've seen all sorts of diners here from families to tourists to loud BYO students - beef noodle soup is welcoming to all!

text:
Wow, this place is straight out of my childhood trips to China when my grandma would go out before I woke up and get the whole family street-cart breakfast dishes that I've rarely found in the States, rock-bottom prices and all. 

The two hidden gems here are the salty tofu soup and the sticky rice. The salty tofu has a silky pudding-like texture similar to Korean soondoobu, but only optionally spicy. Give it a good stir to spread out the salty dried shrimp, and get some fried dough or youtiao (literally a fat stick of deep-fried dough, like a sugarless churro) to dip and eat along with it. The sticky rice as they call it here (but also known as Chinese tamale, rice dumpling, and zongzi) is a chunk of, well, flavored sticky rice tightly wrapped in a bamboo leaf and encasing one of several fillings. I personally like the Shanghai-style meat filling with fatty pork, though I wish it also had nuts or beans like I've had it elsewhere to liven up the texture and that it was served hot. The small space makes this place better for takeout anyway, so just throw it in the microwave at home.

Perhaps a little more well-known are the steamed buns, and while the roast pork or char siu buns seem to be the most recognized kind in the States, I actually find the ones here to be lacking in meat. On the other hand, I LOVE both the pork, egg, and sausage buns and the pork and vegetable buns, which are more generously filled and closer to the Northern Chinese food I grew up eating. I haven't really had the sweet items here, but given the place's name, I don't doubt that they're good. This is a perfect place for a snack or breakfast if you get one item, or lunch if you get a couple. Try giving french toast and eggs a break and sampling a new style of breakfast here instead!

text:
Got a prix fixe menu for $40/ person. 

We were so full we couldn't finish all of our food. The quantity was plenty. Quality was great as well. Although some of our smaller dishes were cold by the time they came out. We also got, which were reasonably priced and delicious. The outdoor dining situation was perfect as well. We went in February so it was still decently cold. There were heaters and we were sitting in our own little booth. Still amazes me how restaurants like Sampan can adapt so well to COVID restrictions and still offer such quality service. 

Out of all of the dishes, I'd probably go back for the chilean sea bass or the pork bao buns. Definitely worth another visit.

text:
This used to be my fav spot to get a super quick pho bo or delicious grilled pork chop on rice. We used to eat there at least once every few months and ordered a ton of foods to go. It was fast service, affordable, and just the right 4-star rating. 

Recently, the ownership must have changed hands or the chefs changed, the whole vibe was different when we came in last Sunday. The service took 20 mins to get our pho (which is pretty much unacceptable in Vietnamese restaurant for foods to come out. Especially pho since everything already cooked/sliced, just a matter of assembling it on a bowl).  We ordered our usual beef pho dac biet and grilled pork chop on broken rice and the grilled meat came out sliced and not on the bone. Pho was watered down. They didn't have bean sprouts with our pho, and the soup spoon was also out. Everything about a solid vietnamese experience was not there, not fast and not delicious, and the reason why I gave 2 stars instead of 1 is because it's still cheap. 

Won't be back.

text: This place has nice karaoke rooms but considering that if you have a party of 10 or more it's $20 per person it's not worth it. they give you like seven dollars worth of food per person  which is ridiculous. 11 people in my party and they brought out 5-6 plates for everyone to share. They started taking away out plates and I literally was like "that's it?" In disbelief I was still very much hungry. It's definitely not worth it. Not the greatest service either and it was difficult to get a room as well. There's other karaoke rooms in Chinatown that are more worth it. The food was okay, your typical Chinese food. They didn't give us any expensive dishes either with the big party, just chicken dishes, lo mein, fried rice, chow fun, that you can get for a fraction of the price at your local Chinese restaurant by your house.

text:
TLDR: Come here for a solid bowl of authentic noodles at a reasonable price! Just be sure to bring some cash along.

For appetizers, my girlfriend and I split the three-flavor aromatic mixed platter, which came with marinated beef, pig ears, beef tendon. We got it spicy, although the heat was very manageable actually. For mains, we ordered the dry noodle with peanut sauce and the house special noodle soup. Both of us opted for shaved noodles, which are slightly shorter and thicker than the hand drawn ones. The bill came out to ~$35 for all 3 dishes (before tax and tip), so price-wise it was not bad at all!

text:
I was so excited for this place to finally open! The layout is clutch. The design is everything. It is an Instagramers dream.  The neon lights welcome you, and the layout provides such a cool vibe that anytime you go, it is a good time.

We went for happy hour and the drink prices were ok. There were no food options for happy hour, but that is ok. I ordered the watermelon marg and it was so fresh. It tasted like they cut the watermelon right away and poured it into my glass. 

We randomly asked our waitress what to order and surprisingly the Cesar salad was amazing. The fried calamari was perfect. 

I will say we got the shrimp egg rolls and the baby corn, which weren't amazing. 

The Quesa Birria Taco with the dipping sauce was a heavenly experience. 

All in all, it is a fun place to go, I would not run back to it, but I also would never say no on returning.

text: First time ever having Korean BBQ and it did not disappoint. Went with a group of 9 and had a private room. The room was great and we would definitely reserve it again. Can't comment on the Hot Pot but the all you can eat BBQ was reasonably priced and delicious.   If you don't know much about Korean BBQ the waitress will definitely help you through the ordering process. We had someone in our party who grew up eating Korean BBQ and could order for us and knew how long to cook everything and what sauces went best with what, but it was nice having the waitress recommend proper amounts so we didn't over order! She also started the first round of food on the grill. We tried an assortment of proteins and enjoyed getting all types of sauces at the sauce bar. Highly recommend ordering a few seafood pancakes to split with your party because they were amazing.  The table had peanuts, edamame, seaweed salad, and kimchi when we arrived. And then two large bowls of rice came out with the BBQ. They also come about halfway through the meal to change out the grill pans.

text:
Walked in off the street with some friends after noticing this new place opened up. My favorite dish at any Chinese place is Dan Dan noodles, so I immediately ordered those and it may have been the best I've had in the city. Very delicious, spicy, and has incredible texture to it. That alone will keep me coming back.

Also had the general tso chicken which was very crispy, chili oil dumplings which were very good, and the soup doublings that exploded with flavor in your mouth. 

All of the food was VERY reasonably priced for the portions and on top of that - A1 service...Very nice family running this place too. Will be coming back here a lot.

text:
Delicious place for all-you-can-eat hotpot. Their service is fast and friendly. I've been here at least 4 times and have never been disappointed! I think the prices are quite fair because you literally can order as much food as you want! I tend to come here when I'm feeling down and looking for something nice and warm to eat. 

The soup bases taste great and I've tried a variety of them but my favorite is the Szechuan Hot Spicy broth. I've actually had hotpot in Szechuan and I say the flavor is very similar! I always at least get beef slices, fish balls, frozen tofu, quail eggs and enoki mushrooms. For the DIY sauce, I keep it simple with peanut sauce and some spicy oil. Definitely experiment around when you come here though! The options are endless

text: Our new favorite authentic Szechuan place in Philly. Quick service with complimentary tea and peanuts. The restaurant is clean and bright. Loved the ambiance here. The prices are reasonable for the large portion size. A lot of the dishes can be (and are meant to be) shared. The menu is large and has pictures. We got the chicken griddle which was a dry pot style and the Dan Dan noodles. The chicken came in a bowl with a flame underneath it to keep it warm. Both so packed with flavor and the right amount of spice. Both are also garlic heavy so beware. We are definitely coming back to try more!

text:
Good food and price point. The shanghainese soup dumplings aren't my favorite soup dumplings, but I would come here solely for the spicy wontons (recommend adding even more crunchy chili oil that they have on every table on top of most things but that's just me). I wasn't a fan of the pork bun either, but I can't really judge that fairly because I don't really like buns very much to start with.  

The house special dumplings in soup was delicious! Also a big fan of the turnip cakes and shrimp siu mai as well. The server seemed a little overwhelmed, seemed like she was the only one running the whole show, takeout, in house, checking out. While some people like to complain about that, this woman was on top of it, props to her, if you need your server to put on a show and sing you a serenade, this might not be the place for you. 

They had a fully stocked bar, but it didn't look like they were serving that right now. Got 7 orders for about $37 before tip and had some left overs.

text:
Wow, this place is fantastic!  I live in the neighborhood and noticed it being readied for opening so came for dinner on their 6th day of operation.  It was one of the best meals I've had in ages!  It reminded me of Susanna Foo that used to be on Walnut Street - without the snooty attitude and at 1/3 the cost!

The menu but especially the daily specials are incredibly extensive, from vegetarian to seafood to meat and poultry.  Everything sounded fabulous and interesting.  Our group of 4 shared 2 sampler appetizer platters (Seafood and Vegetarian), and they were delicious.  Each with a selection of 4 perfectly prepared, beautifully presented appetizers that were complete creations themselves.  For dinners our table enjoyed the seafood curry medley, a tofu dish, crispy chicken, and everything was excellent.  Rich flavors, well balanced, interesting, perfectly prepared and presented.  Creme brulee for desert was excellent.  Appropriate sized portions (I have had too much experience with "fine dining" where the food is so precious and portions so small I leave only half-full).  As I said, one of the most delicious meals I've had in ages!   

We ate outside on the sidewalk because it was a nice evening, which at the corner of South & Juniper was fine, but they say they will soon have a deck in the back for outdoor dining.  Service was very nice and did not have the usual hiccups of a new restaurant.  Staff and particularly the owner Corey were great, and it is clear he really enjoys hosting people and pleasing them with his skills.  It took a long time for the food to be ready, so this is not fast in-and-out, not surprising given the extensive menu offerings.  No liquor license so BYOB.

Finally, you can't beat the price.  Appetizers, dinners, shared desert with tax & tip came to $40pp.  Given the quality of the food, it can't stay at that level for long and be a profit-making restaurant, but while it does it is an incredible bargain!

I'm excited to have this restaurant in the neighborhood, its a real gem!

text:
My roommate and I brought our bfs to the city for a date night. As a last minute decision, we booked a 10 PM reservation for Friday night. 
We got there and got seated right away! I was surprised at how packed it was for 10 pm. Definitely a great night life atmosphere! 
Our waiter was very nice and made sure we had everything we needed.
My boyfriend and I got the dim sum sampler. You need to try it!! We couldn't decide which appetizer to get so decided to do a taste test and they were DELICIOUS! 
The 4 of us got a pitcher to split (I forget the drink name) which was very tasty! However, expensive and only filled us up each with about 1 1/2 glasses.
For entrees I got the pad thai. Holy crap- amazing!!!! It was so good and well worth the price.
My boyfriend, who is an avid steak lover, decided to get the char grilled aged beef. When I tell you he was blown away by this!! He literally talked about it for a week afterwards that's how much he loved it.
Although this place is pricey, it's a beautiful place for a night out.
5 stars for a pretty atmosphere, nice staff, and delicious food!!

text:
I've been waiting for years for a Pho restaurant to pop up in the Northeast that is actually good. Pho Nam Giang doesn't disappoint as the food here is actually better than most restaurants by Adams Ave (NE) and Washington Ave (SP).

We've been here a few times and have only tried the Pho Dac Biet and Bun Bo Nuong, the portions are plentiful and they don't skimp on the meat either.

The service was great; this isn't your typical Vietnamese restaurant where they only show up to take your order and send your food out. The server and even the manager came by to see how we were doing and refilled out glasses of water when they were empty.

This place is clean, obviously it's new but probably one of the cleanest Vietnamese restaurants I've ever been to, so there's zero complaints there.

I've read in a few other reviews that the prices are high but most restaurants are raising their prices and even the other Pho restaurants in Philly might be $1 less per dish, not a big deal...

I would definitely recommend giving this place a try if you're in the area or after you're done shopping at FM.

text:
I normally wouldn't give a bad review, but this was one of my biggest misses in terms of quality and flavor of food, and I'm extremely confused by the other reviews that have positive things to say about the food. We got four items: shrimp tostada, fish tacos, wontons, and baby corn. Every single one of them tasted off to us- the tostada was totally overwhelmed by bland refried black beans with basically no other flavor, I didn't taste the fish tacos but my partner said they were extremely salty. The wontons were... I mean, they were fried wontons, I'm not complaining about the concept, but the salsas they were served with all had off flavors and very minimal spice, and... last but not least... the baby corn. Why, just... why. Nothing about those flavors made any sense, it was extremely salty and was not at all palatable. And all together with a Topo Chico it cost $87 (That's including tip, but still) Just... save yourself the trouble, unless you are just going to hang out and drink there and don't care about the food. Would maybe be less noticeable if we were drunk. For context, I can't remember the last time I didn't like any of the food items I ordered at a restaurant, if ever. This is a restaurant that exists to be instagramable and sell drinks - if you are looking for good food or even in the ballpark of a reasonable price for the quality, look elsewhere. 

Good things were the drink I got (grapefruit and smoked sea salt) and the server and host staff were very friendly, helpful and doing an excellent job. Back of House also did an excellent job - food came out quickly and seemed to be executed as designed. Big thumbs ups to the folks working here, but the concept and menu really needs some work.

text:
I came here with pretty high expectations considering the quantity of good reviews. We had reservations on a Thursday at around 7pm and it was extremely busy that night but were seated pretty quickly. Our table was very close to the others so it was difficult to conversate but we managed. 

We ordered a few drinks, the Strawberry Mansion and SGT. Pepper, both were just average and probably wouldn't order either again.

I asked the server what appetizers he would recommend and mentioned the Zucchini Blossom Tempura, it came as a pair about the size of a pickle, definitely not worth it considering the price, especially since the ricotta overpowered the truffle flavoring. The Crispy Octopus was probably the best thing that we had here, we ordered two. The Mafaldine Carbonara had a nice twist with the crispy pork belly, similar to how you would get crispy pork belly at an authentic Chinese restaurant. We ordered the Spicy Jawn pizza and it was decent, but it didn't WOW us.

Overall, we had a decent time here but probably won't be coming back and won't be recommending it to friends, there are better restaurants to go to for the price.

text: This place is truly a hidden gem for amazing authentic Italian food. We decided to try it because the outdoor seating seemed cute, but the food surprised us. We had the crispy octopus which was delicious and cooked perfectly. We then tried the double Margherita pizza, the frank white pizza, and the saffron malloreddus. The pizzas were both perfectly done Neapolitan style pizzas, from a perfect chewiness of the dough to high quality cheeses and original flavors on the frank white. The malloreddus were perfectly cooked too (a pasta shape that I don't think I have ever seen in the US). The service was great, our server made great recommendations and was helpful in everything. The outdoor ambiance is so cute as well. They have a whole garden in addition to regular sidewalk seating and covered sidewalk tables with private chalets, all surrounded by beautiful fairy lights. You can make reservations and easily choose between sidewalk, indoor, or garden seating on resy. The price of the food is absolutely fair for the quality that you get. We will definitely be back.

text:
It's surprising how much great Chinese food is in Philly.  There's a lot of good Asian food in Houston, but it's mostly Vietnamese, or Vietnamese-influenced Chinese, or, stranger yet, Vietnamese versions of American Chinese food (or even Vietnamese-American Chinese-Mexican smash-ups).  But in Philly it's different, unlike anything I've had anywhere else.  So every time I come here I make the rounds of the Chinese restaurants.

I come to this one, like others do, for the Braised Beef Soup. I like it spicy, which has a little less heat than regular Buffalo wings.  The noodles are excellent. The broth is kind of bland compared to pho, but the braised beef compensates for the lack of flavor in the broth. I think the beef is brisket, and the good fatty kind that Texans love to smoke for hours in their smokers, until it melts in your mouth. Here it also melts in your mouth, releasing a cacophony of chili oil and spices as you savor the meat.  For each bite I like a to twirl some noodles (yes, I use a fork), get a small piece of beef, then capture a few herbs.  Sometime I need to to get past the soup and see if they have stir-fried noodles with braised beef.

This was my second time here, and, like the first time, there was a line out the door at the adjacent dim sum joint.  But, also like the first time, there were plenty of seats available in the tiny, sterile space so I was seated right away.  The tables are jammed together, with tables-for-four spaced about an inch from the tables-for-two, and, even if the restaurant is nearly empty, they always seat one party adjacent to another. It's almost as if you're all dining at the same table.  Some folk like that, I guess.

I couldn't find the braised beef soup on the menu. I flipped back-and-forth, looked on the back, and still couldn't find it. The waiter came to take my order, and I asked him, in panic mode, if they still had the braised beef soup. They did.  The pages of the menu were sticking together, and I was skipping the entire middle part.  

I wanted something in my stomach to avoid eating all the  carb-heavy, delicious noodles, so I ordered the diced cucumber.  The dish was a cucumber salad with lots of salt and chopped garlic, a sprinkle of cilantro, and a slice of a scallion. It was refreshing; I think I'll make this at home, but with more cilantro and scallion.

Besides the crowdedness, the only other downside to Nan's is that they don't take credit cards. If the soup were priced a few dollars less, I could understand that, but it's not.  At $11 a pop, they can afford to take credit cards.

text:
I will say this place has the most authentic Peking duck & Wonton noodle soup to try in Philly Chinatown because they taste the same as the place I tried in Hong Kong!

[Peking duck]: perfect crispy skin with tender & juicy duck meat, which is the perfect combination for a perfect Peking duck!

[Wonton noodle soup]: egg noodles was tender, wonton skin is silky (very smooth to swallow), and the soup was clear taste and not too salty! 

The overall food quality here was good, but the Peking duck portion was a bit small compared to its price. I probably will come back to get their wonton soup dishes. Still highly recommend this place if you miss authentic Cantonese cuisine!

text:
Chinatown, PA is popping, and it seems like majority of the people there choose this place to have dinner.

I heard about the long wait times, especially on a Friday night, but I didn't expect to be 14th in line despite waitlisting an hour early. Try going early despite having waitlisted as they told us a shorter wait time than what was indicated on Yelp.

The service was phenomenal, honestly the best I have ever seen. The young lady who welcomed us was friendly and patient and held our spot for us even though we walked off for a bit during our wait time.

Our server was just as friendly and sweet. You can choose to order through the conveyor (it's cheaper, more for 1 person) or through their menu (bigger portions, more expensive). I had the House Original Pot and my boyfriend got the Tomato Oxtail Pot. We both argue our own is better.

The hot pot ingredients are extremely overpriced, and I'm talking $1 for one mini sausage. However, their soup does wonders in making any food taste phenomenal. I barely even needed sauce, although their ponzu sauce was delightful. 

The Wagyu Beef w/ Wasabi ($12) was expensive for the small stick size, but it was oh so good and full of beef aroma. And I don't think I will ever forget the creaminess of the Wagyu Short Rib with Egg ($26). Who knew egg can do such wonders? Wait 10 seconds for it to cook in the broth and then you'd be reaching heaven each time you have a piece. 

I had a fantastic time here, and I can see the hype. You have to get their meats for sure!
