text:
My friends and I decided to pop into Bai Wei on a whim because we hadn't been there before and didn't know what to expect. We were pleasantly surprised at how good the food and service was. But, for us, the downsides outweighed the positives. Although the food tasted good, the portions were so small. Usually, Chinese restaurant gives customers large serving sizes--which is what we expected when we ordered--but we were shocked at how small of a size the servings were. From what we saw, either the food was overpriced or the servings didn't meet the exceptions set by the price. Rice was free but it was served in the smallest rice bowl I have ever seen in my life. I would recommend going here if you're alone but never with friends or in a group because you'll spend more than $50 before you feel like you're full. 
Also, they alone accept cash or Venmo as payment

text:
This is like a traditional Chinese Restaurant that is from like the 90s. The way it's decorated and the purple light gives it the 90s vibe. It's not a modern restaurant by any means. This place is located in China Town and I highly highly recommend Ubering or taking a taxi as there is literally no parking here.

I ordered a variety of foods such as a variety plate that had beef slices, clam, intestine, jellyfish and some cured meat. I would say that this was not good at all. The jelly fish reminded me of the jelly fish you find at the grocery store for like 2 dollars. It's bland and it seems like they forgot to mix the sauce with it. The beef was really dry and tough. The intestines is a weird touch as that's not usually on this kind of platter and the best thing was probably the cured meat as that is probably something they bought instead of making it in-house. 

The braised tofu tasted decent. The sauce goes great with white rice (which you need to order). The snow peas are correctly prepared as the ends are cut off and the fiber strip was taken off. The beef chow fun tasted good, very traditional style and it was well seasoned. The beef was tender and easy to eat. The snow pea leaf was just okay as well. It's weird as it's sold by market price and not a fixed price.

Portion sizing is good, plenty of food but the beef chow fun didn't have many beef pieces. Some of these dishes are priced moderately well. Service here wasn't so good. It took a few tries to get something like napkins and we had to keep asking about the white rice.

The cleanliness of the restaurant is... questionable. It looks pretty run down and the bathroom is really really disgusting. It's really small like a standing shower and there's water everywhere (at least I hope it's water). 

Overall, just a mediocre Chinese restaurant. Would I recommend? Only if you're really hungry and there's not many places opened. This places closes late like at 2:30 AM.

text: I went there for my birthday with my fiance and best friend. We had a split check. My fiance told the server to charge $14 dollars for the one meal that my friend order that cost $14. He paid cash for the other check. The server charge my friend $40. He came back and my fiance told him that he overcharged my friend. The server said no you said $40. He began to argue that my fiance said $40 not $14. This went on a few minutes the server refused to refund the money. Finally after the long exchange in argument He finally refund the money. Don't they no that the customer is always right. We shouldn't go through that just to get the money back. Rudest server I ever dealt with. I wish I knew his name. He blamed us for his bad English.

text:
I came  here with my family and was told we couldn't eat because my daughters were wearing "gym attire". The staff were unpolite, especially Tara. I called to make reservations and never was told about the dress code. They asked us to go home and change, but we refused to do so because we live 45 minutes away, they offered to us to speak to the manager, and they called security before calling the manager. They had a very intimidating guy standing next to us the whole time, and the manager, Edgar Da Silva, when he finally came was of no help. My young daughters didn't understand what was happening and why we were being treated like that.
We had to pay their Valets full price for being there 10 minutes (most of the time waiting for the manager)
Overall a very bad experience, not returning there.
We ended up going to Fogo de Chao, with no dress code, great ambience, and most importantly great food.

text:
Above average price for far far below average quality hot pot. Would greatly recommend going literally ANYWHERE else. 
Our server on Monday night clearly did not care about our satisfaction or presence at all for that matter. In fact, we practically expected to be automatically charged for gratuity after this terrible to nonexistent level service. Our server deliberately avoided our table and chose to hide from us over clearing anything or taking care or any of our needs or requests. The food quality is very mediocre and bland compared to any other hotpot place and the dining area is minimal to tight. The only upside to coming here is that they offer a free seat for birthdays however you must pay in cash in full. ( there is no fine print or notification of this policy except when you pay ).

text:
My colleague and I walked in here during lunch and  found ourselves to be the only customers. This establishment has a short list of menu; this is great so you don't take a lot of time to choose. I generally appreciate if the counter person greets me with a good vibe, but maybe she was having a not so good day- no smile/energy whatsoever. Nevertheless, we came there for the food; I decided to get the Pistachio Pesto Pappardelle with Sausage and a can of san pellegrino. The whole thing costs me $18 and some change. My coworker got the Bolognese Pappardelle with Spinach. When the counter person brought put boxes, mine smells great- i can smell the pesto. However, I was disappointed after taking the first bite; the pasta was chewy and the taste was pretty bland. The sausages were these miniature cuts that i can just swallow without the need to chew. The only good part was the garlic bread. My coworker felt the same way about her food and the price was a bit up there for mediocre food. 

I believe this place just opened, so maybe they need some time to adjust. Please check it out for yourself. As for me, I won't come back bc It's not worth it in my opinion.

text:
Takeout (ordered directly off their site) is not as tasty as dining in. I realized that I also DoorDashed from here previously.

I had three completely different experiences with dining in, picking up, and ordering delivery.

When ordering delivery, the portion size wasn't great for the $100 price tag. When picking up, the portion for the dandan noodles was huge! But the texture was lost (became soggy) for a 10 minute walk home which made the huge portion not satisfying.

If I ever decide to order from here, I'll opt for dining-in (rated 4/5) because the quality is just night and day for the different order scenarios especially for the dandan noodles.

text:
Really enjoyed my experience here. Ambience is great with well decorated outdoor seating. Great interior design as well. 

Drinks were delicious. I got the Bring the Beet In cocktail which I highly recommend. 
We started off with the crispy octopus, the most expensive small plate but well worth the price. It was very meaty and the pesto sauce complimented the octopus well. We shared the Pork Belly Carbonara pasta and Sawzeech pizza. The pasta tasted homemade, and the pork belly was delicious, although portion is slightly on the smaller size. The pizza comes in 6 slices and is a good portion. The crust was light and airy. I was not blown away by any particular dish but I appreciated each one. 

Service was friendly and welcoming. Would definitely come back here.

text:
Found this gem in Philly Chinatown. Lovely family-owned business with all the comfort foods and hospitality!

All of their coffees & drinks are great! I tried the lattes, matcha latte, cold brew coffee (very smooth) & Siphon coffee - pricey but well worth it. Rare to find a place with Siphon coffee gear from Japan & I am happy to be supporting a small minority-owned business.

I also LOVE their Rasberry Oat bar. They hv a delectable selection of breakfast muffins, cake slices, cookies etc.

Meals - I tried their dumpling sampler. Awesome choice and love the homemade chili oil.

The Taiwanese Beef Noodle Soup was SO worth it. Again a bit on the pricey side I know BUT try it at least once! (And then come back for more..) The soup is sooooo flavorful, the noodles smooth and soft but not soggy, plentiful veggies and the beef slices melt in your mouth. It's also a good size bowl so I definitely had leftovers.

Also, I was pleasantly surprised that Angela (owner's daughter & expert barista) remembered me by my name on the second day I came back.

text:
We tried to place an order and were quite surprised by the total. The prices on the menu were not what they charged us and when we asked why they had no explanation. We asked them to honor the prices on their site and could provide snapshots of the online prices the person working said he couldn't make any adjustments and he would "alert Managment" about the discrepancy. 

We asked if there was anything that could be done and he said want moved or interested in finding a solution. We ended up canceling our order and he mumbled something as he hung up the phone. 

The price discrepancy was apparently across every item. A total bill went from $49.35 to over $62 before tax.

This is a great example of a business that is uninterested in serving the customer or rectifying their own mistake. They seem ok losing business due to inconsistency or concern for customer satisfaction.

text:
My husband was craving for pho and this place is the closest pho restaurant around us, that is how we first visited this location. For now, we have been there for a good number of times. 

Parking: They have their own decent size parking lot so there's no need to look for street parking. 

Location: The restaurant is located very close to the Philadelphia Mills, aka Franklin Mills.

Services: Employees were nice. They check on you throughout your meal or are available when you need them. 

Covid: All employees are masks on. They do tried to sit you apart from other customers if you requested. Most customers are sitting at the booth on the side back to back from other booth. 

Food: Pho taste not bad, at a good average level. Sometimes I do feel the soup broth might be slightly a bit salty, but overall not bad at all. Around the upper Northeast area near Bensalem, the food quality is consider pretty good. Portion wise maybe a tad bit small compare to other Vietnamese or pho restaurants.

Price: Their price are consider on the high end but not the ridiculous price I have seen at other locations. It is still acceptable. Maybe because I'm paying this price, I might expect a bit more out. 

Would I recommend this restaurant? Yes, I probably will if you want to eat pho or looking for some Vietnamese cuisine around this area.

text: The Pickled Flounder Soup was very good, nice kick and rich pickled broth. Seafood Soup has big pieces of silky tofu with a lot of artificial crab meat , would of preferred to have more of the squid and larger sized shrimp, after all it is a "Seafood Soup" . Dumplings we're good, but small.. should be bigger in size or more quantity for price they charge. Hot oil wontons were yummy, good spice and flavor.

text:
This is a good choice for when you aren't sure what you want, so you can get your top 4 with a soup and rice or noodles. For just $6.50 (at the time of this review) you get an incredibly generous portion of food - probably the best bang for your buck in Chinatown! The food choices are much more diverse than your typical American Chinese restaurant, so you'll find some good stuff here. It doesn't taste as great as most of the other restaurants in Chinatown, but it's hard to argue with the cost. 

So, if you want a lot of food and a lot of choices to choose from, this is the place for you.

text:
TLDR: Overpriced average food and snooty staff that will ignore you if they don't think your party is spending enough (or maybe just if you're less than 30).

We were a party of 6 celebrating my friend's engagement. We all ordered a drink, appetizers, and a couple of us shared multiple appetizers or entrees. The waiter (bald older man) kept trying to push the $60 per person tasting menu on us- which, while it seems amazing, isn't what we were looking for on our medical school student budgets- we wanted nice food, but not quite that pricy.

After we ordered the waiter was clearly irritated we hadn't ordered more and proceeded to ignore our table the remainder of the night. He went and took drink orders and refilled the water at the two large party tables beside us (twice) but ignored us  completely and never refilled our water after we put our order in (probably at least an hour). The previous hour while we'd had drinks and waited for our friend this had not been the case. We would have liked to have order more drinks, but after being ignored for that long decided not to and to just get the check because we were tired of the staff looking down their noses at us. 

In addition to that, the food was far from original in my opinion, and nothing to justify the price point. Sure some of the appetizers were unique, and the duck was delicious, but I don't think they were any better than what I've had at any other Philly dim sum restaurant or Asian fusion restaurants (and was considerably more expensive). I'd save your money and go elsewhere for dim sum, and there are any number of nicer restaurants at this price point that actually care to cater to and be nice to their customers regardless of how much they spend. Won't be back even when I do have more to spend.

text:
Very surprised this place does not have more reviews considering how delicious their food is!

They specialize in rice noodles (aka boat noodles), based on an old Chinese story. You get the soup in a hot pot and add your own ingredients.

I got the tomato base with brisket and my friend got the traditional base with sliced beef. Both were solid though I preferred the tanginess of the tomato broth, perfect on a cold fall day. The prices are also very fair for the portion size.

The restaurants interior is very clean and welcoming with quick service. Highly recommend!

text: We stopped in for a very quick bite late at night just before they closed and ordered the shrimp dumplings, the soup dumplings, and the Dan Dan noodles. The food was good. I'm sure this is one of those places where you can order anything on the menu and it will taste good. The neighborhood is pretty far from Chinatown and if you need a quick fix then this is a good spot however, if you can make the trip to Chinatown you can get more bang for your buck.

text:
Hainanese chicken with chicken flavored rice and the roti canai is friggin good. 

Definitely back to basics feel with the chicken dish but it was price efficient, and filling. Without the two sauces on the side, it can be a bit bland but just pour/dip that sauce and everything should be good and dandy.

Roti  canai is, as always, good texture with the yummy chicken+potato curry dipping sauce. Definitely the starter you should try.

No pics for this one because I didn't dine-in and just vacuumed the food down into my stomach at home. The dine-in experience is great as well. It was actually my first dine-in experience with fam when moving to Philly. It was a casual experience and felt a part of the Chinatown here.

text:
Might be the most popular dim sum place in Chinatown, but is it the best? I certainly hope not?

They only serve Shanghainese dumplings and snacks, so you came here craving cantonese dimsum stamples like cheung fun or turnip cake or a legit hargow you will be disappointed. 

Looking around their consistently crowded dining room the most popular items are by far dumplings of all kinds - soup dumplings, potstickers, sheng jian bao - and scallion pancakes. 

The scallion pancake doesn't look particularly good and seems overpriced, so I've never tried it. We've tried almost all the dumpling options at least twice over several occasions though, both there and for delivery, and.. it's alright.

The xiao long bao are particularly underwhelming. The skin is really thick, the filling not very flavorful. Not a delicate purse bursting with umami like you would hope or crave. The rest of the dumplings are fine, but doesn't really live up to the hype or is any better than elsewhere. It tastes like something mass manufactured you could order, like frozen fries out of a box. Very comforting, very generic, but you expect more from a place that specializes in dumplings.

The rest of the dishes are also just okay. Not memorable, not enjoyable, but not completely offensive in taste either? Like I wouldn't have eaten here again after any of the times I've tried it had I not known it was "supposed to be good."

Maybe this place just doesn't cater to an asian palate. Most of the clientele here is not Asian, and they seem to enjoy it here. Not really the type of dim sum or kinds of dishes I expect or necessarily want to eat though.

text:
Whenever I am at reading terminal or happen to be in the area, I make sure to grab some duck rolls and any of the noodle soups! I also order takeout, as my husband loves the duck rolls as an afterword snack, and I really enjoy the soups and noodles for lunch during my work from home days.

Prices are extremely reasonable. Absolutely delicious and fresh food, staff is friendly.

text:
5 star taste. The Wagyu beef combo and Shrimp paste meatballs were most memorable. The House broth was perfect in terms of having a light yet rich flavor.

All the dishes were aesthetically pleasing (excluding the conveyer belt items). The conveyer belt is a cool aspect although I'm unsure of its necessity here.

I'd recommend coming here with a small party of up to four people. However, I would not recommend for large groups. For this reason and my personal experience thus far, I have to give 3 stars.

Service in detail: Our server was very kind despite offering a drink option and not delivering on it. Previously, I came here with a group of 8 and due to miscommunication on their end, we called to see if we could come in to be seated and got the approval to do so. When we got there, they rescinded their statement and said it was a mistake because they thought our number belonged to another group of 8.

Price: Some items are not priced correctly. A $.50-$1 amount of enoki mushrooms costed $8.

text: This was the first meal I had after moving to Philadelphia and it was a great introduction! It stays open a bit later than most of the other restaurants in the area, which is much appreciated. The boiled chicken rice is so good and reminds me of hainanese chicken. We got the set for 2 people, which also comes with soup! There was a regular sauce and a spicy sauce and I actually really liked the spicy one. We also got the pad Thai which I thought was just ok, which is why this isn't 5 stars. The chicken rice was def 5 stars though!! The value is also so great - we were 3 people and still had a good amount of leftovers! Definitely 100% recommend stopping by here for the chicken rice :) I'll come back and try the fried chicken instead next time (or do half and half bc the boiled chicken is so good)

text: I've heard so much about Sampan so I had really high expectations, but in my opinion, the food was really just ok. The pork potstickers were pretty flavorful, but a little too salty imo. The pork bao buns were alright, but I think they're breaded & fried with some sweet and sour sauce, which I feel hides the tenderness of pork belly and made it seem like it could be any meat. I was expecting more of a braised pork belly as is typical because that really allows the pork belly to shine. The Ming Mule was also just fine - I really couldn't taste the lychee much & my glass was cracked unfortunately. If you go, I would probably go for happy hour to save some money but the happy hour prices weren't that great to the portion size in my opinion like one stick of satay for $5 is too much imo. It's alright Asian fusion food but could've been much better & did not live up to the hype in my opinion. The service was nice & so is the ambience but the food is just meh. I would stop by if you haven't been & are looking for a new happy hour, but I personally wouldn't make it a happy hour staple.

text: BEST HAPPY HOUR IN THE CITY. So so so good and affordable. Happy hour daily from 4-7pm. No reservations for happy hour. Can sit at the bar or outside for happy hour - dining room doesn't do it. However I made a reservation and we sat outside and got happy hour menus so not really sure what they're trying to accomplish. Drinks are delicious and their food is amazing - love their fried rice, pork belly bao buns and crispy Brussel sprouts.

text: My friend told me a few days ago about her bad experience here and I should've  has listened. Overpriced and mediocre food. The skin on the soup dumplings and shanghai wonton was so thick that I just ate the meat. I had to drown the soup dumplings with vinegar and wonton with hot sauce because it was so bland. I couldn't wait to get out of there!

text: I was a little underwhelmed which is upsetting because I was so excited to try this place. We started with the wonton chips which were amazing, but we needed 2 orders to satisfy the three of us (there is a small up charge for more chips). I got the Spiked Champurrado for my drink and it was way too strong and really not good at all. For our app, we got the Tuna Ceviche which was extremely small for $17, so my two friends decided to split that between the 2 of them. It was good but very overpriced. For our entrees we got the Birria Tacos and Mushroom Tacos. Both were good, but I was looking for that wow factor with the Birria Tacos. To end the meal, we got the Churros which were very yummy but I wasn't a fan of the chocolate sauce that went with it. Overall, I like the vibe of La Chinesca--the service was amazing and the food was good in some aspects. However for how much they charge and how little you get, it wasn't really worth it and I still left hungry.

text: I have been wanting to try this place the last few times I visited so I was happy to get a chance this time but wish I didn't. The dim sum is subpar and overpriced. One of the ladies pushing the cart kept coming over every 3 minutes to push you to order something off her cart eventhough you told her THREE times we are fine and we would like to wait until we finish first. Only one waiter working that never comes by after he takes your tea order. You have to pay at the desk so when I went up to pay, the cashier/owner noticed i was in front of her but was too busy signing a delivery invoice and made me wait another two minutes before she took my credit card/bill. The credit card machine only gives you the option to tip 18% or more, What?!? She never said a word throughout the whole transaction, not even a thank you, she had a "i want to kill you" stare the whole time. For just a moment there I had the urge to stick my hand through the little opening and grab her by the shirt and say "What's your problem"?!

text: It so pricey but my favorite hot pot place.  The quality of their meat and seafood is really fresh, service is good and hot pot broths and ponzu sauce you dip your food with is so good.  I love their original broth, spicy broth and tomato oxtail broth and I usually just drink it as soup at the end.  The waygu meat combo is usually what I go with and I also love their fresh mushroom platter, pork belly and their shigoku oysters were really good.  Try to make a reservation ahead of time because wait times can be really long and it's not a filling meal for what you pay but quality is great and I'd come back here.

text:
Absolutely terrible quality of food. I've been here a couple of times per covid and it was fine and not sure what happened but it's absolutely a place to avoid now. We got 5 dishes the wait took a long time, the quality was so bad and the portion size was so small compared to the price that we paid. For reference I am Cantonese and know what these dishes taste like if they were made properly. 

The first was the pineapple fried rice and it was so sad. They used canned pineapples but they didn't even look diced like they straight up poured it out the can, strained it, and threw it in fried rice. It didn't come in a pineapple (which I supposed makes sense if they don't use real pineapple but comon the picture had a pineapple isn't it false advertising at this point). The flavor was also really unimpressive. 

The garlic pea leaves we got were supposed to be stir fried but they BOILED it. There was no flavor at all. I can't believe they boiled it.. either they are super short staffed in the kitchen or they absolutely don't care anymore. Nothing on the pictures look like that came on the table. 

The Dan Dan noodle portion was so small. The flavor was okay but overall not good and wouldn't get again. 

The dry pot chicken was also sad. The coating And the chicken didn't mix well at all. And the texture was all wrong. I'm not sure how they messed this up but they really did. It was also really really salty. 

The chongqin noodles were okay. Not a super huge fan but the portion size was also really small. 

Over all we paid over 80 dollars and not everyone was full there was 4 of us. What and epic waste of time, money, and rental space. Honestly I am so upset I don't think I will ever come back this experience was absolutely abysmal.

text:
I am not sure how this place has so many reviews and 4 stars. It was very ok but the prices are definitely cheap. I got the peanut noodles and the steamed chicken curry dumplings. The peanut noodles were literally just noodles drenched in peanut sauce. It was very good but I like dishes with a lot of different flavors and textures and this definitely did not deliver that. As far as the dumplings, I thought there was too much "dough" (is that what it's even called?) and not enough filling. However, they came out super hot and you get 8 of them for like $7. My whole meal was $14 and change and I was stuffed -- I didn't even eat 3 of the dumplings. 

Service was quick which is always great -- I came in around 5:45pm on a Thursday night and got my food by probably 6pm. 

Overall, I would only eat here again if a friend recommended it but I am not dying to go back.

Overall, we will settle for this place for any quick peking duck cravings. :~)

text:
I think the only word I could use to describe this restaurant is 'janky.' I was definitely excited when reading up on this place. Now onto reality. Imagine being ushered in to a dark corner of the restaurant where you hardly make out the words on the menu. Where the convenient touchscreen ordering apparatus is dangling from its socket as if on its last breath. For the record, I did ask a waiter for a different seat, but I had the pleasure of being escorted to an even dimmer area adjacent to the bathroom. 

The conveyer belt is full of non-meat items, which I suppose makes sense for freshness sake, but the items on it seemed more like a joke than anything else. I'd imagine that most things were previously canned or is able to keep in a freezer for more than a year without spoiling. So items like little sausages, quail eggs, and fish tofu. Paying $1+ per mini-sausage or fish tofu seemed not quite a good deal. Side note: the handmade noodles arrive in one-biters.

Soup base is alright and waygu/beef was very nice, albeit with a price markup. When you order, the waiter/tress will haul over a tray full of sauces and condiments which is really cool, except for the fact that it was all open to the air and also during Covid season. Staff were very kind. Unfortunately, food was not great(besides beef) and the environment was dubious. Kudos to you if you are graced with the opportunity to bask in the light, and pro tip is to go during lunch for discounts if you must.

text:
This is the first time I came here and I was satisfied with the meal. I was craving soup dumplings and ShangHai 1 does not disappoint. 

They have a decent variety of soup dumplings and fried dumplings. I tried both and they were very good. I got other dishes such as the fried squid which I highly recommend, cold seaweed and fungus, Dan dan noodles, and meat dish with rice (forgot the name). 

Overall, it was a good meal with a decent price point. The food came out quick and the service was good. I highly recommend the dumplings, the rice dish with ground pork, and the fried squid.

text:
Nothing beats a cold winter day like a hot bowl of noodle soup. I came across this place by chance when a friend, who was visiting the area, expressed a craving for noodle soup and found this place on Yelp. Ever since, it's been a frequented place. Every time I go, it seems to be more packed than the last visit, which attests to their popularity. 

Food and Drink Ordered:
* worth trying

- [Scallion Pancake*]: A friend told me that Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House has the best scallion pancakes and I can wholeheartedly agree. Crisp to perfection and a complementary dipping sauce.

- [Spicy Pig Ears*]: Hands down the best place to get pig ears. I like how thin they slice the pig ear and the pickled veggies underneath make this combination a delicious duo. 

- [Beef Brisket Hand Drawn Noodle Soup*]: I would choose the hand drawn noodles over the shaved noodles. They are pretty generous with the portions so I would recommend sharing a bowl or taking the rest to go if you don't usually eat a lot. You can reheat it by heating up the soup separate from the noodles and then put the noodles into the heated up soup. 

Would I go back? : Yes! If I was rating the food alone, I would easily rate this place a 5 but I do agree with some of the other Yelpers that the service is very hit or miss so I would more accurately rate them a 4.5. But at the end of the day, the food is good and you can't beat how affordable it is.

text:
I didn't realize crossover hot pot/yunnan rice noodles were a specific type of noodle soup bowl until I stumbled upon this restaurant! I was browsing Yelp and was intrigued since I love all type of soup noodles (especially rice noodles). Essentially it is a meal where you put all the ingredients into a hot stone bowl yourself (no gas for the bowl). They give you all the add-ins and for the most part what they give you is standard (although I didn't try and ask for anything extra/substitutions, the staff was so nice I'm sure they would if you ask!). I ordered the classic bowl and asked for some chili oil to give it a little spice. I thought the broth was very flavorful without being overly/unnecessarily salty. The noodles mixed into the broth very well (I was worried they would be clumpy). Very fair portions of everything for the price. Highly recommend!

The waitress was very nice, I told her my phone was dying and she provided me with a charger!

text:
This is a gem in Chinatown! The restaurant is huge so there's always seating. And the noodles are amazing. 

My go to appetizers: beef dumplings or scallion pancakes 

My go to entree: beef brisket noodle soup

I love it on a cold day or just any day really. The portions are enormous for the price and service is very prompt. I recommend eating in rather than take out but I've had take out and it's been good too. Also- they only take cash or Venmo so prepare accordingly... like take $20 per person to be safe. 

Pro tip: the tables have this amazing chili paste you can add to your food that just livens things up if you like your food spicy like I do. If you don't like food spicy, anything on the menu without the chili sign will be okay for you to try!

text:
It's great to have a Panda Express downtown in the burgeoning East Market retail district, even though nearby Chinatown has so many more authentic Asian food options--but Panda dishes out food quicker and cheaper.

One can't help but be impressed with how clean and pretty this Panda Express is, especially you've seen this location in its previous, dingy McDonald's incarnation.

The main issue I have with this Panda Express is that a number of food options are not available for we pre-noon lunch folk. I'll stop by around 11:30am (typically considered to be time for prime lunch hours), and I haven't been able to get various sides or entrees--serving dishes are empty, even for something basic like vegetables.

I haven't been to other Panda Express locations to compare with this location, and I'm not a Panda manager (who probably knows when to stock the counter with which options that sell best), but it's just a bit disappointing to an occasional customer like myself to have their choices feel limited.

Otherwise, I reiterate that this is a beautiful, clean location to visit, and the staff always provide quick, friendly service. Recommended for decent food at a decent price!

text: Not sure why the reviews aren't higher, but I quite enjoyed my experience here. I got the dry pot in the soup (I feel weird calling it hot pot? because it's really like dry pot in some creamy soup?) which was great. It reminded me of Mala Project in NYC, where you order your own ingredients and it comes out with the classic mala dry pot flavor. The soup was something new to me though, and I quite enjoyed it (although it was really hot, it was also quite a lot of food which was good). I may come back for the dry pot without the soup sometime. I feel that the price is just correlated with how much you order - I got a substantial amount of food for a bit under $20, but my friend ordered much more and it came out to be more expensive.

text: Would not recommend this establishment. I walked in and asked for the chicken and broccoli with fried rice (pretty standard) and she told me the price was $8.75, however it was inly 2:30 so I asked if they were still doing lunch specials and she told me no (even though the menus in the window said lunch specials were until 3pm). So I still paid and waited about five minutes for my food. I noticed when she handed me the container it wasn't really hot and when I got home I had to put it in the microwave. At first glance it did not look bad but the rice was not cooked all the way and there were hard bits in my food. The broccoli was fresh and crunchy though so I added a star for that.

Overally, the food was fine but not my choice of sichuan.

Lets also say they handled a hard situation with a solicitor very well, they kept him as close to the door as possible and honestly it took me a while to even notice the situation. Please be patient with food workers, and they did everything  professionally.

text: Tried this place that was right next to our hotel and was recommended!! I was so excited since there aren't great dim sum options where I'm from. We ordered the shrimp dumplings, siu mai, pork bun (cha siu bao), fried dough in cheung fun (炸兩), custard bun (流沙包), fried shrimp balls! My favorite was probably the custard bun, fried shrimp balls, and the siu mai was up there too. All the buns were super fluffy and everything came out steaming hot! Prices were not bad either! I didn't like the cha siu bao / pork bun bc it was actually huge and the flavor inside was overpowered by the onions and it wasn't as sweet as usual. The shrimp in the shrimp dumplings was not that flavorful but the skin was chewy! Fried shrimp balls were surprisingly really good - it was crunchy and flavorful! We had also ordered soup dumplings but they had missed it so we just cancelled it and it was all good!! I felt bad since they only had 1 server working and she was really busy!
